<hr noshade size=3> <h1>Entitlements and the Elderly</h1>
            <h2>A Major Story for the  90s and Beyond</h2>
            <strong>Entitlement programs constitute an enormous share of government spending.
 They are big 
news now and will be bigger news as the US population ages.
 Economist Marilyn Moon 
gives journalists ways of thinking about the issues in one of the nation s longest-running 
budget arguments.

<p></strong><strong>by  Marilyn Moon<p></strong><TABLE CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=20> <TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG SRC= "../../facsnet_grafix/report_tools/Moon.gif" ALT = " Marilyn Moon"> </TD><TD><B>Marilyn Moon</B> is a senior fellow with the Health Policy Center of the Urban 
Institute. She serves as one of two public trustees of the Social Security and Medicare 
Trust Funds. She is a board member of the national Academy of Social Insurance and is on 
the steering committee of the National Academy of Aging. Dr. Moon s book, 
<I>Entitlements and the Elderly</I>, with Janemarie Mulvey, is published by the Urban 
Institute Press.
</TD> </TR> </TABLE><P>In 1996, the federal government of the United States will spend nearly $500 billion on entitlement         programs for Americans aged 65 and older.
 Those programs are dominated by Social Security,         Medicare and Medicaid.
 Most of the money will be spent on Medicare and Medicaid.
 Moreover,         spending on the elderly under just these three programs will constitute over 30 percent of all         federal spending in 1995.
 It is no wonder that those serious about cutting the federal budget have         taken on what have sometimes been viewed as sacrosanct programs.
        <P>Increasingly, proposals to deal with these entitlements have been bolder and more dramatic in         the 1990s.
 For example, in the debate over the federal government s 1996 budget, reductions in         spending on Medicare and Medicaid made up over half of all the proposed spending cuts.
 So far         these significant reductions have only been proposed, but if they were to become law, this would         mark a major turning point for public policy.
        <H2>What Are Entitlements?
</H2>        Entitlement programs have been characterized as government giveaways that are out of control         because people behave as though they are "entitled" to particular benefits.
 Indeed, many         proponents of entitlement cuts treat this as the official definition.
 However, entitlement is simply a         budget term for programs that were established to be outside the usual appropriations process.
         The Congress controls these programs indirectly by establishing rules for eligibility and benefits,         rather than through the annual appropriations process.
         <P>Four programs represent the most important entitlements for the         elderly:<UL><LI><B>Social         Security</B><LI><B>Medicare</B><LI><B>Medicaid</B><LI><B>Supplemental Security         Income</B>.
</UL>        <B>Social Security</B> and <B>Medicare</B>, are traditionally thought of as "social         insurance.
" That is, wage earners contribute to a dedicated tax and after meeting minimum         standards of contributions or other eligibility requirements, they are then assured of benefits.
         These two will likely be the most critical programs in the debate over entitlements and the elderly.
         <P><B>Medicaid</B>, a joint federal/state program that offers health insurance for people with         low incomes, is also important to older Americans.
 Medicaid is particularly crucial for its         coverage of long-term care services — a fact sometimes overlooked by those who concentrate on         its benefits for mothers and children.
 A fourth program, <B>Supplemental Security Income</B>,         provides additional cash support to low income elderly persons, but over time it has declined in         importance for this age group of the population.
 Because of its small size, only about $6 billion in         1995 for persons aged 65 and above, it does not usually receive the same attention as the other         three.
        <H2>Why Cut Entitlements?
</H2>        The most obvious answer to the question of whether to cut entitlements is that this is where the         money is in the federal budget.
 In any serious effort to reduce the federal deficit, some or all of         these programs need to be considered.
        <P>In addition, reductions in Social Security and Medicare carry the implicit promise of killing         two birds with one stone - reducing the federal budget deficit and helping the long-run stability         of the trust funds that finance these two programs.
 For example, the 1995 trustees report on         Medicare's Hospital Insurance program was adopted by the Republican Congress as a rationale         for reducing spending on Medicare in order to save the trust fund and, hence, continue paying         benefits.
         <P>But some of the justifications for entitlement cuts include overstatements and misconceptions         about the program.
 For example, entitlements are sometimes mistakenly equated with “welfare”         programs.
 Welfare programs are only a small piece, since Social Security and Medicare dominate         the entitlement category.
        <P>Further, it is often implied that spending on entitlements is out of control.
 However, there is         nothing inherent in the category of entitlements itself that necessarily leads to disproportionate         growth in spending.
 Rather, growth depends upon the eligibility and benefit definitions built into         law.
 Since 1975, most entitlements have grown at about the same rate as other government         programs.
 The two exceptions are Medicare and Medicaid.
 Like the rest of our healthcare system,         these programs have expanded rapidly in recent years.
        <H2>Overarching Issues for the Debate over Entitlement Spending</H2>        One of the most difficult issues facing rational policy-making on federal entitlement programs is         the apparent convenience of combining “saving” the Social Security and Medicare programs while         reducing federal spending.
 The problem is that these two goals do not always mesh well.
 Savings         that help the federal deficit in the next few years may not coincide with the best long run         strategies for reforming the social insurance programs.
         <P>Social Security and Medicare offer a floor of financial protection during retirement.
 Many         Americans carefully make savings and other decisions in the expectation that these programs will         be there.
 Moreover, once individuals retire, it is difficult to return to the labor force or make other         changes to compensate for benefit reductions.
 Thus it is important for changes in these programs         to allow for a considerable transition period so individuals can adjust.
         <P>Further, Medicare and Social Security (and the part of the Medicaid program that serves the         elderly) need to be considered together in developing a long range strategy.
 Unfortunately,         saving one of these programs may weaken others.
 For example, a change that has been discussed         by the recent Advisory Council on Social Security would shift the revenues from taxation of         some Social Security benefits from Medicare s trust fund to Social Security s trust fund.
 This         would help put one program on firmer ground, but at the expense of the other.
        <P>Medicare and Medicaid do face problems that are more consistent with efforts to reduce         federal spending in the near term.
 This is not due to increases in the number of persons eligible         as the population ages, but rather because for many years, the costs of these health care programs         have been rising faster than the revenues raised to support them.
 In the case of Part A (Hospital         Insurance) of Medicare, revenues mainly from payroll taxes flow into a trust fund that is         supposed to finance spending on that part of the program.
 Revenues coming in are growing at         about the rate of 5 percent per year, while spending is growing at about 10 percent per year.
 As         long as the revenue base was larger than the spending base, this discrepancy could be tolerated.
         But in 1995, the amount of revenues coming in was just exceeded by the amount of income         flowing out.
 This trust fund will thus be rapidly depleted — likely by about the year 2001 —         unless policy changes are made.
 (Medicaid and the part of Medicare that funds physician         services also use up resources at a rapid rate, but do not face the constraint of the type of trust         fund associated with Part A of Medicare.
)        <H2>Sorting Out Proposals for Reform</H2>        It is likely that the debate over what to do about Social Security and Medicare will continue for         some time with many permutations of options.
 Rather than trying to outline all of these possible         details, consider some of the broad decisions that anyone thinking about reform needs to make.
         <P>A first decision in sorting through proposals is whether to emphasize an incremental         approach or major structural reforms.
 It is possible to achieve enough savings with either         strategy.
 For example, if we were to make changes today in Social Security, we would have to         either raise the payroll tax by a little over 2 percentage points per year or come up with a         comparable level of savings.
 Raising the age of eligibility for Social Security by a year or two         would solve a substantial share of the problem.
 Other incremental changes could modestly         reduce benefits for those with higher incomes.
 A combination of modifications to the current         system could achieve the savings needed.
        <P>The alternative is to seek a major structural change such as “privatization” of either Social         Security.
 One way to privatize the system would be to allow individuals to invest part or all of         their payroll contribution in securities while having the government offer only a basic minimum         floor of support.
 Much of the intellectual appeal of broader structural reform is not that it would         be painless for beneficiaries, but that it offers the opportunity to change the nature of the         program.
 <P>In sorting out the advantages and disadvantages of such a broad reform, are the         savings going to come from higher returns on equities as compared to the Treasury securities, or         because of a basic change in the relative amounts going to different individuals?
 And what         arrangements will be made to take care of those already drawing benefits?
        <P>The current Social Security system provides a higher benefit to those who have had a history         of lower earnings.
 Will the same balance be maintained from these new proposals?
 If there is to         be an honest debate, it is important to understand where the savings come from.
        <P>A similar issue arises with Medicare.
 Some of the proposals to restructure Medicare by         allowing individuals to choose private plans imply that savings will come from the greater         efficiency of the private sector.
 This may take place, but often these proposals establish a fixed        contribution, to be paid on behalf of beneficiaries, rising at some set percentage each year.
 That         would be the basis of the guarantee of savings to Medicare.
 If the private sector did not prove to         be more efficient, costs would simply be shifted on to the beneficiaries.
        <P>Another major type of structural change would be to limit these programs to means-tested         benefits — that is, to restrict eligibility to persons with low incomes.
 But one of the strengths of         these social insurance programs has been the stake that most Americans feel they have in both         contributing to and drawing from these programs.
 Would such changes strengthen or weaken the         programs?
        <P>And for any means-tested proposal, the details are very important indeed.
 To obtain large         amounts of savings, a new (and cumbersome) bureaucratic structure would need to be added         unless the IRS were used to administer the program essentially as a tax increase on the elderly         and disabled.
 In addition, there are not enough very high income beneficiaries to generate         savings of the level likely to be needed, so the income cutoff level might be moved lower and         lower to achieve the desired savings.
        <P>Another key question for the future is whether we will reduce the size of one of these         programs much more than the other.
 Will we decide, for example, that Social Security is the         more basic of the two programs and concentrate more efforts on cutting back on Medicare?
 This         is likely to become a major issue, although very few people have as yet addressed it as such.
        Implicitly, the 1995 political discussions that raised the spectre of $226 billion of Medicare         reductions but no change in Social Security, suggesting that some politicians have already         decided that Medicare is easier to take on.
        <P>It will be tempting as this debate proceeds for policymakers to advocate strategies as magic         bullet solutions.
 In practice, the challenge for the media will be to help balance the real         advantages and disadvantages of what are likely to be difficult choices.
                <H2>Other Key Points</H2>        <B>1.
 Closing the federal government was a tactic used during the budget debate in 1995 and1996.
</B> In this way, the Congress can block spending on appropriated programs.
 But when it         comes to entitlements, the President has more power.
 In that case, unless the Congress actively         passes legislation to change entitlements and can either get the President to agree or override a         veto, spending continues as usual.
 Thus, in the recent budget stalemate, spending was slowed by         the Congress, but all entitlement spending continued as usual.
        <P><B>2.
 Part of last year s debate centered on whether slowing the growth in a program like         Medicare constituted a “cut.
”</B> This is an extremely hard issue to assess.
 Certainly some         growth in spending is essential if eligibility is not changed, since the number of beneficiaries is         growing by about 1.
9 percent per year — or over 700,000 new beneficiaries each year.
 After         making adjustments for inflation, the original Congressional proposal would have increased real         spending by about 2.
7 percent per capita, and the Administration's initial proposal would have         allowed growth of about 3.
4 percent per year per capita.
 Projections for the private sector         indicate a likely growth of 3.
9 percent per year.
        <P><B>3.
 The trust funds for Social Security and Medicare are important early warning devices         to indicate when there is an imbalance between revenues and spending.
</B> Projections for         Medicare, for example, signal the need for legislative change in the program.
 But the recent         warnings about the trust fund's imbalance are certainly not unprecedented.
 Since 1980, eight         trustees reports have predicted exhaustion of the Medicare Part A trust fund within ten years.
         And Social Security has come much closer.
 Before implementation of the 1983 amendments,         funds were transferred from the Part A Medicare trust fund to Social Security's funding order to         keep it solvent.
 (The fund was subsequently repaid).
        <P><B>4.
 The relationship between the trust funds and the federal deficit is         complicated.
</B> Social Security and Medicare trust funds are held in the form of special         Treasury Bills of varying maturity.
 The interest payments on these funds are essentially the same         as you or I would earn on Treasury Bills of the same length to maturity.
 But since the trust fund         is thus “lending” its reserves to the federal government, those dollars are spent by the US         government to meet current obligations.
 The trust funds hold promises to pay at future dates that         must ultimately be backed by future revenues.
       
<br>
