Title: FACSNET: Promises and Pitfalls for Journalists on the Information Highway
Link: <mailto:pattimcc>; rev="Made"
</DOCHDR>
<html><head>
<title>FACSNET: Promises and Pitfalls for Journalists on the Information Highway</title>
</head>
<body>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<hr noshade size=3>
<center>
<img src="../../facsnet_grafix/report_tools/backgrounder.gif" alt="NewsBackgrounders:">
<br>
Briefing Papers for Journalists
</center>
<hr noshade size=3> <h1>Promises and Pitfalls for Journalists on the Information Highway</h1>
            <h2> </h2>
            <strong>Too often, a trip on the Internet means getting lost in cyberspace.
 Journalists in search of information, sources and background don’t have time for side trips that lead nowhere.
 FACS’s online maven, Randy Reddick, offers tips for navigating the cosmos of the web and cautions us about the dangers of unverified Internet info.
<p></strong><strong>by Randy Reddick<p></strong><TABLE CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=20> <TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG SRC= "../../facsnet_grafix/report_tools/reddick.gif" ALT = "Randy Reddick"> </TD><TD><B>Randy Reddick</B> is director of FACSNET at the Foundation for American Communications. Born into a newspaper family, he began his career as a reporter/photographer at <I>The Daily Press</I> in Paso Robles, California and became managing editor and a company vice president. He began computerizing his paper in the mid-1970s. After earning his journalism Ph.D. from Ohio University, Dr. Reddick taught at Ohio U’s E.W. Scripps School of Journalism and at Texas Tech University. He is the author of <I>The Online Journalist: Using the Internet and Other Electronic Resources</I>. He has taught online journalism to hundreds of news organizations in the United States and the United Kingdom.</TD> </TR> </TABLE><P><P>Two Massachusetts university professors associated with revolutionary causes speak of people “getting wired.
” For Timothy Leary a generation ago, getting wired meant something quite different from what it does for Nicholas Negroponte today.
 Leary spoke of a drug revolution, Negroponte of an information revolution.
 Two professors.
 Two eras.
 Two revolutions.
     <P>Today’s revolution, according to Al Gore, is “an information revolution that will change forever the way people live, work, and interact with each other.
” Centerpiece for the information revolution is something called an “Information Highway,” of which the Internet is a small portion.
 Among the people whose lives will be changed are news people of every stripe.
     <P>What does the information revolution portend for journalists?
 For those already into the revolution and using the Internet, it affects the way journalists gather information and the way they package their reports.
 It also means loss of jobs in some areas and new jobs in others.
      <H2>Packaging News Reports</H2>     <P>In the packaging realm, one World Wide Web site (www.
newslink.
org) boasts links to nearly 3000 media organization sites.
 These are traditional news organizations (newspapers, magazines, and broadcasters) that are publishing on one of several “new media,” the World Wide Web.
 Mike Reed, editor of <I>Houston Chronicle Interactive</I>, told a recent gathering of university journalism deans, “we’re making up the rules as we go.
 What works on paper does not necessarily work on the Web.
”     <P>Traditional media like newspapers, television, and radio are constrained by time and space.
 A newscast lasts only so many minutes.
 The newspaper has only so many pages.
 In a digital world, computer network servers run 24 hours a day.
 Space is virtually unlimited because of hypermedia linking and because of the low cost of mass storage (disk space).
 On the one hand, that seems to suggest less of a need for tight editing.
 On the other hand, Reed and others who have worked with hypertext publications on the World Wide Web generally agree that shorter is better, and that readers who are truly interested in a piece can easily follow any number of hypertext links to read more about the event or issue in question.
     <P>This suggests that the “infinite” news hole possible on the Internet may in fact be encouraging a couple of different kinds of writing for news stories.
 The first, is the core news piece, short and crisp.
 Second, hypertext linking encourages ready access to more complete background information — the kind of material that does not perish quickly.
 These archive pieces could be stored indefinitely.
 Thus a detailed piece, or group of pieces, on “militia groups” in general and on some specific groups could be linked to frequently updated stories on something like the bombing of the Oklahoma City Federal Building, the arrests, and trials of the suspects.
     <P>Such a story, written in several distinct modules with an eye to an interactive environment, leads to a situation in which the audience takes part in creating the story it reads.
 Six people reading the same “core” story could create for themselves six different story packages as they follow different combinations of links.
 Audience participation of another kind — direct response — has been noted by Journalists whose e-mail addresses appear with stories they have written or aired.
     <P>In any case, the unique properties of new digital media will certainly lead to a number of news packages with characteristics setting them apart from more traditional media.
 These new characteristics will demand new skills from reporters and editors alike.
     <H2>News Gathering</H2>     <P>When it comes to news gathering, many journalists find the Net to be a double-edged sword.
 On the one hand, databases and communications tools available through the Internet promise to give the net-wise journalist a great edge over those who are not “wired.
” On the other hand, the Internet is a world-wide collection of programs and documents that are poorly organized; and there are reasons to doubt the validity of net-based information.
     <P>The speed and reach of the Net offer several possibilities for journalists.
 Five of these immediately suggest themselves: Collaboration, access to distant sources, an infinite news hole, greater staying power of some news material, and greater audience participation in the news product.
 The last three were described under packaging.
 On the news gathering side of the cycle, the benefits — and the woes — of collaboration and access to sources are better known.
     <P><B>Collaboration:</B> Journalists who are already online routinely collaborate with one another.
 They do so through news groups, forums, and e-mail discussion lists.
 E-mail discussion lists sponsored by SPJ, IRE, NICAR, RTNDF and other groups and individuals provide daily exchanges among journalists.
 The “conversation” may range from how to manipulate government data files on newsroom systems to “Does anybody out there know some good sources on toxic waste?
”     <P>Several Usenet news groups starting with <I>alt.
journalism</I> also provide a place for journalists to chat about mutual concerns, and thus enable a kind of collaboration.
 The CompuServe Journalism Forum is so popular (it has had more than 10,000 members for years) that it has divided into several more specialized journalism interest groups.
 Science writers communicate with each other in one corner of the forum, sharing ideas, observations, tips, and more.
 Job listings of all kinds routinely appear as another part of the forum banter.
     <P>A couple of dangers are apparent from network collaboration.
 First, any message posted to a discussion list, newsgroup, or forum for journalists will be read by others who “inhabit” that online community.
 This means that your competition knows what you are working on.
 More sinister is the potential for “herd” journalism growing out of network collaboration.
 Because journalists tend to congregate in the same online places and read the same messages, they may wind up covering the same material and a healthy diversity of viewpoints is lost.
 In fact, media critics have observed this phenomenon in a world without Internet communications.
     <P><B>Access to sources:</B> Sources come in two formats — people and documents.
 The Internet and related online facilities can help with each.
 Electronic mail shines in several ways as a people-communicator.
 First, it is a good way to put an end to “telephone tag” with sources who are hard to reach.
 People who regularly check their e-mail respond at their convenience.
 Well-constructed e-mail “interview” questions often produce thoughtful, meaningful answers.
 And because e-mail passes the source’s words directly to the interviewer, the chance for misquoting is minimized.
 News sources who are sheltered from telephone inquiries by zealous office staff sometimes can be reached by e-mail.
 Here’s an improvement for those who wonder if telephone messages have been delivered to the intended recipient; many e-mail programs include a feature that reports back to the sender when an e-mail message has been opened.
     <P>Document sources abound on the Net.
 They include the full text of legislation, court rulings, books, poetry, background papers, scientific studies, press releases, speeches, position papers, sound and video clips, and more.
 It can be a frustrating challenge to find those documents in an environment that generally values unfettered entrepreneurship more than it does uniformity or rules.
 Weighing the credibility of documents found on the net can be even more challenging.
     <P>In the finding department, many sophisticated keyword search mechanisms are available to journalists.
 They include:<UL><LI>Yahoo, http://www.
yahoo.
com<LI>Galaxy, http:/galaxy.
einet.
net<LI>Metacrawler, http://metacrawler.
cs.
washington.
edu:8080/<LI>Inktomi, http://inktomi.
berkeley.
edu<LI>InfoSeek, http://www.
infoseek.
com/</UL><P>At any of these sites, a journalist enters terms for the computer to match, and receives some kind of listing.
 Some of these search engines will also search Gopher servers, WAIS databases, and archives stored on FTP, mail, or news servers.
 Some of these sites will also lead a journalist to still other network search engines.
     <P>A great shortcoming of many of these search tools is that they report back many irrelevant “hits.
” Learning how to construct searches and which engine to use can take time and become a matter of personal preference.
 Even when material appears to be relevant, there is always a credibility question.
     <H2>Source Credibility Dangers</H2>     <P>A science reporter for <I>The New York Times</I> did a search looking for information on predicting earthquakes.
 What looked like a lot of good material turned out to be based mostly on astrology.
 There’s a lot of great, reliable, credible information out there on the Internet, but there’s also a lot of junk.
 A few simple strategies can help.
     <P>For newsgroups, forums, and e-mail discussion lists, start by treating all information and quotes much the same as you would random interviews on the street or as a conversation overheard on the subway.
 First of all, you have no way of knowing who the person “speaking” is, what credentials he or she has, or even if the person posting the message is really who he or she says she is.
 These places are starting points only.
 They may provide leads to more substantive source material.
 In some cases, you may want to telephone the person, exchange personal e-mail messages, and take other steps to verify the source.
     <P>For documents found on the Internet, one should take similar cautions.
 Anybody can claim to represent “Scientists for Colonizing Space,” set up a server (or rent space on an existing server), load the server with authoritative looking documents, and see to it that those documents get indexed by some ofthe more popular search engines.
 There will come a day when journalists, too hurried (or too careless) to verify network sources, will give us the Internet equivalent of the Janet Cooke case.
 Again, until you have taken steps to verify that the site is maintained by credible people with credible credentials, treat it as you would any other elementary school project, fraternity prank, or scam — all of which are on the Internet.
     <P>Journalists have always had the ultimate responsibility for verifying sources, validating documents, and otherwise testing the veracity of all they report.
 That responsibility has grown in a world of global computer networks.
     <H2>FACSNET</H2>     The Foundation for American Communications, in concert with <I>The Detroit News</I> and the San Diego Supercomputer Center, has embarked on a project to create a service designed to help journalists manage Internet resources, gain quick access to documents explaining complex issues, and to find context for much of the day’s report.
 Called FACSNET, it is accessed at <B>http://www.
facsnet.
org.
</B> The site contains background papers on many public policy issues, especially those with economic or environmental impact.
 There are also “Reporting Tools” to help reporters find people and information.
 A section on “Internet Resources” provides searchable, annotated links to material organized around beats.
 The person or organization responsible for maintaining each Internet resource is identified.
 Another section of the site endeavors to identify people sources for journalists.
 These people may be scholars, government officials, or members of the private sector.
      <P>FACSNET is up and running.
 Visit it, and feel free to make suggestions.
 Watch it as it grows, and see if it doesn’t help journalists in a digital age.
         
<br>
<br>
