<html><head>
<title>FACSNET: Radiating Misinformation</title>
</head>
<body>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<hr noshade size=3>
<center>
<img src="../../facsnet_grafix/report_tools/backgrounder.gif" alt="NewsBackgrounders:">
<br>
Briefing Papers for Journalists
</center>
<hr noshade size=3> <h1>Radiating Misinformation</h1>
            <h2> </h2>
            <strong>What happens when the political reporter covers science?
 The radiation experiment story offers some troubling answers.
<p></strong><strong>by Richard Harris<p></strong><TABLE CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=20> <TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG SRC= "../../facsnet_grafix/report_tools/Harris.gif " ALT = "Richard Harris"> </TD><TD><B>Richard Harris</B> has been science correspondent for National Public Radio since 1986. Prior to that he was a science writer for <I>The San Francisco Examiner</I>. Mr. Harris is the recipient of the AAAS-Westinghouse award and Lewis Thomas award for science writing and is an officer of the National Association of Science Writers. He has a B.A. degree in biology from the University of California at Santa Cruz.</TD> </TR> </TABLE><P><P>It was a classic case study in news reporting: Americans were hearing about the dark and twisted souls of scientists of a generation gone by.
 The stories recounted “secret,” “radiation-tolerance experiments,” all done on people the Atomic Energy Commission considered disposable: prisoners, mental patients, indigents, blacks, pregnant (unmarried?
) women who were soon to give their children up for adoption.
"    <P>There was more.
 We were informed that some 800 people were involved in 600 experiments (or 600 people involved in 800 experiments, as other stories would have it).
 We learned that American scientists, apparently driven to evil deeds by the cold war, were no better than the Nazis of the Buchenwald death camp.
 If they weren't injecting lethal doses of plutonium into people (who miraculously survived), they were feeding college students atomic fallout from bomb blasts in the Nevada Desert, jamming radiation up the noses of aviators, or dropping radiation bombs on the town of Los Alamos, New Mexico.
 If ever there were a test for the science press, this was it: a story charged with emotion and based on a kernel of truth, yet a story spinning so far out of control that the challenge for many reporters was to find and tell the truth without sounding like an apologist for the scientific establishment.
    <P>It began when Eileen Welsome of the <I>Albuquerque Tribune</I> put names and faces to five of the 18 people secretly injected with plutonium during the 1940s.
 The series won a Pulitzer Prize and moved Energy Secretary Hazel O'Leary to declassify records, including some for people who had been abused in radiation experiments performed by scientists funded by the DOE's predecessor agencies.
 (For a detailed account of this history, see the March 1994 issue of the <I>American Journalism Review</I>.
)    <P>But then a funny thing happened.
 When reporters heard that as many as 800 people had been involved in research funded by the energy department s predecessors, many quickly assumed that all the experiments were equivalent to the plutonium-injection cases reported by the <I>Albuquerque Tribune</I>.
 It s instructive to see how the story unfolded in two newspapers with strikingly different approaches: <I>The Washington Post</I>, which assigned a political reporter to the story, and <I>Newsday</I>, which turned it over to the science desk.
    <P>“The <I>Post</I> was a bit slower than other publications to pick up on the story, because we had nobody covering the DOE,” said Gary Lee, who has since shifted from covering lobbyists to covering the environment and DOE at the <I>Post</I>.
 So when the <I>Boston Globe</I> broke the story about radiation experiments among children at a state institution for the mentally retarded, Lee got the radiation assignment.
    <P>Lee's take on the story was clearly one of politics and scandal, of people victimized by their own government.
 Lee keyed into the distressing fact that some experiments were conducted on vulnerable populations but he fed the myth that the victims were “all.
.
.
disposable,” as <I>Post</I> columnist Jessica Mathews put it, by writing that all the subjects of Vanderbilt University's notorious experiment with pregnant women were black.
 In fact, the original scientific publication of that study states plainly that all the subjects were white.
    <P>In another page-one blockbuster, Lee tracked down a Florida man who displayed his medical record to show that the government had shoved (radioactive) radium up his nose during his service in the Air Force.
 The man said his personality had been forever changed by this horrifying practice.
 The <I>Post</I> was satisfied to leave this story hanging right there and the information made perfect sense if one truly believed that scientists in the 1950s were driven to mad extremes by the Cold War.
    <P>But science writer Earl Lane at <I>Newsday</I> made one more phone call to an otolaryngologist.
 Lane learned and reported that radium treatments were commonly given to airmen and submariners (as well as children with adenoids) because doctors found that the radiation opened up the nasal passages and Eustachian tubes, helping the men maintain balance.
 Lane says that scientists of the era “did an awful lot of things that probably shouldn't have been done, but it was not weird science, it was medical practice.
”    <P>Lane and his colleague Laurie Garrett set out to reveal what had transpired, but also to make sense of it.
 Garrett combed through the records of Columbia University College of Physicians and Surgeons and reported the sometimes agonizing deliberations of a safety-review committee, which struggled to balance the rights of patients against the desires of scientists.
 In this view of the world, the scientists don't come off as incomprehensible lunatics, but as reasonable people one can choose to agree or disagree with.
 Lane also took the time to plow through the congressional report Rep.
 Edward Markey, D-Mass.
, released in 1986, which retold the plutonium injection study and cataloged dozens of others.
 It turns out that most of the experiments involved not only low doses of radiation but what passed for informed consent at the time.
 Not uncommonly, the subjects of these experiments included the scientists themselves.
    <P>Meanwhile, the White House issued a memorandum calling for a complete review of all “human radiation experiments,” defined so broadly that only “common and routine clinical practices” are excluded.
 If taken literally, this White House order could lead to the review of tens of thousands of experiments conducted with radioactive materials to develop new diagnostic procedures and cancer treatments and tracers used to study basic human biology.
 So far as I know, only science reporters have noted the incongruity that radiation rather than misconduct is the unifying feature of this review.
    <P>Here I must confess my own experience with the story.
 I have met dozens of scientists who routinely work with radiation and dozens more who were involved in nuclear weapons research.
 One can certainly question or second-guess their decisions and one can even accept some bad apples in the lot but my experience told me research with radiation was not overwhelmed by Mengele wannabes.
    <P>My reports for National Public Radio struggled to put the stories we were hearing into perspective rather than dwelling on any one horror story.
 I pointed out the difference between medical experiments using radiation and those few radiation-tolerance studies.
 We talked about how much risk a given dose posed (even the airmen flying through mushroom clouds incurred just one percent added lifetime risk of cancer, according to the National Academy of Sciences estimates).
    <P><I>Washington Post</I> science editor Curt Suplee says he thinks that in stories like these, political reporters tend to be less skeptical than science reporters because it s harder for them to get past emotionally charged words or concepts like radiation.
 “Part of what our readers pay us for is to be skeptical of any claim,” he says.
    <P>John Easton of the University of Chicago medical school spent a frustrating couple of months trying to cope with a flood of reporters from tabloids and infotainment TV.
 It was not Easton s regular clientele.
 “It was the biggest science story of the year, and for some reason, science reporters lay down, and political reporters who had cut their teeth on Watergate took over,” he says.
    <P>Despite the occasional calm voice in the crowd, the image of the mad scientist seems to have prevailed.
 Columnists like Meg Greenfield of <I>Newsweek</I> and Jessica Mathews at the <I>Washington Post</I> made the seemingly logical jump that the most egregious stories in the press were a representative sample of the experiments of the day.
 (They are the authors of the quotes at the beginning of this <I>NewsBackgrounder</I>.
)    <P>Before the story fades entirely from memory, the nation's editors and news directors should be considering the lessons for next time.
 Did the nation s science reporters fall down on the story, or run away for fear of appearing to be apologists for science?
 Were they muscled aside by more influential political reporters?
 Or were they simply trampled by galloping sensationalism?
 Most important: what will happen next time a major story bridges politics and science?
        <H2>Reporting Tips for Radiation Stories</H2>    <P>There are some built-in major difficulties covering a radiation-experiment study:<UL><LI>There is usually no clear evidence about the extent and quality of consent by the study subjects.
 <LI>If is difficult to gauge the degree of risk involved in these experiments.
</UL>    <P>I found it important to consult with health physicists, who can often quantify how much radiation a person was exposed to, given information about the dose of the isotopes involved.
    <P>A word of caution: there is some disagreement in the field about the hazards of radioactive materials.
 Frequently quoted experts like John Gofman and Ernest Sternglass represent extreme points of view.
 Many members of the Health Physics Society (703/790-1745) are more likely to agree with the judgment of the National Academy of Sciences, which produced reports known as the BEIR IV and BEIR V (BEIR being the Biological Effects of Ionizing Radiation, pronounced Beer).
    <P>There are four different forms of radiation capable of disrupting (ionizing) atoms: alpha, beta, gamma and neutron.
 Most experiments dealt with alpha (emitted by plutonium, for instance) and gamma, which is the most common and most penetrating form of radiation.
 Health physicists consider the intensity of these various forms of radiation before making judgments about their potential to harm.
    <P>You may read that plutonium is one of the deadliest substances known to man, but it s a myth.
 In fact the hazard isn t much different from similar substances that emit alpha particles, such as the decay products of radon gas, or the americium in your smoke detector.
    <P>Many stories trade on the fact that there is no safe dose of radiation, but perspective is important.
 Radiation exposures are measured in units called rems, or frequently millirems (thousandths of a rem).
 Most Americans aren t exposed to plutonium, but according to the National Academy's BEIR V report, here's what a typical American receives each year in other types of radiation, expressed in millirems:<UL><LI>cosmic rays from space: 27 mrem <LI>natural radioactive isotopes in body tissues: 39 mrem <LI>terrestrial sources such as isotopes in granite: 28 mrem<LI>radon gas: 2,700 mrem<LI>medical/dental x-rays: 39 mrem<LI>consumer products such as smoke detectors: 10 mrem<LI>fallout from atmospheric weapons testing: less than 1 mrem</UL><P>The occupational exposure limit in the U.
S.
 is 5,000 mrem a year.
 This number is often used as the benchmark in stories about radiation, though reporters don't always note that this applies to whole-body exposures, while some experiments delivered doses only to specific tissues.
 Radiation doses for cancer therapy can easily be one thousand times higher than the occupational limit.
    <P>The National Academy of Sciences BEIR V estimates that a typical person who receives a single, 10,000 mrem dose of gamma radiation to all organs increases his lifetime risk of cancer by 0.
8 percent.
 Of course, that risk estimate depends on a lot of factors, including a person's age and the type of radiation involved.
         
<br>
<br>
