<title>FACSNET: Economic Reporting and Two-Way Learning</title>
</head>
<body>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<hr noshade size=3>
<center>
<img src="../../facsnet_grafix/report_tools/backgrounder.gif" alt="NewsBackgrounders:">
<br>
Briefing Papers for Journalists
</center>
<hr noshade size=3> <h1>Economic Reporting and Two-Way Learning</h1>
            <h2> </h2>
            <strong>Lo and behold; Here are two economists who think that journalists have learned some economics and that economists have learned from journalists.
<p></strong><strong>by Frank Levy and Richard J. Murnane<p></strong><TABLE CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=20> <TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG SRC= "../../facsnet_grafix/report_tools/Levy.gif" ALT = "Frank Levy and Richard J. Murnane"> </TD><TD><P><B>Frank Levy</B> is the Daniel Rose Professor of Urban Economics in the Department of Urban Studies and Planning at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. Before joining M.I.T. in 1992, he taught at the University of California, Berkeley, and the University of Maryland. Professor Levy has written extensively on trends in living standards and income inequality. His book <I>Dollars and Dreams</I> is a standard reference on the development of U.S. income distribution. He and Richard Murnane co-authored <I>Teaching the New Basic Skills</I>, published by The Free Press. Dr. Levy has taught economics at FACS conferences.</TD> </TR> </TABLE><TABLE CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=20> <TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG SRC= "../../facsnet_grafix/report_tools/Murnane.gif" ALT = "Frank Levy and Richard J. Murnane"> </TD><TD><P><B>Richard J. Murnane</B> is a professor of economics at the Harvard Graduate School of Education. He has written widely about the relationship between education and the economy, about public-private school comparisons and the effects of family choice in education, and about teacher labor markets. In addition to <I>Teaching the New Basic Skills</I>, his books include <I>Who Will Teach? Policies That Matter</I>.</TD> </TR> </TABLE><P><P>In January of 1996; Louis Uchitele, an economics reporter for <I>The New York Times</I>, moderated a panel of economic journalists and economists, including one of the present authors, at the annual meeting of the American Economic Association.
 While the meeting maintained good humor; the economists offered a number of criticisms.
              <P><B>THE ECONOMISTS</B> offered a number of criticisms.
 Reporters are too quick to couch issues in terms of personalities rather than the ideas that the personalities espouse.
 Reporters are too interested in controversy and so will give great play to a provocative idea that is almost surely nonsense.
 The cure, advanced by at least some economists on the panel, was that more reporters should take courses in economic theory.
       <P><B>THE REPORTERS</B> were equally critical.
 Economists, they argued, were far too interested in writing for other economists and far too uninterested in writing for a broader audience.
 If this was their choice, the reporters argued, they were in no position to complain when their ideas were misinterpreted or ignored in situations where they might do some good.
 The cure, the reporters argued, was for economists to think far more about the public when they wrote.
       <P>One can interpret this squabble as pointing to a real problem that needs fixing.
 But the proposed solutions (reporters should learn more economics, economists should learn how to reach an audience) are unlikely to make much difference, because they conflict with strong incentives.
 Reporters write about personalities and controversies because they interest readers.
 Economists don't write for the public because status in the profession depends on technical publication in scholarly journals.
 This interpretation of the squabble implies a deep-seated problem that is difficult to solve.
 While the interpretation has some merit, it also implies a static view of the relationship between economists and economic reporting that misses a lot.
  <P>A second interpretation is that squabbles can be part of a functioning system.
 The fights between parents and a teenage child preparing to leave for college, for example, alert both parties to new issues and the need for new behaviors.
 On balance, we think that the conflicting opinions reflected on the panel represented a squabble of the second kind, in which the underlying system works fairly well.
 That system is characterized by two-way learning.
 Reporters use economists both to learn ideas new to them and to test their impressions of the world against economic theory.
 Economists use reporters and their writings to discover aspects of the world that they don't directly encounter, aspects that may provide the topics for subsequent research.
       <UL><LI>Because the two groups have such different functions, neither is particularly happy with the way the other approaches the world.
<LI>But much of the time, they complement each other fairly well.
</UL>       <P>To make our point clear, we offer two examples.
 The first begins with a January 30, 1986 Associated Press story carried in <I>The New York Times</I>.
 The article reported that the nation's nonfarm productivity had dropped at an annual rate of 1.
8 percent per year in the final quarter of 1985.
 The article discussed the productivity number along with several other numbers released on the previous day by the Bureau of Labor Statistics.
 It briefly quoted Alan Sinai and Michael Evans on the number's implication for future inflation.
 Nothing was said about the connection of productivity to living standards.
 The article ran about four column inches.
       <P>Put differently, five years after Ronald Reagan's election, supply-side thinking had made only a small dent in the economic media.
 Productivity, the long-run determinant of the nation's standard of living, is central to supply-side economics.
 But here was the latest news on productivity, buried in an AP dispatch on page 12 of the <I>Times</I> business section, with no real discussion of the number's implication.
       <P>From 1981 to 1986, reporters wrote extensively about supply-side <I>personalities</I>   Jude Wanniski, Paul Craig Roberts, and others.
 They wrote about the supply-siders' largest claims, for example the idea that tax cuts would spur growth to the point of being self-financing.
 They also reported the argument that reduced taxes would increase savings, which would more than offset any additional government deficit.
 Most reporters did not make the basic connections among investment and technology, productivity, and people's incomes   the core of supply-side thinking.
       In the language of a memorable Herb Stein <I>Wall Street Journal</I> column, the media had absorbed "punk" (as in outlandish or attention grabbing) supply-side but they had not absorbed regular supply-side.
       <P>This should not surprise us.
 On the economist's yellow pad, these connections come together neatly.
 From a journalist's perspective, they span a disparate range, from the factory floor, engineering calculations and census numbers, to purchases of plants and equipment.
 And yet, a decade later most economic journalists make these connections as a matter of course.
 Articles on productivity automatically refer to living standards.
 Equally important, reporters are now freer to investigate the sources of productivity growth: case studies of the implementation of new processes and other looks inside the black box of technical change.
 Among newspapers, <I>The Wall Street Journal</I> is far ahead in such writing, but other newspapers and business magazines are making much greater effort in these areas.
 The reason is straightforward: Once technology and productivity were connected to wages and living standards, they became of interest to a much wider audience.
       <P>Over the past 10 years, then, the press has had its own supply-side revolution in which the structure of production has gained more equal footing with the traditional focus onthe rates of unemployment and inflation.
 When they hand out the revolutionary medals, economists can take some credit.
 Beginning in the early 1980s, a growing stream of economic writing made reporters aware of the stagnation of real incomes, a less-than-obvious subject to those who are used to writing in nominal dollars.
       <P>The knowledge that real incomes were stagnant naturally led to questions of causality.
 In that regard, certain economics writing stood out: the superb essays in the National Bureau of Economic Research volume <I>The American Economy in Transition</I> (edited by Martin Feldstein), and the writings on productivity of various Brookings Institution economists, including Martin Baily and Barry Bosworth.
 But many more economists were involved in a general process of educating the press.
 [The FACS economics programs for journalists and sessions run by universities played a role.
] For example, economists were able to explain to reporters that the primary cause of the post-1973 decline in the rate of productivity growth could not have been a decline in the quality of American education because the productivity decline was too precipitous to blame on relatively slow-moving changes in the quality of the work force.
 Moreover, the rate of productivity growth also fell in other countries where student test scores did not decline.
       <P>In the case of earnings inequality, the learning went in the opposite direction.
 At the beginning of the 1980s, few economists regarded inequality as an interesting subject.
 The few who followed the numbers knew that while inequality declined during the 1950s and 1960s, the decline stopped during the 1970s.
 But the subsequent increase did not appear to be large and, in any case, some increase in inequality could be expected from the entrance into the work force of the large baby-boom cohorts.
 In 1982, Martin Dooley and Peter Gottschalk published a technically sound article demonstrating that inequality was increasing andthe increaseswere not attributable to the baby boom.
 But the article failed to get much attention.
1       <P>While the links among investment, productivity and incomes played to the economists' advantage, developing inequality played to the journalists' advantage.
 From an economist's perspective, investigating inequality means analyzing data tapes like the Current Population Survey, which become available with a considerable lag.
 A reporter is free to write about the events contained in the tapes, as those events happen.
       <P>During the early 1980s, the recession and an overvalued dollar put significant pressure on US manufacturing to restructure.
 In the process, many unionized high-wage jobs were lost.
 Reporters could write about "the Rust Belt" as the rust belt was being created.
 As these stories continued to roll in, some reporters began to create a broader picture.
 Again, certain articles stand out.
 An early example was Robert Kuttner's influential "The Declining Middle" in <I>The Atlantic Monthly</I> (July 1983).
 Equally important was David Wessel's 1986 page one story in <I>The Wall Street Journal</I>, a newspaper not previously known for its interest in the subject.
       All of these articles contained large numbers of anecdotes.
 They were, in effect, case studies or collections of case studies.
 As economists are quick to argue, one or two case studies don't "prove" anything.
       <P>The economists' point is well taken and the first attempt to generalize from these case studies proved to be wrong.
 This was the theory of US "deindustrialization," according to which workers were losing high-paying manufacturing jobs and taking low-paying service-sector jobs, the cure being an expansion of manufacturing.
 By the end of the 1980s, economists' research would establish that the primary process at work was something different: a rising return to education that led to falling earnings among less-educated men within manufacturing and within services.
 But in the early 1980s, most economists were looking at other topics.
 They turned to inequality largely because the stream of articles on "the vanishing middle class" whetted appetites to see if the issue was real.
 Reporters can argue that the country could not afford to wait until economist "discovered" the issue.
       <P>The process by which journalists educate economists continues most clearly today in the case of income volatility.
 A growing number of reporters are exploring what appears to be increased year-to-year income fluctuations.
 An example is a week-long series of articles in <I>The New York Times</I> in March 1996 on the consequences of corporate down-sizing.
 There are, however, no more than one or two serious academic articles on the subject of income volatility, and economists as a group are not yet interested.
 Stay tuned.
       <P>In describing this process, we do not mean to say that the state of economic journalism is perfect.
 Most reporters still want a page-one byline, and a page-one byline requires a snappy idea.
 Too often, the snappiest of economic ideas can be debunked in five minutes by a good economist.
 That is why, in these cases, many reporters will write up the idea without calling the good economist in the first place.
 On the other side, few good economists express their ideas and evidence in non-technical writing and not all are skilled at explaining to reporters what their ideas really mean.
       <P>On the whole, however, the process works reasonably well.
 Consider how the subjects of both economic journalism and economists' research have changed over the past decade.
 Reports on tax cut proposals today are much more likely than they were a decade ago to describe the possible impacts on investment and productivity and to criticize overblown claims that the cuts are self-financing.
 That is largely thanks to economics research evaluating the consequences of tax cuts during the 1980s.
 At the 1996 National Bureau of Economics Research summer labor economics workshop, seven papers were presented on topics related to earnings inequality.
 This growing cottage industry of activity was catalyzed in inequality stories in the news.
 Tax cuts and earnings inequality; just two examples that illustrate how two-way learning has advanced the work of economists and economics reporters.
       <P><I>In a slightly different version, this article appeared in the Summer 1996 issue of "Jobs & Capital" a publication of the Milken Institute.
 FACS is grateful for permission to use it.
</I>        
<br>
