Title: FACSNET: Reporting from the Environmental Frontier
Link: <mailto:pattimcc>; rev="Made"
</DOCHDR>
<html><head>
<title>FACSNET: Reporting from the Environmental Frontier</title>
</head>
<body>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<hr noshade size=3>
<center>
<img src="../../facsnet_grafix/report_tools/backgrounder.gif" alt="NewsBackgrounders:">
<br>
Briefing Papers for Journalists
</center>
<hr noshade size=3> <h1>Reporting from the Environmental Frontier</h1>
            <h2>Environmental protection goes international, loaded with delicate complexity and enormous risk.</h2>
            <strong> <p></strong><strong>by Frances Cairncross<p></strong><TABLE CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=20> <TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG SRC= "../../facsnet_grafix/report_tools/frances_cairncross.gif " ALT = "Frances Cairncross"> </TD><TD><B>Frances Cairncross</B> has spent most of her journalism career explaining complicated economic ideas in comprehensible, interesting ways. She did that with great skill in her most recent book, <I>Costing the Earth</I>, published in the U.S. by Harvard Business School Press. Ms. Cairncross received a B.A. in history from St. Anne s College, Oxford University, and an M.A. in economics from Brown University. She is the Environment Editor of <I>The Economist</I>. This <I>NewsBackgrounder</I> was edited from a talk to a FACS journalism conference on global environmental issues.</TD> </TR> </TABLE><P><P>When we report stories on the environment, it seems to me we need this clear perspective: Environmental issues that really matter in the world today are not happening in the rich countries.
 The environment doesn t kill very many people in your country and mine.
 People don t actually die of acid rain, and they don t often die of toxic waste.
    <P>On the other hand, in developing countries people die in the thousands, in the millions even, of what are in effect environmental problems.
 They die from drinking filthy water, they die from inhaling the fumes from cooking fires in little huts.
 They suffer respiratory diseases because they have coal-fired power stations that have none of the pollution controls that we now consider to be normal.
    <P>Very simply   too simply for most of you   all these environmental problems tend to arise because people get something for nothing.
 People are able to impose some of the costs of their activities on the rest of society, or on posterity.
 And factories pollute knowing that the true costs of discharging filthy water into their nearest river will not be carried by them   they will be carried by the people who live downstream, or the people who have to clean up the mess afterwards.
    <P>The environment is an area that inescapably needs government intervention, but as international issues become more important, we ve become more conscious of the limited number of ways we can influence what happens to environmental policy in other countries.
 In the international arena there is no world government, there is no body that can step in and say you must carry the full costs of your actions.
 Countries must come to an international environmental agreement.
 That s all that s open to us.
    <P>The number of agreements signed every decade has been rising.
 Between 1940 and 1959, the U.
S.
 apparently signed just two.
 Between 1960 and 1979 there were ten.
 In the 1980 s alone, there were eleven.
    <P>But international agreements are fragile instruments.
 They will work <I>only</I> if countries are better off because they take part in them.
 And there s a constant problem of preventing free riders, countries that want to enjoy the benefits without doing their share of the work.
 How do you keep them on board?
 How do you stop countries from cheating?
 All the negotiation of international agreements is basically designed to try to find ways of solving this problem.
    <P>Governments have very few weapons to use against countries which break international agreements.
 You can hold them up to shame and ridicule.
 That worked effectively with Britain, when Britain was being recalcitrant about cutting its output of sulfur dioxide.
 The other EC nations labeled Britain the "Dirty Man of Europe.
" Or, as one British minister kept saying by mistake, the "Dirty Old Man of Europe.
" But basically, there are only two tactics.
 You can bribe, or you can bully.
    <P>Bribery makes a great deal of sense in some ways, but it s also a very difficult trick to pull off for at least two reasons.
 One, it increases the costs to the rich countries of signing any international agreement.
 Two, it s often extremely hard to know who you should give this money to.
    <P>That really leaves bullying, and bullying means trade sanctions.
 It is no accident that the Montreal Protocol, which many people regard as the most successful international environmental agreement in recent years, contains fairly tough trade sanctions designed to be used against countries that continue to use CFC s.
    <P>Getting countries to agree to sanctions like those is extremely difficult, which is why I think we will see far fewer agreements.
 The international meetings will be hard work and not headline grabbing.
    <P>It will also become increasingly apparent how complicated it will be to finish negotiation of some treaties.
 A lot of people felt that after Brazil the greenhouse treaty and the planet convention were signed and finished.
 Not so.
 The next ten years at least are going to be taken up with officials trying to work out all the answers to the questions that really matter.
 How do you know the baseline?
 How do you monitor what s happened to the targets?
 Which gases are included?
 Which gases aren t going to be included?
 How are you going to measure the relativities of those gases?
 And all the time, the science will be changing, and making the picture look more muddled.
    <P>Certainly China, which is sitting on perhaps a third of the world s known coal reserves, will be very reluctant to do very much to make that agreement work.
 Without the cooperation of the large energy producers, it s very hard to think how it will all come together.
    <P>There are tremendous difficulties involved in monitoring international agreements, and these will become more of a worry the more these agreements are asked to do.
 It s hard enough, when you re dealing with nuclear nonproliferation treaties, to send a team of U.
N.
 inspectors into Saddam Hussein s Iraq, or into North Korea, to try to find out what s happening to the bombs.
 You just try to imagine sending a team of inspectors into Brazil to try to find out what s happening to the trees.
 Or into India to try to find out what s happening to energy consumption.
 I shouldn t think they would emerge for a hundred years.
    <P>Trade and environmental policy are truly closely entwined.
 The crucial question with trade is this: In what circumstances does one country have the right to impose its environmental standards on others?
 It s a very difficult question.
 There are some perfectly good reasons why environmental standards differ from one country to another.
<UL><LI><B>Differences in levels of wealth.
</B> If you have children dying of measles and diarrhea, does it really make sense to make your environmental investment in an American style toxic waste clean up plant?
 Shouldn t you first just put in a bit of plain, ordinary sewage treatment, for example?
<LI><B>Differences of geography.
</B> The British have a lot of handy clay-lined brick pits out of which they dug the bricks that have built the midlands and London.
 And those brick pits are pretty impermeable.
 There is no reason why Dutch standards on landfills, which are so high that there is nowhere to put a scrap of rubbish from one end of Holland to the other, should also be applied in Britain, which actually disposes of quite a lot of Holland s rubbish for it.
 <LI><B>Differences in national priorities.
</B> Americans think it s funny, but the British get extremely excited about anything to do with birds.
 By far the most powerful environmental society in Britain is the Royal Society for the Protection of Birds.
 It campaigns very effectively.
 Meanwhile, the Germans go around shooting birds.
 They don t care.
 They don t think there s anything wrong with that.
 These are just differences in national attitudes.
</UL>    <P>The General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT) deals with these differences by drawing a distinction between two kinds of local environmental laws.
 GATT tends to say:<UL><LI>Each country can impose whatever domestic product standards it likes, as long as they re applied equally to imports and domestic producers.
<LI>No country can discriminate against products just because it does not approve of the process by which they are made.
</UL>    <P>If a country is clearly trying to use a product standard as a way of keeping out other countries  products, then the GATT doesn t much like it.
 There haven t yet been many cases of that.
 My guess is that one will come within the next few years, probably the German standards on recycling rubbish.
    <P>GATT does not allow a country to bar products that are made by processes that it disapproves of if those products look exactly like products that are made by processes that it does approve of.
 A pair of trousers made in a sweat shop look exactly the same as a pair made by union workers.
 There is no visible distinction, and therefore you can t discriminate against one productjust because you don t like the way it s made.
    <P>That point causes many problems for environmentalists.
 You see, for an environmentalist, a product is really intrinsically different if it is made in an environmentally unfriendly way.
 A chair made out of a piece of unsustainably managed tropical timber is intrinsically in some sense a different product than one that s made from a tree farmed in a proper environmentally friendly way.
 There is no way now, apart from eco-labeling, that the rules of world trade allow environmentalists this discrimination that they passionately feel.
    <P>I think that in looking for solutions, there is one guiding rule, which is absolutely essential to follow.
 We should ask first, do we really want to solve a problem, or do we just want to make a big fuss?
    <P>For instance, my impression is that American fishers who caught tuna in dolphin-unfriendly ways were driven out of the American market by the simple and perfectly legitimate device of environmental labeling, long before the American federal government was taken to court by the Earth Island Institute.
    <P>If environmentalists really wanted to get Mexicans to fish in a way that didn t kill dolphins, it would have been a great deal cheaper to give those fishermen the kind of nets that the American fishing fleet had.
 It probably would have cost about the same as all the legal fees involved in dragging the case through the courts, and it certainly would have caused a lot less ill feeling.
    <P>Efforts to spread protectionism on the excuse that it protects dolphins or furry animals or anything else is, to my mind, thoroughly irresponsible.
 It s the sort of thing that can bring the whole temple down about our heads rather than leading us to badly needed solutions.
    <P>The world has a lot of serious problems.
 To begin to repair those problems will take the most careful kind of negotiation and cooperation among nations with widely different resources, needs and priorities.
    <P>How toovercome "greenhouse fatigue"   that look in the editor s eyes when you try to sell     yet another story on ozone depletion over the Falkland Islands.
<UL><LI>One of the delights of environmental stories is that they often have many facets.
 Try selling your story to the sports, business, or life style pages.
 One of the pleasures I ve had on <I>The Economist</I> has been getting stories into everything from the world columns right through to the books and art section at the end.
<LI>Beware of depression.
 One of the things that seems to me to have turned people off about environmentalism is the endless procession of stories about extinction and toxic waste, and things getting worse and dirtier.
 We have done too much to sell what can t be solved.
 We haven t done enough writing about projects and companies (for those who are not too puritanical) which are genuinely making an attempt to say "good for you, let s have more like that.
"<LI>Remember that you are not necessarily a paid-up member of the environmental community.
 Journalists must not allow themselves to be captured if they are to be credible.
 It s particularly difficult for environmental journalists, who often are made to feel that they are heretical members of some extraordinarily powerful church.
 But we ve all got to do it to keep our independence.
<LI>Finally, beware of bandwagons.
 Particularly scientific bandwagons.
 This is a hard one to follow, particularly for somebody like me, who doesn t have scientific training.
 But we have to pause and question, even when 99 scientists assure one that some environmental peril or other is for real.
</UL>         
<br>
<br>
<center>
<a href="http://www.facsnet.org/navigation.map">
