Title: FACSNET: Will You Make More Money Tomorrow than You Do Today?
Link: <mailto:pattimcc>; rev="Made"
</DOCHDR>
<html><head>
<title>FACSNET: Will You Make More Money Tomorrow than You Do Today?</title>
</head>
<body>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<hr noshade size=3>
<center>
<img src="../../facsnet_grafix/report_tools/backgrounder.gif" alt="NewsBackgrounders:">
<br>
Briefing Papers for Journalists
</center>
<hr noshade size=3> <h1>Will You Make More Money Tomorrow than You Do Today?</h1>
            <h2>The economic lowdown on why America s standard of living has hit the wall.</h2>
            <strong> <p></strong><strong>by Barry Bosworth<p></strong><B>Barry Bosworth</B> is a senior fellow in economic studies at the Brookings Institution in Washington, D.C. From August 1977 to August 1979 he was director of the Council on Wage and Price Stability. He is a former faculty member of Harvard University and the University of California at Berkeley. Dr. Bosworth s undergraduate degree and Ph.D. in economics are from the University of Michigan. This <I>NewsBackgrounder</I> was adapted from a talk by Dr. Bosworth at the sixth annual FACS <I>Institute on Economics for Journalists</I>.<P><P>Consider a fact that clashes with popular perception: the United States economy is a job machine.
 By an enormous margin, we have had the fastest growing employment of any of the industrial countries around the world.
 If there s one thing the United States is good at, it s creating jobs   an 80-percent increase in employment since 1960.
 Surprising as it may seem, Europe has had essentially no growth in jobs for over 30 years; total private sector employment in Europe is actually lower today than it was in 1960.
   <P>But while the U.
S.
 was creating all those jobs, we ve been much less successful in raising wages.
 Since 1965, wages in Japan have almost tripled.
 In Europe, they ve almost doubled.
 And the United States?
 The average wage of a typical American worker adjusted for inflation is essentially the same as it was in 1970.
   <P>That s a rather remarkable result in a society that got used to thinking that tomorrow was going to be better than today.
 We believed that our children were going to live better than we do, for the same reason that we live better than our parents did.
 When you compare the historical trend up to the 1970s, the average American worker s income adjusted for inflation would go up two and a half to three percent every single year.
   <P>I think this leveling off of wages has a lot to do with complaints over taxes.
 Many Americans have the impression that their taxes are going up rapidly.
 In reality, for over twenty years taxes as a percentage of income have not changed.
 When did taxes go up in the United States dramatically?
 In the 1960s.
 Why don t people remember that from the 60s?
 Who cared?
 We thought, my income s going up two and a half to three percent a year, on average.
 So the federal government takes another half of a percentage point for increased Social Security taxes or Medicare program   I still have much more income left over.
 But the moment your income stagnates and the government tries to take a little bit more, they re not asking you to reduce the rate at which you increase your living standard, they re asking you to reduce your living standard.
 That s a lot more painful, and has been very hard for people to do.
   <H2>Socioeconomic Revolution</H2>   <P>When the average wage of a typical American worker began to level out in the early 1970 s, a socioeconomic revolution occurred in this country   the movement to dual earner families.
 If you couldn t earn more money per worker, just throw more workers out into the work force.
 We have now gone to a society in which the typical American family has two earners, not one.
   <P>This huge change camouflaged the effect on our standard of living.
 For almost two decades it meant we could sustain the growth in average family incomes despite the fact that the average worker wasn t making more.
 Now that s come to an end.
 Women are working almost as much as men, and there s really no room to keep on increasing family income by throwing more workers per family out there.
   <P>Some other striking facts:<UL><LI>For adult males in the lowest fifth of the wage distribution, real wages have fallen 25 percent in a twenty-year period.
 That is an enormous decline for anyone to have experienced   characteristic of a depression.
<LI>The lowest fifth of black males lost even more than white males.
 And the top fifth of black males gained a little bit more than white males.
 Black female workers did almost exactly the same as white female workers.
<LI>In 1969 the typical female worker earned two thirds of what the average American male worker earned; by 1989 she had closed only to 75 percent of the earnings of the average male worker.
<LI>We all know that there is a tremendous increase in the number of women who are single parents.
 And we know it s very hard for a female worker with children not to be in poverty.
<LI>It appears that men and women seeking a spouse consider economics more than they used to, so that men at the top of the wage distribution are more likely than in the past to marry women at the top of the wage distribution, tugging up the top family income.
</UL>   <H2>Haves and Have Nots</H2>   <P>No matter how you separate the data, you re left with the striking result that the whole wage distribution in the United States is pulling apart.
 We are dividing into what almost might be called a dual income economy: half of us doing better than ever before and half of us doing worse than ever before.
 It has enormous social repercussions.
   <P>When the pie doesn t expand, you start fighting over its distribution, and in the United States, we don t handle distributional issues well.
 If you start to get to the point where more than half the population doesn t benefit from the system any more, then you start to tear apart.
 The belief in the economic system used to be the one fundamental thing that kept all Americans together.
   <H2>The Productivity Key</H2>   <P>Why are wages not growing the way they used to?
 There s only one way to increase the income of all of us.
 We must produce more per worker.
 American workers are not increasing their productivity.
   <P>From the end of World War II to about 1972, the productivity of an American worker increased about two-and-a-half to three percent a year, after adjusting for inflation.
 Since 1972, it s been about eight-tenths of one percent per year.
 Fringe benefit changes essentially canceled out that small growth.
 Social Security taxes and health care cost more, while pension contributions cost less.
 Pension funds have begun to evaporate, with far fewer American companies contributing.
   <P>Economists wouldn t claim that we know all the reasons that the productivity slowdown occurred.
 We know it happened around the world, but it doesn t hurt in other countries as much as in the United States, where productivity was already much lower.
 For instance, in Japan, annual productivity growth used to be 10 percent and now it s dropped to five.
   <P>But, even though we don t know all the reasons, there are clearlythree fundamental driving factors making U.
S.
 productivity growth wither:<P><B>Capital per worker.
</B> If you build a highway with a Caterpillar tractor, you re going to be a lot better off than people who are still trying to do it with a bushel basket and a shovel.
 Americans used to have more capital per worker than any country in the world, and that was the biggest distinguishing feature between an American worker and a Japanese or a European worker.
 That simply isn t true anymore.
<P><B>We have the lowest rate of saving and investment of any industrial country in the world.
</B> Europeans have always saved and invested more than Americans, but historically they ve then blown everything up and have had to start all over again.
 The U.
S.
 gained a higher standard of living in comparison with Europe, because of a series of wars, peaking with World War II.
<P><B>Improved technology.
</B> The United States used to lead the world in the amount of resources we devoted to research and development.
 We are now in the middle of the pack, and we devote most of our resources to very few industries.
 Traditionally much of our national R&D ran through the Department of Defense.
 The end of the cold war leaves health research and the space program as the major national R&D programs.
<P><B>Better education.
</B> We were the first country to think of generalized education for everybody   not a great education, but a basic education.
 The Asians set up education systems that look like those of the United States and we re now competing with the graduates of those systems.
 It is amazing to Americans to find out that the educational level in Korea is about the same as in the United States today.
 Japan is better educated by almost every measure.
   <P>Worldwide, high-skill workers are in great demand.
 But what about the person with a high school degree or less?
 The truth is, they re a dime a dozen.
 Old technology was the assembly line.
 Break tasks into small, simple steps, do them repetitively andthrow capital at them.
 The education we gave American workers made them perfectly suited for that.
 Now nobody wants exactly the same product as anyone else and we can t create enough product variety on a standard assembly line.
 More and more we just eliminated those sorts of workers, replaced them with machines and skilled workers.
 I m not going to turn over a ten million dollar machine to some guy who can t read.
 Mexico s not stealing their jobs.
 Their jobs are just disappearing; it s the nature of technological change.
   <H2>A Grim Outlook</H2>   <P>So in all three dimensions that economists can identify as crucial to improvement in the average standard of living, Americans do worse than they did in the past.
 If you don t invest anything in the future, sooner or later the future s going to look pretty grim.
    <P>Typical Americans are waking up and realizing that their family income isn t what it was.
 The stagnation of the average real wage has become a major issue driving the economy.
 Some economists are more optimistic, but I think standards of living are not likely to improve.
 Unless trends change, I think, realistically, our children will probably live a little bit worse than we do.
   <H3>Long-term Unemployment</H3>   <P>The United States has avoided the large increases in unemployment that currently plague the European economies.
 In the 1960s European unemployment rates were well below those of the U.
S.
, but in recent years they have averaged more than ten percent of the workforce.
 Long-term unemployment, defined as the proportion of the workforce unemployed over a year, is particularly severe at four percent.
 The rate here is one tenth as high.
   <P>The probability of being unemployed during the year in the U.
S.
 is ten times that of Europe, but the duration of a spell of unemployment is one tenth as long.
   <P>Why the difference?
 Europe has a very rigid labor market with many restrictions on firms' ability to lay off workers.
 Knowing that, firms are reluctant to hire workers on a temporary basis.
 Furthermore, many European economies provide very generous unemployment insurance benefits for several years.
 In contrast, in the United States there are few restrictions on discharging workers, less than one third of the unemployed receive unemployment benefits, the benefits are a low share of prior wage and benefits and last for a relatively brief time.
 In effect, the U.
S.
 system forces the unemployed to return to the labor market even if that means accepting a reduced wage, whereas with more generous subsidies, European workers can afford to be more choosy in accepting a new job.
   <P>Which is the better system?
 We both face a growing mismatch of skills between workers and available jobs.
 The choice is to be unemployed in Europe or one of the working poor in the United States.
 Neither sounds like an answer.
   <H3>Have Wages Dropped?
</H3>   <P>You will sometimes hear people say that average hourly earnings of production workers in the United States have fallen by about 18 or 20 percent in the last 20 years.
 That is simply an artifact of a particular statistical series the government publishes.
 They really should stop publishing it.
 It is known to be severely biased in its measure of wages.
 It s not reflected in any other wage measure.
   <P>Organized labor loves to cite it, because it appears that workers are somehow being cheated.
 But all the analysis suggests that it s just an inaccurate measure of wages.
   <P>I think it is correct to say that real income   real wages   have stagnated in the United States.
 To say they ve declined is a bit of an exaggeration.
         
<br>
<br>
<center>
<a href="http://www.facsnet.org/navigation.map">
