Title: FACSNET: Covering the Internet
Link: <mailto:pattimcc>; rev="Made"
</DOCHDR>
<html><head>
<title>FACSNET: Covering the Internet</title>
</head>
<body>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<hr noshade size=3>
<center>
<img src="../../facsnet_grafix/report_tools/backgrounder.gif" alt="NewsBackgrounders:">
<br>
Briefing Papers for Journalists
</center>
<hr noshade size=3> <h1>Covering the Internet</h1>
            <h2>Does Your Economic Thinking Compute?</h2>
            <strong>This <I>NewsBackgrounder</I> is a set of frequently asked questions and answers about the economic, institutional and technological structure of the Internet.
 Jeffrey MacKie-Mason of the University of Michigan and Hal Varian of UC Berkeley discuss some of the Internet's pressing economic problems and speculate how best to solve them.
<p></strong><strong>by Jeffrey K. MacKie-Mason and Hal R. Varian<p></strong><B>Jeffrey K. MacKie-Mason</B> is an associate professor of economics, information and public policy at the University of Michigan, teaching in the Department of Economics, the School of Information and the School of Public Policy. He is also a research associate at the National Bureau of Economic Research. Professor MacKie-Mason has published many papers on the economics of information technology and content, telecommunications, industrial organization and finance.


<p><B>Hal R. Varian</B> is dean of the School of Information Management and Systems at the University of California at Berkeley. He also teaches in the Haas School of Business and the Economics department. Professor Varian s current work involves the economics of information technology, including strategic technology management, the economics of intellectual property and public policy of information technology. He is a former co-editor of the <I>American Economic Review</I>.<P><H3>What is the Internet?
</H3><P>The Internet is a global network that links, through a common protocol, a worldwide set of computer networks using local protocols including Ethernet, Netware, Apple Talk, DECnet and many others.
<H3>How big is the Internet?
</H3><P>From 1985 to July 1996 the Internet grew from 1000 hosts to nearly 13 million.
 A host is a computer through which Internet users go to get on the net.
 In some cases, thousands of users' computers go through one host.
 That leads to speculation that there may be 100 million Internet users, more or less.
<H3>Who runs the Internet?
</H3><P>The short answer is  no one.
  The Internet is a loose amalgamation of computer networks run by many organizations in more than 70 countries.
 Most of the technological decisions are made by small committees of volunteers who set standards for the interoperation of those networks.
<H3>Is the Internet different from telephone networks?
</H3><P>Yes and no.
 Most backbone and regional network traffic moves over leased phone lines, so at a low level the technology is the same.
 Phone networks, however, use circuit switching; an end-to-end circuit must be set up before the call can begin.
 A fixed share of network resources is reserved for the call, and no other call can use those resources until the original connection is closed.
 A long silence between two teenagers uses the same resources as an active negotiation between two fast-talking lawyers.
 One advantage of circuit-switching is that it enables performance guarantees such as guaranteed maximum delay, which is essential for real-time applications like voice conversations.
 It is also much easier to do detailed accounting for circuit-switched network usage.
<P>By contrast, the Internet uses  packet switching.
  The term  packet  refers to the fact that the data stream from your computer is broken into packets of about 200 bytes (on average), which are then sent out onto the network.
 Each packet contains a  header  with information necessary for routing the packet from origination to destination.
 Thus, each packet in a data stream is independent.
<P>The main advantage of packet-switching is that packets from many different sources can share a phone line, allowing for efficient use of the fixed capacity.
 With current technology, packets are generally accepted onto the network on a first-come, first-served basis.
 If the network becomes overloaded, packets are delayed or discarded.
<H3>What types of Internet pricing schemes are used?
</H3><P>Until recently, nearly all users faced the same pricing structure for Internet use.
 A fixed-bandwidth connector was charged an annual fee, which allowed for unlimited use up to the physical maximum flow rate (bandwidth).
 We call this  connection pricing.
  Most connection fees were paid by organizations, including universities and government agencies.
 Individual users paid nothing.
<P>Because nearly all use of the Internet is unpriced at the margin, organizations pay a fixed fee in exchange for unlimited access within their technical capacity.
 This creates an incentive to  overuse.
  The incentive exists because a packet-switched network is a shared-media technology.
 Each extra packet that Sue User sends imposes a cost on all other users because the resources Sue is using are not available to them.
 The cost can come in the form of delay or lost (dropped) packets.
 Because the price she pays for the extra packets is zero, Sue has an incentive to ignore such costs.
<P>Without an incentive to economize on use, congestion can become quite serious.
 Indeed, because of the tremendously wide range of usage rates, the problem is more serious for data networks than for many other congestible resources.
 At a given moment on a highway, for example, a single user is more or less limited to putting either one or no cars on the road.
 In a data network, however, one user at a modern work station can send a few bytes of e-mail or put on the network a load of hundreds of megabits per second (Mbps).
 Today, any undergraduate with a new Macintosh is able to plug in a digital video camera and transmit live videos to another campus or home to mom, demanding as much as one Mbps.
 Because the maximum throughput on current backbones is only 100 Mbps, it is clear that even a few users with relatively inexpensive equipment could bring the network to its knees.
<H3>What non-price mechanisms can be used for congestion control?
</H3><P>For economists, the most obvious approach is to charge some sort of congestion price.
 However, so far, there has been almost no serious consideration of congestion pricing for backbone services.
 Even tentative proposals for usage pricing have met strong opposition.
 We will discuss pricing below, but first we examine some non-price mechanisms that have been proposed.
<P>Many participants in congestion discussions suggest that peer pressure can control congestion costs.
 A weakness of peer pressure, however, is that it may be effective only after a user has caused a serious disruption.
 Peer pressure is unlikely to reduce congestion caused by novice users who do not understand the impact of their actions.
 As network access becomes ubiquitous, there will be an ever-increasing number of such novice users who employ applications capable of causing severe congestion.
 Moreover, peer pressure is likely to be quite ineffective against malicious users who want to cause network congestion.
<P>A completely different approach to reducing congestion, overprovisioning, is purely technological.
 Overprovisioning means maintaining network capacity that is sufficient to support peak demands without noticeably degrading service.
 This has been the most important anti-congestion mechanism used in the Internet.
 However, overprovisioning is costly.
 With both very-high-bandwidth applications and near-universal access fast approaching, it may become too costly.
 In simple terms, will capacity demand grow faster than the decline in capacity cost?
<P>A third non-priceapproach to controlling congestion is to have users declare how much bandwidth, what maximal delay and what type of delay variation they require for a given session, and allocate those resources to them.
 Because of different resource requirements, network efficiency can be increased if different types of traffic are treated differently.
 This means giving minimum delay guarantees to real-time video sessions, which can tolerate only minor delays, but not to routine e-mail or file transfers that can more easily tolerate delay.
 In order to do that, however, the user must truthfully indicate what type of traffic he or she is sending.
 If real-time video bit streams get the highest quality service, why not claim that all of your bit streams are real-time video?
<H3>Why should pricing be taken seriously for congestion control?
</H3><P>Pricing approaches have the overwhelming advantage that they permit users to express the value that they place on obtaining network services.
 Thus, pricing directly provides the information needed during times of congestion to allocate scarce resources to those users who value them most.
 There is no need to assign arbitrary priorities or to force high-value users to suffer from being stuck in a line behind low-value users.
<H3>How might prices be used to control congestion?
</H3><P>The basic problem is that when the network is near capacity, a user's incremental packet imposes costs on other users in the form of delay or dropped packets.
 Our scheme for internalizing this cost is to impose a price on use that is determined by the congestion the use creates.
 We call this a  smart market.
 <P>The basic idea is simple.
 When the network is uncongested, as it most often is, the price for use should be zero.
 When the network is congested, packets are queued and delayed.
 The current queuing scheme is first-in, first out.
 We propose instead that packets should be prioritized based on the value that the user puts on getting the packet through quickly.
 To dothat, each user assigns her packets a bid measuring her willingness to pay for immediate servicing.
 At congested routers, packets are prioritized based on bids.
 In order to make incentive the key to the scheme, users are not charged the price they bid.
 They are charged the bid of the lowest priority packet that is admitted to the network.
 It is well known in economics that this mechanism provides the right incentive for truthful revelation.
<P>This scheme has a number of nice features.
 In particular, not only do those with the highest cost of delay get served first, but the prices also send the right signals for capacity expansion in a competitive market for network services.
 If all of the congestion revenues are reinvested in new capacity, then capacity will be expanded to the point where its marginal value is equal to its marginal cost.
<H3>How large would congestion prices be?
</H3><P>Assuming 20 million users, we estimate that full cost recovery of the Internet would result in an average bill of no more than 50 cents per user each month.
 This estimated cost is so small because the technology is so efficient; packet-switching allows for cost-effective use of existing lines and switches.
 If everyone sent only ASCII e-mail, the Internet would probably never have congestion problems.
 However, new applications are creating huge demands for additional bandwidth.
 A video e-mail message could easily use 9000 more bytes (where a byte corresponds to one ASCII character) than a plain-text e-mail with the  same  information content.
 Providing this amount of incremental bandwidth could be quite expensive.
 Well designed congestion prices would not charge everyone the average cost of this incremental bandwidth.
 Instead, users whose demands created the congestion would pay for the needed additional capacity.
<H3>What are the problems associated with Internet accounting?
</H3><P>One of the first necessary steps for implementing usage-based pricing is to measure and account for use.
 Accounting poses some serious problems.
 For one thing, packet service is inherently ill-suited to detailed usage accounting because every packet is independent.
 As an example, a one-minute phone call in a circuit-switched network requires one accounting entry in the usage database.
 In a packet network, that one-minute phone call would require around 2500 average-sized packets.
 Complete accounting for every packet would then require about 2500 entries in the database.
 Maintaining detailed accounting by the packet, similar to phone company accounting, may be too expensive.
<P>Another accounting problem concerns tracing traffic to users.
 Certainly, if the purpose of accounting is to charge prices as incentives, those incentives will be most effective if they affect the person making the decision to use or not to use.
 But the network is, at best, capable of reliably identifying only the originating host computer, just as phone networks identify only the phone number, not the caller.
 Another layer of expensive and complex authorization and accounting software will be required on the host computer in order to track which user accounts are responsible for which packets.
 Imagine, for instance, trying to account for student e-mail at a large public computer cluster.
<P>The higher the level of aggregation, the less costly accounting is likely to be.
 For example, information could be tabulated on use by each of the subnetworks connected to the Internet backbone.
 Whether accounting at lower levels of aggregation is worthwhile is a different question that depends importantly on low-cost saving innovations in accounting methods.
<P>However Internet pricing schemes develop, journalists will be called upon to explain them to the public.
 We hope that this brief overview will help them to think of these issues in terms of economic analysis.
<BR><P>The original article upon which this <I>Backgrounder</I> is based appeared in the Summer 1994 issue of <I>The Journal of Economic Perspectives</I>.
 The Internet version can be found at: http://sims.
berkeley.
edu/~/hal/resources/infoecon/background        
<br>
<br>
