HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: WN/1.14.6
Date: Wed, 15 Jan 1997 19:04:49 GMT
Last-modified: Thu, 09 Jan 1997 21:18:29 GMT
Content-type: text/html
Title: FACSNET: Economic Thinking and Campaign Coverage
Link: <mailto:pattimcc>; rev="Made"
</DOCHDR>
<html><head>
<title>FACSNET: Economic Thinking and Campaign Coverage</title>
</head>
<body>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<hr noshade size=3>
<center>
<img src="../../facsnet_grafix/report_tools/backgrounder.gif" alt="NewsBackgrounders:">
<br>
Briefing Papers for Journalists
</center>
<hr noshade size=3> <h1>Economic Thinking and Campaign Coverage</h1>
            <h2> </h2>
            <strong> <p></strong><strong>by Frank C. Wykoff<p></strong><TABLE CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=20> <TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG SRC= "../../facsnet_grafix/report_tools/Wykoff.gif " ALT = "Frank C. Wykoff"> </TD><TD><B>Frank Wykoff</B> is the Eldon Smith Professor of Economics at Pomona College and the Claremont Graduate School. He specializes in macroeconomics theory, monetary theory and policy, econometrics and public finance, particularly investment and taxation. His most recent book is <I>Understanding Economics Today</I>, written with Gary Walton. He is editor of the influential journal <I>Economic Inquiry</I>. Professor Wykoff is director of the FACS Institute on Economics for Journalists and economics adviser to the foundation. Since 1979, he has taught economic principles to thousands of journalists at FACS conferences.</TD> </TR> </TABLE><P><P>National elections mean high drama.
 The public eats up marital infidelity, dirty tricks, corruption, negative campaigning and charges and counter-charges of every imaginable immoral or illegal act.
 Midterm elections, while not quite as racy as Presidential elections, have many of the same ingredients and consequences.
  <P>Pointy-headed intellectuals may tell us that all issues are local.
 But, like it or not, Democratic congressmen and senators up for re-election will be perceived as surrogate candidates for President Clinton.
 Commentators will total up the numbers.
 Democrats lose 15 house seats and four senate seats: a Republican victory.
 Democrats enlarge their majorities: a presidential mandate.
  <P>Outcomes of this bi-annual ritual really do matter.
 Public policy will be reshaped by the elections, by the campaigns and by news coverage.
 To have the most constructive impact, the journalist should plan now to ask the right questions, analyze the responses and put the answers into context for voters.
 Whoever ends up in Washington, the state house or city hall is going to be called on to make hard economic choices.
  <P>The purpose of this piece is to help the journalist contribute to an understanding of those choices.
 In 1994, major economic issues are being debated, among them health care, trade policy, immigration, crime, budgets.
 Deep down, many journalists feel unequipped to analyze tough, technical issues.
 They describe the extremes of arguments and leave to the wonks the wide range of substance in the middle.
 An economic way of thinking can help journalists who wish to cover the story constructively and thoughtfully.
 Here, we shall analyze trade policy and medical care policy to illustrate the tools of economic thinking applied dispassionately to cut through the blather and isolate the crucial sub-text in public debates.
  <H2>U.
S.
-Japan Relations: Trade, Bash and Trade Again</H2>  <P>Despite passage of the NAFTA and GATT international trade agreements, the sticky question of U.
S.
-Japan trade relations keeps percolating to the surface.
 The issue is important both because Japan is a major world power and important trading partner and because its success makes it a natural role model for emerging economic powers.
 If restrictive Japanese trade practices are copied by other nations, then the U.
S.
 trade balance could deteriorate.
  <H3>A bilateral trade deficit is not by itself a problem</H3>  <P>The U.
S.
 runs large, chronic trade deficits with Japan.
 A deficit with one trading partner, a bilateral trade deficit, is not by itself a problem.
 Think of yourself as an individual country.
 You trade with other people (other countries).
 You run many bilateral trade deficits.
 That is, you buy food from the grocer, who buys nothing from you.
 You run a trade deficit with your dentist; he fixes your teeth, but you re unlikely to sell him one of your stories.
 You do run one trade surplus, though.
 You have a surplus with your employer.
 If you work for a newspaper, it pays your salary (not enough, to be sure) in exchange for your reportorial skills.
 Countries behave the same way.
 They may run several bilateral deficits, buying more from countries A, C, D, and G, and several bilateral surpluses, selling more to countries B, E and F.
 This is not a problem.
  <H3>Chronic Deficits and Surpluses</H3>  <P>But the facts in the U.
S.
-Japan case are more complex.
 Japan runs chronic trade surpluses with almost every country.
 Conversely, the U.
S.
 runs chronic trade deficits against almost everyone, and the sum of these deficits has for decades exceeded the sum of the surpluses.
 It s as if you consistently bought more from others than you earned to pay for it.
  <P>Question: if you were to do that for a very long time, would you eventually run out of money?
 Perhaps.
 Perhaps not.
 The same is true of a nation.
 You may be very wealthy and prefer to spend without working.
 A rich nation could do that too, if its people chose to.
 If your offspring (future generations) were aware of your conduct, they might resent your spending their inheritance.
 But it is your wealth and your decision.
 When you buy more than you earn, you dissave by borrowing or by spending income from wealth.
  <P>What does this imply for countries in general?
 Nations may run trade deficits when they are young and growing, because they are, in effect, borrowing money from the rest of the world.
 As long as they are investing the borrowed funds in productive capital, they will have no problem paying back the loans, with interest.
 In economic terms, their accumulated productive capital will enable them to run trade surpluses in the future without lowering living standards of future generations.
  <P>Japan may sensibly consume less than it produces (save and run a trade surplus), just as some people save for long periods.
 Meanwhile, the U.
S.
 sensibly consumes more than it produces (dissaves and runs a trade deficit).
 Thus, there is nothing inherently wrong with one nation running a net trade surplus with the rest of the world for several years while another runs persistent trade deficits.
  <H3>The Negotiating Challenge</H3>  <P>Even though the bilateral trade deficit with Japan may not be an inherent problem, it is certainly fair to ask whether the U.
S.
, as a nation, wants to trade with a people who through history, tradition, culture or habit, impede market access to foreigners, in this case American exporters.
 Many people are troubled by stories about cultural and social impediments to American products like Chrysler autos and Motorola cellular phones.
 Suppose, for the sake of argument, we agree that Japanese markets are more impenetrable to U.
S.
 exports than are U.
S.
 markets to Japanese exports.
 If so, then American negotiators have to decide how to deal with these impediments.
  <P>Here, the two political parties disagree about how to proceed.
 Jean Kirkpatrick, former U.
S.
 Ambassador to the U.
N.
, asked by way of argument whether if the Japanese mined theirown harbors (to keep their citizens from buying U.
S.
 goods) we should retaliate by mining our harbors?
 This thought suggests that we do nothing about trade restrictions in Japan, since the most damaged party is the Japanese consumer.
 Laura D Andrea Tyson, President Clinton s chief economic adviser, believes that the U.
S.
 should threaten Japan with trade sanctions unless Japan imports more U.
S.
 products.
  <P>The administration s outcome-oriented approach is controversial.
 Obviously, it suggests tolerance of a trade war.
 How does a nation proceed if it threatens a trade opponent, and the opponent refuses to buckle?
 As every parent knows, threats must now and then be enforced to make them credible.
 How many of us have watched a child ignore a mother s threat, knowing that it will never be enforced.
 All that is accomplished in either case is an increase in the decibel level.
  <P>It is impossible for a democracy to make unenforceable threats in a trade dispute because everything is public information.
 That creates a problem for a U.
S.
 trade brinkman (or brinkperson), for two reasons.
   <UL><LI>First problem: can the Administration deliver the sanction if it s needed?
 In this case, delivery means restraint of trade, Super 301 lawsuits taken to the Federal Trade Commission and other acts that would require the acquiescence of congress.
 Is such political support assured?
  <LI>Second problem: trade sanctions require that American consumers be prohibited from purchasing from Japan large quantities of high quality products that they want at low prices.
 Will American consumers be willing to tolerate this fallout from a trade bomb intended for Japan?
</UL>  <H3>You Can t Have It Both Ways</H3>  <P>If Japanese negotiators calculate that the President does not have the political clout to effectively impose trade sanctions, then the threat would be seen as worthless bluster.
 Were the threat serious, then the Administration would have to restrain the very trade that Americans want.
 Thus, one cannot logically support the Clinton administration s brinkmanship and support free trade at the same time.
 Free trade and fair trade are at odds with one another.
 If you favor one, you are logically opposed to the other.
 You cannot have it both ways.
  <P>Do congressional candidates understand the full consequences of their positions on trade?
 Journalists should not let a candidate off the hook if he bashes Japan and says he supports free trade.
 In my view, journalists can expose such fraudulent positions on both sides.
 Make these potential decision-makers tell the voters which side of the trade fence they re really on.
  <P>Journalists should not let a candidate off the hook if he bashes Japan and says he supports free trade  <H2>Health and the Medical Industry</H2>  <P>We turn now to an important industry under serious scrutiny, the medical industry.
 Americans spend more of their Gross Domestic Product (GDP) on medical treatment than at any other time in history and more than any other advanced industrial country.
 In 1994, approximately 14% of GDP will go to medical expenditures.
 This is up from less than 10% in the nineteen fifties and early sixties.
 Less than 10% is now being spent by any other advanced country and, even more worrisome, President Clinton forecasts that medical care costs will rise to 19% of GDP by the year 2000.
  <P>Milton Friedman calls the health industry a black hole in the economy.
 It is soaking up national resources, capital, labor, materials and energy at an accelerating rate without producing significant improvement in health indicators of the American people.
   <P>This is the core question: how do we stop this industry from absorbing more resources while failing to improve Americans  health?
 There are two ways.
 No one in the public arena is talking about either.
  <H3>The Burden of Restraint</H3>  <P>One approach is to place the burden of restraint directly on doctors and their patients.
 (I use the term patient to include surrogate decision makers and family members.
) Preferred solutions for health care reform do not necessarily fall along party lines, but Republicans tend to favor this approach.
 The patient, as consumer, is the main beneficiary of expenditures on his health.
 He should bear most of the burden of deciding how much should be spent on his medical treatment.
 He can and will do this only in a system in which he directly incurs the cost of treatment.
 Prepayment will not work.
  <P>The principal beneficiary of the supply of medical treatments is the medical professional.
 (Here I will use the term "doctor" to refer to all medical professionals who reap the rewards of expenditures on medical treatment.
) The doctor, as producer, should also bear a major portion of the burden of deciding how much it should cost to treat the patient.
 This requires that doctors take direct fiduciary responsibility for the treatments they recommend.
 That is, doctors  incomes, or profits if you prefer, should be linked directly to the amount spent on treatment.
 (Note that this radically conflicts with views professed by most medical professionals.
) Profits, far from being sinful, are a constructive systemic device that actually restrains suppliers and holds down costs.
  <H3>Third Party Control</H3>  <P>The second, alternative, approach is to insulate doctors and patients from choosing limits on treatments and place the decision to restrain costs on some third party.
 Democrats, generally, favor the second approach: keep patients and doctors free from deciding how to constrain care.
 But, given the fiscal realities of human conduct, the decision to limit costs then must be made by a third party and imposed on the doctor and patient.
 The third party will then have to monitor the behavior of doctors and patients and must be able to enforce restrictions with a credible, effective enforcement mechanism.
  <P>There is no third way to solve this core medical industry problem: either the medical industry acts like a private self-regulated market subject to competition, incentives and choice, or it becomes an industry regulated by a third party, probably the federal government.
  <P>In the Clinton plan, the third party who will restrict medical costs would appear to be monopolies called health alliances.
 In other plans, restraint may be imposed by employers in negotiation with insurance companies.
 In Oregon, a rare political climate, elected officials, with the advice of "wise men," rank-order treatments they deem appropriate for Oregon s medically covered public charges.
  <H3>Questioning the Candidates</H3>  <P>Which approach a candidate favors will tell you a lot about his or her philosophy and attitude toward social problems.
 Of course, if candidates fail to understand that the medical industry reform problem is failure to control costs and fail to explain how they choose to deal with it, they are displaying either disingenuousness or incompetence.
 Neither is a promising quality in a government leader.
  <P>Candidates who fail to admit where they think the resource allocation decision should lie are not going to help solve the problem.
 Journalists should make this clear to the voters.
 It is important to recognize that the Clinton plan tries to obfuscate the allocation mechanism.
 Similarly, conservative critics who attack the Clinton plan on grounds that it will impose limits are dishonest.
 Of course, it will limit expenditures on medical treatment, but that is essential to any solution to the core problem.
 If conservatives attack alliances, then they should be compelled to explain how they would constrain growth of costs.
 On whom would the burden of restraint fall: on the doctor and patient, on the hospital, on the insurance company, or the public sector?
 Where and how will this be done, and is the answer credible?
  <P>In summary, the key to understanding the economic perspective of campaign issues is to determine the likely consequence of policies and compare them to the consequences of alternatives.
 If a policy to raise the minimum wage is proposed to reduce poverty, how will it effect the labor market, the poor and business?
 What are the alternatives and their consequences?
 How does a policy alter economic incentives of decision makers?
 If a policy to hire more border patrol officers is preferred, what is the likely success rate in curtailing migration flows in comparison to the increased costs?
 Will this have a significant impact on migration or will the migration stream simply flow through another part of the dike?
 And why must migration flows be curtailed anyway?
 What are the likely consequences of an incremental reduction in the flow of immigrants?
   <P>Thinking about these questions in a rigorous fashion will equip the journalist with tools to produce original reporting that advances the cause of democracy by elevating the level of the debate.
 That, after all, is the only justification for the first amendment right that makes journalism a profession and not just another job.
       
<br>
<br>
