Title: FACSNET: Fixing Superfund Failures
Link: <mailto:pattimcc>; rev="Made"
</DOCHDR>
<html><head>
<title>FACSNET: Fixing Superfund Failures</title>
</head>
<body>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<hr noshade size=3>
<center>
<img src="../../facsnet_grafix/report_tools/backgrounder.gif" alt="NewsBackgrounders:">
<br>
Briefing Papers for Journalists
</center>
<hr noshade size=3> <h1>Fixing Superfund Failures</h1>
            <h2> </h2>
            <strong> <p></strong><strong>by Paul R. Portney and Katherine N. Probst<p></strong><B>Paul Portney</B> is vice president and senior fellow at Resources for the Future (RFF), an independent, non-partisan research and educational organization concerned with natural resources and the environment. He was formerly director of the RFF Center for Risk Management, and is a former chief economist of the President s Council on Environmental Quality.<BR>

<p><B>Katherine Probst</B> is a research fellow at the RFF Center for Risk Management. A specialist in Superfund issues, she was a member of the Superfund Evaluation Committee convened by EPA Administrator Carol Browner to advise the agency on changes to the statute.<P><P>Superfund was born a problem child, and little wonder.
 A program that cost billions, designed to sanitize hundreds of toxic waste sites, paid for by companies that often dumped the stuff legally   if the government can find them and get them to pay.
 It's a prescription for disputes, and Superfund has lots of them.
 The Rand Corporation estimates that about one-third of the money spent on Superfund goes to legal and administrative costs.
   <P>Right now Superfund pleases no one, and with Congress scheduled to re-authorize the program, there are plenty of suggestions on how to fix it.
   <P>Over the last 22 years, Congress has enacted seven major laws that are the basis for Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) regulation.
 Six of the seven control current and future pollution.
 Number seven aims to fix the past.
 That one is Superfund, known in officialspeak as the Comprehensive Environmental Response, Compensation and Liability Act (CERCLA).
   <P>Superfund was enacted to clean up the legacy of areas contaminated from such things as mining, refining, manufacturing, and waste disposal   problems from history, and sometimes as far into history as the last century.
   <H2>What Superfund does</H2>   <P>At the risk of oversimplifying a very complicated statute, here's what Superfund has tried to do:<UL><LI>Set up a way to identify and rank contaminated sites that pose serious threats to human health and the environment.
 The worst of the bunch go on the National Priorities List (NPL), making them eligible for federal cleanup money.
 Right now there are 1,286 sites on the NPL.
<LI>Establish a process to decide how each site will be cleaned up.
<LI>Find out who was responsible for the pollution and make them pay to clean it up.
<LI>Build a trust fund from taxes on petroleum and chemicals and general taxes on corporations.
 The trust fund money can be used to clean sites in an emergency, or for long-term cleanup when EPA can't find a responsible party to pay the bills.
</UL>   <H2>Cost and Controversies</H2>   <P>As best we can determine, total spending on Superfund in 1993 was about $6 billion.
<UL><LI>$3 billion by the U.
S.
 Departments of Energy and Defense for cleaning up nuclear weapons plants and military bases.
<LI>$1.
5 billion by <LI>Approximately $2 billion by all private firms, individuals, and state and local governments.
 Since private parties are not required to report their annual cleanup expenditures, there is great uncertainty about this number.
</UL>   <P>Superfund's $6 billion is a relatively small portion of the $130 billion EPA estimates we spent on all federal environmental compliance last year, but we'll eventually spend much more.
 Right now cleanup is costing about $30 million per site, which suggests $40 billion to complete the current NPL.
 If EPA continues to add sites at the current rate of 50 per year for the next decade, the total bill will be more like $55 billion.
   <H2>How clean is clean?
</H2>   <P>Two questions lie at the heart of virtually all serious disagreements over Superfund.
 First, how much should we clean up each site?
 Second, who should pay?
   <P>There is a lot of concern   particularly in the business community   that we're spending a lot of money to eliminate very small risk.
 These critics charge that EPA systematically overestimates the health and ecological risks, often by making unreasonable assumptions about likely human exposure to contaminants.
 They resent squandering scarce resources on what they regard as trivial problems.
 On the other hand, environmentalists contend that serious contamination at some sites is going unaddressed.
   <P>The law calls for cleanup that "utilizes permanent solutions and alternative treatment technologies.
.
.
to the maximum extent practicable" at each site.
 But should every site be cleaned up equally?
   <P>Consider this example: The site is a fenced-off, vacant, former industrial dump located away from any residential area.
 The soil is contaminated, but the ground water is safe.
 Would it be enough to secure the area and monitor it carefully?
    <P>This is a risk-based approach, one that balances the cost of cleanup against the risk that someone will be harmed by the contaminated soil.
 To clean it up more, advocates of this approach argue, would take money away from other problems elsewhere.
   <P>The critics of a risk approach say it's a nice concept, but a practical impossibility, given the almost total lack of reliable data on the actual health and environmental risks at sites.
 And trying to make those decisions, they say, would drag out the process into the next millennium.
   <P>Is there a compromise possible?
 Perhaps.
 EPA could establish different maximum permissible contaminants in soil and ground water, depending on how the site will be used.
 A Superfund site redeveloped as an industrial park would have to meet less stringent standards than one that became a housing development.
 The hierarchy would reflect that people (especially children) are less likely to be exposed to remaining contaminants at an industrial park than at a housing development.
   <H2>The Practical Effect</H2>   <P>Actually, a change like that would make less difference than you might expect, based on a strict reading of the law.
 When Resources for the Future studied cleanup remedies nationwide, we found that EPA actually does seem to consider health and environmental risk, in spite of the fact that the Superfund statute discourages risk-based cleanup.
   <P>We also found that the selection of a remedy seems to depend in part on which EPA regional office is in charge and in part on the amount of attention the site gets from the public, TV and newspapers.
   <H2>Who Pays?
</H2>   <P>Congress had no appetite for increasing federal spending to clean up contaminated sites, so it created a liability system to make private parties pay.
 The system has:<UL><LI>Retroactivity, demanding payment from companies for what they did before Superfund was enacted<LI>Strict liability, meaning companies payfor cleanup regardless of whether they were negligent in the past.
<LI>Joint-and-several liability, which means that any one party at a site can be required to pay for the entire cleanup, regardless of the share of the waste it contributed.
 (That party can in turn sue other contributors, but must pay the cost of the suit.
)</UL>   <P>Each of these liability provisions has been exceptionally controversial.
 For instance, it's galling for one responsible party to be told to shoulder a disproportionately large share of cleanup because none of the other contributors can be found, or because they're insolvent and can't pay.
 And firms that took pains to manage hazardous substances in a responsible way bristle at the fact that their efforts are no defense against Superfund liability.
   <H2>How broad is the responsibility?
</H2>   <P>Other firms are being drawn into paying too.
 Banks and other lending institutions are afraid they'll be held liable because they loaned money to firms found to be responsible parties.
 These institutions are pressing for elimination of what has come to be known as lender liability.
   <P>Since a number of Superfund sites are landfills that municipalities contributed to or operated, they've been pulled into the argument.
 They claim the law was never meant to cover municipal waste (what we used to call garbage), even though some of the household trash is every bit as toxic as some industrial wastes.
   <P>Insurance companies have been ensnarled too, and they're certainly the most unhappy of all.
 Many of the firms found liable for cleanup under Superfund have sued their insurance companies to force them to pick up the cost, claiming their general liability policies should cover it.
 Insurance companies point to standard language that says coverage is for "sudden and accidental" damages, not the slow leak of contaminants.
   <P>So far the overall results of the insurance law suits are confusing at best.
 The decisions are coming from state courts (because insurance is regulated almost exclusively at the state level), and both sides are winning about half the cases.
   <P>There are two legislative solutions under consideration.
 Each has a quid pro quo trade off:   <UL><LI>Don't hold anyone responsible for cleaning up waste disposed of before the Superfund law took effect in 1981.
<LI>Absolve insurers from having to pay for cleanup costs of the firms they insured.
</UL>   <P>To win these concessions, insurance companies would finance all or part of a new fund to pay for cleanup costs at the sites affected.
   <H2>Some Predictions</H2>   <P>With Congress you never go broke betting on the status quo, but we see support gathering for some changes in the Superfund law.
 Here are two likely ones:<UL><LI>Allow for different degrees of cleanup of Superfund sites, depending on how they'll be used in the future.
<LI>When some of the responsible parties are not able to pay, have EPA pick up the unpaid shares, rather than requiring the rest of the responsible parties to pay the "orphan" share.
</UL>   <P>While the current liability standards in Superfund are unfair in several respects and produce a lot of litigation, our research indicates the suggested changes will create new inequities and encourage new law suits.
    <P>In fact, so far there's only one undisputed benefit of the program: Superfund has created powerful incentives for companies to better manage hazardous substances   and reduce the use of them.
 That's the best way to avoid being caught up in Superfund in the first place.
   <H2>Contacts:</H2><P>Elliott Laws<BR>EPA (Solid Waste)<BR>202/260-4610<P>Maryann Froehlich<BR>EPA (Policy Analysis)<BR>202/260-4012<P>Michael McGavick<BR>Superfund Improvement Project<BR>American Insurance Association<BR>202/828-7499<P>Bernard Rielly<BR>Dupont<BR>302/774-2117<P>Ed Pollack<BR>Olin Corporation<BR>202/356-3084<P>Bill Roberts<BR>Environmental Defense Fund<BR>202/387-3500<P>Linda Greer<BR>Nat'l Resources Defense Fund<BR>202/783-7800<P>Paul Portney/Kate Probst<BR>Resources for the Future<BR>202/328-5061<P>Tom Curtis<BR>Nat'l Governors Assn.
 <BR>202/624-5300<BR>         
<br>
<br>
