<html><head>
<title>FACSNET: The Hubbell of Economics: The CPI Is Off By One-Third</title>
</head>
<body>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<hr noshade size=3>
<center>
<img src="../../facsnet_grafix/report_tools/backgrounder.gif" alt="NewsBackgrounders:">
<br>
Briefing Papers for Journalists
</center>
<hr noshade size=3> <h1>The Hubbell of Economics: The CPI Is Off By One-Third</h1>
            <h2> </h2>
            <strong>Every month, the Federal government releases the latest consumer price index figures.
 By rote, news organizations report the CPI numbers, but few journalists know what they mean.
 As 1996 wound down, along came the biggest CPI story in years; a board of experts said that the consumer price index is flawed and gives Americans a distorted picture of the economy.
 Economist Frank Wykoff offers journalists a way to help their audiences understand the CPI mix-up and the importance of the index.
<p></strong><strong>by Frank Wykoff<p></strong><TABLE CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=20> <TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG SRC= "../../facsnet_grafix/report_tools/Wykoff.gif " ALT = "Frank Wykoff"> </TD><TD><B>Frank Wykoff</B> is the Elden Smith Professor of Economics at Pomona College and the Claremont Graduate School. He specializes in macroeconomics, mathematical economics, growth, capital formation, productivity and econometrics. His most recent book is <I>Understanding Economics Today</I>, written with Gary Walton, is in its fifth edition. Professor Wykoff is chief economist and academic dean of FACS and directs the FACS Institute on Economics for Journalists. He has taught thousands of journalists at FACS conferences.</TD> </TR> </TABLE><p> <P><P>A few years ago, US astronauts shuttled into outer space to fix the broken Hubbell Space Telescope.
 Because of design flaws, the lens was warping humankind s vision of the stars and planets.
 News coverage of the bold trip into space to correct the flawed lens was extensive and riveting.
 <P>The event had no personal impact on average readers, viewers and listeners.
 Their immediate lives would not be altered by it, yet the Hubbell adventure received comprehensive, detailed and enthusiastic coverage.
 Why such great interest?
 Because the Hubbell flaw and correction fit everyone's definition of news.
 Even after four decades of the space program, it is unusual to see humans working in outer space.
 The Hubbell story had the added attraction of catching a major government agency, NASA, in a blunder that cost taxpayers millions of dollars.
                          <P>In early December of 1996, five academics on the Boskin Commission disclosed the economic equivalent of the Hubbell's distorted lens.
 Named after its leader, former Council of Economic Advisors chairman Michael Boskin, the commission announced the most important statistical correction in US history.
 The Consumer Price Index was broken.
 It was off by thirty percent, and had been off even more during an important inflation period of our recent history.
 It cost American taxpayers billions of dollars and distorted numerous economic decisions.
                          <P>The flaws reflected procedures of the Bureau of Labor Statistics.
 They cost the federal government budget alone more than a trillion dollars.
 The CPI bias was about a million times more costly to American taxpayers than the Hubbell mistake.
 Boskin estimates thatif the corrections are implemented, they cansave the government more than a trillion dollars over the next decade.
                           <P>This monumental economic story, vastly more important to Americans than the Hubbell, has profound and significant financial implications for every one in the nation.
 Given its scientific importance and its financial implications, we might have expected the CPI-correction report to receive coverage at least comparable to the Hubbell story.
                           <P>My impression was that immediate coverage of the CPI story dealt primarily with political fallout and not at all with economic implications.
 Energetic reporters can still tell this compelling and important story.
 It lacks white collar crimes, businessmen in black hats and poor old ladies suffering as a result of the mistake, but, the CPI-correction is extremely important.
                          <H2>A Story Waiting to be Told</H2>                          <P>Just as a telescope enhances the view of outer-space, the CPI is a window into the national economy.
 The CPI was badly distorting our picture of the economy.
 Decisions based on that distortion were resulting in costly mistakes in policy design and financial decisions.
 The first rule of successful bureaucrats and politicians, CYA (cover-your-duff), prevented them from openly acknowledgingthe mistake.
 Instead Congress,and the bureaucracy bucked the problem to a handful of academics.
             <P>Perhaps courageously, perhaps naively, the academics on the Boskin Commission took their task seriously and apolitically.
 They collected and studied the extensive CPI research literature, dissected the index into its component parts, examined its most serious flaws, and measured them.
 They proposed a series of major measurement changes to bring the economy into sharper focus.
 This problem was every bit as interesting and scientific as the Hubbell correction.
              <H2>The Science Spin</H2>             <P>As when an astronomer aims his telescope at a constellation of stars, the economist uses the CPI as a lens to bring aspects of the economy into sharp focus.
 The consumer price index is the tool used to study changes in the overall level of prices of goods and services consumed by Americans.
 Constructed by the Bureau of Labor Statistics, the CPI measures the change from one year to the next in the price of a <I>market basket</I> of goods.
 The basket is chosen to reflect the expenditure patterns of a <I>typical</I> consumer.
                          <P>That sounds simple enough, but the minute someone starts to draw inferences from the CPI figures about some actual policy, problems arise.
 Like cigarette packs, the CPI comes with a warning label: <H3><I>The CPI is not a cost of living index.
</I></H3> <P>Yet, everyone uses it asif it were a cost of livingindex; that is, a measure ofthe change in the cost of living between periods.
 Ifthe CPI rises by 3.
5%, then labor contracts allow automatic wage increases of 3.
5% to cover the increase in <I>the cost of living</I>.
 Social security payments and government pensions are automatically increased to reflect this 3.
5% increase in <I>the cost of living</I>.
 Legal contracts trigger automatic increases of 3.
5% in rents paid to landlords.
 The effects are legion.
                        <P> design of the CPI prevents it from representing changes in the cost of living for three major distinct reasons:<OL><LI><B>Substitution Bias:</B> A cost of living index could not price a fixed bundle of goods, because Americans adapt their consumption patterns to avoid goods whose prices rise the most.
 Thus, the CPI always overstates inflation.
 Economists have a name for this upward bias in the index: substitution bias.
 Americans do not consume exactly the same basket of goods and services year in and year out.
 Knowledgeable and intelligent consumers that they are, American shoppers adjust the bundle they consume in response to relative price changes.
 As Boskin pointed out, if the price of red Delicious apples rises, many shoppers shift to relatively less expensive Granny Smiths.
 That partly insulates the family s cost of living from rising as much as the price of the Red Delicious.
 Substitution is the essence of what shoppers do when they look for sales, clip coupons, shop around, change stores and follow advertising.
 Substitution is the key to preventingsellers from raising prices too much.
<LI><B>New Goods Bias:</B> If the basket of goods priced by the CPI is fixed, then when new goods are invented, they are not adequately accounted for by the CPI.
 This is called new goods bias.
 Ask yourself, "How much income would I have needed in 1960 to buy the basket of goods I buy today?
" This sounds easy enough   what would be the cost in 1960 of your living standard in 1996?
 This question is at the heart of a cost-of-living index.
 The problem is that a lot of the goods you consume today did not exist in 1960, among them VCRs, car phones, beepers, home computers, and big screen TVs.
 How much would it take to get you to give up these new goods?
 <LI><B>Quality Change Bias:</B> Goods we buy today are better.
 Consider your car.
 It drives faster, is safer, pollutes less, is more durable, needs fewer days in repair and is more fuel-efficient than even the best cars of 1960.
 Economists have a name for this bias, too: quality change bias.
 Consider your television set.
 The screen is bigger.
 The picture is sharper.
 The set is sturdier.
 You no longer get frequent visits from the TV repair man.
 The sound is stereo.
 You have dozens of cable stations, not just a handful of local affiliates and independents.
 This is not to mention the potential of your TV to accommodate your computer and link to your VCR and surround-sound system.
 You take for granted today abundance and quality of goods that most Americans didn t dream of in 1960.
 Yet, if these improvements in your living standards are in the CPI at all, they are usually treated as price increases, not offsets to the cost of living.
 Economists now know more than they did a decade ago about how to correct price increases for quality change, so that when a price reflects a much better product it does not look like an increase in costs.
</OL>             <P>If these and similar defects in the CPI as a cost-of-living index remain uncorrected, they will cause us to continue to exaggerateinflation by 30% a year.
 When the CPI says 3.
6%, it is really only 2.
5%.
 The error, according to the commissioners is about 1.
1%.
 Just as the design flaw in the Hubbell lens was an error, the 1.
1% shortfall is a mistake.
 This is not a political point, a conservative hidden agenda or an attack on social security.
 Economists are applying advances in the science of economics to correct a lens used to focus on an important aspect of the economy.
 How the political system makes use of this improved science is another matter altogether.
                          <P>There are numerous other issues raised by the CPI-correction story, each of which could comprise a major story.
 Are we really better off today than we were in 1960?
 What about pollution and crime?
 We can study data in order to see how we are doing on these important social indicators.
 What about spiritual thinking and true happiness?
 Are we too hurried?
 These intangibles are also important to living standards, but are difficult to capture in a cost-of-living index.
 This suggests a number of other stories on the quality of life in America, how it has improved or declined over the years and its implications for the society's sense of well-being.
 Are you better off because you have a security system or worse off because you need one?
                          <P>How about implications to the readers?
 What would a CPI correction mean for federal pensioners, retired congressmen, social security recipients, the poor, union members, corporations, small businesses, renters and homeowners?
 The answers will depend on how the political system responds to the correction, and that depends to a large extent on the quality of news coverage of the story.
 A number of exciting questions are raised by this story, each with plenty of personal-interest angles.
                          <P>There are enormous implications for the economy in general.
 If a federal program is indexed to the CPI, then the dollar value of the program moves with the CPI.
 Social security payments and federal pensions, for instance, are indexed to the CPI.
 This indexing is called a cost-of-living adjustment (COLA, for short).
 As you now know, the CPI is not a cost of living index, so COLA is really a misnomer.
 COLAs tied to the CPI are too large because the CPI distorts increases in the cost of living by as much as 30%.
 This has huge consequences for inflation, interest rates, monetary policy, foreign trade balances, productivity measures, and many other aspects of economic policy, performance and evaluation.
             <P>The historical ramifications are obvious.
 If the CPI overstated inflation by more than 100 percent during the inflationary seventies, then COLAs that were intended only to prevent inflation from eroding living standards had other substantial consequences.
 We shifted real resources away from workers who were paying payroll taxes and families who didn't receive benefits.
 We transferred these resources to social security recipients, pensioners and retired government workers.
 Because our lens was broken, we transferred from one group of citizens to another millions more each year than Congress evidently intended.
 In terms of social security, this little mistake resulted in billions of dollars shifted from one generation, the young, to another, the old.
                           <P>A reporter or editor who actually reads the Boskin Commission report will see historical example after example of even more egregious errors caused by a poorly designed economic lens.
 The report is replete with cases of industries in which change has been so prevalent in recent years there is an enormous measurement error.
 It indicates that the public has not been aware of what is going on in major sectors of the economy.
 <P>A most glaring and complex example is medical care.
 Two years ago, we were so concerned with reports of the rising cost of medical care that we practically dissected the health care industry.
 But think a minute about the quality of health in America.
 In 1960, some cancers and heart diseases meant certain death.
 No longer.
 I had champagne and caviar last week to celebrate with a 58 year-old-friend who had a new heart.
 Ten years ago, his heart condition meant certain death.
 Medical care is costly to society, but it is improving the length and the quality of our lives.
 How many people are alive today, have their eye sight or hearing or can walk free of pain, who years ago would have been dead or infirm?
                          <P>Yet, the CPI acts as if nothing has happened to the quality of medical care, as if only the cost has gone up in medical care.
 This point opens our minds to more fascinating and fundamental issues.
 How should we seriously evaluate the quality of life in America today?
 Does reality reflect news coverage?
 Are things really as bad as the daily news would lead us to believe?
 According to Boskin, crime has fallen in the last decade, the air is less polluted, life expectancy has risen.
 Perhaps, just perhaps, some bold editor will let some creative reporter demonstrate to us, by really telling the CPI story, that things are not so bad after all.
                                       <H3>Suggested background information on the CPI and the cost of living:</H3>                          <P><AHREF=" http://www.
