<html><head>
<title>FACSNET: Why Do Financial Markets Listen to Alan Greenspan?</title>
</head>
<body>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<hr noshade size=3>
<center>
<img src="../../facsnet_grafix/report_tools/backgrounder.gif" alt="NewsBackgrounders:">
<br>
Briefing Papers for Journalists
</center>
<hr noshade size=3> <h1>Why Do Financial Markets Listen to Alan Greenspan?</h1>
            <h2> </h2>
            <strong>When the chairman of the Federal Reserve Bank speaks, Wall Street listens.
.
.
and acts.
 In this primer on the Fed, its power and policies, economist Frank Wykoff gives journalists insights that will bolster their reporting on the intended or unintended results of comments by the chairman.
 <p></strong><strong>by Frank C. Wykoff<p></strong><TABLE CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=20> <TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG SRC= "../../facsnet_grafix/report_tools/Wykoff.gif" ALT = "Frank C. Wykoff"> </TD><TD><B>Frank Wykoff</B> is the Elden Smith Professor of Economics at Pomona College and the Claremont Graduate School. He specializes in macroeconomics, mathematical economics, growth, capital formation, productivity and econometrics. His most recent book is <I>Understanding Economics Today</I>, written with Gary Walton, is in its fifth edition. Longtime editor of the influential journal <I>Economic Inquiry</I>, Professor Wykoff is chief economist and adademic dean of FACS and directs the FACS Institute on Economics for Journalists. He has taught journalists at FACS conferences since 1979.</TD> </TR> </TABLE><p> <P><P>In the last week of November, 1996, Henry Kaufman sent a warning to Wall Street in the lead op-ed page piece of the <I>Wall Street Journal</I>.
 Kaufman, a prominent, respected and reliable securities analyst, warned that the stock market was overvalued and that a recession would force a substantial downward correction.
 Kaufman s missive was not the first hint of an overvalued market.
 In fact, the <I>Journal</I> had carried several articles suggesting the market was unreasonably robust.
 Financial markets, evidently ignoring Kaufman and other Journal warnings, continued bullish.

     <P>During the first week of December, 1996 this author, an economics professor for twenty eight years, was asked at a Rotary Club if I knew why the market was setting record highs?
 In a word, my answer was "No.
" The world economic system appears to be healthy, and growth seems quite likely.
 Still, I could not understand the long-running euphoric rise on world-wide stock exchanges.
 Stocks, from Japan and China to Europe, have been rising as if to suggest that we are about to embark on a sustained period of economic growth comparable to that in the US between War II and Vietnam.

     <P>As a rule, though, professional investors are short sighted.
 Even if long run growth is likely, investors sell off at a hint of an even brief slowdown.
 I did not feel the economic prospects could justify these markets  uniquely positive, even explosive, performance.
 The US is about to enter the seventh year of an expansion.
 That is very long by historical standards.
 Much as we wish it were not so, capitalism cannot avoid recessions.
 There will be another one.
 Wall Street, indeed the financial markets of the world, ignored my warning as they had Kaufman's.
 Stocks continued to reach new highs.

     <H2>Greenspan Speaks, Markets Listen</H2>
     <P>Then, in December 5, 1996 dinner speech, Alan Greenspan warned that stock markets, subject to "irrational exuberance," can rise with speculative bubbles.
 Too much optimism, Greenspan noted, would eventually evaporate and force a crash that might damage the firms and the underlying economic systems the stock markets reflect.
 Greenspan warned that uninterrupted expansion could not continue.
 Remarkably, unlike after Kaufman s editorial and unlike after my remarks, world stock markets took a sudden downward hit.

     <P>London, Hong Kong and Tokyo stocks plummeted immediately.
 When the New York Exchange opened Friday morning, stocks began to fall, hitting a nadir of over 140 points before bulls bought low for a comeback.
 The market finally closed 55 points down.
 Virtually all observers concluded that financial markets were responding to Greenspan s admonitions.
 The <I>Journal</I> called this "the Greenspan effect.
"
     <P>This raises the obvious question: Who is this Alan Greenspan, that markets listen to him?

     
     <H2>Who Is Alan Greenspan?
</H2>
     <P>Alan Greenspan is Chairman of the Board of Governors of the US Federal Reserve System (referred to as the Fed).
 To many observers his chairmanship makes Alan Greenspan the second most powerful person in the US capital and perhaps in the world.
 President Bush appointed Mr.
 Greenspan chairman of the Fed in 1990 and the appointment was ratified by Congress.
 President Clinton re-appointed Mr.
 Greenspan for the next four-year term.
 Unlike other presidential appointees, the Fed chairman does not serve at the pleasure of the president.
 He serves a fixed four-year term, which overlaps that of the president.
 Thus, the chairman holds office whether or not the president likes his policies.

     <P>In 1993, Bill Clinton had to accept Alan Greenspan as chairman for two years before he could make his own appointment.
 Re-appointed by Clinton, Greenspan s current four year term will end in the middle of the President's second four years, 1998.
 This procedure helps to make the chairman (some day, perhaps, chairwoman) of the Fed partially independent of the vagaries of presidential politics.

     <P>Greenspan,a Ph.
D.
 economist, had his own Wall Street consulting firm before ascending to the Fed.
 He had also been an important financial scholar and financial advisor to presidents for many years.
 Philosophically, Greenspan was a disciple of Ayn Rand, the famous author of <I>Atlas Shrugged</I> and <I>The Fountainhead</I>, books espousing objectivism, a brand of libertarianism.
 But markets listen to Greenspan not because of his philosophy, academic credentials, or Wall Street experience.
 Markets listen to Greenspan because he is chairman of the Fed and as such has considerable authority over Fed policies, most importantly over monetary policy.

     <P>This raises a second question: What is the Fed and why is its monetary policy so important to financial markets?

     <H2>What is the Fed?
</H2>
     <P>The Federal Reserve Bank, created in 1913, is the US central bank.
 It is the bank for bankers.
 Just as you can keep your cash at your bank in checking and savings accounts, your bank can deposit its cash at the Fed, usually in one of the twelve Federal Reserve District Banks.
 Most banks, and all major city center banks, have Federal Reserve charters.
 That is, they belong to the Federal Reserve System.
 This means that they have bought into the Fed and thus are partial owners.
 Ownership does not mean control.
 On the contrary, membership in the Fed means that the bank must obey regulatory rules set by the Fed and is subject to both periodic and random Fed inspections.

     <P>Just as you can borrow from your bank, your bank can borrow from the Fed.
 When you need funds for a legitimate purpose, if your credit is good, you can borrow money from your bank.
 Likewise, your bank, if it needs funds, can get them on loan from the Fed.
 The Fed sets and enforces rules governing lending practices and regulates the balance sheet properties of member banks.

     <P>While this regulatory authority over banks is powerful, the Fed has another more important and powerful tool called open market operations.
 Open market operations are the principal mechanism used by the Fed to conduct monetary policy.
 It is this monetary policy that gives the Fed and therefore its chairman, Alan Greenspan, the clout that forces financial markets to listen to his opinions.

     <P>Essentially, through monetary policy the Fed can influence short term interest rates and bank balance sheets, and, therefore, the cost and availability of credit.
 Short-term interest rates are extremely sensitive to Fed monetary policy, and what markets fear most is that Mr.
 Greenspan will exercise his power to raise short-term interest rates, end the expansion and cause a recession.
 That is why many investors around the world sold off stocks after Mr.
 Greenspan hinted that stocks may be over-valued due to "irrational exuberance.
" If interest rates are about to rise and the world s economic engine, the US economy, falters, then world- wide recession is possible.
 That, in turn, means that businesses slow down, sales decline, revenues fall and profits are hit.
 Anticipating this, forward-looking investors who to sell off at the peak force down the return on stocks.
 Thus, there is a sell-off.

     <H2>How Open Market Operations Work</H2>
     <P>More fundamentally, how do open market operations work?
 Their mechanics are easy to see.
 As everyone knows, financial markets are flooded with US government securities, the debt instruments of the Federal Government, over $5 trillion worth.
 The Fed trades in those securities on the open market, and these trades are called open market operations.
 This open market centers in New York, where some very large traders, (big stock brokerages like Goldman Sachs or Shearson Lehman), surreptitiously serve as brokers for the Fed.
 The Fed will simply place with their brokers buy or sell orders for US government securities.

     <P>Once the Fed tells brokers to buy securities and they do so, the Fed credits the seller s bank with reserve deposits at the Fed.
 This is all done electronically, but these new reserves in the seller s bank are financial instruments that are claims on the Fed.
 These instruments are called federal reserve notes.

     <P>The bank can then lend these federal reserve notes to customers, as long as the bank keeps a small fraction on reserve.
 As banks make these loans, the new borrowers deposit their new loans in new banks, creating more deposits.
 As this process rolls through the banking system, the quantity of reserves in the system increases and loans increase.
 Thus, credit expands throughout the economy.
 The result of increased availability of money and credit is lower interest rates.
 Thus, just as Archemedies could move the world with his lever, the Fed can inject new reserves into the banking system by buying US securities (government debt instruments) with Federal Reserve Notes, driving down interest rates.

     <P>To reverse the process and raise interest rates, all the Fed does is instruct its traders to sell US securities on the open market.
 A Fed sale of securities means someone in the public buys the securities.
 (That is, of course, a voluntary transaction, so the Fed must offer an attractive yield to the seller.
) When that happens the Fed simply deducts reserves from the bank of the buyer by withdrawing reserves from that bank s account of federal reserve notes.
 The banks then have to turn the lending process around and start to reduce loans in order to build their reserve base back up.
 (Remember, without adequate reserves backing up their deposits, banks can be closed down by the Fed.
) With fewer reserves in the banking system, loans and credit start to dry up and, voila, interest rates rise.

     <P>The last three recessions were all caused by Fed monetary policy in exactly this way.
 The Fed chose to sell US securities on the open market in order to soak up bank reserves, limit loans and restrict credit.
 Interest rates increased and the economy slowed down.
 The Fed may not have wanted a recession, but it felt it had to slow things down to contain inflationary pressures.
 The US is so pivotal to the world economic system that when the Fed threatens a recession, the entire world listens.

     <P>The piece de la resistance in all this is that the very federal reserve notes that the Fed uses to buy US securities on the open market and that the Fed receives when it sells securities on the open market are money.
 A dollar bill, five dollar bill, ten dollar bill, hundred dollar bill, says right at the top "Federal Reserve Note.
" This paper money forms the base of our financial system.
 Most actual money we use is bank money in the form deposits in our various financial institutions.
 By increasing or decreasing the supply of federal reserve notes in the banking system, the Fed can increase or decrease the supply of money in the economic system.
 In short, open market operations are the mechanism that the Fed uses to increase or decrease the money supply.

     <P>This leads to yet another question, how does Fed control of the money supply influence short-term interest rates.
 In other words, how does monetary policy work?
 
     <H2>How Monetary Policy Works</H2>
     <P>How does a change in the money supply cause the private market economy to respond?
 Bank reserves and cash form the base of the credit system.
 If these federal reserve notes in the system increase, then money, loans and credit in general become readily available.
 If federal reserve notes are withdrawn by Fed open market sales of securities, then the credit available in the entire system begins to contract.
 Obviously, spending by both businesses and individuals responds to the cost of credit, the interest rates charged for loans.
 Thus, monetary policy influences the economy through the Fed s ability to influence interest rates.
 As a general rule, short-term rates are more sensitive to Fed actions than longer-term rates, but even long-term loan rates (for example mortgage rates) can respond to Fed action.

     <P>The market interest rate most sensitive to Fed actionsis the rate that banks charge one another for overnight loans of reserves.
 (Remember, banks have to satisfy every day a reserve requirement set by the Fed, so borrowing and lending is necessary each day to cover shortfalls and to use surplus reserves.
) This rate for bank reserves is called the federal funds rate.
 Fed watchers, who try to get a jump on what to expect for the pace of economic activity, look at the federal funds rate to see what it can tell them about the cost of bank reserve loans and, therefore, the availability of bank reserves.
 This, in turn, may signal a turn in Fed monetary policy.

     <P>The values of stocks in financial markets must ultimately reflect expectations of the performance of the firms in terms of their ability to generate returns on investment.
 This market is an important arena in which investors bet their dollars on how firms will perform in the future.
 In the aggregate, it amounts to an indicator of how investors think the economy is going to perform.
 With this background information, you can now evaluate the really interesting question: Is Mr.
 Greenspan right that stock markets are overvalued?

     <H2>Is Mr.
 Greenspan Right?
</H2>
     <P>Why do people think Mr.
 Greenspan is right about the stock market?
 Investors have access to all the information he has, and they invest their own funds, putting their money out with their bets.
 (Government agencies often supply Greenspan with new statistics a few hours before they go to the public.
) So why should we believe Greenspan?
 Or, is this a self-fulfilling prophecy: Mr.
 Greenspan tells us that the market is overvalued.
 He then raises interest rates, sending the market into a downward spin, and says ,"I told you so.
" But, why would he do that?
 He doesn t want the economy to sour.
 He will only raise rates if he feels he has to slow things down to prevent upward pressure on prices, to prevent inflation.

     <P>Perhaps there is a third possibility.
 Mr.
 Greenspan may simply be hedging his own bets, so that if he should decide to impose contractionary monetary policy (sell securities, dry up reserves, raise interest rates, slow the economy), then the market will have been warned and he won t be responsible for the ensuing stock market crash.
 By taking the glow off stock markets now, Mr.
 Greenspan is clearing the table so that he can act without worrying too much about being the fall guy for a stock market crash.
 
     <P>One should recall that in October of 1989, a major stock market crash confronted Mr.
 Greenspan.
 The crash was on the order of the 1929 October crash that preceded the great depression.
 Greenspan responded correctly to that crisis by offering to lend money to the large New York financial firms whatever they needed to honor brokers' claims.
 He would have been willing to accept toilet paper as collateral if need be to protect the solvency of financial markets.
 The stock market recovered in a few days and the crisis was over.
 Perhaps when he made that November speech Mr.
 Greenspan feared a repeat of October 1989.
 Or, perhaps he intended no such thing.
 Perhaps markets are just jittery and Greenspan's comments came at a time when any slight piece of bad news would cause a shock.
 We'll never know for sure.

     <H3>SOURCES</H3>
     <P>The US Federal Reserve System produces numerous free primers on monetary policy and on the operation of the Fed and the economy.
 A visit to the nearest Fed branch is a must for any journalist covering financial markets.
 
     <P><A HREF=" http://www.
bog.
frb.
fed.
us/">Federal Reserve Board Homepage</A>
     <P><B>Recommended FACS sources on Federal Reserve Policy:</B>
     <P><B>Richard Sweeney</B><BR>Sullivan/Dean Professor of International Business & Finance<BR>School of Business<BR>Georgetown University<BR> Box 571147<BR>Washington, DC 20057-1147<BR>202-687-3742<BR>e-mail: sweeneyr@gunet.
georgetown.
edu
     <P><B> Thomas D.
 Willett</B><BR>Horton Professor of Economics<BR>The Claremont Graduate School and Claremont McKenna College<BR>Claremont, CA  91711<BR>909/621-8787
     <P><b>Brian Motley</B><BR>Federal Reserve Branch Bank<BR>P.
O.
 Box 7702<BR>San Francisco, CA  94120<BR>MS 1130<BR>415/974-3203
     <P><B>Bernard Saffran</B><BR>Economics Department<BR>Swarthmore College<BR>201 Garrett Ave.
<BR>Swarthmore, PA  19081<BR>215/328-8124<BR>
     <P><B>Lawrence Slifman</B><BR>US Board of Governors, Fed.
 Washington, DC
     <P><B>Benjamin Friedman</B><BR>Department of Economics<BR>Harvard University<BR>Littauer 127<BR>Cambridge, MA  02138<BR>617-495-4246<BR>e-mail: bfriedman@harvard.
edu      
