<H1>The <EM>FACSNET </EM>Section on Covering Business</H1>

<P>These resources are made possible through a grant from the E.L. Wiegand Foundation

<p><EM>Editor James K. Gentry is dean of the School of Journalism at the University of Nevada, Reno, where he runs the Nevada Fellows Program in business reporting. Gentry is the former executive director of the Society of American Business Editors and Writers</EM>. 
<P>
<BR>

<FONT SIZE=+1 color=navy>Mapping the Business Beat</FONT>
<UL>
<a href="map.html">Understanding the Business Story</a> A survey of “the territory” for reporting on business including descriptions of alternative approaches by James K. Gentry with help from Donica Mensing. <BR>
</UL>
<P>

<FONT SIZE=+1 color=navy>The Numbers of Business Reporting</FONT>
<UL><a href="part1.html">Part I: Reading Business Financial Statements</a> By James K. Gentry. Description of  the major documents used in reporting business activity in annual statements. Includes the Income Statement, Balance Sheet, Cash Flows. Accounting philosophy behind some of the major entries.<BR>
<BR>
<a href="part2.html">Part II: Financial Analysis</a> By Gary L. Trennepohl. Uising the entries on the Balance Sheet and the Income Statement (Part I, above), this piece explains financial ratios, how to calculate them, and what they tell you about the health of a company.


</UL>


