<hr noshade size=3>
<BR>
<BR>
<H1>Financial Analysis</H1>



<p><STRONG>By Gary L. Trennepohl</STRONG>

<p>
<EM>Dr. Trennepohl is dean of the College of Business Administration at 
Oklahoma State University. He has worked with numerous journalists as the 
finance professor for the Nevada Fellows and Davenport Fellowship 
programs since 1983. He is author of two finance texts, and consults 
widely on finance and markets.
</EM>. 
<P>



	Once you feel comfortable with the entries on the balance sheet and 
income statement, you can move to the next step, analyzing a company’s 
performance. With a little practice, you can calculate financial ratios using 
balance sheet and income statement data to evaluate the financial health of 
a company. 
<P>
	To illustrate, we will use data from the annual reports of  Coca-Cola, 
PepsiCo and WalMart, all for fiscal 1995. WalMart is the world’s largest 
retailer, known for low prices and high volume, Coca-Cola is a premier soft-
drink company, and PepsiCo is a diversified food company with soft drinks, 
snack foods (e.g. Frito-Lay), and fast-food restaurant chains (such as KFC, 
Taco Bell and Pizza Hut) .
<P>
<H3>Evaluating Ratios</H3>

	To make sense of the ratios, it is necessary to compare them to 
benchmark values. One comparison is with similar firms in the same 
industry.  This technique is particularly helpful for large companies that have 
only a few competitors in their markets. Another procedure, especially 
usefule for smaller firms, is to compare their ratios to industry averages for 
similar sized firms.  Industry comparison data is available from Dun and 
Bradstreet and other sources. A third technique appropriate for all firms  is 
to compare data from the same firm through time. Changes in ratios through 
time may be caused by business cycles or management decisions that 
change the firm, which leads to good story ideas.
<P>
<H3>Analyzing the Numbers</H3>

	To evaluate the financial health of a company, focus on four areas:  
<OL>
<LI> liquidity, 
<LI> profitability, 
<LI> use of debt and 
<LI> return on equity. 

</OL>
Below, 
we’ll calculate ratios to evaluate each of these categories, and then combine 
three ratios to gain an overall perspective about how the company 
generates shareholder return. 
<P>
	Don’t be concerned if our ratios differ slightly from those reported in 
the company’s annual report or other financial publications. Different 
analysts use various calculations to smooth the data (e.g. using an average 
of beginning and ending values of certain accounts),  which they believe 
gives a better interpretation of certain ratios. We have used only year-end 
numbers for our calculations below. 
<P>
<H3>Liquidity</H3>

	Liquidity refers to a company’s ability to meet its requirements for 
cash. Liquidity is necessary to meet both expected and unexpected cash 
demands, so all businesses need liquidity to operate. Too little liquidity can 
stunt growth and ultimately could lead to bankruptcy if debts cannot be 
repaid.  However, too much liquidity can detract from profits, because liquid 
assets are low returning investments.  
<P>
	The standard measure of liquidity is the <STRONG>current ratio</STRONG>, calculated by 
dividing "current assets" by "current liabilities." The current ratio for 
WalMart of 1.54 indicates it is the most liquid of the three companies. The 
ratios for Coca-Cola and PepsiCo are close to, or below 1.00, not atypical 
for high quality companies with easy access to capital markets to finance 
unexpected cash requirements. However, smaller companies should have 
higher current ratios to meet unexpected cash requirements. The rule of 
thumb current ratio for small companies is 2:1, indicating the need for a 
level of safety in the ability to cover unforeseen cash needs from current 
assets.
<P>
<CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER>
        <TR>
                <TD ROWSPAN=2>Current ratio</TD>
                <TD><STRONG>WalMart</STRONG><BR>(Jan. 96)</TD> <TD><STRONG>Coca-Cola</STRONG><BR>(Dec.95)</TD> <TD><STRONG>PepsiCo</STRONG><BR>(Dec. 95)</TD>
        </TR>
        
       <TR>
              <TD>1.54</TD> <TD>0.74</TD> <TD>1.06</TD>
         </TR>
      
</TABLE>
</CENTER>



<H3>Profitability</H3>

	Two common measures of profitability are the <STRONG>net profit margin</STRONG> and 
the <STRONG>return on assets</STRONG>. Each provides a different perspective about the firm’s 
profits.
<P>
	To measure the profitability of a company’s operations, calculate the 
net profit margin (NPM), which is "net income" divided by "sales," with 
both entries coming from the income statement. Net profit margin indicates 
the percentage of each dollar of sales that the firm is able to flow to the 
bottom line as profit.  
<P>
	NPM is a function of the price of the product (which produces sales 
revenue) and efficiency of operations (cost of goods sold). A firm selling a 
unique product to a captive market may be able to charge a premium price 
and thus generate greater NPM. Conversely, a firm selling a generic product 
in a highly competitive market will have a low NPM. It must be a very 
efficient company, or it will not survive.  
<P>
	The net profit margins of our three sample firms illustrate these 
concepts.  WalMart’s NPM of 2.9% is low compared to the other 
companies, but is consistent with its image as a discount retailer. Coca-
Cola’s NPM of 16.6% is much higher than WalMart or PepsiCo, and is due 
primarily to its proprietary product and monopolies in certain foreign 
markets. PepsiCo derives the majority of its income from lower margin 
snack foods and restaurants;  less than half its sales come from soft drinks.
<P>
	The <STRONG>return on assets</STRONG> (ROA),  sometimes called <STRONG>return on investment</STRONG>, 
is calculated by dividing "net profit" by "total assets." It indicates the rate 
of return provided by the book value of the company’s assets. The higher 
the ROA, the more profitable the company. Consistent with the NPM, Coca-
Cola has the highest ROA of 16.6%, but WalMart’s 7.3% is now second, 
reflecting its ability to generate significant sales volume from its asset base.  
<P>
<CENTER>
<TABLE>
        <TR>
                <TH></TH> <TH>WalMart<BR>(Jan. '96)</TH> <TH>Coca-Cola<BR>(Dec. '95)</TH> <TH>PepsiCo<BR>(Dec. '95)</TH>
        </TR>
        <TR>
                <TD>Net profit margin</TD> <TD>2.9%</TD> <TD>16.6%</TD><TD>5.3%</TD>
        </TR>
        <TR>
                <TD>Return on assets</TD> <TD>7.3%</TD> <TD>19.9%</TD><TD>6.3%</TD>
        </TR>
<TR>
                <TD>Total asset turnover</TD> <TD>2.49</TD> <TD>1.20</TD><TD>1.20</TD>
        </TR>
<TR>
                <TD>Inventory turnover</TD> <TD>4.66</TD> <TD>6.21</TD><TD>14.16</TD>
        </TR>

</TABLE>        
</CENTER>
<P>

	
	Another indicator of a company’s ability to generate profit is the <STRONG>total 
asset turnover</STRONG>, calculated by dividing "sales" by "total assets." It indicates 
how effectively the company generates sales from its asset base. The more 
effective the company in generating sales revenue (the greater the amount 
of sales generated by a dollar invested in assets), the higher the asset 
turnover.  Differences in industries cause differences in asset structure and 
total asset turnover.  
<P>
	Coca-Cola’s and PepsiCo’s turnovers are slightly above 1.00, typical 
for big firms with large investment in fixed assets and inventories. However, 
WalMart’s ratio is twice as large, 2.48, driven primarily by its high inventory 
turnover and efficient use of fixed assets. Thus WalMart’s low NPM is offset 
to some extent by its ability to generate sales from its asset base (its a high 
volume, low overhead producer).
<P>
	For companies that have a large investment in inventory, it is useful 
to calculate the <STRONG>inventory turnover ratio</STRONG>, which is the "cost of goods sold" 
from the income statement divided by the "inventory" shown on the balance 
sheet.   Too low a turnover indicates too much investment in inventory, 
whereas too high a turnover could cause lost sales due to lack of 
merchandise to meet customer demand. WalMart and Coca-Cola have 
similar inventory turnover numbers while PepsiCo’s is higher. This reflects 
differences in their industries, with Pepsi’s snack food and restaurants 
driving the ratio higher than for typical merchandisers like WalMart and 
Coca-Cola.
<P>
<H3>Use of Debt</H3>

	<STRONG>Financial leverage</STRONG> is the use of fixed cost funds such as  debt or 
preferred stock to increase the common stockholder’s return. For example, 
if the firm can borrow at 8 percent and earn a rate of return on assets 
(ROA) of, say 12 percent, the 4 percent above the cost of funds will accrue 
directly to the common stockholders. Conversely, if earnings decline and the 
company’s return on assets falls below 8 percent, the deficit must be borne 
entirely by the common stockholders. Using debt in the firm produces a 
stream of earnings that has greater volatility (risk) than would occur in the 
same firm if it had less debt.  
<P>
	There is no rule of thumb to indicate the proper amount of debt for a 
firm.  One major factor is management’s willingness to accept financial risk. 
Some managers are more risk averse than others; consequently they  allow 
only a small amount of debt in their firm. Others see leverage as a means to 
increase profitability and therefore borrow substantially to expand their firm.   
<P>
	A second factor is earnings predictability. A company or industry 
whose earnings stream is more predictable can have a higher debt ratio and 
try to take advantage of the leverage it provides. Regulated utilities, for 
example, which have a predictable earnings stream typically have very high 
debt ratios while high tech companies often use very little debt, because 
their earnings are quite volatile. Because of the tax advantage of using debt 
(remember that interest expense is tax deductible for the firm while 
preferred and common stock dividends are not), it generally is agreed that 
the use of some debt is advantageous for the firm.  	
<P>
	Two debt ratios you should know are the <STRONG>debt to total assets ratio</STRONG>, or 
the "debt ratio," and the <STRONG>equity multiplier</STRONG>. The debt ratio is calculated as the 
sum of all the liability accounts divided by "total assets." 
<P>
	For our three sample firms, the numerator is the sum of everything on 
the right side of the balance sheet from "current liabilities" through 
"deferred income taxes." The debt ratio lies between zero and slightly less 
than1.00 with zero indicating no debt in the firm, and 99% indicating that 
the firm is almost totally financed by debt.  As you can see for our sample 
firms, their debt ratios vary from WalMart’s 60.7% to Pepsi’s 71.2%.  We 
can conclude that Pepsi is using more financial leverage in the firm and thus 
is exposed to more financial risk than WalMart and Coke.  We cannot say 
that one firm is right and the other is wrong in its financing approach.
<P>

<CENTER>
<TABLE>
        <TR>
                <TH></TH> <TH>WalMart<BR>(Jan. '96)</TH> <TH>Coca-Cola<BR>(Dec. '95)</TH> <TH>PepsiCo<BR>(Dec. '95)</TH>
        </TR>
        <TR>
                <TD>Debt ratio</TD> <TD> 60.7%</TD> <TD>64.2%</TD><TD> 71.2%</TD>
        </TR>
        <TR>
                <TD>Equity multiplier</TD> <TD> 2.54</TD> <TD>2.79</TD><TD>3.48</TD>
        </TR>

</TABLE>        
</CENTER>


<P>
	The <STRONG>equity multiplier</STRONG> is a similar calculation, determined by dividing 
"total assets" by the "common equity" account.  If a firm is totally financed 
by equity, the equity multiplier will equal 1.00, while the larger the number 
the more highly leveraged is the firm. Consistent with the "debt ratio," the 
equity multipliers of the three firms show that Pepsi has the greatest amount 
of leverage, and Coke has the lowest. We’ll use the equity multiplier later to 
help understand how a firm generates return to the stockholder’s 
investment.
<P>
<H3>Return on Equity</H3>

	Many would argue that the most important ratio to calculate for a 
company is its return on equity (ROE), which is "net income available to 
common stockholders" divided by "common equity." ROE represents the 
rate of return the company earned on the book value of its equity 
investment.  The higher the number, the greater the return the company is 
earning for its shareholders. For our sample companies, Coca-Cola has the 
greatest ROE, 55.6%, an exceptionally high number. WalMart’s is a very 
respectable 18.6% and PepsiCo’s is 22.0%. All three are relatively high 
compared to most companies.   
<P>

<CENTER>
<TABLE>
        <TR>
                <TH></TH> <TH>WalMart<BR>(Jan. '96)</TH> <TH>Coca-Cola<BR>(Dec. '95)</TH> <TH>PepsiCo<BR>(Dec. '95)</TH>
        </TR>
        <TR>
                <TD>Return on equity</TD> <TD> 18.6%</TD> <TD>55.6%</TD><TD> 22.0%</TD>
        </TR>
       
</TABLE>        
</CENTER>

<P>


<H3>Evaluating the ROE</H3>

	OK, you might say, I know something about liquidity, profit margin, 
asset turnover and debt ratios, but how does it all fit together?  WalMart 
has a lousy NPM, but its return on equity is better than many companies.  
Coke starts with a great NPM and generates an exceptional ROE.  How?  
<P>
	The answer is that basically three ratios drive the company’s ability to 
generate return to shareholders. They are:  (1) profitability from operations 
(the NPM),  (2) asset utilization (the total asset turnover), and (3) leverage 
(the equity multiplier).
<P>
	ROE can be calculated as the product of the "NPM" times the "total 
asset turnover" times the "equity multiplier." Knowing this relationship can 
help you understand and explain why a company makes certain financial 
decisions. For example, WalMart knows it has a low NPM by the nature of 
its business; therefore, it must excel at asset utilization and use an 
aggressive debt strategy to increase its ROE. 
<P>
	Coke, by contrast, has an excellent ROE which results from it high 
profit margin, effective asset utilization and use of leverage. Because of its 
high NPM, Coca-Cola could choose to use less debt in difficult economic 
times, and still earn a very respectable ROE. PepsiCo probably is pursuing 
an aggressive debt strategy because of the lower profitability of some of its 
product lines.
<P>

<CENTER>
<TABLE>
        <TR>
                <TH></TH> <TH>Return on<BR>equity =</TH> <TH>Net profit<BR>margin x</TH> <TH>Total asset<BR>turnover x</TH><TH>Equity<BR>multiplier</TH>
        </TR>
        <TR>
                <TD>WalMart</TD> <TD>18.6%</TD> <TD>2.9%</TD><TD>2.49</TD><TD>2.54</TD>
        </TR>
        <TR>
                <TD>CocaCola</TD> <TD>55.6%</TD> <TD>16.6%</TD><TD>1.20</TD><TD>2.79</TD>
        </TR>
<TR>
                <TD>PepsiCo</TD> <TD>22.0%</TD> <TD>5.3%</TD><TD>1.20</TD><TD>3.48</TD>
        </TR>

</TABLE>        
</CENTER>
<P>

<P>
	To really understand how these companies generate profit, it would 
be necessary to compare these ratios over a period of several years. 
Because financial markets love consistency, a company will be more highly 
valued if its results are consistent over time. For example, a company 
reporting a  NPM consistently at or above 15% over time will be viewed 
more favorably that one that reports 25% one year and 5% the next. 
Looking at these numbers through time will provide a better perspective 
about the firm. 
<P>
<H3>Using Financial Analysis</H3> 

	The examples above are a brief introduction to the arcane world of 
financial analysis. It is not intended to make you a financial expert, but to 
make you aware of the depth of information available in financial statements 
and to motivate you to further study by using one of the many texts 
available about financial analysis. 
<P>
	This exercise also should give you a greater appreciation for the 
financial data that is widely available from various investment services. Two 
popular ones  that provide a wealth of financial data including selected 
ratios are <STRONG>Bloomberg</STRONG>, the on-line data service, and <STRONG>Value Line</STRONG>, which 
provides a weekly report covering 1700 companies, including many of the 
ratios described above.
<P>
	Because there are thousands of paid financial analysts evaluating the 
financial data of most public companies, it is highly unlikely that you will 
discern information about the company from your analysis that others do 
not know. However, most analysts are looking at the company from a 
financial perspective, not as a business reporter. Their motivation is profit, 
not news.  
<P>
	Your ability to perform some basic financial analysis can give you an 
edge as a business reporter in developing story ideas about a company 
before other reporters think of them. Knowledge of terms familiar to the 
chief executive or chief financial officer will increase your credibility and 
help you to develop questions and to structure interviews to get the best 
possible information for a story you are working.  
<P>
	Finally, don’t be afraid to ask experts to help you understand and 
interpret the numbers you might calculate. In this case, the old adage that a 
little knowledge is a dangerous thing is very true. Experts can be stumped 
about income statement and balance sheet entries for firms they don’t 
cover, so don’t hesitate to question how to calculate a particular ratio if the 
accounting data seems confusing. Remember that your objective is to get 
behind the numbers and interpret what they tell you about the firm.    




<BR><BR>
<FONT SIZE=-2>Last Revised 28 October, 1996</FONT>

