<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Covering Business: Getting Started</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff">
<hr noshade size=3>
<CENTER>
<img src="http://www.facsnet.org/facsnet_grafix/report_tools/covering_business.gif" alt="Covering Business">
<P>
<H2>
Introduction</H2>
<p>By James K. Gentry with help from Donica Mensing.
</CENTER>
<hr noshade size=3>

<p><A NAME="introduction"><STRONG>Introduction</STRONG></A>

<p>When the Boston Globe's Mitch Zuckoff started work on his much-honored series, "Foul Trade," he knew enough about world trade to see what a challenging task lay ahead. But he had a strategy.  

<p>"It was an immediately daunting task because I was in Boston, not southeast Asia," Zuckoff says. "So I had to use all sorts of reporting techniques to get a sense of what was going on there."

<p>So Zuckoff launched a series of classic reporting maneuvers to prepare 
himself for the package examining how U.S. corporations conduct themselves in 
Third World countries. Before he was finished, Zuckoff had:

<ul>
<li>Waded through a thicket of databases, including Dialog, Vu-Text, 
Lexis/Nexis.</li>
<li>Scoured the morgues of Investigative Reporters and Editors, Inc., and 
numerous newspapers to examine other projects on trade issues.</li>
<li>Posted an e-mail query on ProfNet that yielded hundreds of responses. </li>
<li>Consumed hundreds of articles from obscure journals and trade magazines.</li>
<li>Interviewed experts ranging from academics specializing in labor issues and ethics to government officials to environmental groups.</li>
<li>Visited four countries to see manufacturing facilities and talk with hundreds of sources.</li>
</ul>

<p>The payoff, published in July 1994, was a detailed three-part series that  revealed U.S. companies' unsavory treatment of workers, consumers, and the environment in developing countries.
<p>The series won a number of awards, including the Livingston Award for Young Journalists for International Reporting and the Heywood Broun Award of the Newspaper Guild.
<p>Looking back, Zuckoff especially credits the experts in the Globe's electronic library for playing a key role in the series. "The people who work in a newspaper's library are very selfless. They're an enormous untapped, unappreciated resource at most newspapers."

<p><A NAME="gettingstarted"><STRONG>Getting started</STRONG></A>
<p>What separates a business story from other types of stories is the knowledge required to ask the right questions, to recognize newsworthy answers and to write a story in a way that readers without specialized knowledge will understand. Reporters who understand the subject can explain what the jargon means.
<p>The starting point in writing a business story is similar to the first step in reporting any story -- understanding the subject you're writing about. For business reporters, that almost always means some basic research -- in your newspaper's morgue, through electronic data bases, or at a university or public library.
<p>When Zuckoff started thinking about his series, "Foul Trade," he immersed himself in background. "This was a four-month project," Zuckoff says, "and I spent the first four weeks just talking with smart people, working the phones and reading material through my computer...I wanted to make sure I didn't  miss anything. That's why I spent so much time out there on the front end of the project."
<p>While most business reporters don't launch four-month projects, they nevertheless need to develop research skills, which are at the heart of good reporting. 
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=3>
<CENTER>
