Title: Covering Business: Reporting the Business Story -- the modern way
Link: <mailto:pattimcc>; rev="Made"
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Covering Business: Reporting the Business Story -- the modern way</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff">
<hr noshade size=3>
<CENTER>
<img src="../../facsnet_grafix/report_tools/covering_business.gif" alt="Covering Business">
<P>
<H2>
Reporting the Business Story -- the modern way</H2>
<p>By James K. Gentry with help from Donica Mensing.
</CENTER>
<hr noshade size=3>

<p>With the development of digital data bases and the growth of the Internet, the business reporter's job has changed over the past several years.   Although the tools have changed, the business reporter still needs to remember that the starting point in writing many business stories is similar to the first step in reporting any story-understanding the subject you're writing about. For the business reporter, that almost always means some basic research into the subject. For openers, check the paper's library  -- paper or electronic -- to learn what's been written locally about your topic or company.

<p>In the world of the Internet, that means knowing how to use some of the many search engines for scanning the World Wide Web, Usenet groups, and Gopher. Search engines such as Yahoo, Altavista and Lycos make it possible to find valuable background, numbers and tips among the chaos.

<p>Familiarity with Boolean search techniques and knowing which search engines to use for different tasks is helpful when working under deadline and looking for obscure or up-to-the-minute information. While a lot of worthless material is online, the reporter also can find invaluable, timely sources with up-to-date stock reports, SEC documents and market information. The World Wide Web is the easiest sector of the Internet to use and has numerous pages listing important business and investment sites.  Gopher provides access to many university and government databases and is searchable through Veronica or Archie. Usenet news groups are a good way to find story ideas, get tips on 
possible angles and monitor general discussion about particular issues or companies, and can be searched using engines such as DejaNews.

<p>When looking for background on a story, the searchable archives maintained by many online newspapers are a good source. <a href = "http://www.nytimes.com">The New York Times</a>, for example, has a searchable archive dating back to June 1980. The full-text of an article can be downloaded for a small fee ($1.95). If the reporter is tracking specific companies or industries over time, it would be useful to subscribe to a news clipping service that sends articles from specified papers and the wire services on customized topics directly to your e-mail address. Many of the Knight-Ridder papers offer this feature under a premium service called NewsHound; The New York Times calls its service the Clipper.

<p>Increasing numbers of government records are available online, including many documents filed with the SEC. Both the New York University <a href = "http://www.edgar.stern.nyu.edu">EDGAR database</a> and the <a href = "http://www.sec.gov">SEC Web site</a> provide searchable databases of SEC filings. The New York University site has a utility which converts SEC EDGAR documents into Word for Windows documents; it also includes company profiles from the R.R. Donnelley Library of SEC materials. 

<p>The <a href = "http://www.access.gpo.gov/su_docs/aces/aaces004.html">Government Printing Office</a> (<A HREF="http://www.lib.utk.edu/gpo/GPOsearch.html">another version at University of Tennessee, Knoxville</A>)  maintains a Web site that includes a searchable full-text database of the Federal Register, Congressional Record, congressional bills, public laws and General Accounting office reports. 

<p>Corporate data is of increasing interest online. Three of the many sites which keep up-to-date links to the stock markets, finance pages, stock quotes, trade magazines and investment sources are <a href = "http://www.moneypages.com/syndicate">The Syndicate</a>, <a href = "http://pathfinder.com/money/">Money Magazine</a> and the <a href = "http://www.krislyn.com/sites/">Krislyn Corporation</a>. 

<p>Besides ProfNet, another service for locating academic experts on business issues is <a href = "http://top.monad.net/~gehrung/">Bznet, USA</a>. You can e-mail a request from the Web site and Bznet promises direct responses from its pool of academic and government information sources within 24 hours.

<p>Many of the directories and indexes available in libraries are moving to the Internet. <a href = "http://www.dbisna.com">Dun & Bradstreet</a> and <a href="http://www.disclosure.com">Disclosure</a> (which offers real-time EDGAR filings) for example, offer a mix of timely business reports available by subscription or by one-time fee.

