Title: Covering Business: Pulling it all together
Link: <mailto:pattimcc>; rev="Made"
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Covering Business: Pulling it all together</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff">
<hr noshade size=3>
<CENTER>
<img src="../../facsnet_grafix/report_tools/covering_business.gif" alt="Covering Business">
<P>
<H2>
Pulling it all together</H2>
<p>By James K. Gentry with help from Donica Mensing.
</CENTER>
<hr noshade size=3>


<p>Most stories don't fit neatly into just one of the types or categories above. More commonly, reporters provide answers to a variety of questions about a company. For an example, let's look at a recent Wall Street Journal analysis of the challenges facing Packard Bell. 

<p>Reporter Jim Carlton draws on information gleaned from "interviews with dozens of customers, vendors, past employees and others" to build a profile of a company that "has for some time been suffering chronic losses, sliding market share, shriveling growth rates and complaints from customers and suppliers."

<p>Carlton explains how Packard Bell scored early successes by choosing as its target market "an unguarded industry flank, the mass retail market, then neglected by other computer marketers, and deploying cunning strategems." The company also convinced "mass retailers such as Wal-Mart Stores...that they could sell computers as easily as garden supplies." 

<p>Packard Bell's pricing strategy has been to ignore "profit margins to build market share and consistently priced his machines at 15 percent  to 20 percent below those of other PC makers." The outcome of the strategy was to assure the loyalty of retailers because the low prices sparked mass sales and "transferred some or all of his profits to them (the retailers)."

<p>On the finance side, Carlton points out that Packard Bell required a $470 million emergency loan from Intel and a $700 million capital infusion from its minority shareholders. Carlton also notes that the conditions of that deal could cost Packard Bell's chief executive Beny Alagem majority control of the company.

<p>Carlton takes his reporting another step by informing readers that the privately held company had "substantial losses" last year. His source is Sacramento City Treasurer Thomas Friery, one of the few people outside the closely held company to get a look at its books (because the city loaned Packard Bell $26 million in 1995)." Carlton then adds, "As a result, Packard Bell has had to play an increasingly tricky game of balancing its cash needs with its creditors' demands."

<p>Carlton then notes that, according to a former employee, the company "has often deferred vendor payments as long as 100 days, compared with an industry average of between 30 and 45 days, as he (Alagem) waited for new sales to come up with the money." 

<p>Packard Bell has money problems with other vendors, Carlton reports, citing a lawsuit filed in Los Angeles state court by Hall-Mark Electronics seeking $512,400 for computer parts.

<p>By citing the overall handling of finances, Carlton give an insight into Packard Bell's management. Carlton also describes other instances of Alagem in action , including an anecdote in which the CEO grabs a golf cart and drives an advertising executive through a warehouse, shouting, "Ship that! Ship that!"

<p>Overall, Carlton's piece is mostly analysis with a bit of a profile of the CEO tossed in. It has no true news peg but still manages to be quite "newsy." But because of the use of the four approaches, the reader gains true insight into Packard Bell and Alagem.


<HR NOSHADE SIZE=3>
