Title: Covering Business: What can go wrong: How three magazines handled Patten Corp.
Link: <mailto:pattimcc>; rev="Made"
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Covering Business: What can go wrong: How three magazines handled Patten Corp.</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff">
<hr noshade size=3>
<CENTER>
<img src="../../facsnet_grafix/report_tools/covering_business.gif" alt="Covering Business">
<P>
<H2>
What can go wrong: How three magazines handled Patten Corp.</H2>
<p>By James K. Gentry with help from Donica Mensing.
</CENTER>
<hr noshade size=3>


<p>To gain a better appreciation for the importance of doing serious reporting, let's look at how three national business magazines handled stories about land developer Harry Patten. Although the stories all appeared just after the start of 1987, the lessons are as vibrant as if they had been published yesterday.

<p>The first story appeared in a Fortune magazine section entitled "The Year's 50 Most Fascinating Business People" where Patten was cited as a rising "backwoods tycoon" in a piece headlined "Ex-Hick Sells Sticks, Is Market Pick." The breathlessly complimentary story centered around how "Patten and his rural land-sales company ... are quietly defying a law of physics: What goes up must come down." For evidence the story cited profit growth so rapid that  Drexel Burnham Lambert analyst Kurt A. Feuerman had raised "his earnings estimates five times in nine months." It also noted the company's "explosive" growth and soaring profits. The story, however, failed to note that Drexel was one of Patten's banks.

<p>Along the way, the reader is treated to a number of folksy nuggets, learning that Patten "claims his best friend is 'my dog, Duke,'" that his second wife is a former Pan Am stewardess, that Patten owns two vacation homes, that he is collecting a stable of race horses and that he enjoys chartering a Caribbean sailboat or Western skiing. Patten offers, "Rich or poor, I'd rather be rich."

<p>Fortune also assures the reader that Patten is inclined "to extreme conservatism in business" and  provides assurrances that he "keeps most of the risk out of his business."

<p>At about the same time, Business Week featured Patten in its "Inside Wall Street" feature with a piece entitled "Landing a Bargain with Patten." The story praised Patten as the kind of company that investors wish they'd bought into when the company first went public. It cited dramatic rises in sales and earnings per share. The prognosis was so good that Drexel analyst Feuerman gushed, "If there's a risk in our estimates, it is that they are too low."

<p>By that time investors might have been asking themselves if Patten Corp. were too good to be true. In fact, that's exactly what Forbes' Gretchen Morgenson was asking herself. Her answer -- yep, too good to be true.

<p>In a Jan. 12 piece entitled, "Old Game, New Twist," Forbes set out its premise in the subhead, "Fortune magazine cites Patten Corp.'s founder as one of the year's most fascinating business people. Forbes finds Patten's fancy bookkeeping depressingly familiar."

<p>Morgenson dissected Patten's empire, setting up what's to come in the first  paragraphs: "Forget Florida. Today's undeveloped land hype centers on good old New England...Who's there to sell wide-open spaces to cramped but creditworthy city dwellers? Patten Corp...." Morgenson follows by describing how Patten buys hundreds of acres of land and divides them into 15-acre plots and sells them for about $1,500 an acre, and how per share growth had almost quadrupled in two years. 

<p>Then she starts getting serious. Morgenson explains how Drexel "comanaged  Patten's $34.5 million convertible bond offering last May and holds warrants on the company's stock. The broker also published a series of glowing research reports on Patten." In two sentences, Morgenson displays Drexel's incentive to see the stock price rise -- the warrants -- and the potential conflict of interest in a Drexel analyst praising the stock of the same company.

<p>In the following paragraph, Morgenson describes how "Fortune recently named founder Harry S. Patten one of the year's most fascinating business people and rhapsodized about his luxurious lifestyle." 

<p>Then Morgenson gets tough: "Patten's earnings suffer serious shrinkage when scrutinized. And the asset side of the company's balance sheet looks a bit bloated."

<p>Morgenson follows up by questioning the way Patten books its revenues, although it receives only 10 percent to 50 percent of land sales in cash. She points out that Patten carries more than $17 million in receivables with but $10,000 in reserve for possible losses. Morgenson observes that "Patten's accounting techniques are, to put it mildly, aggressive." She compares the costs and expenses against Patten's revenues and determines that the company is operating at a negative cash flow.

<p>Morgenson notes that tax reform could have an impact on both potential property buyers and Patten itself, although Patten officials deny the bill could do damage. Morgenson, however, speculates that strong revenue growth before the end of Patten's fiscal year might have been due to a "last-minute sales push in which prospective customers were encouraged to take advantage of the disappearing tax deduction."

<p>Morgenson further seals her case by relying on the SEC Form 144 to report that in a recent 12-month period, "Patten executives were unloading shares of their stock. For every Patten insider who bought shares, nine of his colleagues were selling." She concludes with, "Do they know something other investors don't?" 

<p>Almost a year later, Morgenson paid a return visit to Patten Corp. in a story entitled, "Suckering the City Bumpkins." Morgenson's piece pointed out that Patten was a strong stock several years earlier, "zooming from around $3 to nearly $19." Then she notes that the stock has settled back to around 3 3/4 and that officials in five states "are investigating the Big Board-listed company's advertising and sales practices for violations of consumer protection statutes." She follows that by citing Patten documents filed with the SEC that state "'a limited number of lots' worth some $2.4 million 'may have been sold' without meeting 'technical statutory exemption requirements.'" 

<p>Morgenson then cites a number of sources who think the $2.4 million is far too low. After noting the rising number of complaints against Patten, Morgenson reports that "very, very quietly, Patten is buying back property in numerous areas, either because lots didn't meet regulations or because buyers became unhappy when they couldn't use their property as planned." 

<p>The piece concludes that Kurt Feuerman, the Drexel analyst who was touting Patten earlier, had stopped following the industry. 

<p>In early April 1996, Patten Corp. was selling for around 4 1/2.


