<DOCNO>WT24-B02-32</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA062-000351-B041-258</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.facsnet.org:80/report_tools/newsbackgrounders/side4.html 132.249.40.46 19970115194451 text/html 4845
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: WN/1.14.6
Date: Wed, 15 Jan 1997 19:44:51 GMT
Last-modified: Thu, 09 Jan 1997 21:18:29 GMT
Content-type: text/html
Title: Reporting Tips
Link: <mailto:pattimcc>; rev="Made"
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Reporting Tips</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<center>
<img border=0 src="../../facsnet_grafix/report_tools/sidebar1.gif"
alt="Sidebar: "><br><h1>Reporting Tips</h1>
</center>
<hr>Legitimate confusion and deliberate misinformation abound in the global climate change issue. These cautionary tips will help you avoid both.
<br>
<ol>
<br>
<li>Despite its name, "global warming" is not likely to produce a uniform warming of the Earth's surface; the changes are expected to differ between regions, seasons, day and night. Some regions may even experience cooler average temperatures.
<br>
<li>Daily weather and even seasonal and annual averages are highly variable, so it is difficult to discern trends. Hot summers, droughts and unusually large numbers of hurricanes provide little evidence that climate change is occurring. Similarly, long-term cooling in a region does not prove that global warming is not occurring. 
<br>
<li>Climate change depends on the concentrations of carbon dioxide and other greenhouse gases. Since these gases remain in the atmosphere for decades, their concentrations are determined by average emissions over many years. Emissions in a single year are unimportant. 
<br>
<li>The claim that "the uncertainties are too great to warrant preventive measures" is no more, or less, legitimate than the claim that "the uncertainties are too great to permit continued emissions." As Professor Alan Manne of Stanford University has written, there are elements of truth in both [of the seemingly contradictory maxims] "look before you leap" and "you can cross that bridge when you come to it."
<br>
<li>Be aware of the orientations of analysts who offer perspectives on the potential for technological changes to provide low-cost measures for reducing greenhouse-gas emissions. Engineers tend to be optimistic, finding pervasive opportunities to save energy and reduce emissions inexpensively, even opportunities to reduce emissions and save money too. Economists tend to be skeptical of these "free lunches"(and lunches you are paid to eat), since they assume that people are adept at serving their own interests. Economists point to factors the engineers may overlook, such as "rebound," where greater energy efficiency, by reducing operating costs, can lead to greater consumption. (In a well-known joke, two economists spy a $10 bill lying on the sidewalk. Neither retrieves it, believing that if it were genuine, someone else would have already have picked it up.)
<br>
<li>Climate change and stratospheric-ozone depletion are often confused, which is not surprising since the problem are interrelated. Chlorofluorocarbons contribute to each, depleting ozone by transporting chlorine to the stratosphere and enhancing greenhouse warming by absorbing infrared radiation from the Earth's surface. Ozone depletion and global warming both cool the stratosphere, which reduces the extent of ozone depletion. 
<br>
<li>Most of the benefits of limiting climate change may accrue to the future populations of today's developing countries because those countries will account for most of the world's population and because sensitivity to climate seems to decrease with industrialization. As University of Maryland economist Tom Schelling asks, to the extent that the industrialized countries are willing to help the developing countries, why should they target aid to the future populations of those countries who will be, in all likelihood, better off than the current populations?  
<br>

<br>

<br>
<hr><center><h3>Return to <a href="../../report_tools/newsbackgrounders/back4.html#sidebar">Global Climate Change: Are We Over-driving Our Headlights?</h3></center></html>

