<DOCOLDNO>IA062-000351-B041-422</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.facsnet.org:80/report_tools/newsbackgrounders/side14.html 132.249.40.46 19970115194709 text/html 2640
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: WN/1.14.6
Date: Wed, 15 Jan 1997 19:47:15 GMT
Last-modified: Thu, 09 Jan 1997 21:18:29 GMT
Content-type: text/html
Title: Reporting Tips
Link: <mailto:pattimcc>; rev="Made"
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Reporting Tips</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff"><center><img border=0 src="../../facsnet_grafix/report_tools/sidebar1.gif"
alt="Sidebar: "><h1>Reporting Tips</h1></center><hr><OL>
<br>
<LI>Since people lose jobs suddenly and often in batches, they are easy to find and usually make good stories. But what are you doing to cover the winners from trade? How will consumers benefit? What businesses benefit? What jobs will "creative destruction" create?
<br>
<LI>Comparisons from other places and other times can be useful in evaluating the merits of trade. Think about the effects of the Smoot-Hawley Tariff in the 1930s or the protectionism adopted by most of Latin America and the Soviet Bloc since the 1930s.
<br>
<li>Take an economist to lunch (or breakfast or dinner). While most economists will tell you that there is no such thing as a free lunch, it is amazing how many of them will respond to your offer to share their views on the trade issue over a meal.
<br>
</OL>
<br>
<H3>Further Reading</H3>
<br>
Two short books worth consulting on the trade issue are: Jagdish Bhagwati, <CITE>Protectionism</CITE> (Cambridge, Mass., MIT Press, 1989); and<CITE> Trade Policy and U.S. Competitiveness,</CITE> edited by Claude E. Barfield and John H. Makin (Washington, D.C., American Enterprise for Public Policy Research, 1987).
<br>

<br>

<br>
<hr><center><h3>Return to <a href="../../report_tools/newsbackgrounders/back14.html#sidebar">Sorting Out the Trade Debate</h3></center></html>

<br>
<br>
<center>
<a href="http://www.facsnet.org/navigation.map">
<IMG  border=0 Align=Top SRC="http://www.facsnet.org/facsnet_grafix/splash/navigation_bar.gif" ISMAP></a><br>
