<html>
<head>
<title>
Risk Handbook--Footnotes</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<hr noshade size=3>
<CENTER>
<img src="image/risk_book_banner_small.gif" alt="Reporting On Risk">
<P>
<H2>
Risk Footnotes</H2>
</CENTER>
 <hr noshade size=3>
<P>
<DL>
<DT>
<B>
extrapolation:</B>
<DD>
the process of estimating or inferring something by extending or projecting known information, often by mathematical equations.</DL>
<HR>
<A NAME="major_component">
Other components</A>
 are toxicity assessment (Chapter 3) and problem identification and risk characterization (Chapter 1).<P>
**Ideally, scientists would like to know the amount of chemical that gets to the site in the body where toxicity occurs. Since this is not possible in most cases, the amount that the individual is in contact with is used as the measure of exposure. Exposure can lead to either local effects (burns, rashes, etc.) as a result of direct contact, or to systemic (whole body) effects when it is absorbed into the bloodstream.</KBD>
 <HR>
<P>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=3>
<CENTER>
