<html><head> <title>Product Tampering: A Worldwide Problem</title></hea
d>
 <body bgcolor="#ffffff">
 
<hr noshade size=3>
<center>
<img src="http://www.facsnet.org/facsnet_grafix/report_tools/product_ta
mp_banner_small.gif">
<br>
</center>
 
 <hr noshade size=3>


<h3>Corporate Guidelines</h3>
 
<h2>Survey of U. S. Companies' Responses</h2>

<i>Dr. Deborah Lowes crisis communications study of Fortune 500 
manufacturing 
companies crisis guidelines created in the aftermath of tampering threats 
or incidents.</i><p>


 <b>Johnson & Johnson</b>, Tylenol, Sept. 29, 1982 
 <li> Set up a crisis management team and plan. Focus on the key people
who need to be involved. Make sure phone numbers of company and government
officials are useable outside business hours, are current, and are carried
at all times. The incident and journalists' inquires could be in the
middle of the night. 
 <li> Limit the number of spokespeople.
 <li> Use the latest technology for news conferences.<p>

 <b>Thomas Lipton Co.</b>, Chicken Noodle,  Cup-A-Soup,  Aug. 4, 1986 
 <li> Regionalize or localize coverage of the tampering incident if possible.
 <li> Be open with the media but be brief and characterize the company as 
the victim, not a villain.
 <li> Prioritize news coverage during a crisis.<p>

 <b>Gerber Products</b>, Baby Food,  Feb. 20, 1986 
 <li> To show concern, companies must respond with their side of the 
story within 24 to 48 hours of a crisis.
 <li> Companies need to provide broadcast media with visuals to show that 
the company cares about the safety of the public.
 <li> To craft quick responses to media inquires, use technology to set  
up an early warning system that feeds into the crisis management team for 
all complaints.<p>

 <b>Proctor and Gamble</b>, Encaprin,  March 27, 1986 
 <li> Understand the scope of the problem before talking to  the press.
 <li> When you get false phone calls, track them down and prosecute. Make 
this a part of the media strategy for the company.<p>

 <b>General Foods</b>, Jell-O,  July 11, 1986 
 <li> Go to the media where there is a threat because the company      
and the public are the victims.
 <li> Demand responsible reporting.<p>

 <b>Pepsico</b>, Slice Soda,  July 12, 1986 
 <li> Emphasize that the threat is geographically limited.
 <li> Maintain close links with key officials and government agencies,  
locally as well as nationally.<p>

 <b>Pepsico</b>, Diet Pepsi Cola,  June 9, 1993 
 <li> Responded quickly and created easy media access to executives  and 
facilities.<p>

Not all companies in the study chose a pro-active media strategy. Some 
chose a more 
conservative approach. These companies worked from the security point of 
view. From 
an enforcement standpoint, if putting on the air threats that are 
verified as true  creates 
more incidents and more danger to the public, security experts argue that 
keeping a low 
profile may be in the public interest. The Grocery Manufacturers of 
America worked with 
John Lyon and Jonas Rappaport from Johns Hopkins University. Their 
research on 
tampering indicated that a cautious approach was best. That meant not 
telling the public 
anything beyond what was essential to inform them about a real public 
health threat. 
Tampering threats, until they were verified, were not disclosed to the 
public. In some 
cases, this policy of not sharing information on a threat until it was 
verified was observed 
in  reporting incidents to the FDA or FBI. Some experts would argue that 
this is why the 
number of tampering threats in the FDA data base is significantly lower 
than the actual 
number that companies had to cope with during the height of the tampering 
crisis.<p>

A major structural change has taken place inside American companies. The 
study showed 
that 78 percent of Fortune 500 companies had created crisis teams and 
plans to respond to 
targeting threats and incidents. <p>

Some companies did not immediately change their packaging in the wake of 
a product 
tampering threat. The study found that by 1988, eighty-nine percent of 
companies were 
putting their products in tamper-evident packaging. Variables that might 
have delayed the 
companies reaction included cost factors and lack of government 
regulation. <p>

<h3>Defensive Measures Adopted</h3>

The 1983 Anti-Tampering Act required tamper-evident packaging for 
over-the-counter 
drugs and some cosmetic and hygiene products. Since 1992, food companies 
have been 
adopting tamper-evident packaging voluntarily, but still may face FDA 
regulation.<p>

Along with these defensive measures, U.S. companies have tightened 
security at 
manufacturing plants and bought tampering insurance. Executives have 
invested in 
technology, including batch control to track products from manufacturing 
to retail outlets. 
In an effort to manage the tampering problem, U.S. companies have worked 
together in 
an unprecedented way, as well as with trade associations and government 
agencies. <p>

Trade associations in the food and pharmaceutical industries banded 
together to create 
crisis management teams and plans. The trade associations, including the Non-
Prescription Drug Association, the National Association of Food 
Processors, the Food 
Marketing Institute and the Grocery Manufacturers of America, also worked 
on crisis 
security planning. Former FBI and top security professionals helped them 
draft crisis 
policies and methods to deal with tampering threats, as well as threat 
analysis, decision 
analysis, extortion, profile analysis, and ways to reduce the 
vulnerability of their member 
corporations. These methods use high tech approaches like artificial 
intelligence and 
profile methods developed by the FBI. They are invaluable to 
multinational companies 
and trade associations overseas.<p>

<h3>High Tech Advancement is Slow Overseas</h3>

Journalists must recognize that many companies overseas do not have the 
technology to 
do quick threat assessment. Companies overseas are just beginning to 
recognize the need 
for product tampering crisis teams and plans. Packaging is another area 
in which progress 
lags behind the U.S., but a few food products in Europe are beginning to 
be sold in 
tamper-evident packaging.<p>

<h3>Coverage Overseas is Difficult</h3>

For companies faced with organized marketplace terrorism overseas, the 
key is to 
coordinate efforts with the government. The attacks may be politically 
motivated and 
aimed at the government and the economy more than at an individual 
company. For the 
journalist covering the story overseas, this means access to crisis 
planning meetings 
between companies and the government will be crucial.<p>

<h3>United States Coverage is a Perspective Problem</h3>

Organized marketplace terrorism is an emerging trend in the United States 
with isolated 
incidents created by a few groups. The marketplace terrorism story is one 
that should be 
tracked. Crucial to coverage will be an understanding of the high tech 
solutions that are 
being developed to handle aspects of the problem and sources who can 
explain those 
solutions simply to listeners, viewers, and readers. Experts in this 
country include 
consultants, authors, government agency contacts, and crisis management 
specialists. 
Because the U.S. faced an extensive problem with marketplace terrorism, 
its crisis teams 
and plans are in place in the food and pharmaceutical industries. The 
security, legal, 
packaging, and insurance industries are now helping these industries to 
cope with the 
problem of marketplace terrorism.<p>

Journalists should compile resources from all areas, so that when the 
story arises, all 
aspects of threat assessment from government to business can be covered 
effectively. 
Most important will be discovering the scope of the problem. It must be 
determined  
whether the incident is politically motivated and directed at the 
economy, directed at one 
aspect of how the company does testing (as in animal rights incidents), 
or is simply a case 
of random tampering directed at the company. Coverage of tampering 
incidents must now 
put the incident within these perspectives. Discovering which motive was 
underlying the 
incident will be the challenge for the journalist, for the company, and 
for the 
government.<p>



<br>
<br>
<center>
<a href="http://www.facsnet.org/navigation.map">
<IMG  border=0 Align=Top SRC="http://www.facsnet.org/facsnet_grafix/splash/navigation_bar.gif" ISMAP></a><br>
