<DOCHDR>
http://www.facsnet.org:80/report_tools/guides_primers/tampering/coping.html 132.249.40.46 19970115203727 text/html 9049
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: WN/1.14.6
Date: Wed, 15 Jan 1997 20:37:30 GMT
Last-modified: Thu, 09 Jan 1997 21:18:29 GMT
Content-type: text/html
Title: File coping.html
Link: <mailto:pattimcc>; rev="Made"
</DOCHDR>
<html><head> <title>Product Tampering: A Worldwide Problem</title></hea
d>
 <body bgcolor="#ffffff">
 
<hr noshade size=3>
<center>
<img src="http://www.facsnet.org/facsnet_grafix/report_tools/product_ta
mp_banner_small.gif">
<br>
</center>
 
 <hr noshade size=3>

 
<h3>Journalists' Guidelines</h3>
 
<h2>Coping with Domestic and International Product Tampering</h2>

<br clear>

Effective threat assessment is essential if reporters are to find out
whether the terrorist group is trying to use the media to extort money,
panic the public or threaten the company. The reporter needs to assess the
threat and check the facts. Deadlines mean a reporter needs to reach
experts quickly for information. It is important to know what questions to
ask, but knowing who to call is even more important.<p>

<h3>Call the company.</h3>

Get access to companies' threat verification processes. Edward Arlen Marks
put rat poison in Contac, Dietac and Teldrin and then called TV newsrooms
in hopes of making money in the stock market. When ABC News received a
tampering threat phone call, Peter Jennings contacted President William
Learnard of SmithKline Beckman's Consumer Product Division, who hadn't
known about the incident. Jennings held the story for three days while the
threat was being verified. Learnard said the delay "gave the company, the
FDA, and the FBI time to handle the situation responsibly." <p>

If a reporter calls the company, the company should keep him or her
apprised of the threat assessment, and his or her story will have more
depth and details. <p>

<h3>Call the FDA.</h3>

Call Richard Swanson, the FDA's director of emergency epidemiology
operations in Rockville, Maryland.  Swanson has created a centralized
operation that coordinates action among the company, news organizations,
trade associations, the FBI, local law enforcement agencies and a variety
of public health officials. If the threat is made against a U.S. company,
the FDA maintains a 24-hour emergency service to handle marketplace
terrorism. In the case of overseas threats, the FDA works with Customs
Department, the U.S. Department of Counter-Terrorism and the Justice
Department to manage the situation. The FDA is the lead agency in this
area. <p>

The company should notify the FDA and the FBI that there is a problem with
tampering, but the journalist should still call government agencies
because different agencies handle different parts of the story.<p>

The FDA is in charge of testing products threatened by marketplace
terrorists. Companies often test their products as well. Reporters can
talk to research people at either the FDA lab or a company lab. The FDA
has a threat assessment database designed to track tampering threats. Its
information can be obtained by Freedom of Information requests. <p>

<h3>Call the FBI.</h3>

The FBI's Behavioral Science Services Investigative Support Unit is in the
Center for the Analysis of Violent Crime. This unit, in Quantico,
Virginia, profiles terrorists, serial murderers and other violent
criminals. It is staffed with top behavioral scientists. Its background
profile information gives depth to stories on marketplace terrorism. The
center's Behavioral Science Profiling unit is excellent for interviews or
background information about motivations behind these crimes. It also
focuses on prosecution. Under the 1983 anti-tampering legislation, the FBI
is responsible for prosecuting people charged in tampering threats and
incidents. As incidents move from marketplace terrorism to other types,
the FBI is a good source of information for statistics on prosecution. <p>

<h3>Purchase crisis equipment.</h3>

Try to get your radio or TV station, newspaper or magazine to invest in
equipment to tape incoming phone calls. Ask for installation of Caller ID,
the technology that lets a company instantly know the caller's name and
location; it's a key to effective threat assessment. Voice characteristics
can help determine a profile. If your organization records the tampering
threat, the recording can give the FBI's behavioral scientists clues to
help in the investigation and add to a comprehensive story. The technology
for voice identification and profile analysis is impressive and highly
effective. Since many threat calls come directly to newsrooms, crisis
training can teach journalists to get more information from the person
making the threat. Crisis threat questions should determine what specific
products, what stores and what geographic locations were targeted. <p>

<h3>Create a file of crisis story contacts.</h3>

This file should list experts in crisis management for product tampering
terrorism, the law, tamper-evident packaging, counter-terrorism, law
enforcement and security. It can include experts who can explain decision
support software. This valuable tool can perform information scenario
analysis to help the crisis team in planning and making decisions before
an incident of marketplace terrorism.<p>

Cross impact simulation is one technique that can be adapted for product
tampering. It was originally used to predict corporate susceptibility to
crisis and to reduce corporate vulnerability to it. C.F. Smart, W.A. 
Thompson and I.B. Vertinski are three experts who research cross impact
simulation, cross impact analysis, and trend impact analysis.<p>

<h3>Overseas coverage tips</h3>

All of these sources have been valuable in analyzing product tampering
terrorism overseas in our research.  They are equally valuable to
journalists. Knowing whom to call is essential. Little has been written on
overseas product tampering except in trade publications. This makes
writing a factual story difficult. It should be noted that requests for
data gathered by the U.S. government often must be accompanied by a
Freedom of Information request letter from the journalist or the academic
doing the research. <p>

Call trade associations. When covering marketplace terrorism stories
concerning product tampering, trade and professional associations are
instant sources of contact names in companies and in government. Since
they are working actively on the problem, this is often the fastest way to
get background. <p>

Ask your contacts with the FDA and FBI for overseas contacts in
government. A contact name for a cooperative government official is
essential to a U.S. journalist calling overseas, because no other country
has a centralized agency like the FDA. Officials may not be very helpful
on the phone unless a U.S.  colleague has paved the way for you.<p>

Call international insurance companies. The major insurance companies that
carry special services for product tampering, kidnapping and bomb threats
are Lloyd's of London, American International Underwriters Special
Services Division and Reliance. Insurance companies are deeply interested
in extortion payoffs and security measures in terrorism, and can provide
background information on marketplace terrorism.<p>

Call the State Department Office of Counter-Terrorism. This office
collects information on terrorism directed against U.S. businesses.
Although it does not now collect information on marketplace terrorism
incidents such as product tampering, it does have information that would
help to cover such a story. It has statistics on the methods that
terrorists use against business, including bombing, arson, armed attacks,
kidnapping with extortion, and hijacking. In addition, it keeps
information on profiles of organized groups as well as on how many
incidents are directed against U.S. targets in every country.<p>

Call overseas universities' public relations departments and ask for
experts conducting tampering research.  Often a professor in the
international relations department, the marketing department or the
packaging design department will be studying information on tampering and
can give insights and suggest other experts who might be helpful. <p>


<br>
<br>
