<html><head> <title>Product Tampering: A Worldwide Problem</title></hea
d>
 <body bgcolor="#ffffff">
 
<hr noshade size=3>
<center>
<img src="http://www.facsnet.org/facsnet_grafix/report_tools/product_ta
mp_banner_small.gif">
<br>
</center>
 
 <hr noshade size=3>

 
<h2>Journalists' Guidelines</h2>

by <strong>Thomas Cashman</strong> and <strong>Deborah Lowe</strong><p>

<br clear>

<i>Dr. Thomas Cashman works with Interactive Corporate Learning in San 
Rafael, California. He conducts 
interactive seminars for corporations on a variety of business topics.</i><p>

<i>Dr. Deborah Lowe is associate professor of marketing at San Francisco 
State University's School of 
Business. She specializes in crisis management planning, specifically 
regarding marketplace 
terrorism.</i><p>

Product tampering is emerging as a major problem in the U.S. and abroad. 
The trend internationally is 
toward product tampering incidents coupled with extortion demands. This 
new version of an old story 
creates coverage challenges for reporters. Overseas marketplace terrorism 
cases covered in the news fall 
into two categories, malicious tempering and politically-motivated 
tampering.<p>

<h3>Malicious Tampering with Extortion</h3>

The terrorists' motive here is money. They usually contact a company and 
make demands before going to 
the press. Companies with insurance may decide to make the payment rather 
than suffer a drop in sales. If 
the company doesn't make the payment, the terrorists call newsrooms. 
Extortion tampering can be political 
or social in nature, with the money to be used to finance a cause.<p>

In this tampering threat or incident, the terrorists call news 
organizations first and make threats, attempting 
to reduce public confidence in the company or the government. If the 
attack is against the government, then 
the objective is to damage the country's economy. If the company is the 
target of the attack, the objective is 
to damage sales of its products.<p>

<h3>Politically-Motivated Tampering</h3>

In Europe, past tampering threats have usually been called in by 
individuals. A new type of malicious 
tampering, sometimes coupled with extortion, has become a reality for 
foreign countries and corporations as 
well as American multinationals. In this new form of marketplace 
terrorism, groups, rather than individuals, 
are behind the threats.<p>

<b>Targeting an Economy</b><p>

Political and social causes aimed at the economies of countries have 
emerged as a motive behind product 
tampering overseas. Brian Jenkins, a top product-tampering terrorism 
security expert from Kroll and 
Associates in Los Angeles, offers these as recent examples: 
anti-apartheid extremists in Canada and in 
Europe who have threatened South African fruit; Tamil separatists from 
Sri Lanka who wanted to create a 
separate state and threatened to contaminate tea, Sri Lanka's number-one 
export; and tampering threats 
aimed at Israel's leading export, citrus fruit.<p>

Jenkins mentions animal rights activists in the United Kingdom who have 
threatened companies involved in 
animal testing. Along with animal rights issues are anti-smoking issues 
in the U.S. Smoking issues in 
general, however, have provoked threats against companies that sell 
tobacco products. Tampering 
contamination of products by animal rights groups has been aimed at 
cosmetic companies involved in 
animal testing. According to Jenkins, contamination of turkeys during the 
holidays has been perpetrated by 
animal rights extremists.<p>

<b>International Marketplace Terrorism Strikes the U.S.</b><p>

Threats have been directed against U.S. consumers and the U.S. companies 
that import Chilean grapes. 
These grapes were imported for wine production and table use in the 
United States. In 1989 the tampering 
problem surfaced in the vertical marketing chain, moving backward from 
manufacturer to supplier. 
Terrorists phoned the U.S. Embassy in Santiago and claimed to have laced 
all Chilean grapes with cyanide. 
This threat was directed at U.S. consumers, U.S. wine companies involved 
in production and distribution, 
and at the Chilean economy. It was taken very seriously by the U.S. 
government because after assessing the 
nature of the threats made by the terrorists, it appeared that the U.S. 
consumer and wine manufacturers were 
at risk. The Food and Drug Administration worked with the press, 
manufacturers, distributors and retailers  
to quickly assess this threat to the food supply and swiftly pull all 
fruit imported from Chile off grocery 
shelves.<p>

In 1989, Anthony Morphew, then-president of American Underwriters 
International's (AUI) Special 
Services Division, which provides specialized insurance for product 
tampering, predicted that tampering 
coupled with extortion would be an emerging trend in the 1990's. He has 
proven correct. Morphew says that 
in Colombia and Brazil, "it's a full-time business to raise money," while 
in Europe, "the tampering tends to 
have people who are doing it for a cause." Countries targeted in 1989 and 
1990 included Israel, the U.K. 
(including Hong Kong), France, Sweden, Italy, Brazil, Spain, Colombia and 
Taiwan.<p>

David Samuel, current president of AUI Special Services, confirmed that 
in 1991 and 1992, "about 60 
percent of the tampering incidents in Europe are tampering with extortion 
and the other 40 percent are 
random malicious tampering." He claims that "countries that are currently 
coping with product-tampering 
incidents coupled with extortion threats include the U.K., Australia, 
Germany, Brazil, and Spain, with the 
products targeted being mostly food and beverages."<p>

According to Samuel, "the difference in 1992 is that we have seen much of 
the malicious tampering move 
beyond single individuals to organized groups.'' He says organized 
tampering falls into two groups: "The 
first group disagrees with a company's policies and targets the company 
or companies using malicious 
tampering as a form of protest. The second group is criminal in intent 
and is using malicious tampering to 
raise money."<p>

In April and May 1989, the London Daily Telegraph reported more than 250 
tampering incidents connected 
with extortion threats in England and Ireland. According to the paper, a 
"gang of extortionists had 
threatened to poison food and received $85,000 from one supermarket 
chain." The gang then reportedly 
asked two other companies for $1.7 million not to poison baby food. After 
H.J. Heinz and Cow and Gate 
Ltd. allegedly refused to pay the extortion, fifty babies were rushed to 
the hospital after eating baby food 
spiked with glass and needles. The gang had made good on its threats.<p>

In 1989, tampering extortionists threatened to poison candy made by the 
Morinaga Candy Company in 
Japan. The ransom payment was not completed because of a series of 
problems. The terrorists then called 
news organizations and made threats. Finally, terrorists actually sent 
samples of poisoned candy to the 
newsrooms. Morinaga's candy sales dropped drastically. Ten months later, 
the terrorists called the Japanese 
media to tell them to inform the public that it was safe to buy Morinaga 
candy again. <p>

<h3>Partnerships to Manage the Problem</h3>

The Foundation for American Communications, in an effort to help 
journalists cover the story effectively, 
developed seminars to create a partnership among journalists, government 
agency sources, experts and 
corporate executives willing to share their experiences with product 
tampering threats and incidents. Other 
groups are bringing government, journalists and businesses together to 
manage the problem of marketplace 
terrorism. Seminars created for companies helped executives develop 
crisis teams and strategies to handle 
external crimes such as tampering combined with extortion. These seminars 
were held in October and 
November 1991 at Bristol, Haydock, London and Glasgow. <p>

In England and Belgium, food and pharmaceutical companies are grappling 
with the problem of product 
tampering terrorism. Many of the U.S. trade associations that help 
companies learn how to do crisis 
planning are now consulting to trade associations overseas. Over the past 
ten years, the Non-Prescription 
Drug Manufacturers Association, the Grocery Manufacturers of America, the 
Food Marketing Institute and 
the National Food Processors Association helped U.S. companies trying to 
cope with the problems of 
product tampering. These trade associations also worked to strengthen 
tampering legislation and succeeded 
through passage of the 1983 Anti-Tampering Act. Trade associations in 
packaging are still working to 
develop tamper-evident packaging.<p>

There is less tamper-evident packaging in Europe than in the United 
States. Dr. Jerome Rienstein, director 
general of the World Federation of Proprietary Manufacturers, says that 
"one hundred percent of all 
medicine is available only from behind the counter, which is why 
tamper-evident packaging is not as 
prevalent overseas, with the exception of the U.K., where twenty percent 
is sold over the counter. And that 
is at risk."<p>

Sherwyn Gardner of Grocery Manufacturers of America (GMA) thinks Europe 
is coping with more serious 
tampering problems than those in the United States in the past ten years. 
"What they are facing," he says, "is 
organized terrorism directed against products, and what we faced was 
disorganized marketplace terrorism." 
Gardner says the GMA has helped the Food and Drink Federation in the 
United Kingdom as well as the 
Belgium Food and Agricultural Industries Association with their tampering 
problems. <p>

<h3>The American Response to Tampering </h3>

In 1974 the U.S. Department of Defense began a $10 million research 
effort aimed at upgrading its 
computer based political and military crisis warning and decision making 
systems. The Department of 
Defense conducted this research effort because a study determined that 
U.S. companies had no structured 
way to deal with crisis situations. <p>

The importance of having crisis teams in place is illustrated by Steven 
Fink's study of various disasters, 
"Crisis Management: Planning for the Inevitable." He found that companies 
having crisis management 
procedures in place recover from crises 2.5 times faster than companies 
without them. Fink also noted that 
52 percent of the responding companies, both with and without crisis 
management plans, reported that a 
crisis caused direct and calculable damage to their profits. <p>

<b>Companies Form Crisis Teams</b><p>

A national study, "The Development of Corporate Management Responses to 
Incidents of Consumer 
Product Tampering,'' completed by Dr. Deborah Lowe in 1988, examined 45 
Fortune 500 companies in the 
food and pharmaceutical industries. All had experienced product-tampering 
threats or incidents. Seventy-
eight percent were food companies, twenty-two percent pharmaceutical 
companies. Each threat or incident 
took place in 1986 or 1987 and was directed at a name brand packaged 
consumer product. If the incident 
had received news coverage, its effects were studied. <p>

Companies in the wake of a product tampering threat or incident chose 
either defensive or pro-active 
communications strategies. Because the experts on media strategy are 
divided over whether to seek or avoid 
news coverage during tampering threats and incidents, different media 
guidelines have been developed. 
These depend on the outcome of threat assessment of the incident, the 
crisis communication philosophy of 
the company and the extent of media involvement in the tampering threat 
or incident.<p>

The Fortune 500 manufacturers in the study chose a pro-active public 
relations strategy that informed the 
inquiring media  about all parts of the threat and the threat assessment 
process. The crisis communications 
argument for openness is that talking to the media reassures customers 
that the company is acting in the 
public interest and that the company will take socially responsible 
actions. A pro-active communications 
strategy includes a policy that the company must tell its side of the 
story in the first 24 hours after a crisis 
takes place if the public is to perceive that the company cares.<p>



<br>
<br>
<center>
<a href="http://www.facsnet.org/navigation.map">
<IMG  border=0 Align=Top SRC="http://www.facsnet.org/facsnet_grafix/splash/navigation_bar.gif" ISMAP></a><br>
