<html><head> <title>Product Tampering: A Worldwide Problem</title></hea
d>
 <body bgcolor="#ffffff">
 
<hr noshade size=3>
<center>
<img src="http://www.facsnet.org/facsnet_grafix/report_tools/product_ta
mp_banner_small.gif">
<br>
</center>
 
 <hr noshade size=3>


<h3>PERSPECTIVE TWO:</h3>
<h2>The Legal Framework of Product Tampering</h2>
 <br clear>

by <strong>Eric Greenberg, J.D.</strong><p>

<i>Eric Greenberg is a partner with the Chicago office of Bullwinkel 
Partners Ltd., a law firm which represents domestic and foreign companies 
that operate in highly-regulated technical industries. He is the author 
of "The Legal Impact," a monthly column for Packaging Digest.</i><p>

The federal or state government may bring criminal charges against a 
tamperer or one who has threatened tampering. A civil lawsuit, one 
between two private parties, such as an injured person versus a 
manufacturer, may result from injury allegedly caused by a tampered 
product. Because the U.S. Food and Drug Administration (FDA) requires 
tamper-resistant packaging for over-the-counter human drug products and 
some cosmetics, a company that makes such products or its key officers 
could be subject to FDA enforcement action for failing to properly follow 
regulations. The Federal Bureau of Investigation may work with the FDA, 
the United States Department of Agriculture or other federal agencies to 
investigate possible tamperings.<p>

<h3>Federal Criminal Prosecutions Possible</h3>

In 1983, following the Chicago-area Tylenol poisonings, the Federal 
Anti-Tampering Act (FATA) was passed. It created a series of new 
categories of crimes to supplement traditional federal and state laws 
against, for example, extortion and attempted manslaughter. An accused 
tamperer or extortionist might still be charged with one or more of these 
traditional crimes. The FATA, however, adds to the prosecutorUs arsenal. 
It outlaws:<p>

<ul>
 <li>Tampering with a consumer product or its  labeling or container;
 <li>Tainting consumer products or rendering their    labeling or 
container materially false or  misleading, with intent  to cause serious 
injury to a business;
 <li>Communicating false information that a  consumer product has been 
tainted, if such tainting would create the risk of death or  bodily 
injury;
 <li>Knowingly threatening to tamper with a consumer product, its 
labeling or container;
 <li>Conspiring to tamper.<p>
</ul>

The FATA contains specific sentences, fines and imprisonment for 
convictions under each crime. Journalists, however,  should check with 
prosecutors regarding sentencing, because general federal sentencing 
guidelines may apply instead.<p>

<h3>Varied Grounds for Civil Suits</h3>

A typical scenario in civil suits related to tampering is one in which a 
product is tampered with (sometimes by an unknown attacker), and a 
consumer is killed by ingesting or applying it.  The consumer or his 
family then files a civil suit for money damages against the 
manufacturers in the appropriate state or federal court alleging one or 
more separate grounds. The terminology and applicable standards for these 
suits come from the laws of the state involved, and may vary.<p>

As with any type of lawsuit, it is always useful to report the specific 
grounds alleged in a tampering suit. Typical civil suit grounds include:<p>
<ul>
 <li> Product Liability In what is sometimes referred to as strict 
liability, the injured party accuses the manufacturer of  making a 
product that was unreasonably dangerous or defective because of 
inadequacy in packaging. Such a defect might include a failure to design 
packaging properly to prevent tampering, or failure to make tampering 
evident to the consumer. To explore this issue, existing packaging 
technologies are often relevant.<p>
 <li> Negligence To show that a company was negligent, the plaintiff must 
prove that the company acted with a level of care below what a reasonably 
prudent person would have done under the circumstances. At issue is what 
the company did to design and employ packaging technologies to prevent 
foreseeable tamperings or make them evident. The adequacy of warnings and 
other label statements is a frequent part of the debate. So is the 
foreseeability of tampering. These must be evaluated by the judge or jury 
according to the specific facts of each case. The notorious Tylenol 
poisonings themselves led to changes in the law and increased awareness 
among manufacturers of many different types of consumer products. For 
this reason, it might be more difficult today to argue that a particular 
tampering is not foreseeable.<p>
 <li> Breach of Warranty Sale of a product may carry with it an implied, 
or sometimes explicit, product warranty from the manufacturer. If a 
product reaches a consumer in tampered condition, the consumer may 
contend that the warranty was breached.<p>
 </ul>

This brief overview of the three primary types of legal contexts for 
tampering should be considered a start in exploring these issues. 
However, in no instance should this brief overview be considered 
comprehensive. It is crucial to talk with experts or the attorneys and 
companies involved in prosecutions, civil suits or regulatory actions in 
order to obtain greater detail and context. It is also important to 
distinguish clearly among different types of legal actions, and to make 
mention, however briefly, of the specific grounds of any legal activity.<p>

<h3>Regulations Require Enforcement</h3>

FDA regulations require manufacturers or packers of most over-the-counter 
drug products for retail sale to package the product in tamper-resistant 
packages. Some cosmetics, liquid oral hygiene products and vaginal 
products, must also have tamper-resistant packages. The FDA defines a 
tamper-resistant package as one with one or more indicators or barriers 
to entry which, if breached or missing, can reasonably be expected to 
provide visible evidence to consumers that tampering has occurred.<p>

Most products need at least one tamper-resistant packaging feature. 
Two-piece, hard gelatin capsules require at least two tamper-resistant 
packaging features. Most retail packages of over-the-counter drug 
products, with some exceptions, must also "bear a statement that is 
prominently placed so that consumers are alerted to the specific 
tamper-resistant feature of the package."<p>

A variety of tamper-resistant technologies have been developed or have 
grown in use in recent years. These include bottle mouth-seal covers, 
shrink-wrap bottle covers, taping over the ends of a folded box, caps 
that contain a band that must be broken upon first use, and blister 
packaging, in which individual pills or capsules are encased in a 
foil-backed plastic sheet.<p>

A manufacturer of these drugs or cosmetics has a regulatory obligation to 
employ tamper-resistant packaging. If a manufacturer fails to do so, he 
is subject to the full range of FDA enforcement powers, which include 
product seizure, injunction and criminal prosecution. Typically, prior to 
any of these more serious sanctions, a manufacturer receives a warning 
letter which notifies it that the FDA has found a problem with its 
packaging. If the company responds appropriately to the warning letter, 
the FDA may not choose more serious action. Injunctions, seizures and 
criminal prosecutions are public court actions, so journalists typically 
have access to information about them. Warning letters are made public 
with certain information, such as trade secrets, removed.<p>

Over-the-counter drug manufacturers are subject to FDA inspection, and a 
problem with tamper-resistant package features could be discovered during 
an inspection. Alternatively, a problem could be the result of a consumer 
complaint or publicized incident that triggers an FDA plant inspection.<p>



<br>
<br>
