<html><head> <title>Product Tampering: A Worldwide Problem</title></hea
d>
 <body bgcolor="#ffffff">
 
<hr noshade size=3>
<center>
<img src="http://www.facsnet.org/facsnet_grafix/report_tools/product_ta
mp_banner_small.gif">
<br>
</center>
 
 <hr noshade size=3>

 
<h3>Corporate Guidelines</h3>

<h2>Computer Aided Crisis Teams and Plans</h2>

<br clear>

 In 1974, the Department of Defense began a $10 million research effort
aimed at upgrading its political and military crisis warning and
decision-making computer based methods. The Department of Defense
conducted this research effort because a study determined that U.S. 
companies did not have a structured way to deal with crisis situations.
These systems are now in place. Many of them are being adapted to help
companies with five sets of generic problems. Crisis expert Michael F. 
O'Connor, writing in Corporate Crisis Management, discusses the five
options. Briefly summarized the five programs include the following:<p>

<ul>
 <li> One Department of Defense computer program is action evaluation. 
The company uses the software to 
evaluate an action it wants to take. The outcome is dependent on certain 
events.
 <li> There is a computer program to help companies determine from a 
range of options what type and 
amount of resources might be needed in a crisis. 
 <li> Another program helps in evaluating complex options. This software 
can help in analyzing choices by 
assigning attributes levels of importance.
 <li> One computer program simulates a payoff analysis by examining 
options and actions for terrorist 
situations involving tampering or kidnapping. Often the simulated event 
has unknown factors that will 
impact decisions. This software shows the decision maker the regret that 
might be experienced from an 
unwise action and suggests viable actions that might result in less regret.
 <li> There is also software for negotiation analysis developed on the 
major premise that negotiators will go 
issue by issue and not budge from their positions. It focuses on 
negotiation strategies and fosters better 
communication in the decision process.
</ul>

<br>
<br>
