<html><head> <title>Product Tampering: A Worldwide Problem</title></hea
d>
 <body bgcolor="#ffffff">
 
<hr noshade size=3>
<center>
<img src="http://www.facsnet.org/facsnet_grafix/report_tools/product_ta
mp_banner_small.gif">
<br>
</center>
 
 <hr noshade size=3>

 
<h2>Case Study: Lipton Cup-A-Soup</h2>

<br clear>

<i>An incident where  the company got accurate coverage and was portrayed 
accurately as a victim of 
product tampering terrorism.</i><p>

Thomas J. Lipton company, a subsidiary of Unilever, coped with a 
tampering incident that resulted in a 
death in 1986. The company was not notified about the incident until two 
days after Louis Denber died 
from drinking cyanide-laced Lipton Chicken Noodle Cup-A-Soup.<p>

There were varied explanations from authorities on why there was a delay 
in notifying the company about 
the incident. One report said that because it was a holiday when Louis 
Denber drank the soup, an autopsy 
was delayed until Tuesday and blood tests were not done until Wednesday, 
when the company was notified. 
Another report noted that doctors initially attributed his death to 
natural causes because Denber had been 
recovering from salmonella poisoning contracted two weeks earlier. The 
county prosecutor and coroner 
explained that during those two days they were doing an autopsy and an 
analysis of the cyanide in the 
package.<p>

This is an example of a company that practiced proactive public 
relations, with good coverage, despite a 
delay in finding out about the incident.<p>

The company immediately performed effective threat analysis, product 
withdrawal in a targeted geographic 
area, and worked with journalists to keep them updated about the process.<p>

<h3>Geographic Withdrawal and Quick Product Tracking</h3>

As soon as the company was notified it immediately did a geographic 
withdrawal of all Cup-A-Soup from 
the Camden area where Denber lived, including a portion of the nearby 
areas of Philadelphia and Ocean 
county. In a fifty square mile circle around DenberÕs house, Lipton kept 
the products off the shelves for 
two weeks to try to prevent a copycat tampering. Lipton has a batch 
control system that allows it, within 
seven or eight hours, to trace a product all the way down to the grocery 
shelf in a particular town.<p>

<h3>Government and Company Tests Run Quickly</h3>

Lipton reported that with the exception of the box in DenberÕs home, no 
cyanide was found in any of the 
5,000 packages the FDA tested, or in the tests run on the 3,235 samples 
the company selected from 30,000 
cartons returned from 152 stores. The remaining products were destroyed.<p>

<h3>Proactive Media Notification</h3>

After being notified late on Wednesday September 3, 1986, Lipton held a 
news conference with the 
Camden County Prosecutors office early the following morning. The company 
management team launched 
an investigation, did batch control and tracking, and by September 5 were 
able to announce that the 
tampering did not take place in the manufacturing process. Lawrence 
Hicks, Lipton vice president of quality 
control, two technical experts and the Camden County Prosecutor answered 
questions at a news 
conference.<p>

<h3>Good Coverage Results</h3>

Hicks said that because the facts were given quickly in a non-sensational 
manner, the coverage accurately 
portrayed the company as the victim. Hicks said that Lipton  tried to 
give brief, factual answers to fit into 
the broadcast practice of short sound bites. He explained that it is 
essential during a product tampering 
threat or incident to emphasize that the company is trying to act in the 
public interest because the company 
image is at stake. To get good results from crisis coverage often 
requires that management be trained to 
effectively speak with reporters.<p>

<h3>Why Coverage Problems Might Occur</h3>

The delay that Lipton experienced in being notified about a tampering 
threat or incident is not uncommon. 
A delay makes it difficult for a company to investigate and respond 
within 24 to 48 hours so that consumers 
and the media perceive that it is acting with concern. When threats go to 
sources other than the company, it 
becomes a problem because the company does not get to make a timely 
assessment. Even while the 
assessment is being done, the company does not appear to be acting 
quickly.<p>

The company must explain the assessment process and give journalists what 
facts it does have in order to 
overcome this situation. Company managers should use the phrase, "I can't 
tell you that, but I can tell 
you..." This helps the journalist in getting known facts and an idea of 
when the other information will 
become available.<p>

The government agency involved often gives the only sample of the 
tampered product to a lab. Then the 
company cannot run tests on it. If the company does not know what type of 
threat the consumer is facing, it 
cannot offer advice in press conferences on what symptoms to look for and 
what actions the consumer 
should take. It puts the company at a disadvantage in determining the 
extent and nature of the threat and the 
geographic area and extent of product withdrawal needed.<p>

The journalist must understand all aspects of a product tampering 
investigation for the company and for the 
various government agencies involved. Poor coverage can result if the 
company does not explain the 
process or if the journalist is unfamiliar with the investigation and 
assessment of product tampering threats 
by either the company or the government agency.<p>

When the results of assessment of the tampered product come in from the 
lab, often the government agency 
does not release the results to the company immediately, making crisis 
planning and media relations 
difficult.<p>

It is important for the company to establish strong government agency 
links so that information reaches the 
company quickly and the press gets information quickly. It is important 
for journalists to understand which 
agencies handle testing, tracking, and prosecution aspects of marketplace 
terrorism incidents.<p>

<br>
<br>
<center>
<a href="http://www.facsnet.org/navigation.map">
<IMG  border=0 Align=Top SRC="http://www.facsnet.org/facsnet_grafix/splash/navigation_bar.gif" ISMAP></a><br>
