<html><head> <title>Product Tampering: A Worldwide Problem</title></hea
d>
 <body bgcolor="#ffffff">
 
<hr noshade size=3>
<center>
<img src="http://www.facsnet.org/facsnet_grafix/report_tools/product_ta
mp_banner_small.gif">
<br>
</center>
 
 <hr noshade size=3>

<h3>Journalists' Guidelines</h3>
 
<h2>Domestic and International Product Tampering:<br>
Background</h2>
 <br clear>

To help news directors, working reporters and corporate officers 
understand product tampering issues, the 
Foundation for American Communications has compiled background 
information from a number of experts. 
Dr. Deborah Lowe and Dr. Thomas Cashman discuss the importance of crisis 
coverage and a crisis 
communications strategy for journalists faced with covering tampering 
problems in the U.S. and overseas. 
Dr. Park Dietz, director of the Threat Analysis Institute in Los Angeles, 
writes about the importance of 
threat analysis in tampering. Eric Greenberg, J.D., who writes a legal 
column for Packaging Digest, covers 
the legal problems the issue is causing. Dr. Jack Rosette, author of 
Improving Tamper-Evident Packaging, 
comments on the role of tamper-evident packaging and how training will be 
needed by law enforcement to 
cope with tampering and threats of tampering. <p>

The first chart compares tampering threats and incidents. These numbers 
are from unpublished Food and 
Drug Administration (FDA) data on tampering complaints and incidents over 
the past ten years.<p>

The second chart shows the number of products that ended up with 
contaminants like cyanide. Compared 
with the previous chart, it also illustrates the higher number of 
unfulfilled threats made each year against 
products. <p>

In 1982 most of the tampering threats were aimed at packaged name-brand 
pharmaceutical products. In 
1986, threats against packaged food began to emerge in the tampering 
threats data. This chart illustrates the 
change in the threat pattern over the past few years.  <p>

In the United States in 1982, seven people died after swallowing Johnson 
& Johnson Tylenol capsules that 
had been laced with cyanide. This product tampering incident brought home 
the horror of a product being 
used as a weapon of terror. No one claimed responsibility or was arrested 
for the Tylenol tampering 
incident. News coverage focused on what the company was doing to make the 
manufacturing process safe 
and on the changes being made to create tamper-resistant packaging.<p>

Localized coverage, rather than national reporting of threats and 
incidents, became the norm in news 
coverage from 1982 to 1986. Tampering incidents and threats were mainly 
directed against name-brand 
packaged pharmaceutical products. In 1986 a wave of fraudulent 
complaints, copycat incidents, product-
seeding problems, tampering threats and incidents flooded the United 
States as the problem moved from 
packaged pharmaceutical products to the food industry. There were 1,706 
tampering complaints that year. 
Coverage of tampering incidents again hit the national wires. Because the 
problem was so widespread, 
companies took a number of defensive steps: They formed crisis teams, 
purchased tampering insurance and 
began using tamper-evident packaging for a large number of food and 
pharmaceutical products.<p>

FDA statistics are not complete records of the number of product 
tampering threats or incidents. Not all 
threats are reported to the FDA. Some calls are directed to poison 
centers and are not recognized as 
resulting from tampering incidents. Calls to the police are not always 
reported to the FDA. For the overseas 
journalist, it is difficult to get reliable statistics because there is 
no central agency collecting data and 
because police in each country have different methods of reporting 
threats and incidents.<p>

Product tampering threats and incidents continue. In 1991, two people 
died and one was seriously injured 
after ingesting tampered Sudafed 12-hour time release capsules. Three 
other cyanide-contaminated capsules 
were found in the testing that followed the incident. A nationwide recall 
was instituted by Burroughs 
Wellcome, the manufacturer of Sudafed capsules. Pepsico's problems in 
1993 brought considerable media 
attention to product tampering. <p>

 

