<HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>History and Purpose</TITLE></HEAD> 

<body bgcolor=#FFFFFF text=#000000 link=#0000FF vlink=#52188c alink=#ff0000>




<center><IMG WIDTH=290 HEIGHT=67  SRC="IM/agchallenges.gif" ALT="Ag-Challenge '96">
<br><br></center>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE="+2">HISTORY OF AG-CHALLENGE</FONT></CENTER>
<P>The first Ag-Challenge was hosted by the Agricultural Students' Association at the University of Saskchatchewan in 1989. Ag-Challenge involves top Canadian and American agriculture students exchanging ideas and striving to acheive higher levels of academic performance. The event is competitive and edcational, encouraging integrated approaches to solving agricultural issues. Participants have the opportunity to tour the wide variety of agricultural research facilities at the University of Saskatchewan. Ag-Challenge also emphasizes fun, and social interaction.</p>
<p>There are many reasons to participate in Ag-Challenge, such as:</p>
<dd>- it promotes educational acheivement by challenging participants
<dd>- it provides the opportunity to attend the Western Canadian Farm <dd>Progress Show (one of the largest agricultural shows in the world)
<dd>- it encourages lasting contacts between students, professional <dd>agrologists, academia, and industry
<dd>- it increases industry's awareness of the potential of young <dd>agriculture professionals entering the work force
<dd>- it enhances awareness of specific agricultural issues particularly those involving scientific research, and
<dd>- FUN, FUN, and MORE FUN!!!</p>
<p>On an annual basis Ag-Challenge attracts approximately seven universities and 35 students. Over the seven years of Ag-Challenge the following universities have participated:
<dd>- McGill University
<dd>- University of Guelph
<dd>- Nova Scotia Agricultural College
<dd>- Montana State University 
<dd>- Universite of Laval
<dd>- University of British Columbia
<dd>- Oregon State University
<dd>- University of Idaho
<dd>- University of Alberta
<dd>- University of Arizona
<dd>- Washington State University
<dd>- University of Manitoba 
 
<br><br>
<FONT SIZE="+2">PHILOSOPHY OF THE AG-CHALLENGE COMPETITION</FONT>
</center>
<br>
<br>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><B>GENERAL</B></FONT>	
<p><dd>Agricultural scientific research is becoming more specialized and is being carried out in greater quantities than ever before!  It is more difficult to keep pace with the vast amount of research results that are published every year.  The importance of the research results is reflected through industries use of this valuable information.  Agricultural specialists need to be aware of this growing source of knowledge and also be competent at reviewing facts concerning a specific problem.  Furthermore, they need to be able to identify areas where research scientists disagree or where published results may not be applicable.  Ultimately, their goal is to find scattered research results and put them together into a coherent package which has numerous potential applications.</p>

<FONT SIZE="+1"><B>CATEGORY I</B></FONT>
<p><dd>Category I is designed to provide the student with an opportunity to communicate the findings of a literature review or research conducted by the student.  The use of audiovisual aids such as overheads and slides is encouraged however,  videos are not permitted.</p>

<FONT SIZE="+1"><B>CATEGORY II</B></FONT>
<p><dd>One of the most important goals of the AgÐChallenge competition is to encourage critical and interdisciplinary thinking among its participants.  The Debate Category is designed to give participants the opportunity to use the debating format's structure to present cohesive, academic arguments.  Evaluation of the Debating Challenge is primarily concerned with the academic strengths of the arguments and not the emotional appeal of the presentations.
<dd>The Debating Challenge allows students to demonstrate their abilities to formulate constructive counterÐarguments in a set period of time.  The debaters must also show general knowledge of the Resolution as it applies to agriculture.  The Debating Challenge encourages students to consider all perspectives of an issue.  The Debates at AgÐChallenge are unique in that competitors know the Resolution ahead of time.  Each team should be prepared to formulate a case for either the Affirmative or the Negative.  This format encourages a comprehensive understanding of the issue at hand.</p>

<FONT SIZE="+1"><B>CATEGORY III</B></FONT>
<p><dd>The Team Challenge emphasizes general knowledge, teamwork, and the ability to "think on one's feet" while addressing a challenge.  In particular, the Team Challenge is designed so that students will not have to put in long hours of preparation in advance.  With this format, the Team Challenge is enjoyable to those students who do not have time to prepare a presentation in advance, but who would nevertheless like to participate.
<dd>The Team Challenge provides an ideal forum for students to demonstrate their abilities.  Groups must analyze a given problem and present their solutions within a given time period.  As students will discover when they begin employment, the skills needed to do well in this challenge are similar to those necessary to be successful in the workplace.  The Team Challenge mimics real-life situations and measures the groups ability to review necessary information and concepts and apply them to problem solving.  A successful team will be made-up of students who have a sound understanding of their particular discipline. 
<dd>The selection and makeÐup of the team representing each college will be important to the success of that team. Ideally, the team should consist of students from a number of different backgrounds, since the presentations will be judged on their ability to incorporate material form different disciplines.  The team should also consist of those students who are able to think broadly about the challenge facing agriculture.  Finally, a team will benefit from having students that are able and willing to inject some enthusiasm and creativity into their presentations.  The competition is envisioned as being an enjoyable and educational experience, not only for the participants, but also for the judges and audience.
<br>
<br>
<center>
<table border=1 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=3>
