<HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>Academic Format and Requirements</TITLE></HEAD> 

<body bgcolor=#FFFFFF text=#000000 link=#0000FF vlink=#52188c alink=#ff0000>




<center><IMG WIDTH=290 HEIGHT=67  SRC="IM/agchallenges.gif" alt="Ag-Challenge '96">
<BR>
<BR>

<B><FONT SIZE="+2">AG-CHALLENGE "FACT SHEET"</FONT></B></CENTER>

<p><dd>Ag-Challenge is an academic competition that brings together top agriculture students from across Canada and the United States.  Ag-Challenge is the result of an innovative idea created by agriculture students from the University of Saskatchewan.  Dedication and hard work have made this idea a reality.</p>

<p><dd>The first Ag-Challenge was held in Saskatoon in 1989 and was a resounding success.  This is our eighth year running and we look forward to producing a competition as successful as its predecessors.  We believe that with your support we can make Ag-Challenge '96 an event to remember.</p>

<B>Ag-Challenge - a three tiered competition:</B>

<p><dd><B>Category I</B> is a Research Paper Presentation. It consists of a 300 word abstract, a 15 minute oral presentation, and a five minute question period. This is an excellent opportunity for students 	to demonstrate their knowledge of a particular topic in agriculture (a full-length research paper is not submitted).</p>

<p><dd><B>Category II</B> is a Debating Challenge.  Debating teams (two individuals per team, one team per university) must prepare to argue  the affirmative and negative side of a resolution.  Competitors learn which side of the Resolution they are arguing the night before the debate.</p>

<p><dd><B>Category III</B> is a Team Challenge. Each team consists of four students. One graduate student in their first year of graduate studies is allowed to participate on a team.  Competitors must be able to pull the necessary information and concepts from the material they have learned throughout their university education and apply it to a problem they have never seen before.  The challenge covers all facets of agriculture and is not limited to only one discipline. The analysis and presentation of solutions to the challenges must be performed in a fixed length of time.</p>

<p><dd>Various activities are held throughout the week of Ag-Challenge. Aside from providing students with healthy competition Ag-Challenge also introduces students to western Canadian agriculture through tours and allows students an opportunity to form longlasting contacts with new friends and future collegues during a varity of social activities. Ag-Challenge can be a very rewarding, fun-filled, educational experience.  We hope to see you at Ag-Challenge.</p>

<p><b>The Categories:</b></p>
<BR>
<B>CATEGORY I</B>

<p><dd>Category I consists of:</p>

<p>1) An abstract including:
<dd>- title, name, and address of author
<dd>- 300 word (maximum) summary of the paper to be presented</p> 
<p><ADDRESS></ADDRESS>2) A 15 minute oral presentation based on that paper
<p>3) A 5 minute question period from the panel of judges.</p>

<p><dd>It is expected that the author will follow generally accepted style and format practices for the abstract.  The abstract should be consistent with a recognized scientific journal.  It is up to the author  to evaluate the different formats and style requirements of various publications, and decide which is most effective and appropriate to use.</p>

<CENTER>EVALUATION CRITERIA FOR CATEGORY I</CENTER> 

<p>ABSTRACT (20%)</p>

<p>Style (40%)
<dd>Readability
<dd>Grammar
<dd>Appropriate Format</p> 

<p>Content (60%)
<dd>Informativeness
<dd>Conciseness</p>

<p>ORAL PRESENTATION (80%)</p>

<p>Development of Subject (40%)
<dd>Introduction
<dd>Interpretations
<dd>Relevance or Application
<dd>Conclusion</p>

<p>Delivery of Paper (40%)
<dd>Visual Aids
<dd>Grammar
<dd>Platform Style
<dd>Speed, Timing</p>

<p>Ability to Field Questions (20%)</p>

<B>CATEGORY II</B>

<p>Category II: Debating Challenge</p>

<p>How the Debating Challenge is Run</p>

<p><dd>All debates are divided into two portions, the constructive section and the rebuttal.	In the debate, the Affirmative speaks first and last because it has the more difficult task.  The Negative side of the resolution is generally assumed to be true; the burden is on the Affirmative to change this.</p>
<p><dd>The constructive portion  is where arguments are presented and constructed.  The Affirmative always starts by stating the terms of the debate.  From here, the Affirmative goes on to present its case.  The first speaker need only construct his or her own arguments.  The three following speakers will then construct their own cases, and argue major points.  If the Negative disagrees with the Affirmative's definition of the argument, the first negative speaker must say so in their speech.</p>
<p><dd>The rebuttal portion is a summary of the debate.  The rebuttal allows the debaters to sum up their points and argue against their opponents' major points.  No new information may be introduced during the rebuttal.  As well, a rebuttal can not be referred to or rebutted during their opponents' rebuttal.</p>


<p>Format Of The Debate
<dd>First Affirmative Construction					4 minutes
<dd>First Negative Construction					4 minutes
<dd>Second Affirmative Construction				4 minutes
<dd>Second Negative Construction					4 minutes
<dd>Break								4 minutes
<dd>Negative Rebuttal							2 minutes
<dd>Affirmative Rebuttal 						2 minutes</p>

<p>TOTAL								28  minutes</p>


<p>EVALUATION CRITERIA FOR CATEGORY II</p>

<p>Organization and Strategy (25%)
<dd>¥	a good debate should consist of an introduction, a logical development of the case, and a conclusion
<dd>¥	strategy refers to the definition introduced by the Affirmative, and the ability of the Negative to work within that definition
<dd>¥	organization refers to the ability of the debaters to identify and summarize their opponents' most important points</p>

<p>Delivery (25%)
<dd>¥	demonstrate good speaking skills
<dd>¥	show poise , quality and use of voice, effectiveness of gesture, eye contact, emphasis, enunciation, and use of audiovisual aids</p>

<p>Evidence and Academic Argument (20%)
<dd>¥	logic, facts, statistics, authorities used in arguments
<dd>¥	must be able to provide the name of a reference upon request, but it is not necessary to produce the source itself
<dd>¥	debaters must demonstrate a comprehensive understanding of the resolution and the issues surrounding it</p>

<p>Refutation (15%) 
<dd>¥	ability of the speaker to rationally and logically refute the contentions of their opponent 
<dd>¥	ability of the speaker to synthesize and summarize successfully</p>

<p>Questions (10%)
<dd>¥	ability of the speaker to field questions from the judges</p>

<p>Presentation (5%)
<dd>¥	speakers shall behave courteously towards the audience, the judges and their opponents
<dd>¥	arguments should be confined to using academic, logical rationale rather than emotional appeal</p>


<B>CATEGORY III</B>

<p><dd>The task in the Team Challenge is to evaluate, analyze and present a plausible solution to an agricultural problem. Teams have no prior access to the problem until they enter isolation. All teams receive identical problems. The teams are provided with the necessary materials such as pens, paper, and overhead sheets to make their presentation. Outside reference material is not permitted. Teams are given three hours to develop a response and prepare a 15 minute presentation on their solution. Judges are given five minutes for questions.</p> 
<p><dd>Sample problems will be sent to each university along with the registration forms in February.</p>

<CENTER><b>EVALUATION CRITERIA FOR CATEGORY III</b></CENTER>
	
<p>Development of Subject (60%)</p>
<dd>Introduction
<dd>Approach
<dd>Interpretations
<dd>Conclusions
	
<p>Delivery of Presentation (20%)</p>
<dd>Grammar
<dd>Platform Style
<dd>Speed, Timing
<dd>Visual Aids
	
<p>Ability to Field Questions (20%)</p>

<CENTER><b>Judging</b></CENTER>

<p>Each category is judged by three judges whose scores are totalled.</p>




