<HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>PAST QUESTIONS AND TOPICS</TITLE></HEAD> 

<body bgcolor=#FFFFFF text=#000000 link=#0000FF vlink=#52188c alink=#ff0000>




<center><IMG WIDTH=290 HEIGHT=67  SRC="IM/agchallenges.gif" alt="Ag-Challenge '96">
<BR>
<BR></center>

<p><dd>This feature of the Ag Challenge Homepage is designed to give registered and potential competitors an idea of the types of topics and problems competitors in Category II and III are faced with. If you have any questions or comments feel free to e-mail them to: <A HREF="MAILTO:ss_acss@duke.usask.ca">ss_acss@duke.usask.ca</A> or phone us at 306-966-8890.</p>

<p><b>Category II: Debate</b></p>

<p><B>June 1995</B>
<dd>"Genetic engineering should receive priority in agricultural research funding initiatives."</p>
<P><B>June 1994</B>
<dd>"Farmers should provide all of the funds required for agricultural research."</p>

<p><b>Category III: Team Challenge</b></p>

<p><B>June 1993</B>
<dd>You are a group of professors who are in charge of developing a new undergraduate course Agricultural Science  110. The course is a novel attempt to integrate the physical, social and economic aspects of agriculture (see description below). As various topics are covered in the course, all pertinent components and interactions are to be considered. Your challenge is to develop and present a fifteen minute outline of a lecture to serve as a model for how you think the material should be covered and presented to students. You have selected "Crop Rotations" as the tropic of your lecture.</p>
<p><I>Agriculture Science 110</I></p>
<p><dd>The course emphasizes the physical and behavioural relationships among the different components of agriculture. Among the physical relationships are soil, plant and animal interactions, feed conversion, product processing, energy transfers, and effects on the environment and the ecosystem. Behavioural relationships examined include economic decision-making by farmers, processors, and other firms political decision-making by governments, and the impact of community, social institutions, and culture.</p>
<p><dd>The course is presented in an integrated manner rather than in "chunks" of departmental material. The course does not present students with facts, but rather presents principles and get students to think in a broad systems fashion. The course is interactive; through "novel" approaches the students are confronted with the need to problem solve and to think.</p>

<p><B>June 1989</B>
<dd>For the purpose of this problem, consider yourself to be a team of four experts who are on faculty in a College of Agriculture in North America. You have been appointed to carry out an assignment for the North American International Development Agency (NAIDA), an organization that funds and oversees various development projects in the third world. The assignment you have been given concerns Lum Del Cur (LDC), a low income country somewhere in third world. LDC has approached NAIDA for some assistance in solving its agricultural and food problems through a specifically designed educational and extension program. The characteristics of LDC and the nature of the request that LDC has made NAIDA are outlined below.</p>
<p><I>LDC Characteristics</I></p>
<p><dd>The major problem that LDC faces in its agricultural and food sector are:
<dd>1. Low agricultural productivity and output
<dd>2. Low farm incomes
<dd>3. Inadequate food supply, and
<dd>4. Dependence on imported food from neighbouring
<dd>countries that have a better-developed agriculture</p>


<p><I>LDC's Request of NAIDA</I></P>
<p><dd>The assignment that NAIDA has given to you is develop an educational and extension program that will best serve the overall development of LDC's agricultural sector, increase agricultural and food output, increase farm incomes, provide LDC's major food needs, and develop export crops. In short, you are to provide a recommendation to NAIDA as to the type of educational/training program that should be developed in LDC.</p> 
<p><dd>In developing your recommendations, you should consider that the program is to provide expertise to people who will work in the civil service, rural extension, agricultural research, and primary agricultural production (ie. the farmers). Your recommendations should specify very clearly the agricultural disciplines that will be covered, and the type of coverage that will be provided. The resource personnel for the program should be specified along with any infrastructure you believe is necessary for your recommendations to be carried out. The expected number of people that will be involved in the program should also be discussed.<pp>
<p><dd>Your recommendations should include a description of the precise nature of the educational and training courses that will be developed, as well as the orientation of any course material that needs to be prepared.</p>
<p><dd>In your presentation, it is important that you develop an argument for the program you recommend in terms of the goals of LDC. You should also be advised that while additional marks will be given for detailed recommendations, spending too much time on this aspect of the problem reduces the amount available for examining the larger picture and for developing a more integrated approach, something that will also provide additional marks.</p>
<p>NB: attached to this problem was demographic and price information necessary to present a plausible solution.</p>

<br>
