<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT24-B02-101</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA002-000014-B016-270</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://pine.usask.ca:80/cofa/departments/hort/hortinfo/fact/amarylli.html 128.233.59.24 19970101085626 text/html 5197
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: WebSTAR
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>   
<head>   
<title>AMARYLLIS</title>   
</head>   
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif">   
<h1>    
<center>   
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">      
AMARYLLIS</center>   
</h1>   
<B> Appearance</B>    
<P>The amaryllis is a large plant 46-60 cm (18-24 in.); blooms    
are bell shaped and 10-15 cm (4-6 in.) wide. There are usually 4    
blooms per stem that last approximately 2 weeks.  Colours range    
from pure white to salmon, pink and red.  Bulbs can be brought    
into bloom in the late fall to early spring, blooming from 6-8    
weeks after planting.    
    
<P><B>Potting</B>    
    
     <P>Purchase large firm bulbs which have scars or stubs of old    
foliage only; no leaves.  Use a light well-drained potting    
mixture containing some peat moss.  (A good soil mixture would be    
3 parts potting soil:l part sand + l Tbsp bone meal and a handful    
of peat moss).  Make sure that the pot has good drainage and is    
8-10 cm (3-4 in.) wider than the bulb.  The mixture should be    
approximately 2.5 cm (1 in.) below the rim of the pot for ease of    
watering and 1/3 of the bulb should show above the soil level.     
Firm the soil and water well.    
    
<P><B>Care</B>     
    
     <P>Place the pot in a sunny, warm room.  Day temperatures    
should be 18-25 C (65-78 F) with night temperature 5-10 C cooler.     
Good ventilation is needed with moderate humidity.  Water    
sparingly until the first shoots appear.  If a new shoot doesn't    
appear within two weeks, try boosting it with bottom heat.     
    
     <P>Once growth begins, water whenever the soil is dry; keep it    
evenly moist but not overly wet.  Turn the pot every few days to    
keep foliage growth balanced.  Fertilize with a complete water-    
soluble houseplant fertilizer, such as 20-20-20, once per month    
while in active growth, remembering it is better to under    
fertilize than over fertilize.    
    
<P><B>Flowering</B>    
    
<P>Once flower buds are ready to open, move the pot to a different    
spot where it is cooler and where there is less direct light.     
This prolongs flowering and brings out the brilliant colours of    
the amaryllis.  Staking may be required if the blooms are too    
heavy.  Remove flowers as they fade as this prevents seed    
formation, which diverts food from the bulb itself.      
    
<P><B>Aftercare</B>    
    
     <P>Once blooming is over, place pot in a sunny location which    
is well ventilated.  Water and feed regularly to promote vigorous    
foliage.  Food manufactured in leaves will enlarge and feed the    
bulb, which has shrunk as a result of flowering.  The bulb should    
increase 1-2 cm (.3-.7 in) in size each year.  Bulbs may be    
placed outdoors in semi-shaded location during the summer as long    
as they are protected from spring and fall frosts and windy    
conditions.    
         
     <P>Bring the amaryllis indoors in September when the leaves    
have died down.  If they have not died down, bring them in and    
cut back the watering to only once per month.  Store in a cool    
(12 C or 55 F), dry location out of direct light until signs of    
growth reappear. These conditions help to reduce the moisture    
loss from the bulb.  Discontinue watering and feeding during this    
stage to prevent rot.    
    
<P><B>Regrowth</B>    
    
     <P>New growth will appear in about 2 months.  At this time    
remove and replenish the top 2.5 cm (l in.) with finished compost    
or new soil, mixing it with a tsp. of bone meal.  Be careful not    
to disturb the roots or damage the new shoots.  Place pot in a    
warm sunny position and continue watering and fertilizing as    
before.    
    
     <P>An amaryllis bulb may need to be repotted every 3-4 years as    
the bulb increases in diameter, but a slightly "pot-bound"    
amaryllis will do well as long as it is adequately fed.    
    
<P><B>Propagation</B>    
    
     <P>Off-sets of bulbs may be removed and potted separately but    
might take 2 years (or 4 leaves) to produce flowers.  Plants can    
be sown from seeds.  Seed taken from your own plants will seldom    
bred true.  Seed may be easily obtained from seed catalogues or    
purchased at garden centres.    
    
     <P>Sow seeds on their sides indoors during any season.  Keep    
the soil temperature between 21-23 C (70-75 F) during germination    
period, which takes 4-6 weeks.    
    
<P><B>Problems</B>     
    
    <P>Although fungal diseases and rot are not common, they may    
develop under conditions of poor drainage.  Spider mites and    
mealy bugs can also be a problem although it would be rare.    
    
     <P>Several bulbs can be planted at different intervals from    
September to February to ensure a continuous bloom until May.      
    
<P><B>Source</B>     
    
     <P>Williams, Sara. "The Amaryllis", University of Saskatchewan,    
          Extension Division.   
   
<br>   
