<head> 
<title>Blackleg and Bacterial Soft Rot</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
Blackleg and Bacterial Soft Rot</center> 
</h1> 
 
                           Sharon Faye
<p>     Cool, damp conditions, like those we have been experiencing 
this summer, can provide the ideal environment for many disease 
causing organisms.  Two diseases that appear to be flourishing in 
this year's weather are Blackleg and bacterial soft rot.  
Blackleg is a common problem in cool, moist conditions, and the 
tubers from blackleg infected plant can develop bacterial soft 
rot, which renders tubers inedible.  
<p>     Blackleg appears as an inky black decay and usually starts 
on a decaying piece of seed potato and spreads to the stem of the 
plant.  Above the black discoloured part, the tissue inside the 
stem is often decayed or discoloured.  Plants are often stunted 
and have a stiff, erect growth habit, especially in the early 
part of the season.  Leaves are yellowish (chlorotic) between the 
green veins and the leaflets tend to roll upward at the outside 
edges (margins).  Eventually, leaflets or the entire plant may 
wilt and die.  Young shoots may be killed before they emerge.
<p>     In wet weather, stem decay is soft and slimy and may quickly 
spread to a large part of the plant.  Under dry conditions, the 
infected tissues become dry and shrivelled, but may only be 
noticeable on the underground portion of the stem.
<p>     Tubers may be slightly discoloured at point of attachment to 
the main portion of the plant.  It is at this end, where soft rot 
may develop and spread into the tuber.
<p>Soft rot can affect tubers while in storage or in the soil before 
harvest.  The decay occurs after planting.  On the tuber's 
surface, soft rot appears as slightly sunken, tan to brown, 
circular water soaked areas (about 5 mm in diameter).  Under dry 
conditions, there may be sunken areas that are dry and hard.
<p>     Soft rotted potato flesh appears wet, cream to tan in colour 
with a soft, slightly granular appearance.  There is also a 
definite break between healthy and infected tissue.  It is 
usually odourless unless other decay organisms have already set 
in.
<p><B>Disease Cycle:</B>
<p>Blackleg:  The bacteria is formed either on or in the seed.  More 
of the bacteria is released as the seed tuber decays in the soil.  
The potato stem may be infected, as well as certain weeds, and 
may survive the winter in these tubers or stems.  If conditions 
are cool and moist, survival of the bacteria is greater and any 
infected plant debris that remains helps extend its survival.
<p>     Bacteria may move for some distance in the soil water to 
infect young healthy tubers.  The extent of damage depends on the 
environment (climate, temperature...etc.)  The tubers are 
infected by bacteria entering the natural opening in the tubers 
(lenticels) or growth cracks and injuries and may survive the 
entire storage period in these tubers.  The bacteria is readily 
spread during seed cutting and handling operations. 
<p>Soft rot:  It has a similar disease cycle as blackleg.  In fact, 
the two diseases are caused by two varieties of the same species 
of bacterium.  Blackleg affects stems and may produce soft rot in 
the tubers.  Bacteria of soft rot can easily spread in water used 
to wash tubers.
<p><B>CONTROL:</B>
<p>Blackleg:
<p>     1) Plant seed tubers (especially cut tubers) in well drained 
     soil.
<p>     2) Avoid excessive irrigation to prevent the elimination of 
     air space within the soil (ie. anaerobic conditions) which 
     favours seed decay and results in stem invasion.
<p>     3) Treat soil tubers with approved fungicides to reduce 
     infection by Fusarium spp. and other pathogens that make 
     bacterial invasion more promising.
<p>     4) Clean up potato cull piles, discarded vegetables and 
     plant refuse to avoid inoculum sources from which insects 
     transmit the bacteria.<p>     5) Frequent cleaning and disinfecting seed cutting and 
     handling equipment as well as planters, harvesters and 
     conveyers will help eliminate contamination.  This practise 
     is recommended between different seed lots for commercial 
     growers.
<p>     6) Avoid washing seed potatoes unless absolutely necessary 
     and minimize the amount of damage during handling 
     operations.
<p>     7) Fertilize well with nitrogen but not in excess amounts.
<p>     8) Remove infected plants as soon as they appear to avoid 
     contamination of healthy plants.
<p>Soft rot: 
     1) Avoid excessive soil moisture to reduce infection.
<p>     2) Harvest tubers only when mature or when soil temperatures 
     are less than 200C.  Exercise care when harvesting or 
     handling tubers to reduce damage.
<p>     3) Prevent tubers from being exposed to solar irradiation 
     and desiccation. 
     4) After harvest, cool tubers to 100C or less as quickly as 
     possible (preferably 1.6-4.50C).  Good ventilation keeps 
     tubers cool and prevents CO2 build up and avoids moisture 
     films from developing, which also are very important 
     factors.
<p>     5) While in storage, prevent water films from forming on the 
     surface of tubers.  Condensation results from placing tubers 
     with low pulp temperature into storage with relative 
     humidity above 90 %.
<p>     6) Store potatoes without washing them.  If washing before 
     market, dry them as soon as possible and package in well 
     aerated containers.
<p>     7) Use clean water to wash potatoes.  Contaminated holding 
     tanks used for soaking potatoes almost guarantee soft rot 
     problems later.  Treat wash water with chlorine to decrease 
     the amount of soft rot inoculum.
<p>References:
<p>Compendium of Potato Diseases, Edited by W.J. Hooker; American 
Phytopathological Society; St. Paul, Minnesota; 1981.
<p>Potato Production Guide; Alberta Agriculture; Edmonton; 1986.
 
<br> 
