<head> 
<title>GRAPE GROWING IN SASKATCHEWAN</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
GRAPE GROWING IN SASKATCHEWAN</center> 
</h1> 
 
                         Mary A. Beckie
<p>     This may not be Italy, but grapes can be successfully grown 
in Saskatchewan with proper care and a warm sunny summer.  
However, grapes are not a prominent fruit crop in the province, 
and most growers enjoy them for home consumption.  Grape vines 
growing up a trellis, with large clusters of fruit, are a 
beautiful addition to any backyard or greenhouse.
<p><B>Types </B>
  <P>   Grapes come from the vine family Vitaceae, and belong to the 
genus Vitis which consists of climbing woody vines that bears 
non-showy flowers and true berry fruits.  Grape berries range in 
color from red through purple, violet, blue, green to nearly 
white.  There are 30 species native to North America.  Vitis 
riparia, the riverbank grape, is found in Saskatchewan.  These 
native species have been important to the development of pure 
stock and hybrids that are adapted to the local climate, 
particularly for hardy and insect and disease resistant 
rootstock.  Grape cultivars that have been derived for prairie 
conditions include: Alpha, Beta, Valiant, Dakota, Svelter, and 
Hungarian.  Of these Beta and Valiant are the most hardy, and 
Hungarian is the least hardy.  Valiant is an earlier maturing, 
hardier and sweeter than Beta.  Both Beta and Valiant have a 
taste similar to a concord grape, but are generally smaller in 
size.  Most Canadian and American cultivars are self-fertilizing.  
Other more tender cultivars on hardy rootstock can be grown on 
the prairies, but would require winter protection, with greater 
chances of winter kill, and sporadic or no fruit production.  
<p><B>The Growing Site and Planting </B>  
     <P>Location is critical for successful grape growing.  Grapes 
require full sun, warmth and protection from winds.  A southern 
exposure is best.  To facilitate maximum exposure of leaves to 
light and to aid insect and disease control, cultivation and 
harvesting, wires or a trellis should be established for the 
tendrils to attach to and the plant to grow up.  The soil should 
be well drained, not too sandy or clayey, with a pH around 6.   
     <P>It is best to plant in the spring.  The soil should be 
worked with compost or fertilizer prior to the planting of 
seedlings; over fertilizing at planting may burn the root system.  
Dig a hole large enough to accommodate the root system.  Allow 
2.5m between plants.  Leave enough space in the bed to allow 
wires or trellis to be laid flat to the ground in the fall.  
Prepare the plants prior to planting by trimming off extra-long 
or damaged roots.  Place the seedlings in the hole, work good 
topsoil around the roots and firmly tamp the soil around the 
plant.  A layer of sand on top of the ground is good for 
absorbing heat and warming the ground.  Water the plants 
thoroughly.  Keep the area free of weeds and grass, to allow for 
maximum water uptake.  A mulch of clean straw or other suitable 
material of 5-10 cm. will help control weeds and retain moisture.
<p><B>Pruning </B>
     <P>Pruning is important for shaping the plant to fit a trellis, 
and also helps to control the size and quality of the fruit.  
Various pruning techniques can be used, but the most suitable are 
those that allow for the plant to be placed near the ground and 
covered in the fall, to prevent winter kill.  The fan system of 
pruning is one of these techniques. 
     <P>At planting, prune the plant to only one stem, cut just 
beyond the second bud.  Two stems will emerge from the buds.  In 
the fall, prune each cane back, leaving only 2 top buds on each.  
Allow these buds to develop into vertical shoots the next season, 
and tie these to wire or trellis.  These 4 canes will be the main 
arms for the first several years.  In the fall, prune the canes 
to a length of about 60cm, leaving 4-5 buds on each cane.  The 
plant will begin to produce fruit in the second or third year.  
However, the flower buds should be thinned to 1/3 of the annual 
crop for the first 6 years to enable the plant to develop a solid 
vegetative structure.  Each fall prune the canes back, leaving 4- 
5 buds.  Remove all lateral shoots from the arms, accept the 
lowest one on the arm just above the primary trunk.  These shoots 
are pruned to leave only 1 node and called renewal spurs.  After 
the 6th year, the full crop of fruit can be allowed to develop.  
After several years the main arms will become brittle.  Remove 
them and all the renewal spurs to produce shoots that are trained 
to replace the old arms.
<p><B>Winter Protection</B>  
     <P>Although the hardy cultivars mentioned can survive in 
southern Saskatchewan, a good covering of soil in the fall is 
worthwhile protection against severe prairie winters.  Bank soil 
up over the lower trunk and cover the stem with at least 15 cm.  
of soil after placing it on the ground.  If the vine remains 
attached to a trellis, place the trellis on the ground and cover 
with soil.  Additional protection can be provided by mulching 
with straw and keeping a good ground cover of snow.  Remove soil 
in the spring, when danger of cold is past and prior to breaking 
of buds.  
<p><B>Propagation</B>  
     <P>The easiest method of propagating grapes is from cuttings.  
Cuttings, consisting of mature shoots with two successive buds, 
should be taken in the fall.  Cut just below the bottom bud and 
above the top bud.  Bury the cutting a few inches deep in soil 
outdoors or indoors.   Grapes can also be propagated from seed 
and by layering.  Graft scions onto rootstock using the whip and 
tongue method.
<p><B>Harvest </B>
     <P>Clusters of grapes will be produced within the second or 
third year of growth.  It is important to taste the grapes for 
ripeness, as mature size and color will be achieved before grapes 
reach full sweetness.  For wine-making or table use, pick grapes 
at their sweetest.  Pick the grapes earlier for jellies and jams, 
as the pectin content is greatest before maturity is reached.   
Grapes picked by hand should be harvested by placing the hand 
under the cluster and using shears to clip it from the vine.
<p><B>References</B> 
<P>1. Galleta,Gene and Himelrick,David eds.  1990.  Small Fruit Crop 
Management.   Prentice-Hall Inc.  New Jersey. 
<P>2. Harapiak,John.  1986.  University of Alberta Home Gardening 
Course.  University of Alberta, Faculty of Extension.  Edmonton, 
Alta. 
<P>3. Patterson, Cecil.  1936.  Hardy Fruits. 
<p>Useful information was also obtained from Drew Smith of 
Saskatoon, Campbell Davidson at the Morden Research Station, and 
Mr. Harrison of Harrison Garden Center, Carnduff, Saskatchewan.  
 
<br> 
