<html> 
<head> 
<title>HARVESTING GARDEN PEAS</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
HARVESTING GARDEN PEAS</center> 
</h1> 
 
                Why not have a Pea-popping Party?
<p>                           Sharon Faye
<p>     Fresh garden peas are often a wonderful treat for young and old.  
They should be picked when the pods are just about round in cross-section 
and have a bright green colour.  This is when they are at their sweetest, 
are fully developed, but not yet starchy.  
<p>     Back home, we used to eat them by the handfuls.  But what happens 
when you're faced with big 5 gallon pails full of them and it's time to shell?  
The enthusiasm may tend to wane.  One method we used when shelling peas 
for freezing was blanching. It saved a lot of time, and was fun.
<p>Setting the stage:  (What is required?) <BR>
   
     -Outdoors, open kitchen area, or deep sinks. <BR>
     -1 deep basin or pot/person for shelling. <BR>
     -1 footstool/person. <BR>
     -Pail or container to collect empty pods. <BR>
     -Distance from your neighbour so that you don't get hit. <BR>
     -Flexible fingers. <BR>
     -1 Canner or large pot, 3/4 full of hot water, on the stove.<BR> 
     -Peas ready to shell. <BR>
     -1 Colander, (the best type is with a handle).<BR>
<p>Procedure:
<p>     Bring water to boil on the stove.  Pour pods into the boiling water, 
pushing them down with colander since they tend to float.  Fill with as many 
pods as the pot can handle.  (A canner can hold about 2 gallons of pods.).  
Cover with lid.  Every 15-20 seconds, the peas should be pushed down with 
colander, to force the top pods to the bottom and allow the bottom ones to 
float to the top.
<p>Readiness Test:
<p>     Within 2-3 minutes the pods should be blanched and ready to pop.  
Select a pod holding the stem with one hand.  With the other hand, place your 
thumb on one side of the pod and index and middle finger on the other side, 
squeeze the pod just behind the stem while sliding your fingers down the 
pod slightly.  If the other end of the pod does not open easily with the 
pressure, stir the pods, cover the canner and try again a few seconds 
later.  If the pod does open, simply force the peas out through the opening 
by sliding all your fingers down one side of the pod with your thumb moving 
slightly down the other side. If some of the peas look mushy they are 
overcooked; check the pods sooner for the next batch.
<p>Shelling:
<p>     Remove pods quickly from the water with colander into an empty 
container which can later be put into shelling basins.  If the pods are too 
hot to handle, allow them to cool slightly so they are manageable or run 
some cool water over them.  They are easier to pop while they are warm 
rather than too cool.  Turn down heat on stove.  Place pods in shelling 
basins and "fire away".  Throw empty shells in container provided (or at 
your neighbour).
<p>     This may seem difficult at first (ie. the shelling not the throwing), 
but once you catch on to it one person can shell a gallon of pods in 7 
minutes.
<p>     Once you're almost through that batch, bring water to boil again on 
the stove and repeat procedure for the remaining pods.  If your are 
planning to use these peas for your next meal, they now require very little 
cooking time to be completely cooked.
<p>Freezing Peas:
<p>     Once you are finished shelling all the peas, place them in cold water 
to cool them down quickly.  (The quicker they are cooled down the better it 
is.)  Since the peas are already blanched, drain them, bag them and throw 
them in the freezer.  You may choose to freeze them on trays and later 
placed in containers or bags.  This eliminates the large blocks of frozen 
peas that you'll have to contend with when thawing.
<p>Note:
<p>-Overanxious kids may leave floors or themselves sticky from the "flying 
peas" that get  away on them.  Allow space for this or use deeper basins or 
pots for shelling.  The       stickiness is due to the natural sugars produced 
by the peas.   
<P>-You can minimize "flying peas" by pointing the longer side of the pod 
towards the         basin, rather than the pointed end.  
<P>-If shelling outdoors, flying insects may be attracted to the sugary smell.  
Cover the       container for shelled pods when not attended.
<p>Summary:
<p>     Try your hand at popping peas, whether you have a gallon of peas to 
shell or pailfuls, and encourage others to join you. You'll be amazed at time 
that is saved and the fun you may have.
<p>REFERENCES:
<p>Tips in Handling Garden Vegetables; University of Saskatchewan.
<p>When to Pick a Perfect Vegetable, by Warren Asa.
 
<br> 
