<head> 
<title>HERBICIDE INJURY</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
HERBICIDE INJURY TO YARD AND GARDEN PLANTS</center> 
</h1> 
 
                           Sharon Faye
<p>     Damage to plants such as vegetables, trees and ornamentals, 
are becoming more prevalent every year as more and more chemicals 
are being used in and around yards and gardens.  This damage can 
be prevented by increased awareness of what we are using and how 
we are using these herbicides.
<p>General Symptoms:  Chemical injury is recognized by the curling, 
twisting or other distortions of the shoots and leaves.  The 
shoots may elongate and turn yellow and often a fern-leaf effect 
will occur instead of normal size foliage.  Several different 
plant species may be affected by the same symptoms.  This 
distinguishes it from a disease which usually attacks specific 
plants.  Plants usually will grow back to their normal state 
unless a heavy herbicide dose has caused severe dieback.
<p>Herbicide injury can take place in the following ways:
<p>1)   Herbicide drift is the most common cause of chemical damage.  
     Herbicide applied to lawns or fields can drift to sensitive 
     plants and is a risk over a distance of a 1/4 mile or more.  
     Phenoxy type herbicides, such as 2,4-D or MCPA result in 
     distortion and curling of plant parts.  Contact herbicides 
     result in dead spots on leaves, usually unevenly distributed 
     over the leaf surface and uniform in size.  The separation 
     between healthy and damaged tissue is distinct.
<p>2)   Soil applied herbicides or leaf-absorbed herbicides may be 
     taken up by the roots and result in burnt or scorched leaf 
     margins (edges).  Severe damage may cause blotches of dead 
     tissue between the veins which may fall off, giving the leaf 
     a ragged appearance.  Gardens planted in the area can be 
     damaged by persistent herbicides.  Affected evergreens will 
     reveal damage by  their needles turning yellow to purple or 
     brown and eventually dropping off.
<p>3)   The use of sprayers, which are contaminated by a herbicide, 
     to apply a fungicide or an insecticide can also cause plant 
     injury.
<p>4)   Damage occurs when plant material, such as straw or peat 
     moss that was previously sprayed by a persistent chemical 
     such as picloram or dicamba, is introduced into the garden 
     as a soil amendment, mulch or fertilizer (as manure).  
     Included in this category is using soil that has been 
     treated with a herbicide, such as that found at stockpiles, 
     roadsides, etc.  If this soil is incorporated into the 
     garden, problems may result. 
<P>5)   Misapplication can cause injury to plants.  For example:  
     using a higher rate than recommended, (More is not better!); 
     applying a chemical at the wrong time, or using the wrong 
     chemical.
<p>6)   Chemicals which control total vegetation over a long term, 
     such as bromacil, borates and chlorates (soil sterilants), 
     in the home garden should be avoided.  Some of these 
     chemicals can persist for several years, whereas the pattern 
     of garden use could change as a result of a new landscaping 
     plan or property sale. 
   
 <P>    To get the same results, other short-term, less persistent 
     chemicals, such as TCA, round-up or amitrole T should be 
     considered.  Glyphosate (Round-up) works through the plant 
     to it's roots and so provides total vegetation control 
     without soil residue.  The area may be worked and reseeded 
     after a couple of weeks. 
      
 <P>    Amitrole T is slightly more persistent and seeding may need 
     to be delayed until the following season, depending upon the 
     rate used.  These chemicals are recommended for use in the 
     home grounds.
<p>Ways to prevent herbicide injury to yard and garden plants are:
<p>*    Read and follow the directions carefully on all chemicals.   
     Apply according to the rates given and in the manner 
     suggested.
<p>*    Use amine or low volatile types of phenoxy herbicides 
     instead of the ester types to avoid vapour drift.
<p>*    Spray on a calm day or when there is a light breeze, 
     directing the spray away from susceptible plants.
<p>*    Check to see if chemicals are compatible before you mix 
     them.
<p>*    Add wetting agents only when it is recommended.
<p>*    Mix chemicals thoroughly before spraying.
<p>*    For the control of diseases and insects use sprayers that 
     have not been used for applying herbicides.
<p>*    When spraying crops that are sensitive to 2,4-D, use a 
     sprayer which has never contained the chemicals 2,4-D or 
     2,4,5-T. These two chemicals are almost impossible to remove 
     from a sprayer and traces of them in other herbicide 
     solutions will still cause injury to susceptible plants. 
<p>*    Apply at low pressures using coarse spray droplets.
<p>*    Keep spray booms or nozzles near the ground and spray on 
     target.
<p>*    Where spray risk is high, protect your desired plants from 
     drift, paint the weeds with the herbicide using a Q-tip or 
     other means, or weed by hand.
<p>*    Spray in the early morning or late evening when temperatures 
     are cooler.
<p>*    Avoid using long-term, total vegetation control agents in 
     the home garden where water run-off could carry the chemical 
     to non-target plants. 
     Use short-term total vegetation control chemicals instead.
<p>*    Know the source or soil, peat moss, manure, straw or other 
     material used in the garden.  Do not use what has been 
     treated with a persistent herbicide, in your garden or 
     greenhouse. 
<p>*    For protection from aerial sprayed agricultural chemicals, 
     property that is farmed organically (non-chemical farming) 
     may register their fields at municipal offices and post 
     signs (easily observed by ground or air) to mark the limits 
     of the non-chemical use area.  The signs are sold at Sask 
     Wheat Pool Service Centres throughout the province.
<p>SOURCES:
<p>Knud Mortensen; Sask. Agriculture; PLANT DISEASE NOTES: Herbicide 
and Soil Sterilant Damage; Regina; 1979.
<p>Agri-fax / Alberta Agriculture; Herbicide Injury to Yard and 
Garden Plants; August, 1981.
 
<br> 
