<html> 
<head> 
<title>The Birch Tree</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
The Birch Tree</center> 
</h1> 
 
     Birch trees will offer the home owner beauty and shade for 
many years.  A birch tree does not have a problem surviving in 
our climate provided the proper care and growing conditions are 
met.   This article outlines the best conditions, environment and 
care for your birch.  If these basic guideline are followed your 
birch may be enjoyed for many years to come.
<p>  Environment
<p>    Birch trees prefer a sunny location with a well drained, 
light textured soil, that is high in organic matter.  A sandy 
loam is the best.  Other types of soils will be all right, but 
avoid planting in heavy clay.
<p>    Birch trees require more water than most other species of 
trees.  Watering the lawn and watering your trees must be treated 
as separate activities, since a few hours watering the lawn does 
not supply enough water to a birch tree's root system.  In 
general, it's recommended that a soaker hose be placed upside- 
down around the drip line of the tree and run for eight to ten 
hours or until the soil is moistened to a depth of approximately 
24 to 36 inches.  Birch trees should be deeply watered once a 
week, especially in hot, dry weather.  Once fall approaches, a 
reduction in watering is required.  It's best to hold off 
watering during September and October to allow the trees to 
harden off before winter.  A good, deep watering in very late 
fall, just before the ground freezes, will insure an adequate 
moisture supply in the spring but should be late enough in the 
year that new succulent growth will not be the result.  A mulch 3 
to 4 inches in depth will help to reduce the amount of water 
evaporation from the soil surface in addition to reducing the 
weed problem directly under the tree.
<p>    Additional fertilizers are usually not required for birch 
trees, but may be applied in the spring, if their use is 
warranted.
<p>Species
<p>    The two most common birch trees to be grown in Saskatchewan 
are the paper birch and the European weeping birch.
<p>    The paper birch (Betula papyrifera), a native to our northern 
forests, has an upright growth habit and is often grown in a 
clump, multi-stem form.  It can reach a height of approximately 
10 to 12 meters. This species is mainly grown for it's white, 
ornamental bark that peels as it ages.  It's unusual bark adds 
beauty to the landscape especially in the winter months.
<p>  
   The European weeping birch (Betula pendula) has a graceful 
weeping form that can reach a mature height of 16 to 18 meters.  
It's papery, white bark is again of landscape value, especially 
in the winter months. The young branches are long and thin with a 
downward arch providing the tree with it's soft, delicate 
appearance.
 
<br> 
<a href="index.html"><img align=left border=0 alt="" src="im/back.gif"> 
Return to fact sheet index</a><br> 
<br><br><br>Accesses: 206.</Body> 
