<head> 
<title>Tree Problem Diagnosis</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
Tree Problem Diagnosis</center> 
</h1> 
 
                         Russell Friesen
<p>     Accurate diagnosis of a problem in a tree is much like the 
work of a detective solving a murder.  Just as detectives take 
into account all possible evidence in solving a crime, all the 
evidence regarding the decline of a tree must be considered.  
Part of the reason for this is that up to 90% of tree problems 
are caused by environmental stress.  That leaves 10% of problems 
directly due to insects and disease.  Most insects and disease 
problems are the result of nature trying to cull out the weak and 
feeble trees.  The weaknesses are the result of an environmental 
stress.  Insects and disease are symptoms and not causes of tree 
decline.  One can try and control a tree pest, but the causes of 
the tree's susceptibly to the pest should be addressed.
<p>     The steps taken to reach an accurate diagnosis of a tree 
problem is much like the methods of Sherlock Holmes, and that is 
to eliminate the possibilities.  
<p><B>Identify the Tree</B>
<p>     The first step in any investigation is to identify the 
victim.  One must know the species of tree,and ideally the 
variety, origin, age and time of planting.  Knowing the species 
can quickly limit the number of possibilities as each species has 
it's own ideal growing conditions and frequently, pest species.  
Different varieties of trees have different levels of resistance 
to temperature, and disease.  Knowing the nursery origins of the 
trees may solve the mystery outright.  If the tree is from a 
nursery outside of the prairies there is a good chance that the 
problem is because the tree is not winter hardy, even if the 
others from the same species thrive in our conditions.  Another 
consideration in this step is to determine the approximate age of 
the tree and when it was planted.  Just as do people, trees go 
through a period of juvenility, before maturity.  Trees also go 
through a period of transplant shock.  The first three years 
after a tree has been planted are the most critical time for 
proper care.
<p>     Young trees are less able to with stand stress than 
established trees.  A five year old saskatoon bush can with stand 
temperatures of -55 degrees C, a one or two year old saskatoon 
may die back at -40 degrees C.  Most other trees that are grown 
in Saskatchewan do not even come close to the cold tolerance of 
the saskatoon.  Fruit trees are particularly susceptible to cold 
damage, as frequently their roots can only withstand temperatures 
of around -20 degrees C.  
<p><B>Look For a Pattern of Damage</B>
<p>     Step two in our investigation is to try and find a pattern 
of abnormality.  Knowing what is abnormal requires that one knows 
what is normal.  An example of this is that is normal for a 
spruce tree to have no needles in the centre of the tree.  
(Spruce trees typically drop five year old needles, as they are 
shaded out and are costing the tree energy to maintain.)  If one 
doesn't know what is normal, compare the tree to others of the 
same species growing nearby.  This will give an opportunity to 
also determine if the problem is isolated to a single tree or has 
a larger pattern.  
<p>     Random damage is often the result of a living factor such as 
insects and disease.  A regular pattern of damage is usually due 
to a environmental factor particularly if the damage is apparent 
over a number of plant species.  Some possible environmental 
factors for uniform damage are chemicals, physical injuries (eg. 
construction damage), extremes of weather (winter-kill, sun- 
scald), drought or drowning, fall fertilization, and lack of snow 
cover.
<p><B>Examination of Location </B>
<p>     The third step is a careful examination of the site.  Just 
as detectives look for clues on a body, they also look for clues 
at the scene of the crime.  One must check how a tree has been 
situated.  Things to be noted are the contour of the land, and 
the structures near the tree.  Ninety-five percent of a tree's 
roots are within the top 50 cm of the soil surface, and extend 
away from the trunk, two or three times the height of the tree.  
See if the tree is near a roadway, sidewalk, fence, utility 
corridor, building, fuel tank, swimming pool, irrigation line, 
etc.  Determine if any of these factors are present: Has there 
been any nearby construction activity?  Are there chemicals such 
as wood preservatives, pool chlorine, petrochemicals, herbicides 
used nearby?  Is the site used for a snow storage area?  Are 
deicing salts used nearby?  Has the soil grade been changed? 
<p>     Other elements to take into consideration are the past 
weather conditions: Has there been several years of drought?  Has 
the area been flooded?  Was the winter unusual mild/cold?  What 
is the soil pH?  Is there any subsoil salinity or other subsoil 
factors?  Does the tree receive additional water? Is the watering 
timed correctly?  Is the water salty?  Was there a late season 
application of fertilizer?
<p>     These questions help to develop a history of the tree, and a 
pattern may emerge.  Current problems in a tree can be the result 
of an action several years ago.  Using our example of the spruce 
tree, three year old needles falling off this year are often the 
result of a stress that happened three years ago. 
<p><B>Examination of Tree</B>
<p>     The fourth step in the work of a detective is the 
examination of the body, and it is the same with a tree.  First 
look at the leaves,  Are the leaves the correct size, colour, and 
shape?  Are there areas devoid of leaves?  Did the leaves drop 
prematurely or did they stay on too late in the fall?  Are the 
trunk and branches damaged?  Are there signs of wounding, rot, or 
small holes?  Is the damage more prevalent on one side of the 
tree and absent elsewhere?  Are the roots fleshy and light 
coloured or are they brown or black.
<p>     The discolouration or distortion of leaves is caused by 
factors such as drought, drowning, frost and winter-kill of 
roots, salt damage, chemicals, nutrient deficiencies, diseases 
and insects.   Healthy roots are white and fleshy.  Roots that 
are suffering from drought stress or chemical toxicity are brown, 
and black roots are a sign that the tree has either been drowned 
or is being attacked by root-rot organisms.  
<p><B>Possible causes of damage to the trunk and branches:</B>
<p>     Machinery -- girdling the trunk    
<p>     Rope, wire or tree-bands -- girdling the trunk 
      
<P>     Winter sun -- frost-cracks from sap freeze-thaw (south side 
               of the tree)
<p>     Improper pruning- Fungal rot and cavities, sap weeping. 
<p>     Woodpeckers, sapsuckers, and insects - Small holes in bark 
  
<P>     Disease - depressions and discolourations, fungal fruiting 
          bodies, ruptured tissues.
<p>     Insects - girdling the trunk, feeding on decaying wood, 
          foliage discolouration. 
<p><B>Insects and Disease</B>
<p>     By now insects and disease may have been ruled out as the 
cause of the decline of the tree.  Generally insects feed either 
by chewing or sucking.  Leaves will be stippled, stripped, or 
skeletonized.  A healthy tree can withstand most insect attacks, 
but there is always the one fatal pest.  Disease is often the 
result of a unhealthy soil condition,or similar factors.  Most 
diseases are fungal and the way to prevent or cure them is to 
maintain the health of the tree and remove the infected areas 
through pruning.  There are chemical controls for most serious 
tree pests, but those controls will also kill off the predators 
that are the long term control of the pest species.  The use of 
insecticides should be limited to times when the tree is 
seriously threatened.     
<p>     Remember insects and disease are for the most part symptoms 
and not causes of tree decline.  The best means of preventing 
tree decline is to maintain tree health. 
 
<br> 
