<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Winter can be avoided or tolerated</TITLE>

</HEAD><BODY background="im/backgrnd.gif">

<center><img alt="" src="im/line.gif">

<h1>Winter can be avoided or tolerated</center></h1>

Brian Baldwin<P>

<P>

It struck me the other day. You can't wait for a bus on a

Saskatoon street during a record-cold January day without giving

at least cursory consideration to the issue of winter survival.

The strategies of winter survival can be summarized as either

<I>avoidance</I> or <I>tolerance.</I><P>

<P>

In the human world, the difference between <I>winter avoiders</I>

and winter tolerators is usually financial - the option of

avoiding winter is typically only available to those who can

afford it. Sure, these people may stick around long enough to

videotape the grandchildren's Christmas, but the very next day

they aim the car toward Arizona and set off as fast as road

conditions allow. For those of us who cannot afford this

agreeable luxury, tolerance is the only option.

<P>

Plants are also divided into avoiders and tolerators. <P>

<P>

Annual plants take winter avoidance to an extreme. They rush

through summer in a desperate attempt to set seeds before

winter's arrival. In fall they promptly surrender to a frosty

night - dying and leaving only their seeds to represent them the

following year. Seeds of even the tenderest annuals will usually

survive winter if they are fully ripe and dry. This is because

the single most important aspect of any plant surviving winter is

its ability to prevent ice from forming inside its cells. The

instant an ice crystal forms inside a plant's cell, that cell is

killed. A dry seed may contain as little as 5% water. This is

about the same percent of water found in an average bag of flour,

and you can certainly freeze flour without expecting to find ice

cubes forming inside. Dry seeds don't have enough water from

which ice could form.<P>

<P>

Biennials (parsnips and carrots) and herbaceous perennials

(strawberries and rhubarb) avoid some aspects of winter, and

tolerate others. These plants lose their tops to winter's cold,

but the roots and crown remain nestled in the ground where the

soil's store of summertime heat protects them from the full brunt

of frigid winter air. For example, one day in late January when

Saskatoon's air temperature hovered at -30&#176;C, the soil

temperature was -15&#176;C at 5 cm depth, -7&#176;C at 50 cm

depth, and only -2&#176;C at 100 cm. If there is a heavy and

lasting

snowfall in late October, soil temperatures may never go more

than a few degrees below freezing. These are the winters when

even last year's abandoned carrot roots survive.

<P>

Trees and people waiting for buses are similar. They both line

the streets, and they both have no choice but to stand there

tolerating the hideous cold because they can't afford the cost of

avoiding it. If a tree is ever to reach full size it cannot

afford to jettison each summer's growth, spend the winter under

the snow, and resume growing again next spring from the ground.

Splitting the January breeze with your limbs in the air is the

price you pay for being a Saskatchewan tree!<P>

<P>

So how does a living tree tolerate the stress of being frozen to

-45&#176;C or colder without dying? Again, it's a matter of

preventing ice formation inside the cells. To accomplish this,

water in the cells of hardy trees is permitted to slowly leave -

freezing just outside the cells as crystals of ice. As the water

leaves a cell, the dissolved sugars left behind becomes more and

more concentrated. The lower the temperature, the more water will

exit. This means that during times of extreme cold the

consistency of the cell sap will change from being syrupy to

being like solidified honey, fresh brown sugar and finally dry

brown sugar. The hardiest trees are simply those which tolerate

having the driest cells. In spring the cells rehydrate themselves

by re-absorbing the water that froze just outside of them during

winter.<P>

<P>

Apple trees sometimes show winter damage known as sunscald. This

is a condition where the southwest side of the trunk is killed.

It happens on bright cold winter afternoons when the low winter

sun is shining almost directly onto the southwest side of the

tree. Intense light warms the trunk, melting the ice between the

cells and permitting water to be drawn back in. When the late

afternoon sun suddenly dips below the horizon, these rehydrated

cells experience an abrupt return to ambient temperature. The

drop to freezing temperatures occurs more quickly than the cells

can lose their water so internal ice forms and the cells are

killed. To avoid sunscald on apple trees, white latex paint is

sometimes applied to the southwest side of trunks. This reflects

wintertime sun preventing afternoon warming.<P>

<P>

The very hardiest of our trees and shrubs can actually tolerate

much colder temperatures than ever occur naturally on earth. For

example, branches of a saskatoon berry can be collected on a cold

January day and immersed directly into liquid nitrogen (a clear

water-like liquid which always maintains the unthinkably cold

temperature of -196&#176;C). Branches immersed in liquid nitrogen

will cool at a rate of nearly 100&#176;C per second, reaching

-196&#176;C almost instantly. Yet, they survive. Wintertime cells

of

these extremely hardy plants may be so dry that there is

essentially no water available inside them from which ice can

form (like a bag of flour). Since it is the formation of ice, and

not the low temperature which kills the plant, even liquid

nitrogen is not too cold for our hardiest plants. On the prairies

it seems that even the trees agree that winter is tolerable - as

long as it's a dry cold!<P>

<P>

The one other way that trees use to survive winter cold will be

addressed when the forsythia begins to flower early this

spring.<P>

<P>

&copy; 1996 Brian Baldwin<br>

<br><a href="index.html"><img align=left border=0 alt=""

src="im/back.gif">Return to previous index</a><br>

<br><br>Accesses: 115.

</body>

