<head> 
<title>BIRCH, LEAF MINER  BIRCH LEAF MINERS</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
BIRCH, LEAF MINER  BIRCH LEAF MINERS</center> 
</h1> 
 - Northern Forest Research Centre, Edmonton, Alberta.  Text by  H.R. Wong and J.A. Drouin.
<p><B>DAMAGE</B> 
     <P>Damage by these insects is confined to the leaves of 
birches.  The first  signs of attack -- small light green areas 
on the leaf surface -- become  noticeable in early June.  As 
these spots develop they turn into brown blotches,  usually 
several per leaf.  Larvae feeding between the upper and lower 
surfaces  of the leaf are the cause of these blotches, which 
slowly increase in size and  merge; eventually most of the leaf 
turns brown.  This brown blister effect is  characteristic of 
damage caused by birch leaf miners. 
      <P>Although most of the inner leaf tissue where the food for 
tree growth is  manufactured may be destroyed, this need not 
cause serious damage.  A healthy  tree should be able to 
withstand several years of light to moderate attack  without 
being killed.  Birch leaf miners do cause stress that, combined 
with  lack of adequate moisture and attack by tree borers, may 
cause branch dieback.  Soaking the roots in the fall before frost 
sets in, applying a suitable tree  fertilizer each spring, and 
watering during dry periods in the summer will keep  your tree 
healthy and better able to withstand leaf miner attacks. 
      <P>Because the insects feed inside the leaf, special treatment 
is required for  control.  Most of the recommended insecticides 
are systemic, which means that  they are absorbed by the plant 
and carried to the leaves, where they kill the  feeding larvae.  
This takes time (about 1 week), so the blotches may continue to  
expand in size for a while after treatment.  Make the first 
application of the  recommended insecticide to the soil, bark, or 
leaves as soon as damage is  noticed.  If the tree was attacked 
the year before, apply the insecticide as  soon as the leaves are 
fully open, without waiting for the damage to become  noticeable.  
The three recommended treatments that follow are in order of 
their  effectiveness.  Only one type of treatment should be 
applied to a tree in any  one year. 
      <P>A soil drench is the most effective method of control and 
has the added  advantage of eliminating spray drift and 
contamination of nearby plantings.  This method kills the larvae 
in the leaves and also any residual leaf-mining  insect 
populations in the soil.  In late May, after the leaves are fully 
open,  apply undiluted dimethoate (Cygon 2E) 23.4% emulsifiable 
concentrate at the rate  of 50 mL for each 2.5 cm (4 tbs or 2 fl 
oz per in.) of tree trunk diameter  measured 1.2 m (4 ft) above 
the ground.  (For example, a tree 10 cm (4 in.) in diameter would 
require the use of one 250-mL bottle (8 oz) of dimethoate.)   Dig  
four small, shallow holes around the base of the tree inside the 
drip line,  which is the circle defined by the tree's longest 
branches.  Apply the chemical  in roughly equal parts into the 
holes.  Fill the holes with soil, and water  until saturated to 
ensure uptake of the insecticide.  One soil treatment should  
give control for that season.  Do not make more than one soil 
treatment per  year or apply more insecticide than required.  
Soil drenches on newly  transplanted birches may not be effective 
or may cause injury. 
      <P>The most widely used method is to paint, with the 
applicator or a brush, a  band of undiluted dimethoate (Cygon 2E) 
around the trunk below the branches when  the new leaves are 
fully open.  The band should be 2.5 cm (1 in.) in width for  
every 2.5 cm of tree diameter measured 1.2 m (4 ft) above the 
ground.  Do not  use this treatment on trees less than 2.5 cm or 
more than 15 cm (6 in.) in  diameter.  Repeat the application in 
early July, but avoid painting the  insecticide on the same spot. 
      <P>Birch leaf miners may also be controlled by spraying 
insecticides on the  foliage.  Spray with acephate (Orthene 16 
EC) 15.6% emulsifiable concentrate at  22 mL/5 L of water (1.5 
tbs/gal), carbaryl (Sevin 50 WP) 50% wettable powder at  18 g/5 L 
(5 tsp/gal), or dimethoate (Cygon 2E) 23.4%, diazinon (Basudin 50 
EC)  50%, or malathion 50% emulsifiable concentrates at 10 mL/5 L 
(2 tsp/gal).  A  second application should be made in mid-July. 
      <P>Chemical insecticides are toxic to humans, animals, birds, 
and fish.  Follow all instructions and precautions listed by the 
manufacturer.
<p><B>THE CAUSE </B>
      <P>The most common birch leaf miner has the scientific name 
Fenusa pusilla  Lepeletier.  The adult is a small, black wasplike 
insect known as a sawfly.  The  female lays eggs in slits on the 
upper surface of young birch leaves near the  midrib, usually in 
mid-May.  In early June, tiny grublike larvae hatch from the  
eggs and burrow into the leaf, where they feed on the tissues 
between the leaf  surfaces.  The larvae may be seen by peeling 
back the surface layer of the  blotch.  Mature larvae emerge from 
the interior of the leaf in early July and  drop to the ground to 
pupate.  Two weeks later they emerge as adults, and the  life 
cycle is repeated.  Up to four generations per year are possible, 
but  usually only two occur in the prairie region.  The larvae of 
the last  generation overwinter in small earthen cells below the 
soil surface, and the  adults emerge the following spring.  This 
birch leaf miner usually attacks the  newer foliage and has a 
distinct preference for the upper half of the tree crown. 
      <P>Two other sawfly species, which are similar in appearance, 
also attack  birch leaves in much the same manner; however, both 
Profenusa thomsoni Konow and  Heterarthrus nemoratus Fallen 
produce only one generation per year and prefer  more-mature 
leaves.  These two sawflies cause the most damage to birch, with  
feeding damage beginning in mid-July and extending to early 
September or until  the first frost.  Although feeding damage to 
the leaves by H. nemoratus differs  slighty, the control is the 
same as for the other two. 
 
<br> 
