<head> 
<title>BOXELDER BUG</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
BOXELDER BUG</center> 
</h1> 
 
- C.C. Peters, SDA, Regina
<p>ECONOMIC IMPORTANCE 
  <P>    The boxelder bug, Leptocorouos trivittatis sucks the sap 
from leaves and  flowers of host plants but does little damage, 
and in most years is of little  significance.  After several mild 
winters large populations may build up so that  they become a 
nuisance in and around homes and yards.  The bugs congregate in  
large masses on the sunny side of tree trunks, fences, porches, 
patios, garages  and houses.  They normally survive the winter by 
crawling into cracks and holes  in bark but also swarm into 
houses or crawl under siding or cracks in concrete,  window and 
door sills.  They produce no odor nor do they damage clothes or 
bite.   They are harmless.
<p>HOST PLANTS 
<P>      Boxelder bugs feed on the leaves, flowers and seeds of 
female Manitoba  Maples (also called boxelders) and to a lesser 
extent on the male trees.  When  overpopulated they also feed to 
some extent on other trees and shrubs and some  garden plants. 
<P>      Boxelder bugs are true "bugs" and belong to the Order 
Hemiptera and have a  gradual metamorphosis.  The adults are 
somewhat flattened, narrow oblong in  shape, 10-14 mm long and 
about a third as wide. 
<P>      The thorax and wings are dark grey-brown to black in color 
from above and  edged with orange-red.  The body is orange-red in 
general. 
<P>      The head, antennae and legs are all black.  The adults 
congregate in masses  and mate in late summer and fall and 
overwinter wherever they find a safe hiding  place, such as in 
cracks or crevices in tree trunks or buildings or in trash.  In 
spring they emerge, and lay bright red eggs in cracks of bark of 
Manitoba  Maples.  The nymphs that hatch are bright red but 
gradually become marked with  black wing pads.  The nymphs mature 
in September and there is likely a partial  second generation.
<p>CONTROL 
<P>(a)  Natural<BR> 
     Severe winter weather and lack of suitable wintering sites 
appear to be the  major factor that keep populations in check.  
Mild winters result in greater  populations.
<P>(b)  Physical <BR>
      A number of things can be done to prevent or reduce 
problems:  - Eliminate hiding places such as piles of rocks, 
boards and debris near  buildings.  - Repair cracks in 
foundations, siding, windows and doors.  - Tree removal might be 
considerd since Manitoba Maples are not good trees near  
buildings and because of extensive sap flow from aphids and bugs, 
and root  damage to foundations.
<p>(c)  Insecticides<BR>
(1) Foliar Spray <BR>
      If populations have been large, spray the nymphs and trees 
with Carbaryl  (Sevin) at 1.25 - 1.5 g ai/L or trichlorfon 
(Dylox) at 1.25 g ai/L in early  summer (this will also control 
boxelder aphids). <P>
<P> (2) Residual Spray <BR>

    In late summer as they congregate in masses spray the bugs 
on tree trunks,  fences, walls of buildings with Chlordane 2% 
spray or trichlorfon (Dylox) at  12.5 g/10 L. (3) Indoor Sprays 
 <P>     Hand-collecting, repeated vaccuuming or a household spray 
containing  pyrethrins is recommended. 
 
<br> 
