<head> 
<title>Cankerworms: Help Protect Our Trees</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
Cankerworms: Help Protect Our Trees</center> 
</h1> 
 
- Your Guide to Controlling Cankerworms
<p>Leaflet form the City of Saskatoon Civic Buildings and Grounds 
Department
<p>Cankerworms
<p>Cankerworms are caterpillars found primarily on the leaves of 
American Elm and Manitoba Maple trees in May and June. Other 
species of trees may also be defoliated. The caterpillar is one of 
four stages in the lifecycle of a cankerworm. These include egg, 
larva, pupa and adult. The adult,or egg-laying stage of the 
cankerworm, is actually a moth. The pupa is a stage of 
metamorphosis similar to the cocoon stage of a butterfly, and is 
the stage where the caterpillar is transformed into the adult moth. 
The caterpillar is the larval, or leaf-eating stage.
<p>Types of Cankerworms
<p>There are two kinds of cankerworms found in Saskatoon, the fall 
cankerworm and the spring cankerworm. Both of these eat and cause 
damage to leaves at the same time of the year, however, other 
aspects of their biology differ slightly. The fall cankerworm moth 
lays its eggs on the trees before winter, usually after the first 
severe autumn frost. The spring cankerworm lays its eggs after 
winter, usually after the first major spring thaw.
<p>Recognizing Cankerworms
<p>Both spring and fall cankerworm larvae are about 2.5cm long when 
fully grown and range in colour from light green to brownish green 
with a dark stripe down the back. They are often called loopers, 
inchworms,or measuring worms because or measuring worms because 
they crawl in a looping manner. One very characteristic feature of 
cankerworm larvae is their ability to spin down on threads when 
disturbed.
<p> Cankerworm Damage
<p> The first noticeable sign of an infestation is small holes in the 
new leaves, often referred to as "shot-hole" damage.  As the 
cankerworms continue to feed, the holes enlarge until only the 
veins of the leaf remain.  during severe outbreaks, trees may be 
completely stripped of their foliage. Although healthy trees 
usually re-leaf by early July, their growth is slowed and their 
resistance to disease and other insect attack is weakened. After 
several years of severe defoliation, dead branches may develop, 
usually in the upper part of the tree's crown.
<p> As always in nature, there are parasites, predators, disease and 
environmental conditions that keep insect populations to a 
tolerable level. However, when the cankerworm population is high 
these natural checks are less effective and applied control - may 
be necessary to protect your trees. Outbreaks , are very difficult 
to predict.
<p> Tree Banding
<p> The use of tanglefoot bands is a physical method of controlling 
the adult moths. The female cankerworm moth is wingless, and after 
emergence from the soil, must climb the tree to mate and lay her 
eggs. Banding tree trunks with a sticky substance such as "Tree 
Tanglefoot" will trap the female and prevent egg-laying. "Tree 
Tanglefoot" is a commercial product available at local garden 
supply centres, tree companies.
<p>Because cankerworm larvae can travel from tree to tree on their 
silken threads, the banded tree may still be at a risk of 
defoliation from neighbouring trees. Encourage your neighbours to 
band their trees. In addition, we encourage and ask your assistance 
in banding city boulevard trees. It will help to keep the 
neighbourhood green all summer long
<p>Spraying
<p> At times when the larvae are high in numbers it may be necessary 
to control them with the use of insecticides. But remember, a tree 
is normally very tolerant of some defoliation, and applied control 
efforts are unnecessary when only a few cankerworms are present. 
Only if you notice "shothole" damage on a great number of leaves 
will you want to consider chemical controls.
<p> There are two types of spray control for cankerworms:
<p> 1. Environment Friendly Approaches
<p>- Use a mixture of insecticidal or dish soap with water from your 
garden hose. You may need to repeat the operation a number of 
times. This procedure is intended to desiccate newly hatched worms 
or knock larger worms off the tree.
<p>- Use a natural biological control agent such as Dipel or Thuricide 
(Bacillus thuriengiensis) which can be sprayed on the leaves of the 
tree. The Bacillus must be ingested by the larvae to be effective. 
Once it is consumed the larvae will stop feeding. Although the 
larvae will live for several days after ingestion, no more 
defoliation will occur.
<p>2. Chemical Approach
<p>- There are a number of insecticides registered for use against 
cankerworms. Contact insecticides such as malathion or methoxychlor 
kill the caterpillars on contact. If using insecticides, always 
read the label and take precautions to ensure safety to you, your 
family and your neighbours.
<p>STEP 1. <BR>
APPLY FIBERGLASS INSULATION.
<p>Attach a 15 - 20 cm wide band of fibreglass style, insulation 
approximately 1.5 - 2.0 m above ground.
<p>Secure the insulation with two bands of tape (preferably fibreglass 
packing tape or duct tape, etc.) wrapped over the insulation around 
the tree. This will fill the cracks and crevices of the bark and 
prevent the female from crawling under the band.
<p>Step 2.<BR> 
COVER FIBERGLASS WITH PLASTIC SHEET
<p>  Attach a strip of plastic vapour barrier over the insulation 
tight enough to ensure there are no gaps between the plastic, 
insulation and trunk. Wrap tape around both ends of the plastic.
<p>STEP 3. <BR>
APPLY TANGLEFOOT TO PLASTIC SHEET
<p> Apply a thin layer of tanglefoot to the band. About 1 kg of 
tanglefoot is needed to band 8 - 10 medium (50 cm diameter) sized 
trees.
<p> When to Install/Remove the Band
<p>The bands should be in place by September 1. To prevent 
rotting of the bark the bands must be removed each spring after 
approximately May 15. Bands applied in the fall may be kept on the 
trees all winter to control for the spring cankerworm. Just apply 
a new coat of tanglefoot in the spring and make any necessary 
repairs.
<p>  Trees provide beauty, shade and shelter throughout our city. Help 
protect this valuable community resource. If you have any concerns 
or questions about tree maintenance, contact the City of Saskatoon 
Civic Buildings and Grounds Department (975-3300). 
 
<br> 
