<head> 
<title>CANKERWORMS SLOWED BY COLD WEATHER</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
CANKERWORMS SLOWED BY COLD WEATHER</center> 
</h1> 
 
Carl Lynn
<p>Cankerworm infestation is lower than last year (1991).  Cool spring 
weather had slowed down cankerworm hatching and decreased feeding 
damage.  Cool, wet weather occurred at the end of April and 
between May 19 to May 25.  As result, the cankerworm hatch, which 
started in April, did not finish until the third week of May. 
   
<P>For the hatched cankerworms (and for us as well, for that 
matter!), the weather has been miserable. Cool, rainy weather 
stops cankerworm larvae from feeding.  Cankerworms, which hatched 
during April, appear to have died in some instances possibly due 
to the lack of feeding.  The larvae which hatched during May seem 
to have survived.
<p>Observation of several sites within Saskatoon indicate that the 
size of cankerworm hatch is smaller than last spring, 1991.  The 
smaller hatch may be due to a higher ratio of male moths to 
female moths for both the fall and spring species of cankerworm.  
As well, many eggs may have been destroyed by a parasite.    
<p>In the fight against the remaining cankerworms, now is the 
perfect time for you to use a natural insecticide which contains 
Bacillus thuringiensis.  The small 4 to 10 mm length larvae are 
more easily killed by this bacteria than when they are 15 to 25 
mm in length.  Check your trees now.  If you have these small 
pests, spraying now will save the tree or shrub from unsightly 
defoliation.  When the cankerworm larvae are larger, you can  use 
either a chemical insecticide or Bacillus thuringiensis.
<p>Another pest group, leaf rollers and leaf tiers, could cause more 
damage this summer than cankerworms.  The population of leaf 
rollers, a green worm with a black head,  appears to be higher 
this spring compared to previous years.  Green ash trees are 
especially vulnerable to leaf rollers because they leaf out 
slowly, so that the leaves emerge already damaged.   Consider 
checking your ash as well as other trees and shrubs for leaf 
rollers and leaf tiers.  Take control measures before they damage 
the leaves significantly.  Although Bacillus thuringiensis is not 
licensed to control leaf rollers and tiers, it can be effective 
in some cases.  Alternatively, use a chemical insecticide.   
<p>Young leaf rollers may be mistaken for cankerworms.  They both 
spin down on a thread when disturbed.  When small, 1-10 mm  in  
length,  they are both green.  However, the leaf roller has a 
dark black head and vigorously backs up when you place an object 
in front of it.  When they both reach the 15-25 mm length, the 
cankerworm changes from a green to a brown color, while the leaf 
roller remains green.
<p>Lynn is a scientific information officer with Agriculture Canada, 
Saskatoon Research Station  This column is provided as a service 
by the Extension Division and the Department of Horticulture 
Science, University of Saskatchewan. 
 
<br> 
