<head> 
<title>COOLEY SPRUCE GALL APHID</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
COOLEY SPRUCE GALL APHID</center> 
</h1> 
 
- Northern Forest Research Centre, Edmonton, Alberta by  R.M. Caltrell
<p>DAMAGE 
  <P>    Most species of spruce are attacked, but damage to white, 
Engelmann, and  Colorado spruces is most noticeable.  Individual 
trees planted as ornamentals  and in shelterbelts or occurring 
naturally in forest stands can be affected. 
<P>      Damage begins in late May, when new growth on the branch 
tips develops into  cone-shaped galls.  The galls are swellings 
about 5 cm long that contain  hundreds of aphids feeding on the 
sap from the tree's new growth. Initially the  galls are green; 
later they turn reddish purple and dry out.  Old vacated galls  
have mouthlike openings and stunted needlelike projections and 
are reddish  brown. 
<P>      The presence of the cooley spruce gall aphid is also 
indicated by white  cottony specks that appear on the tree early 
in the spring and throughout the  summer.  In heavy infestations 
these white specks, which are produced by female  aphids as a 
protective cover for their eggs, can cover an entire tree.  Only  
first-generation aphids feed inside galls.  Succeeding 
generations feed openly  on the branches, sucking sap out of old 
needles.  Some of these needles may dry out and fall off. 
<P>      Damage is mainly cosmetic.  Old galls remain on the 
branches for 2-3 years,  making trees somewhat unsightly.  If 
gall formation is heavy, growth and vigor  may be reduced, but 
trees are rarely killed. 
<P>      Douglas-fir is the alternate host of this aphid, although 
its presence is  not essential for the buildup of large 
populations.  Aphids on Douglas-fir  exhibit the same white 
cottony specks but do not form the characteristic galls.  Needles 
may drop off, as in spruce, but damage is not usually serious.
<p>CONTROL 
<P>      The cooley spruce gall aphid has very few natural enemies, 
so if  populations are high some form of control may be 
necessary.  Picking new galls  off as they are formed and burning 
them will improve the tree's appearance and  help to reduce aphid 
populations.  For complete control, spraying with an  insecticide 
is necessary. 
<P>      Timing of spray application is critical to prevent the 
formation of galls.  If this aphid was present on a tree last 
year, the chemical should be applied  just as the buds begin to 
open.  Do not wait until new damage shows up.  If new  galls have 
already formed, later generations of the insect can be controlled 
by spraying 7-10 days after the white specks appear and repeating 
the application  once or twice at 7- to 10-day intervals.  It 
usually takes three applications  for satisfactory control. 
<P>      Carbaryl (Sevin 50 WP) and malathion are approved 
insecticides for  controlling the cooley spruce gall aphid.  
Either Sevin 50% wettable powder at  the rate of 21 g/L (1 
oz/gal) water or malathion 50% emulsifiable concentrate at  50 
g/100 L (1.5 oz/gal) water should be sprayed on the tree to the 
drip stage.  Malathion should not be applied when the air 
temperature is below 20 C. 
<P>      Control of the aphid on Douglas-fir is not normally 
required; however,  affected trees may be treated by spraying 
exactly as for spruce after the white  cottony specks become 
apparent.
<p>CHEMICAL INSECTICIDES ARE TOXIC TO HUMANS, ANIMALS, BIRDS, AND 
FISH.  FOLLOW ALL  INSTRUCTIONS AND PRECAUTIONS LISTED BY THE 
MANUFACTURER.
<p>THE CAUSE 
<P>      The feeding nymphs and adults of the cooley spruce gall 
aphid [scientific  name Adelges cooleyi (Gill)] are very small, 
dark insects.  The life cycle is  complicated and takes 2 years 
to complete.  Several generations and all stages are present in 
any one year.  The exact relationship between the primary host  
(spruce) and the alternate host (Douglas-fir) is not yet fully 
understood,  although reproductive cycles can apparently take 
place on either species. 
<P>      On spruce, eggs laid in the autumn at the base of the 
needles hatch into  nymphs in 3-4 weeks.  The nymphs feed on the 
needles before settling on the stem  immediately below the buds 
to overwinter.  In early spring the nymphs develop  into wingless 
females known as stem mothers, which are parthenogenetic, that 
is,  they can reproduce without mating.  Near the buds they lay 
large numbers of  eggs.  In 7-10 days the eggs hatch into nymphs, 
which feed at the base of the  newly emerging needles.  Salivary 
secretions from the stem mother initiate the  galls that form 
around the feeding nymphs.  In midsummer the nymphs emerge from  
the galls and molt to become parthenogenetic females.  Up to six 
overlapping  generations feed on old needles and do not cause 
galls.  At some stage winged  females migrate to other spruce 
trees or to Douglas-fir, if present, and expand  the infestation. 
 
<br> 
