<head> 
<title>FALL CANKERWORM</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
FALL CANKERWORM</center> 
</h1> 
 
by Carl Lynn
<p>Fall is approaching.  When the fall season is upon us, you will 
witness the return of fall cankerworm moths.  It's time to think 
about controlling them again!
<p>During the early summer of this year, fall cankerworm larvae 
defoliated many trees in and around Saskatoon.  Near the end of 
June, the mature larvae dropped to the ground, where they 
constructed a pupal case to wait for the fall.  Fall cankerworm 
moths will emerge from the pupal cases in October or in late 
September after a hard frost.  The female moths are wingless and 
the male moths have wings.
<p>Tanglefoot is a sticky material that can be used to trap the 
female moths as they climb the trees to lay their eggs.  First, 
wrap a band of pink fibreglass insulation around the tree about 1 
m (3 ft) from the ground.  Cover the insulation with a band of 
plastic wrap (from a plastic garbage bag) and secure the wrap to 
the tree with outdoor tape.  Apply the tanglefoot to the plastic 
wrap.  The middle of September is about the correct time to tape 
the bands to the tree trunks and to apply the tanglefoot.
<p>Careful observation this spring showed that tanglefoot applied 
last September did reduce the impact of cankerworms on the banded 
trees.  However, many banded trees were infested by larvae that 
blew in from trees that had not been banded.  The non-banded 
trees were defoliated very quickly.  Banded trees infested by 
nearby unbanded neighbours lost leaves as well, but because the 
infestation was delayed, it was possible to save the remaining 
leaves by spaying the trees.  
<p>Neighborhoods should therefore endeavour to seek the cooperation 
of all home owners so that there are few, if any, unbanded trees 
in the area.  Even if all the trees in a neighbourhood are 
banded, some cakerworm damage will occur because tanglefoot 
banding does not completely eliminate infestations.  In addition 
to banding, spraying, I therefore recommend spraying young fall 
cankerworm larvae in the spring with a biological control agent, 
such as Bacillus thuringiensis.  Biological agents do not destroy 
parasites that attack and kill cankerworms, as some 
non-biological agents do.  Furthermore, by using a biological 
agent, you are helping to reduce problems caused by some 
chemicals in the environment.  BOTH banding and spraying are 
required because of the large numbers of cankerworms currently in 
pupation.  
<p>Lynn is an information officer with Agriculture Canada.  This 
column is provided as a service by the Extension Division and the 
Department of Horticulture Science, University of Saskatchewan. 
 
<br> 
