<html> 
<head> 
<title>FALL CANKERWORM</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
FALL CANKERWORM</center> 
</h1> 
 
- Northern Forest Research Centre, Edmonton, Alberta by V.  Hildahl
<p>DAMAGE 
<P>      Fall cankerworm larvae feed on most broad-leaved trees and 
shrubs, but  prefer American elm, Manitoba maple, basswood, 
Siberian elm, and apple.  The  first noticeable sign of an 
infestation is small "shot-holes" in the young  leaves.  At this 
time the tiny larvae are found on the underside of the leaf.  As 
the larvae continue feeding, the holes grow larger, until almost 
all of the  leaf tissues are eaten.  During severe outbreaks, 
trees and shrubs may be  completely defoliated.  Healthy trees 
and shrubs usually produce a new crop of  leaves by mid-July and 
show little permanent injury from a single defoliation.  However, 
after 3 or more consecutive years of heavy attack tree growth is 
slowed  down and branches in the crown die back.
<p>CONTROL 
 <P>     The insect is controlled naturally by parasites, predators 
(birds and  rodents), starvation, and adverse weather conditions.  
Nevertheless, during  outbreaks when larvae are extremely 
abundant these natural checks are less effective, and applied 
control may be desirable to prevent serious injury,  especially 
to trees with high ornamental value.
<p>TREE BANDING with a sticky substance will prevent adult females 
from climbing up  the host plant to lay their eggs.  In 
mid-September a 4-in. wide (10 cm) band of  glass wool insulation 
with paper backing or similar material should be secured  around 
the tree trunk about 5 ft (1.5 m) above the ground, paper side 
out.  On  older trees loose bark should be carefully removed to 
facilitate proper  installation.  A thin layer of sticky adhesive 
(e.g. Tree Tanglefoot) is smeared  over the paper.  The sticky 
surface should be cleaned at regular intervals of  2-3 days until 
mid-November to remove accumulated debris.  Banding is most  
effective if trees are sufficiently isolated so that they will 
not become  infested with wind-dispersed larvae.
<p>INSECTICIDES reduce larval populations quickly and are relative 
simple to use.  One application of the biological insecticide, 
Bacillus thuringiensis, or the  chemical insecticides, carbaryl 
or methoxychlor, in late May or early June  usually prevents 
serious defoliation.  Bacillus thuringiensis, which is produced  
from naturally occurring organisms, is sprayed on the foliage at 
the rate of .06-.30 billion IU/3 gal of water (there is no metric 
equivalent).  Carbaryl  (Sevin 50 WP) 50% wettable powder is 
applied at the rate of 5 tsp/gal water (18  g/5 L), and 
methoxychlor 25% emulsifiable concentrate at 1 tsp/gal (5 mL/5 
L0.  Best results are obtained when the insecticide is applied in 
the early morning  or evening.  The type of spray equipment 
required will be determined by the size  and number of trees and 
shrubs to be treated.  Dusts and pressurized sprays of  carbaryl 
mixed with malathion, rotenone, or pyrethrins are also available 
for  homeowner use. 
<P>CHEMICAL INSECTICIDES ARE TOXIC TO HUMANS, ANIMALS, BIRDS AND 
FISH.  FOLLOW ALL  INSTRUCTIONS AND PRECAUTIONS LISTED BY THE 
MANUFACTURER.
<p>THE CAUSE 
 <P>     The adult moths of the fall cankerworm (scientific name 
<I>Alsophila pometaria</I>  Harr.) emerge from cocoons in the soil in 
late September and October.  The  wingless females crawl up the 
host plant and lay their eggs in masses on the  twigs, branches, 
and trunks.  The eggs, which resemble minute flowerpots, hatch  
in the spring.  The larvae, often called loopers, inchworms, or 
measuring worms  because they crawl in a looping manner, attack 
the foliage as soon as the buds open.  When full-grown about 
mid-June the larvae are about 1 in. (2.5 cm) long  and range in 
color from light green to brownish green with a dark stripe down  
the back. 
 <P>     A characteristic of these larvae is their habit of spinning 
down on threads  when disturbed.  The threads also aid in 
dispersal of the larvae because they  can be blown considerable 
distances by the wind. 
<P>      The spring cankerworm (scientific name <I>Paleacrita vernata</I> 
Peck), a closely  related species, is less common than the fall 
cankerworm but can also cause  severe defoliation.  Adults of 
this species emerge and lay their eggs in the  spring.  It is 
therefore necessary to reapply the sticky adhesive to the tree  
band in mid-April in order to maintain its effectiveness.  
Insecticides are  applied in late May or early June, exactly as 
for the fall cankerworm. 
 
<br> 
<a href="index.html"><img align=left border=0 alt="" src="im/back.gif"> 
Return to pest index</a><br> 
<br><br><br>Accesses: 54.</Body> 
</html>
