<head> 
<title>LILAC LEAF MINER</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
LILAC LEAF MINER</center> 
</h1> 
 
- Northern Forest Research Centre, Edmonton, Alberta by  D.S. Kusch
<p>DAMAGE 
  <P>    The common lilac is the species most susceptible to lilac 
leaf miner  attack.  Damage is first noticeable in early July as 
a small, transparent,  yellowish spot on the underside of the 
leaf tip.  This is caused by larvae  feeding inside the leaf.  As 
the larvae tunnel further into the leaf tissue, a  light green 
spot appears on the upper surface.  This spot grows larger, turns  
yellowish, and eventually becomes brown and brittle.  Later, the 
larvae vacate  the mines, roll up the leaf from the tip, and 
continue to feed, skeletonizing  the upper leaf surface.  Most of 
the damage takes place in the lower part of the  shrub, and a 
second attack can usually be expected in late summer. 
<P>      Damage by the lilac leaf miner is rarely fatal, but it does 
give the shrub  an unhealthy, unslightly appearance.
<p>CONTROL 
<P>      Although lilacs are almost always hardy enough to withstand 
several years  of attack, you may wish to control the lilac leaf 
miner in order to reduce damage done the following year or to 
prevent spread of the pest.  Single,  open-growing plants can be 
protected simply by picking off all the infested  leaves and 
burning them.  Numerous shrubs or extensive hedges may require  
chemical control using systemic insecticides that penetrate the 
foliage or are  translocated through the sap system. 
<P>      Open-growing lilacs can be treated by painting a band of 
undiluted  dimethoate (Cygon 2E) around each stem the same width 
as the stem diameter about  0.3 m above the ground.  This should 
be done as soon as damage is noticed.  If  the shrub was attacked 
the year before, the insecticide may be applied in mid-  to late 
June, without waiting for damage to show up.  Another application 
may be  necessary about the first of August to control a second 
generation of leaf  miners.  Avoid painting the second 
application at the same spot on the stem. 
<P>      If the paint-on method is not practical because of large 
numbers of stems  to be treated, shrubs may be sprayed in early 
July when damage is first  noticeable using a pressurized hand 
pump and 10 mL of dimethoate (Cygon 2E)  23.4% emulsifiable 
concentrate, acephate (Orthene 16 EC) 15.6% emulsifiable  
concentrate, or malathion or diazinon (Basudin 50 EC) 50% 
emulsifiable  concentrates diluted in 5 L of water (2 tsp/gal).  
Spray should be directed to  the lower leaves and stem portions 
from both sides.  Shrubs should be resprayed in early August.  
Malathion should not be applied when the temperature is lower  
than 20 C.
<p>CHEMICAL INSECTICIDES ARE TOXIC TO HUMANS, ANIMALS, BIRDS, AND 
FISH.   FOLLOW  ALL INSTRUCTIONS AND PRECAUTIONS LISTED BY THE 
MANUFACTURER.
<p>THE CAUSE 
<P>      Adults of the lilac leaf miner [scientific name <I>Caloptilla 
syringella</I>  (Fabricius)] emerge from the soil from late May to 
mid-June.  They are small  moths with a wingspread of about 10-12 
mm and are grayish brown n color with  yellowish patches.  After 
mating, females may lay well over 100 transparent eggs  in groups 
of 5-10 along a vein on the underside of a leaf.  Egg hatch, 
which  takes 7-10 days, is usually completed by late June.  The 
larvae chew through the  egg shell into the leaf and begin 
mining.  Mature larvae are flattened,  yellowish in color, and 
about 8 mm long.  Most feeding by this generation is  completed 
by mid-July, when the larvae drop to the ground and pupate in the  
soil.  Moths from these pupae emerge from late July to early 
August, and the  second-generation larvae may feed well into 
September.  Pupation again takes  place in the soil where the 
insects overwinter. 
 
<br> 
<a href="index.html"><img align=left border=0 alt="" src="im/back.gif"> 
Return to pest index</a><br> 
<br><br><br>Accesses: 44.</Body> 
