<html> 
<head> 
<title>PEAR SLUG</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
PEAR SLUG</center> 
</h1> 
 
- Northern Forest Research Centre, Edmonton, Alberta by J. Drouin.
<p>DAMAGE 
  <P>    Cotoneaster, hawthorn, mountain ash, pin cherry, and fruit 
trees are  commonly attacked.  The first signs of an infestation 
are yellow spots caused by  conspicuous sluglike larvae feeding 
on the upper leaf surface.  As feeding  progresses, the affected 
areas increase in size, merge, and turn brown, giving  the tree 
or shrub a scorched appearance.  Foliage may drop prematurely. 
<P>      Healthy trees and shrubs should be able to withstand 
several years of  moderate attack, because the damage occurs in 
late summer when the growing  season is nearly complete.  During 
years of high pear slug populations, the  mucous-coated larvae 
can be a nuisance, and the damaged foliage is unsightly.
<p>CONTROL 
<P>      Trees and shrubs should be checked frequently from about 
mid-July to late  August for pear slug larvae or evidence of 
feeding.  Nonchemical control of the  larvae can be obtained by 
rinsing the larvae off the tree with a strong stream  of water 
from a garden hose. 
<P>      The pear slug may also be controlled by contact 
insecticides.  Both rotenone and pyrethrum are natural, 
nonpolluting plant products that are  effective and fast-acting 
but short-lived.  Rotenone is applied as a 1% dust,  pyrethrum 
(or pyrethroids) is generally applied as an aerosol spray.  
Infested  trees or shrubs may also be treated with chemical 
sprays of malathion 50%  emulsifiable concentrate at 10 mL/5L (2 
tsp/gal) of water or carbaryl (Sevin 50  WP) 50% wettable powder 
at 7 g/5L (2 tsp/gal).  Malathion should not be applied  when the 
temperature is lower than 20 C. 
<P>      CHEMICAL INSECTICIDES ARE TOXIC TO HUMANS, ANIMALS, BIRDS, 
AND FISH.  FOLLOW ALL INSTRUCTIONS AND PRECAUTIONS LISTED BY THE 
MANUFACTURER.
<p>THE CAUSE 
<P>      The adult pear slug [scientific name <I>Caliroa cerasi</I> (L.)] 
is a small, black  wasplike insect known as a sawfly.  Eggs are 
laid singly in small incisions cut  in the undersides of leaves 
in late June.  Larvae emerge in 9-15 days and begin  feeding on 
the upper surface of the leaf.  Each larva moves on to another 
leaf  after eating a hole about the size of a dime (1-2 cm2) and 
may damage several  leaves before its larval development has been 
completed.  In the early stages  the larvae are easily 
identifiable by their sluglike appearance and dark olive  green 
mucous coating.  Older larvae lose this coating and turn bright 
yellow.  At this point they stop feeding and drop to the ground, 
where they overwinter in  fragile earthen cocoons just below the 
soil surface.  In the spring the larvae  pupate and the adults 
emerge. 
 
<br> 
<a href="index.html"><img align=left border=0 alt="" src="im/back.gif"> 
Return to pest index</a><br> 
<br><br><br>Accesses: 50.</Body> 
</html>
