Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html> 
<head> 
<title>PINE NEEDLE SCALE</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
PINE NEEDLE SCALE</center> 
</h1> 
 
- Northern Forest Research Centre, Edmonton, Alberta by D.S.  Kusch.
<p>DAMAGE 
  <P>    In spite of its name, this insect most commonly attacks 
white and Colorado  spruces in the prairie provinces.  Scots and 
lodgepole pines, other spruces, and  Douglas-fir are also 
susceptible.  The most severe damage occurs in nurseries,  
shelterbelts, and ornamental plantings. 
<P>      Tiny white specks, or scales, on the needles are usually 
the first  indication of attack.  In a continuing infestation 
these waxy white elongated  scales (about 3 mm long) become very 
numerous.  In mid-June newly hatched nymphs  (crawlers) emerge 
from the protective scale covering and migrate to other  needles 
in search of food.  They pierce the needles and extract cell sap,  
causing yellowish green spots to develop around each insect.  In 
severe  infestations the yellow spots coalesce, needles drop 
prematurely, and the  foliage of several branches or the complete 
tree, except for the new needles,  takes on a gray, unhealthy 
appearance.  On severely infested pine trees needles  are reduced 
to about half their usual size. 
<P>      Continuing infestations reduce the vigor and annual growth 
of the tree, making it more susceptible to attack by other 
insects or unable to withstand  adverse weather conditions.  
Severe infestations will eventually kill twigs,  branches or 
small trees.
<p>CONTROL 
<P>      Lady beetles and small wasplike parasites are important 
natural controls  of the pine needle scale.  Heavy rains soon 
after the eggs have hatched may also  destroy many crawlers.  
When populations are high, however, chemical control may  become 
necessary to prevent serious injury.  Spraying with malathion, 
dimethoate  (Cygon 4E), or diazinon (Basudin 50 EC) 50% 
emulsifiable concentrates or  carbaryl (Sevin 50 WP) 50% wettable 
powder using a hand pump sprayer when the  unprotected crawlers 
are active will usually give good results.  The spray  solution 
should contain 1 tbs of one of the emulsifiable concentrates per 
gallon  of water (16 mL/5 L) or 5 tsp/gal (16 g/5 L) of carbaryl 
wettable powder.  Trees  should be sprayed thoroughly in mid-June 
or shortly after the new needles  appear.  A second application 
should be made in early August to kill surviving  females before 
they secrete their protective scale coverings and lay eggs.  
Malathion should not be used when the temperature is below 20 C. 
<P>      INSECTICIDES ARE TOXIC TO HUMANS, ANIMALS, BIRDS, AND FISH.  
FOLLOW ALL INSTRUCTIONS AND PRECAUTIONS LISTED BY THE 
MANUFACTURER.
<p>THE CAUSE 
<P>      The newly hatched nymphs of the pine needle scale 
[scientific name  <I>Phenacaspis pinifoliae</I> (Fitch)] are minute 
insects, oval in shape and reddish in  color, that wander over 
the needles searching for suitable feeding sites.  Infestations 
are spread to other trees by wind-borne crawlers.  The insects  
insert their mouth parts into the needle tissues and then become 
stationary.  In a short time they become flattened, turn light 
brown, and in about 2 weeks  molt.  During the following 3 weeks 
the male secretes a white scale covering  about 1.5 mm long under 
which he develops into a tiny winged form.  At this time  the 
female, which remains stationary on the needle for life, molts 
again to  become a wingless adult.  Mating takes place, the male 
dies, and the female  begins excreting a scale covering.  The 
covering is completed about mid-August,  when it is about 3 mm 
long, and egg laying begins.  As egg laying continues, the  body 
of the female shrinks, and eggs (usually 30-50) fill the cavity 
under the  covering, where they overwinter.  In the spring the 
hatching period may vary  slightly depending on weather 
conditions; however, most nymphs emerge during the  second week 
of June.  In the prairie provinces there is only one generation 
per year. 
<P>      For more information contact the Canadian Forestry Service. 
 
<br> 
<a href="index.html"><img align=left border=0 alt="" src="im/back.gif"> 
Return to pest index</a><br> 
