<head> 
<title>POPLAR BUD GALL MITE</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
POPLAR BUD GALL MITE</center> 
</h1> 
 
- Northern Forest Research Centre, Edmonton, Alberta by  J.A. Drouin
<p>DAMAGE 
<P>      All species of poplar are attacked.  Damage is lightest on 
native species  (trembling aspen, plains cottonwood, and balsam 
poplar) regardless of  geographical location and most severe in 
the southern prairies on the numerous  poplar hybrids developed 
for use as ornamentals or in shelterbelts.  Not all  hybrids are 
equally susceptible.  Some, such as Dunlop or Griffin, are more  
resistant to attack, while others, such as Brooks #5 and 
Northwest, are more  susceptible. 
<P>      Damage is usually confined to the lower branches of the 
tree.  The mites  attack leaf clusters as they develop in the 
spring, sucking the plant sap,  stopping any further twig growth 
at the point of attack, and causing the  formation of 
cauliflower-like swellings called galls.  New galls, in which the  
mites live, are dark green, hairy, and soft, changing later in 
the summer to a  brick red color.  Over 3 or 4 years, active 
galls may grow to 2 cm or more in  diameter.  Old or abandoned 
galls are grayish, hard, and woody and retain the  characteristic 
ridged and furrowed surface. 
<P>      Since new galls are formed every year and old ones persist 
on the tree, the  lower branches become stunted and crooked and 
ultimately die.  The tree itself  is seldom killed, but 
continuing heavy attack reduces its aesthetic value and  may make 
it more susceptible to other pests or to adverse climatic 
conditions  such as frost or drought.
<p>CONTROL 
<P>      Control is difficult because the mites spend most of their 
life cycle  inside the protective galls and reproduce rapidly.  
If only a few small trees  are affected, the insect can be 
controlled by pruning out and then burning all  branches with 
galls on them.  It is imperative to remove all galls, because if  
they are overlooked reinfestation can easily occur.  There are 
enough mites in  one active gall to reinfest not only the host 
tree but nearby trees as well.  Pruning should be done annually, 
preferably in the fall when the tree is dormant  and the mites 
are overwintering inside the galls. 
<P>      At present there is no approved chemical control.  Research 
is currently  underway and some promising results have been 
obtained, but it may be some time  before registration is 
approved. 
<P>      The adult poplar bud gall mite [scientific name <I>Eriophyes 
parapopuli</I>  (Keifer)] is a wormlike insect so tiny that it is not 
visible to the naked eye.  Adult mites feed on new poplar buds or 
unfolding leaves and inject into the tree  a substance that 
stimulates the formation of a gall around them.  The mites live  
inside the gall, feeding on its tissue and producing a new 
generation every 2-3  weeks.  As the population increases, the 
gall grows in size. 
<P>      The mites continue feeding and reproducing inside the gall 
until October.  They spend the winter in the gall and in the 
spring either feed on the gall's  new growth or migrate along the 
branches to where buds are unfolding and there  form new galls.  
Because they are so tiny, the mites are easily blown by a  breeze 
to other trees, where they start a new infestation. 
<P>      Eight or more generations are produced each year.  Each 
active gall  contains 3000 or more mites; galls are inhabited for 
up to 4 years and then  abandoned. 
 
<br> 
