<head> 
<title>Spruce Needle Miner</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
Spruce Needle Miner</center> 
</h1> 
 
Northern Forest Research Centre, Edmonton, Alberta <BR>
by D.S.  Kusch
<p>DAMAGE 
 <P>     White, Engelmann, Colorado blue, and Norway spruces are 
attacked by this  insect.  Plantings growing under adverse 
conditions, such as ornamentals and  shelterbelts on the 
prairies, are particularly susceptible to serious injury.  The 
presence of dead needles and frass (droppings) bundled together 
with silken  webbing is evidence of an infestation and signals 
further damage to the tree or  spread of the insect to adjacent 
trees.  Damage begins in early July when larvae  cut circular 
entrance holes at the base of the old needles and then feed 
inside.  Each larva is capable of eating the entire contents of 
10 needles, leaving only  the outer layer, or epidermis.  When 
mature, the larvae leave the needles and  construct the nest of 
frass and dead needles in which they overwinter.  The  nests are 
usually found near the base of large branches in the thickest 
growth.  On small trees they are commonly located on the lowest 
branches next to the  trunk. 
<P>      The loss of needles weakens the tree, and the nests give 
the tree an  unsightly appearance.  The nests also trap airborne 
material such as dust and poplar and willow cotton, and if the 
infestation is severe or persistent the  branches become covered 
with a thick mat of debris that impairs the tree's  vigor.  
Continued heavy attack along with the presence of secondary 
organisms  could eventually kill the tree.
<p>CONTROL 
<P>      In the spring before the buds break the nests can be washed 
away with a  strong stream of water from a garden hose.  The 
debris should then be gathered  and burned.  This procedure will 
reduce the current year's infestation but not  necessarily 
eliminate it. 
<P>      Chemical control using a pressurized hand pump and an 
insecticide that  penetrates the surface of the needles will 
usually kill the feeding larvae.  Dimethoate (Cygon 2E) 23.4% 
emulsifiable concentrate is the only insecticide  approved for 
controlling needle miners on spruce.  Spray the trees to the drip  
stage with dimethoate at the rate of 10 mL per 5 L of water (2 
tsp/gal).  Trees  should be sprayed in early July because by that 
time most of the eggs have  hatched. 
<P>      Spray should be directed to the center of the tree to 
saturate the older  needles.  A second application may be made in 
early August if larvae are still present. 
<P>      CHEMICAL INSECTICIDES ARE TOXIC TO HUMANS, ANIMALS, BIRDS, 
AND FISH.  FOLLOW ALL INSTRUCTIONS AND PRECAUTIONS LISTED BY THE 
MANUFACTURER.
<p>THE CAUSE 
<P>      Adults of the spruce needle miner (scientific name <I>Taniva 
albolineana</I>  Kearfott) emerge from late May to late June, with 
the peak in mid-June.  They  are small, grayish brown moths 
having a wingspan of about 12 mm.  After mating,  the female lays 
2-8 pale yellow eggs along the side of a needle.  The larvae  
hatch in about 10 days.  Each larva chews a circular hole at the 
base of a  needle and, once inside, mines upward to the tip.  
Newly hatched larvae feed  along one side, but as they grow they 
eat the entire needle contents.  The  entrance hole is then used 
as an exit as the larvae search for other needles.  Full-grown 
larvae are green with a brown head and are about 6 mm in length.  
Generally, the larvae are active until October, when they 
construct a cocoon  inside the next and overwinter.  Pupation 
begins in early May and continues  until early June.  Development 
of the adult takes about two weeks. 
<br> 
<a href="index.html"><img align=left border=0 alt="" src="im/back.gif"> 
Return to pest index</a><br> 
