<html> 
<head> 
<title>SPRUCE SPIDER MITE</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
SPRUCE SPIDER MITE</center> 
</h1> 
 
- Northern Forest Research Centre, Edmonton, Alberta by C.  Tidsbury.
<p>DAMAGE 
 <P>     The spruce spider mite can be a serious problem on planted 
white and  Colorado spruce; damage is less severe on other spruce 
species.  The first sign  of damage occurs in mid- to late May 
when needles appear dingy yellow or  brownish and later dry up 
and drop off.  The discoloration is first noticeable  in the 
lower branches near the trunk, spreading upwards and outwards 
toward the  branch tips as the summer progresses. 
<P>      The damage is caused by spruce spider mites inserting their 
mouth parts  into needles and sucking out the sap.  The mites 
also spin an abundance of fine  silken webbing that is especially 
noticeable between the needles on the  underside of the branches.  
In severe or prolonged infestations, dust particles,  shed 
needles, and dead mites caught in this webbing form a dense mass 
that  contributes to the tree's unhealthy appearance. 
<P>      Infestations that persist year after year reduce the tree's 
vigor and  ultimately cause death.  To keep trees healthy every 
effort must be made to  control this insect at the first sign of 
damage. 
<P>      Heavy rain accompanied by high winds and extreme 
temperatures provides some  measure of natural control.  On small 
trees a weekly washing during the spring  and summer with a 
strong stream of water directed toward the center of the tree  
can achieve the same results.  However, when weather conditions 
favour mite  buildup, and large trees or a large number of trees 
are infested, chemical  control is necessary to prevent serious 
damage. 
<P>      There are three chemicals recommended for mite control:  
dicofol, diazinon,  and malathion.  Dicofol (Kelthane) 18% 
emulsifiable concentrate at a rate of 2  oz/gal of water (62 mL/5 
L) or diazinon (Basudin 50 EC) or malathion 50%  emulsifiable 
concentrates at 1 oz/gal (31 mL/5 L) should be sprayed on the  
tree, directing the insecticide toward the foliage near the stem.  
Usually two  applications are necessary for effective control, 
one during the third week in  May and a second in June or early 
July.  Malathion should not be applied when  the air temperature 
is lower than 20C.
<p>INSECTICIDES ARE TOXIC TO HUMANS, ANIMALS, BIRDS AND FISH.  
FOLLOW ALL  INSTRUCTIONS AND PRECAUTIONS LISTED BY THE 
MANUFACTURER. 
<P>      The spruce spider mite [scientific name <I>Oligonychus 
ununguis</I> (Jac.)] is  extremely small and scarcely visible to the 
naked eye.  Eggs laid in the fall  overwinter under bud scales or 
at the base of needles.  About mid-May larvae  hatch from the 
eggs and develop into nymphs, and the nymphs in turn develop into  
first-generation adults by early June.  The larvae, nymphs, and 
adults feed on  the needles and to some extent on the twigs.  In 
mid-June the female adult lays  about 40-50 eggs that give rise 
to a second generation by late June.  Succeeding  generations are 
produced at 2- to 3-week intervals during the remainder of the  
summer and early autumn so that there may be as many as six 
overlapping  generations each year.  This exceptional 
reproductive capacity and short life  cycle account for the 
rapidity with which a light infestation can develop into a  
severe one. 
 
<br> 
<a href="index.html"><img align=left border=0 alt="" src="im/back.gif"> 
