<head> 
<title>THE ATTACK OF THE ADELGID</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
THE ATTACK OF THE ADELGID</center> 
</h1> 
 
Grant Wood
<p>Remember those tiny, white, fuzzy specks on the needles of your 
spruce trees last year?  If you see them now, the adelgid has 
returned and now is the time to act. . .
<p>Spruce gall adelgids are common pests in the province, causing 
some (but not drastic) harm to white, Engelmann and Colorado 
spruce.  Because they are similar to aphids, they are also 
sometimes called spruce gall aphids, but are more correctly 
called adelgids.  There are a number of different kinds of gall 
adelgids, and each causes a slightly different looking gall - a 
swollen area of plant tissue.  
<p><B>Life Cycle:</B>  Adelgids take two years to complete their complex 
life cycle, which involves two different kinds of trees, both 
winged and wingless insect forms, and sexual and asexual 
reproduction.  We told you it was complicated!  Let's look at 
part of the life cycle of the spruce gall adelgid, starting in 
spring.
<p>Immature adelgids (nymphs) overwinter on the tree.  These nymphs, 
which are all females,  are about 1 mm long. They mature by 
mid-May and begin laying eggs.  At this stage, they are called 
brood mothers; they are capable of laying eggs without having 
mated.  
<p>After laying her eggs, the brood mother spins a cottony, 
protective covering over them.  The egg masses are the fuzzy 
white specks (like tiny pieces of cotton) on the needles.  But 
look closely at these white specks.  If you see firm, slender, 
pointed white specks rather than fuzzy ones, you are not looking 
at adelgid egg masses!  What you are seeing is the pine needle 
scale - an insect that is not related to adelgids..   
<p>Approximately two weeks after the eggs are laid, adelgid nymphs 
hatch.  The brood mothers begin to suck sap from the base of the 
new needles, which causes the characteristic galls to form.  
These galls gradually encase and thus protect the young nymphs.
<p>Starting in June, mature female adelgids emerge from these galls, 
and begin feeding on other needles, but do not cause any new 
galls to form.  Only one set of galls form each year, in the 
spring.  These mature female adelgids also lay eggs, which will 
hatch into another generation of nymphs.  Several generations can 
occur each year.  This is why the tiny, fuzzy, white specks 
re-appear from time to time during the summer.
<p><B>Damage:</B>  Galls formed by the feeding of the adelgids vary in 
shape, size and colour, depending on the type of adelgid doing 
the damage.  Newly formed galls are often red to purple in 
colour.  They remain this colour until the females emerge in the 
summer, and then the galls dry and become brown.  Dead galls may 
remain on a tree for a number of years.
<p><B>Control:</B>  An effective control method is to cut off all the young 
galls as soon as they form and destroy them before the females 
emerge in early June.  
<p>Obviously on a large tree it very difficult to remove all the 
galls.  Contact insecticides may need to be used.  Effective 
control of the brood mothers will decimate the population and 
prevent mass reproduction during the summer.
<p>It may take three sprayings of insecticide at weekly intervals to 
fully control the insects.  The first spraying should occur just 
as the buds begin to open, usually early to mid-May.  Effective 
contact insecticides include insecticidal soap, liquid deritox, 
diazinon, and sevin.  If the air temperature is above 20C 
malathion can be used.  Once the galls have formed, future 
generations can be controlled by spraying trees two weeks after 
the wooly egg masses are seen.  The above contact insecticides 
are equally effective in summer.
<p>Wood was an instructor with the Department of Horticulture 
Science.  This column is provided as a service by the Extension 
Division and the Department of Horticulture Science, University 
of Saskatchewan. 
 
<br> 
