<head> 
<title>THRIPS</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
THRIPS</center> 
</h1> 
 
Thrips are insects that are common to houseplants, roses, 
gladioli and some vegetables and fruits.  They are small and 
slender.  The young are white, yellow or orange in color and the 
adults brown or black.  The life cycle of a thrip takes approx 2 
weeks under warm conditions and longer at lower temperatures.  
Thrips feed on all areas of the plant but are often found in the 
protected areas of flowers and developing buds which makes them 
hard to see.  The most noticeable sign of thrips is white or 
silver streaking on the leaves or flower buds and new growth may 
be deformed.

<p>1.    Cabbage - Thrips will move from the Canola crop once it has 
been swathed onto cabbage, cauliflower and broccoli plants.  The 
damage in the case of cabbage shows a slightly raised yellow to 
light brown patches on the leaves.  Cabbages with a lot of damage 
are unsalable, however only the outer leaves are damaged and 
removing these leaves means the inner portion of the head is 
quite suitable for home use.
<p>2.    Gladioli - thrips are a major pest of gladioli.  They 
overwinter on the corms and can ruin the flowers and also make 
the leaves unattractive.  
<p>3.    Cucumbers - In the home or small greenhouses thrips will 
move in in the summer and fall and distort the shape of 
cucumbers.  Growing cucumbers in the home or small greenhouse can 
be difficult as thrips often move into the house from the 
surrounding outdoor plants.  These thrips damage the leaves as 
well as the developing fruit.  Fruits appear to be misshapened 
and have scarred areas on the skin making them unsalable but 
usable for home use.
<p>4.    Houseplants - Thrips can be a problem all year round on 
houseplants especially the weeping fig.  Figs, when severely 
damaged, are unthrifty and leaves appear mottled with dead tissue 
present.
<p><B>CONTROL:</B>
<p>For control of thrips on plants use malathion or Diazithon as 
directed on the label.
<p>Corms of gladioli can be dusted with carbary before storing for 
the winter and left in open trays for 1 month.  If cold storage 
facilities are available store for 2 months at 35F (2C) or 3 
months ar 40F (45C) to kill all stages of the insect.  If corms 
are not treated before storage they can be soaked in lysol (2 oz 
in 3 gallons of water) for 3 hours before planting in spring.  
Plants may then be sprayed several times to control thrips that 
may come in from the nearby plants.

<p>&copy;1990 Charmaine Newfeld <BR>

<br> 
