<head> 
<title>WHITE PINE WEEVIL</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
WHITE PINE WEEVIL</center> 
</h1> 
 
- Northen Forest Research Centre, Edmonton, Alberta by J.A.  Drouin
<p>DAMAGE 
 <P>     In the prairie provinces the white pine weevil attacks 
white, Engelmann,  Colorado blue, and Norway spruces.  It can 
also seriously infest jack, red, and  Scots pine and occasionally 
black spruce and mugho pine.  Although the insect  will attack 
trees in natural stands, it much prefers open-growing, vigorous  
ornamentals, plantations, or nursery stock less than 10 m high 
that have a top  main shoot, or leader, that is 13 mm or more 
thick. 
<P>      In the spring the presence of adult weevils on the tree and 
resin beads on  last year's leader are the first signs of attack.  
The resin oozes from  punctures caused by adult weevils inserting 
their elongated mouthpart through  the bark and feeding on the 
succulent inner tissues.  Eggs laid in these  punctures later 
hatch into larvae that tunnel downward between the bark and  
wood, eventually girdling the leader.  This feeding activity also 
cuts off the  water supply to the current year's new growth, 
which wilts and eventually turns  brown by mid-July.  At least 2 
years of growth (current and last year's) are  always killed and 
sometimes 3 or more years' growth are killed, depending on how 
far down the main shoot the larvae tunnel.   After the leader 
dies, one or  more of the side branches nearest the top will 
usually turn upward and assume  leadership, resulting in a 
crooked or forked tree with a bushy top.  Secondary  organisms 
such as heartrot can often gain entry through weevil-killed 
leaders. 
<P>      This insect is one of the most destructive pests of North 
American forest  plantations and has created havoc in planting of 
its most common host, the  eastern white pine.  In the prairies 
its impact can also be severe, so control  measures should be 
considered as soon as damage becomes apparent.
<p>PREVENTION 
<P>      Growing ornamentals under 50% shade will help make them 
less attractive to  weevils by reducing the thickness of the 
leader; however, the shade will also  retard height growth.  
Another means of prevention is the use of the insecticide  
methoxychlor at 3- to 4-year intervals until the trees are over 
10 m tall.  If  the white pine weevil is present in your 
neighborhood, preventive spraying of  your spruce and pine should 
be undertaken as a matter of course.  Trees that  were infested 
previously and pruned of their dead parts should also be treated  
to prevent new attack. 
<P>      Only the leader (last year's growth) needs to be sprayed.  
Using methoxychlor (25 EC) 25% emulsifiable concentrate at the 
rate of 16 mL/5 L of  water (1 tbs/gal) together with 94 mL (6 
tbs) of molasses, spray the leader to  the drip point in late 
April or early May.  The addition of molasses or a  commercial 
spreader-sticker (e.g., Chevron) ensures good protection for all  
sides of the leader.  Two applications spaced 10-14 days apart 
give better  control than a single application. 
<P>CHEMICAL INSECTICIDES ARE TOXIC TO HUMANS, ANIMALS, BIRDS AND 
FISH.  FOLLOW ALL  DIRECTIONS AND PRECAUTIONS LISTED BY THE 
MANUFACTURER.
<p>CONTROL 
<P>      Natural predators and parasites appear to have little 
effect on this  weevil, particularly once it becomes well 
established.  There is no chemical  control; however, pruning 
infested trees can be an effective control measure for  young 
ornamentals, shade trees, and trees in small plantings.  The 
damaged  leader should be cut off just above the topmost 
undamaged branches during the  latter part of July or as soon as 
the damage is noticed, in order to prevent the  death of more 
than 2 years' height growth.  The infested leader should then be  
burned.  Pruning must be completed before the adults emerge in 
late summer.  To train a new leader, cut the tips off the 
remaining topmost branches except  for the strongest branch, 
which will rapidly develop as the new leader. 
<P>      Pruning currently infested trees will not put an end to the 
weevil.  All  conifers should be checked yearly for weevil 
symptoms, and any infested leaders  should be pruned and burned.  
<P>THE CAUSE 
<P>      Adults of the white peen weevil [scientific name <I>Pissodes 
strobi</I> (Peck)]  overwinter in the soil under infested trees, 
emerging in the spring.  They are  dark brown beetles about 8 mm 
long, with two elbowed antennae near the top of a  long snout.  
The adults move up to the leader, feed on the soft inner tissues  
and deposit eggs in the feeding punctures in late May.  When the 
larvae hatch,  in about 2 weeks, they feed as a group in the 
woody tissue beneath the outer  bark of the leader and then 
travel downward, girdling the stem.  For the next  5-6 weeks they 
continue feeding and mature through four larval stages.  The  
small, legless grubs reach about 10 mm when fully grown and have 
a reddish brown  head.  At this time they bore into the wood to 
form wood-chip cocoons, where  they change to adults.  The adults 
emerge from the infested stems from early  August to late 
September, feed for a period on the branches nearby and then  
overwinter in the soil.  There is only one generation each year. 
 
<br> 
