<html> 
<head> 
<title>WORMS, WEBS AND WRIGGLES:</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
WORMS, WEBS AND WRIGGLES:</center> 
</h1> 
 
INSECT PESTS OF DECIDUOUS TREES AND SHRUBS <BR>
- By Sara Williams
<p>The last few weeks have brought with it warm temperatures coupled 
with  severe insect infestations in trees and shrubs in some 
parts of the  province.  Among the more noticeable pests on 
deciduous trees and shrubs  have been aphids, spider mites, leaf 
rollers, and "loopers" (or  cankerworms).
<p>APHIDS
<p>Aphids are small (less than 1/3 in. or 1 mm long), soft-bodied,  
oval-shaped insects with six legs, usually light green or black 
in  colour.  They can be winged or wingless.  They cluster under 
leaves and  along stems and attack nearly all species of plants, 
piercing the plant  and sucking the sap.  They usually feed on 
the underside of leaves,  which eventually dry out and wilt. 
Symptoms of aphid infestation can include distorted, curled, 
deformed,  or discoloured leaves.  As well, most aphids excrete a 
sweet, sticky  substance, referred to as "honeydew," which is 
particularly noticeable  if it drips on a parked car or on a 
picnic table under a severely  infected maple tree.
<p>Aphids can be controlled by applying malathion (50% emulsifiable  
concentrate) to the drip stage when the infestation is first 
noticed.  A  second application may be necessary 2 or 3 weeks 
later if aphids are  still present.  Malathion should not be 
applied when the temperature is  below 20C or when bees are 
pollinating.  (It is highly toxic to bees.)
<p>SPIDER MITES
<p>Spider mites are extremely small.  One usually needs a microscope 
or  magnifying glass to see them.  They are soft-bodied, red to 
brown to  white in colour, and have chewing mouth parts and 8 
legs.  Like aphids,  they affect a wide range of plant species 
and do some damage in most  years.  Their populations seem to 
build up during hot, dry periods. 
<p>Infested leaves become silvery and may turn yellow or brown, curl 
up,  become brittle and be covered with a fine webbing.
<p>Infected plants may be sprayed with dicofol, diazinon or 
malathion as  directed on the label when infestations occur.  
Mite populations on  spruce trees can be redued by regular hosing 
with cold water.
<p>LEAFROLLERS
<p>Leafrollers are found on apple and other fruit trees throughout 
the  province and are usually present in small numbers every 
year.
<p>The eggs (which are laid the previous summer and overwinter on 
twigs and  branches) are pale yellow to brown and covered with a 
brownish varnish.  They are laid in masses of up to 100.  There 
is only one generation per  year.
<p>The larvae or worms are thin, green with a dark-brown or black 
head, and about 2.5 (1 in) long.  The adult is a brownish-yellow, 
mottled moth  with two beige spots on the wing margins.
<p>In spring, the young worms hatch just at the leaves and flowers 
are  budding out.  Almost immediately they spin a light web 
around several  leaves, rolling them together.  When the 
caterpillars are full grown 2  cm (3/4 in.) long, they pupate 
inside rolled leaves or make a flimsy  cocoon on the trunk or 
branches.  Moths emerge in July.
<p>A heavy application of a dormant oil spray put on before buds 
break and  leaves emerge and applied so as to cover every egg 
mass has been  effective.  A dormant oil application before the 
leaf buds burst  destroys the overwintering eggs.  Use according 
to label directions.  Do  not use on maples.
<p>Once the worms or larvae have rolled themselves up in the leaves 
they  are much more difficult to control.  A contact insecticide 
is not  usually very effective, as the insecticide should 
actually hit the worm  itself.  Spraying with carbaryl (Sevin) is 
effective if it is done early, while the worms are still exposed.  
Alternatively, a biological  control is equally effective as long 
as the worms are exposed.  Bacillus  thuringiensis is a bacteria 
which kills the larvae of moths but is  harmless to other 
insects, bees, birds and mammals.  Although the larvae  live for 
up to a week after spraying, they stop feeding (and thus  
damaging trees and shrubs) almost immediately.  Bacillus 
thuringiensis  is available in commercial form as Thuricide or 
Dipel.  Systemic  insecticides may only be used on trees and 
shrubs listed on the label.  They can be highly toxic to other 
trees and shrubs.
<p>FALL CANKERWORMS
<p>Fall cankerworms hang down on silk threads when disturbed, making  
themselves rather dramatically conspicuous to the homeowner.  
They  normally affect maples, elms, ash, cotoneasters, apples, 
and plums, but  can affect other trees and shrubs if high 
populations build up.
<p>They are called "fall cankerworms" because the eggs which produce 
them  are laid by a wingless moth in September.  Because she is 
unable to fly and must crawl up the trunk of the tree in order to 
lay her eggs,  banding the trunk of the tree with a product 
called "tanglefoot" is a  preventative control measure.  
Tanglefoot is a sticky substance banded  to cardboard which traps 
the moth on her way up.  It is best applied  about September 1.  
(If applied earlier, other insects and debris will  become 
entangled in it, rendering it ineffective by fall).  Tanglefoot  
is less effective if neighboring trees have not been banded, as 
the  cankerworms can move from tree to tree in the wind on their 
silken  threads.
<p>Once they have hatched, cankerworms can be controlled with Dipel 
or  Thuricide (Bacillus thuringiensis) as described for leaf 
rollers. 
 
<br> 
