<head> 
<title>YELLOW-HEADED SPRUCE SAWFLY</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
YELLOW-HEADED SPRUCE SAWFLY</center> 
</h1> 
 
- Northern Forest Research Centre, Edmonton, Alberta  by D.S. Kusch.
<p>DAMAGE 
 <P>     Most species of spruce are attacked, including white, 
black, Engelmann, and  Colorado blue.  Open-growing trees such as 
ornamentals or shelterbelts are  particularly vulnerable.   The 
first sign of damage, in early June, is the  presence of small 
larvae that eat portions of the developing needles.  As the  
larvae grow during the next 30 days, they consume entire new 
needles and  eventually old needles as well.  By mid-July heavily 
infested trees are ragged  in appearance, especially near the 
top, and take on a yellowish brown color that  is visible from 
long distances.  In extreme cases trees may be completely  
stripped of foliage. 
<P>      Continuing infestations reduce annual growth and make the 
tree susceptible  to attack by other insects or unable to 
withstand vegetative competition or  adverse weather conditions.  
Two or three consecutive years of moderate  defoliation are 
enough to kill a tree. 
<P>      Natural predators and parasites have very little effect on 
this insect when  weather conditions are favorable for a high 
population buildup.  Applied control  is then essential to 
prevent loss of the tree. 
<P>      Effective control on a few small trees can be achieved 
simply by picking  the larvae off when they first appear and 
destroying them.  On large trees or a  large number of trees, 
chemical control using a hand pump sprayer will usually  give 
adequate protection.  Malathion is the only insecticide presently 
approved  for controlling sawflies on spruce.  Spray trees 
thoroughly with 1 tbs of  malathion 50% emulsifiable concentrate 
per gallon of water (16 mL/5 L) without  actually drenching them.  
Trees should be sprayed about mid-June before the  damage becomes 
noticeable from a distance, otherwise most of the current year's  
damage will probably have already occurred.  A second application 
may be made 2  or 3 weeks later if larvae are still present.  
Malathion should not be applied  when the temperature is lower 
than 20 C.
<p>    INSECTICIDES ARE TOXIC TO HUMANS, ANIMALS, BIRDS, AND FISH.  
FOLLOW ALL  INSTRUCTIONS AND PRECAUTIONS LISTED BY THE 
MANUFACTURER.
<p>      Adults of the yellow-headed spruce sawfly [scientific name 
<I>Pikonema  alaskensis</I> (Roh.)] emerge from the soil from late May 
to mid-June depending on  weather conditions.  The insect looks 
like a small wasp and has four shiny  transparent wings with a 
network of visible veins.  After mating, females lay  eggs at the 
base of newly developing spruce needles.  In 5-10 days the larvae  
hatch and begin feeding on the needles. 
<P>      Newly hatched larvae have a yellowish head and light 
yellowish green body.  By mid-July they are fully grown and 3/4 
in. (2 cm) in length with a reddish  head.  The body is green and 
glossy or waxy in appearance with gray-green strips  running its 
length.  When disturbed, the larvae exude a liquid from the mouth  
and arch both ends.  During July they drop to the ground and spin 
a cocoon in  the soil, where they remain until the following 
spring.  The pupal period lasts  about a week, and then the 
adults emerge.  There is only one generation a year. 
<P>      Another less common sawfly also feeds on spruce.  Its 
larvae are darker  with grayish strips and a shiny black head, 
but control measures are exactly the  same. 
 
<br> 
