<head> 
<title>AFRICAN VIOLETS</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
AFRICAN VIOLETS</center> 
</h1> 
<p>The most frequently found house plant in Canada is the African 
violet.  Its enormous variety of colours, forms, leaf shape and 
hue is not matched by many house plants.  The original parental 
plant material for all these varieties was isolated less than 100 
years ago by Baron Von St. Paul.  In fact it was 1892 when he 
sent plants, or perhaps they were seeds, to his father in 
Northern Germany from West Africa.  These little plants flowered 
in Germany in 1893; 35 years later the Los Angeles nursery firm 
of Armacost and Royston Inc. started to develop a range of 
hybridized varieties.  They selected 10 varieities, in the 
violet, purple, blue colour range, for commercialization.
<p>Since their original release these varieties have shown a range 
of mutations, such as doubleness of flowers, colours and leaf 
colour.  These mutations, being crossed back into the original 
varieties, have led to an almost infinite variety of flower form 
and colouring as well as leaf texture in this range of plants.  A 
number of other species of Saintpaulia, as the genus became 
known, have allowed for a trailing habit to be introduced from 
Saintpaulia Grotei by hybridization.  But there are many other 
species of Saintpaulia that have significant opportunities for 
further long-term breeding programs.
<p>There are now a wide range of colourful and intriguing varieties 
of African Violet available from local nurseries.  If you would 
like to get into the habit of growing these plants, here are a 
few tips.  While African Violets will grow in a Northern exposure 
there will probably be only leaves produced rather than heavy 
bloom.  Generally they need all the light they can get throughout 
all seasons of the year, except in the summer, when full sunlight 
can just be too intense for them.  In spring, fall and winter, a 
few hours of sun daily are preferable to produce healthy, 
blooming plants.  It is easy to tell if they are getting too much 
sun, for the foliage turns yellow and the leaf edges tend to burn 
a little.  Too little light produces beautiful dark, green 
leaves, but few if any flowers.  Seek a happy medium, move your 
plants around the house until you find a suitable window for your 
plants.  A western exposure is good all year round for most 
violets if you have such a window.  Keeping turning the pots your 
plants are in so that they don't tend to lean toward the light 
too markedly.  It is advised that the pots should be turned a 
quarter of a turn every day to produce a well balanced form.
<p>From the point of view of temperatures, African Violets will be 
happy when you are.  They like a room temperature of between 72 
and 75F.  Night temperatures, of course, can be a little cooler.  
Extreme cold will damage your plants, so in winter try to keep 
them away from the window panes to avoid temperatures that can go 
below 55 or 50F.
<p>Along with a reasonable temperature, African Violets also require 
good ventilation, but don't expose them to unnecessary drafts.  
In winter, when the windows are generally shut, a small fan, 
operating at a low speed to keep the air moving, is ideal for 
their needs.
<p>Advice about watering African Violets is always difficult.  It 
varies depending on the type of pot they are planted in, the 
potting mix and their location.  However, there are some key 
pointers; one is that you should always use water that is at room 
temperature when watering your violets, be careful not to get 
water in the crown of the plant.  This can be avoided by bottom 
watering, putting the pot in a saucer of water and letting the 
soil of the pot soak it up by capillary action.  Better yet is 
the installation of a wick system within the plant pot.  These 
can be made in a number of different ways, but I have found it 
useful to use a half pound butter dish with a hole in the lid 
through which the wick can come from the pot into a reservoir of 
water.  Such a system will allow your African Violet to 
effectively look after its own water for two, or perhaps three 
weeks at a time.  Salt build-up in the potting mix can be a 
problem using this system and you should remember to water your 
pots from on top at least once a month to leach the salts away 
from the root system.
<p>As for your potting mix, variety is the name of the game.  There 
must be almost as many mixes as there are varieties of African 
Violets to grow.  The secret is what works well for you in your 
environment is the best one to use.  There are a number of 
recommended mixes that are available, but the basic rule for all 
of them is that the potting mix must be light and porous.  It 
should always be sterilized or at least pasteurized in order to 
minimize fungal and bacterial rot problems.  Do not forget that 
in the soilless potting mixes, that are sold or can be made up, 
fertilizer will be required more often for the plants to grow 
satisfactorily than in mixes containing soil.  If you buy a plant 
already potted, ask what kind of mixture they are planted in just 
for an indication of the fertilizer and water needs your plant is 
likely to require.
<p>Why not make one of your New Year resolutions to grow African 
Violets, or if you are already growing them, grow more of them?  
Get a broader selection of the enormous variety that are now 
available.  They are, without a doubt, a plant that will give you 
hours of fun and enjoyment throughout every season of the year. 
 
<br> 
