<head> 
<title>1992 All-America Selections Winners</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
1992 All-America Selections Winners</center> 
</h1> 
 
by Sara Williams, Extension Division
<p>Each year a number of new seed introductions, both flower and 
vegetable, are given awards by the All America Selections (AAS). 
The winners are usually designated with the AAS logo in seed 
catalogues. 
<P>This non-profit organization, supported by seedsmen, tests new 
varieties of flowers and vegetables and selects the best ones for 
introduction in the market. AAS maintains 32 flower trial gardens 
and 27 vegetable trial gardens in the United States, Canada, and 
Mexico. Many of these are open to the public. 
An association of the American seed trade, AAS was established in 
1933 to judge and promote new flower and vegetable seeds. 
Varieties are coded during judging so their name, origin, and 
company are anonymous, and judging criteria are standardized at 
all trial plots. 
<P>Because AAS tests new varieties for home garden performance 
throughout North America, award winners usually will be varieties 
of high quality and reliability. Some award winners have remained 
popular with home gardeners for many decades. ("Straight Eight" 
cucumber was introduced in 1939 and is still a favourite.) 
There is, however, a problem with regional variation. Some AAS 
winners might not be suited to a particular region, where local 
varieties, bred and produced in the area, might do better. 
Likewise, local favourites might not be win AAS awards because 
they do not perform consistently across the entire continent. 
The 1992 AAS winners include four annuals, one tender bulb, an 
herb, and a mini-veggie.
<p>Salvia "Lady in Red" is drought and heat tolerant, easily grown 
from seed, and grows up to three feet in height. The seed, which 
should be sown 6 to 8 weeks prior to planting out., needs light 
to germinate and a soil temperature of 21 degrees Celsius. Cover 
the container with clear plastic to maintain moisture. 
Germination should occur in 12 to 15 days. Plant in full sun. 
This annual is attractive to hummingbirds.
<p>Dianthus "Ideal Violet" is a continuous bloomer that tolerates 
different weather conditions. Grape-purple in colour, it would go 
well with pure whites. Plant in full sun in well-drained soil. 
They are drought-tolerant once established. They may be grown 
from seed 6 to 8 weeks prior to setting out and seeds will 
germinate at 21 degrees Celsius soil temperature in 7 to 14 days.
<p>Vinca "Pretty in White" is a strong plant with continuous bloom. 
Plant in a warm location in full sun under well-drained 
conditions. Seed must be germinated in total darkness. Plant out 
only after the soil has warmed up.
<p>Verbena "Peaches and Cream" provides a delicate blend of apricot 
and salmon colours, heat tolerance, and freedom of bloom. 
Germinate seed in total darkness. for 10 to 20 days. Plant 
outdoors in full sun on well-drained soil. When Water the soil 
rather than the foliage.
<p>Canna "Tropical Rose" is the first canna grown from seed that has 
typical canna flowers 3 to 4 inches across. The plants are 2 1/2 
feet high with soft rose flowers. Sow seeds indoors at 24 degrees 
Celsius soil temperature 4 to 8 weeks prior to setting out. Plant 
in full sun in warm to hot conditions. Remember, this is a 
heat-loving tropical bulb! 
<p>Dill "Fernleaf" is a non-weedy dill well adapted to either urban 
container gardening or herb gardens. Only 24 inches high, it does 
not need staking. It has a compact habit with good dill flavour 
and lots of finely cut foliage.that has ornamental value as well. 
Sow seed directly outdoors once the soil temperature has warmed. 
Cover very lightly as it needs light to germinate. Germination 
will take about 3 weeks. Plant in a sunny location in 
well-drained soil.
<p>Carrot "Thumbelina" shows consistency of production, with few 
misshapen roots and a crisp, crunchy, sweet carrot flavour. Sow 
seed normally. Thumbelina is a mini-carrot with short, round 
roots, usually not much longer than 3 or 4 inches.
<p>Williams is a specialist in horticulture with the Extension 
Division.  This column is provided as a service by the Extension 
Division and the Department of Horticulture Science, University 
of Saskatchewan. 
 
<br> 
