<head> 
<title>All American Selections</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
All American Selections</center> 
</h1> 
 
Sara Williams
<p>All America Selections (AAS) is a non-profit organization, 
supported by the seed industry, which tests new varieties of 
flowers and vegetables and selects the best ones for introduction 
into the home garden market.  AAS maintains approximately 30 
flower and vegetable trial test gardens from Mexico through the 
United States and into Canada.  Many of these are open to the 
public.
<p>Each year a number of new seed introductions, both flower and 
vegetable, are given awards.  These are usually designated with 
the AAS logo in seed catalogues.
<p>As an association of the American seed trade, AAS was established 
in 1933 to judge and promote new flower and vegetable seeds.  
Varieties are coded during judging so their name, origin, and 
company are unknown, and judging criteria are standardized at all 
trial plots.
<p>Because AAS tests new varieties for home garden performance 
throughout North America, award winners are usually varieties of 
high quality and reliability.  Some award winners have remained 
popular with home gardeners for many decades ('Straight Eight' 
cucumber was introduced in 1939 and is still a favourite).
<p>There is a problem with regional variation.  For instance, some 
varieties which are AAS winners might not be suited for the 
Prairies.  Varieties developed and tested locally might be 
better.  Likewise, local favorites might not be winners of the 
AAS awards simply because they do not perform consistently across 
the entire continent.
<p>Vegetables are scored on a one to 10 scale and are evaluated for 
flavour, yield, appearance, texture, disease resistance, 
production and space efficiency, nutrition, and novelty value 
(such as peas with tendrils rather than leaves or purple 
cauliflower).
<p>New varieties are usually judged against existing standard 
varieties.  A new cherry tomato might be judged against 'Sweet 
100' for flavour and 'Tiny Tim' for yield.  Neither of these are 
AAS winners themselves, but are, nevertheless, considered 
standards in their class.
<p>Some Winners
<p>Vegetables - AAS vegetables winners for this year include a pole 
bean, a spaghetti squash, and a watermelon.
<p>The pole bean is called 'Kentucky Blue' and has the flavour of 
'Kentucky Wonder' combined with the round, smooth pods of 'Blue 
Lake'.  The beans themselves are 15-18 in. (6 7 in.) long and 
will mature in approximately 58 days.  'Kentucky Blue' was 
developed by the same plant breeder who developed the 'Sugar 
Snap' pea in 1979.
<p>'Tivoli' is a bush type spaghetti squash (bush meaning it takes 
up less space) which produces 2-3 creamy-yellow fruits per plant, 
of 1.3-2.2 kg (3 5 lb) each.  Because it matures in 100 days, it 
might require a longer growing season to develop ripe fruit than 
we get on thePrairies.  Our growing season averages 100 days so 
it might be advisable to start the seeds in biodegradable peat 
pots indoors in advance of the season.
<p>'Golden Crown' is a watermelon with a rind which turns gold when 
it is ripe - at last a color-coded indicator of ripeness to 
replace the time-honoured "give-it-a-thump" method to determine 
ripeness method!  The watermelons mature in 80 days and weigh 
2.7-3.6 kg (6 -8 lb) each.  The flesh itself is red, and the 
seeds are small.  This variety has been selected for both 
tolerance to powdery mildew and anthracnose.
<p>Flowers - Among the flower All-America Selections winners were 
'Red Plume' gaillardia, 'Orange Appeal' geranium, and 
'Padparadja' and 'Maxim Marina', two new pansies.
<p>'Red Plume' is a dwarf gaillardia only 31 cm (12 in.) in height.  
The plants are compact and bush and covered with 5 cm (2 in.) 
double, brick red flowers.
<p>'Orange Appeal' is the first true orange geranium available from 
seed.  It is free flowering, with tightly packed tangerine flower 
heads and zonal leaves on bushy plants.  It is useful as both a 
bedding or pot plant.
<p>'Padpardja' is a dwarf pansie with a unique pure dark orange 
face.  The flowers are 5 cm (2 in.) in diameter.  Plants are 
tolerant of both hot and cold weather.  'Padparadja' is named 
after a rare tangerine-coloured gem found in India.
<p>'Maxim Marina' is a medium sized mutiflora pansy, ideal for pots 
or beds.  It has a sky blue-dark purple face haloed in white with 
a yellow eye.
<p>Williams is a specialist in horticulture with the Extension 
Division.  This column is provided as a service by the Extension 
Division and the Department of Horticulture Science, University 
of Saskatchewan. 
 
<br> 
