<head> 
<title>Are you willing to abandon some control?</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
Are you willing to abandon some control?</center> 
</h1> 
 
Try Annuals That Self-Seed With Abadon
<p>Sara Williams
<p>Are you tired of growing bedding plants in regimental lines?  Are 
you longing for a more natural-looking border?  Then try annuals 
which can be seeded directly and then perpetuate themselves from 
year to year through self-seeding.
<p>Farm gardens have been graced with such informality for years, 
while their urban counterparts have been bound by annual beds of 
rigid geometry (ageratum, petunia, dusty miller; ageratum 
petunia, dusty miller; ad infinitum).  
<p>Getting Started
<p>So how does one begin?  Start with a well-tilled, weed-free bed 
in full sun.  The first spring plant your seeds directly - but 
not in lines!  Try informal groupings instead.  Or scatter the 
seeds somewhat randomly, following the directions for depth, etc. 
for each type.
<p>In traditional gardens the flowers grow in straight lines, and so 
it is easy to identify the weeds.  With informal plantings, you 
will have to learn what flower seedlings, as well as weed 
seedlings, look like.  Water and weed as you normally would  By 
the second season, identification will come easily.
<p>Annuals for Your Informal Planting
<p>These annuals can be directly seeded and will then reseed 
themselves.
<p>Hollyhock (Alcea rosea) - These are tall plants (up to 2.4 m/8 
ft) in white, yellow, pink and red.  They will do best as a 
grouping toward the back of the border.  Flowers will range from 
single to double.  They are 'heavy feeders' which will do best in 
a rich organic soil with adequate moisture.
<p>Pot Marigold (Calendua offieinalis) - Well known in farm gardens, 
these plants have large, mum-like flowers in shades of yellow, 
orange and apricot which are excellent as cut flowers.
<p>Bachelor's button or cornflower (Centaurea cyanus) - This is an 
old-fashioned, European flower, mostly in blue, but also 
available in red, pink and white.  Its height is about .6 m (2 
ft).  Prior to directly sowing, pre-chill  the seed in the 
refrigerator for a few days.  Cornflowers are excellent as cut 
flowers and tolerate poor soil.
<p>Calliopsis (Coreopsis tinctoria) - Calliopsis is a daisy-like 
flower in shades of yellow, orange and red with a height of .3-.9 
m (1-3 ft).  It is free-blooming, useful as a cut flower and 
tolerant of drought and poor soil.
<p>California poppy (Eschscholzia californica) - Although the orange 
species is more familiar to gardeners, hybrids are now available 
in pink, red, white and yellow.  The plants are only 30 cm (12 
in.) high, but the satin-like blooms can measure as much as 7.7 
cm (3 in.) across.  They are tolerant of poor soil and drought.
<p>Annual Blanketflower (Gaillardia pulchella) - These daisies are 
native to much of North America, including the Canadian Prairies  
Colors include red, orange and yellow, in both single and double 
forms.  The centers are often dark.  Excellent as cut flowers and 
tolerant of poor soil, they are .9 m (3 ft) in height.  
<p>Scarlet Flax (Linum grandiflorum) - These bright red flowers are 
3.8 cm (1.5 in.) in diameter and easily naturalized.  Although 
each individual flower lasts only a day, they are produced 
abundantly.
<p>Shirley or corn poppy (Papave rhoeas) - Shirley poppies are 
available in white, pink, purple, red and salmon; they somewhat 
resemble the perennial Iceland poppy.  The flowers are single or 
semi-double, up to 7.6 cm (3 in.) in diameter and held on .6-.9 m 
(2-3 ft) stems.  If used as a cutflower, burn the stems after 
picking.
<p>Williams is a specialist in horticulture with the Extension 
Division.  This column is provided as a service by the Extension 
Division and the Department of Horticulture Science, University 
of Saskatchewan. 
 
<br> 
