<head> 
<title>Bedding Plant Care</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
Bedding Plant Care</center> 
</h1> 
 
Tom Ward
<p>Bedding plants will give you a jump on the season and help you to 
produce the best vegetable or flower crop of the neighborhood.
<p><B>How Big is the Jump?</B>
<p>Generally you can expect your plants to be about five days ahead 
of plants grown from seed planted directly in the soil.  Plants 
with fine, small seeds such as wax begonia are much more likely 
to become established if they are grown as bedding plants rather 
than seeded directly into the soil.
<p><B>Use the best bedding plants</B>
<p>Use only the best of your bedding plants to transplant (plant 
out) outdoors.  These are are young, robust and rapidly growing 
plants.  Bedding plants that were started too early will will not 
grow well in the soil when planted out.  Tomatoes should not be 
started until April 15 or later.  Plants that have not been grown 
in a well-lighted greenhouse will be weak, tall, pale and thin 
stemmed.  Do not choose these types for planting out.  
<p>If you grow your own bedding plants you must start them at the 
correct time of the year (some as early as February 1 and some as 
late as April 20).  Consult a gardening book for each plant's 
optimum starting time.  They must have full, direct natural 
light.  Once they have been germinated they are best grown at 
temperatures between 18C and 23C ( 65F and 75F), which is cooler 
than many house temperatures.  High temperatures give you weak 
soft growth.
<p>If you buy your bedding plants it is advisable to buy them 
directly from the green house, choose the best, and harden them 
down before planting them in the field or bed.
<p><B>What is hardening off or hardening down?</B>
<p>This is any procedure that slows the growth of the plant down 
slightly and makes them better prepared for outdoor life.  This 
can be achieved by giving them cooler conditions, a bit less 
water, (do not let dry out), and some exposure to wind and dry 
outdoor air.  Do not overdo it.  Too much of any of these 
conditions will stunt or check your plants and they will perform 
poorly.  The ideal hardening off procedure is one of slowly 
making the plants tough but still growing well.
<p><B>Mishandled Plants</B>
<p>These are plants that are too old, grown with little light, not 
given enough fertilizer, hardened down too much, left in the dark 
too long, under or over watered, beat up in transit and a variety 
of other possible injuries.  Avoid buying these plants as they 
may actually take longer to produce than plants that were started 
from directly sown seed.
<p>So take care of those bedding plants, keep them growing with 
plenty of water, light and fertilizer.  Keep them from too much 
heat and cold .  When the time comes to plant them out say about 
mid to late May give them about 4 to 6 days of hardening off 
before you plant them out, to ensure their adjustment to the 
outside world.
<p>Good luck with the earliest and best garden.
<p>Ward was a staff member with the Department of Horticulture 
Science.  This column is provided as a service by the Extension 
Division and the Department of Horticulture Science, University 
of Saskatchewan. 
 
<br> 
