<html> 
<head> 
<title>Get a Jump on Spring with Bedding Plants</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
Get a Jump on Spring with Bedding Plants</center> 
</h1> 
 
Tom Ward
<p>Gardeners sometimes follow prairie lore to guide them in their 
horticultural endeavours.  Some folks think you should plant your 
crops three days before a full moon or wait until it passes.  
Others believe that above-ground crops like tomatoes should be 
planted when the moon is becoming fuller; but root crops, the old 
adage goes, should be planted when the moon is disappearing.  
Garden lore is rich and interesting but successful gardeners 
relying more on tried-and-tested practices.
<p>Consider bedding plants, for example.  If you want a really 
reliable practice that will improve your chances of success, I 
recommend you try using bedding plants.  Bedding plants give you 
a head start on our short growing season by a good five to ten 
days.  Plants can be started at home under lights or in a small 
greenhouse; or they can be purchased from a local greenhouse 
producer.
<p><B>Extending the Season</B> 
<P>In Saskatchewan our average growing season consists of about 90 
frost-free days, but this can vary drastically from year to year.  
There have been growing seasons of 110 frost-free days and other 
years when gardening was virtually impossible because of 
prolonged frosts.  
<p>Even if you do use bedding plants, it is important to choose 
varieties that will mature before our short growing season ends.  
Seed catalogues obligingly indicate the days-to-maturity for each 
variety they offer.  But remember that days-to-maturity is a 
measure of the fastest time you can expect the variety to mature.  
For example, say that a variety of corn is given as maturing in 
65 days.  If there is cool or cloudy weather during the growing 
season, it may take that variety 75 to 80 days to mature.  By 
starting your vegetables as bedding plants, you improve your 
chances of success under adverse conditions.
<p><B>Some Tips for Success with Bedding Plants</B> 
<P>1.  Bedding plants require direct sunlight or very good 
artificial light to do well.  With poor light, tall, weak and 
pale plants will result.
<p>2.  Because bedding plants grow quickly, the soil in the small  
pots soon loses its nutrients.  To provide strong, continuous 
growth, fertilize the bedding plants weekly.  A soluble 
fertilizer such as 20-20-20 is recommended.  Without fertilizer, 
bedding plants will turn pale green or purple and often become 
stunted.
<p>3  "Harden-off" the bedding plants by gradually reducing 
fertilizer and water before you plant them outside.  You can also 
gradually expose the bedding plants to bright sun, wind and cold 
nights before planting outside.  These practices will help to 
acclimatize the plants so that they will not be shocked when 
exposed to outside conditions.  Give the plants enough water so 
that they do not wilt severely before planting outside.  
<p>4.  Bedding plants that are started too early will become 
unthrifty, tall weak or spindly and do poorly when planted 
outside.  Starting times of the most commonly grown flowers and 
vegetables are given in the factsheet, Starting Annual Plants 
Indoors (Publication #153.)
<p>Note:  Most bedding plants are not started until late March or 
early April, so there's still time to get at it.  Happy planting! 
 
<br> 
