<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Biggest is not best with bedding

plants</TITLE>

</HEAD><BODY background="im/backgrnd.gif">

<h1><center><img alt="" src="im/line.gif">

Biggest is not best with bedding plants too</center></h1>

by Brian Baldwin <P>

<P>

With our short gardening season, we need as much of a jump on the

season as possible. Bedding plants offer the head start necessary

to ensure an early crop, or a full season of blooms. <P>

<P>

Although the whole idea with bedding plants is to get a head

start on the season, biggest is not always best. A stocky little

plant will usually establish itself more quickly than a larger,

lankier plant. Similarly, weak or damaged plants which have been

standing for a period of time in a dimly lit store may not be a

bargain even if they are "reduced to clear." Remember that any

plant that has to spend a couple of weeks recuperating from a

near-death-experience has lost whatever head start it may once

have had. <P>

<P>

The ideal transplant will be short, stocky, with thick stems and

sturdy leaves. They should be bright green. Plants with a purple

tinge on the leaves are showing a phosphorous deficiency. This is

easily corrected with an application of 20-20-20 but this stress

will also have slowed their growth. In most cases, bedding plants

should not be in flower when they are planted, but petunias,

geraniums, and the smaller types of marigolds don't seem to

suffer from transplanting after they have begun to bloom.<P>

<P>

<B>Hardening Off</B><P>

<P>

There are two schools of thought on the issue of hardening off.

Traditionalists recommend that plants be slowly introduced to the

outside world by placing them in a sheltered and somewhat shaded

location for a few hours each day over the course of a 7-10 days.

Each day they stay out longer, until they are outside around the

clock. This slows their growth and toughen them up. <P>

<P>

Others choose to avoid the whole process. Sturdy little plants

placed directly into the garden with some form of localized

shelter will not lose that week of growth that the hardening

process cost. Juice cans, milk cartons, or commercially available

hot caps will offer most of the necessary protection a strong

little plant will need for its first week outside. <P>

<P>

Whether you harden them or not, transplanting is best done in the

cool of the evening. If you simply must transplant in the

daytime, be sure to keep the plants very well watered and give

them shade from the full sun for the first few days. A mild

solution of 20-20-20 immediately after transplanting will help

them re-establish quickly.<P>

<P>

<B>Garden Line Re-born!</B><P>

<P>

Sometimes the old ways are the best ways. The Horticulture

Information Service (or Garden Line) at the University of

Saskatchewan will once again be offered as a free service

starting May 13. Funding from Saskatchewan Agriculture and Food

is making it possible for a single telephone line to be operated

by a knowledgeable horticulture student Monday, Wednesday and

Friday from 10:00 a.m. to 12:30 p.m. and 1:00 to 4:00 p.m.

There's only one line, however, so set your speed dial, and keep

trying! <P>

<P>

Baldwin is a horticulturist at the University of Saskatchewan.

This column is offered as a service of the Division of Extension

and the Department of Horticulture at the U of S.<P>

&copy; Brian Baldwin 1996<br>

