<head> 
<title>The Border in Early Spring:  Part 1</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
The Border in Early Spring:  Part 1</center> 
</h1> 
 
Sara Williams
<p>One of the characteristics of a perennial border which is most 
appealing is the variety of bloom provided as the season 
progresses. While few perennials will bloom for more than 4 or 5 
weeks, the border as a whole begins early in May and continues 
until the hard frosts of October. 
<p>On a personal level, I often find it difficult to remember just 
what blooms when. Perhaps this is the year for documentation! As 
of May 15, the following were in bloom in Saskatoon!
<p><B>Bulbs</B>
<p>Among the earliest bulbs are the Siberian squills (Scilla 
siberica). Only  15 cm (6 in.) in height, they make attractive 
ribbon plantings or small colonies, are excellent in the rock 
garden, and soon multiply.  Like most bulbs, they do best in full 
sun with good drainage.
<p>There is a pure white form called Scilla siberica alba, a deep 
blue called "Spring Beauty" and a brighter blue called Scilla 
sibirica taurica.
<p>Species tulips are early. Among the hardiest for Prairie 
conditions are Tulipa tarta and Tulipa urumiensis. Tulipa tarda 
is a native of eastern Turkestan. Only 8-11 cm (3 or 4 in.) high, 
the plant has flowers that are bright yellow with white tips. 
Tulipa urumiensis is similar but completely yellow.
<p>The single early tulips follow soon after the species and range 
in height from 25 to 40 cm. (10-15 in.).
<p>Next are the Frittilaria. The Siberian fritillaria (Fritillaria 
pallidiflora) is the most widely grown on the Prairies. It is 
perfectly hardy and soon multiples. It produces a multitude of 
soft yellow, nodding flowers on stems 25-50 cm (10 to 20 in.) in 
height. It does best in a rich, peaty, but well-drained soil in 
partial shade.
<p>Two newcomers to my garden which show great promise but will need 
further testing over successive winters are Fritillarisa persica 
and Fritillaria reuteri. Fritillaria persica is native to Turkey 
and Iran, 60 cm (2 ft.) in height with broad blue green leaves 
and a stalk of chocolate brown (violet blue??) flowers. 
Fritillaria reuteri is just a miniature  20 cm (8 in.) in height 
with each stem carrying 2-4 bell-shaped flowers of purple  tipped 
with yellow. Growing conditions are similar to those of the 
Siberian fritillaria.
<p><B>Perennials</B>
<p>Draba aizoon is among the earliest perennials to bloom. It is a 
tufted alpine plant only 5 cm (2 in.) in hight with tiny yellow 
flowers. It does best in full sun with good drainage.
<p>While the native marsh marigold (Caltha palustris) does poorly 
under garden conditions unless provided with a bog, the double 
form, "Flore Pleno", is more adapted to life in a border. The 
double yellow flowers are produced on 15 cm (6 in.) stems. It 
does best in a rich, peaty, moist soil in full sun or partial 
shade,
<p>Callianthhmum angustifolium is a member of the buttercup family 
and native to Siberia. It has attractive blue-grey, scalloped 
leaves and white flowers on 15 cm (6 in.) stems. It does best in 
well-drained but evenly moist loamy soil in full sun or partial 
shade.
<p>Another member of the buttercup family is the spring adonis 
(Adonis vernalis). The foliage is delicate and fern-like with 
bright yellow flowers on 30 cm (12 in.) stems. It seems to do a 
real Houdini ace; one day there's no sign of it; the next it"s in 
full bloom.
<p>The dusty miller primrose (Primula auricula) is native to the 
European Alps and reliably hardy throughout the Prairies. It has 
mealy green leaves from which the common name dusty miller is 
derived. It is said it resembles flour sprinkled on the apron of 
a miller. The flowers have yellow centres with either yellow, 
red, lavender, or purple petals and are 30-38 cm (12-15 in.) 
high. The dusty miller does best in partial or full shade with an 
evenly moist organic soil.

<p>Williams is a specialist in horticulture with the Extension 
Division.  This column is provided as a service by the Extension 
Division and the Department of Horticulture Science, University 
of Saskatchewan. 
 
<br> 
