<html> 
<head> 
<title>Cactus:  Dryland Perennials</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
Cactus:  Dryland Perennials</center> 
</h1> 
 
by Grant Wood
<p>Talking about dryland plants may seem odd during the wettest year 
on record.  However, if you have a hot, dry patch on your 
property, you might consider growing a cactus.
<p>Cacti prefer a fine textured (clay loam) soil, but will tolerate 
the coarse textured (sandy) soils.  The root system of a cactus 
is extensive and very shallow, which allows it to use very tiny 
amounts of moisture in the surface soil.  Reducing the leaf area 
into a pad or ball is another way cacti have evolved to tolerate 
severe drought conditions.
<p>Two cacti commonly encountered in Saskatchewan are the prickly 
pear cactus and pincushion cactus.  Both can be found in areas of 
the province where the growing environment is suitable.  By using 
native Saskatchewan plants in your landscape, you get hardy 
vegetation that is well suited to this area.  With a little 
practice, both types of native cacti can be established in a 
yard.
<p>Prickly pear cactus (opuntia polyacantha) is the most common and 
most showy of the two.  The perennial forms a mat that can spread 
over an area up to 60 cm.  Plants seldom grow higher than 20 cm, 
with individual pads being up to 10 cm long.  Brilliant yellow or 
orange flowers develop on the pads, and open in late June to 
early July.  Numerous flowers form on each plant and last about 
two to three weeks.  When in full flower, few perennials can 
compete with Prickly Pear for ornamental value.  After the 
flowers fade, dry fruits, containing the seeds, are formed.
<p>Pincushion or ball cactus (mamillaria vivipara) is not as common 
or ornamental as the prickly pear, but can still provide a highly 
desirable addition to a landscape.  Also a perennial, this cactus 
forms round balls up to 5 cm in diameter.  The spines stick out 
of the ball, so it looks like a pin cushion.  Numerous balls form 
in a mat, which can spread up to 30 cm across.  The purple-pink 
flowers are small but very showy.  Flowers appear in late June or 
early July and last about a week.  After flowering, a fleshy 
fruit, containing the seeds, is formed.
<p>Both types of cactus can be propagated by seed.  Collect seed 
pods when ripe--late August for prickly pear and September for 
pincushion.  Plant seeds immediately after harvesting.  The 
germination percentage is not high, but some new plants should 
emerge the following spring.  Loam soils are best for germinating 
cactus seeds.  A cactus does not transplant very well, so place 
the seed in the bed where you want the cactus to grow.
<p>You may also propagate either of these cacti by division.  Find a 
large patch, and gently dig up some of the pads or balls from the 
outer edge.  Be careful not to damage the rest of the patch.  Do 
not remove the entire patch or denude an area completely.  Remove 
a large portion of soil with the cactus.  Plant these divisions 
in an environment similar to the one where you found them.  
Division is best if done early in the spring.
<p>Grant Wood was an instructor with the Department of Horticulture 
Science.  This column is offered as an extension service by the 
Extension Division and the Department of Horticulture Science, 
University of Saskatchewan. 
 
<br> 
