<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Christmas baking may furnish date palm</TITLE>

</HEAD><BODY background="im/backgrnd.gif">

<center><img alt="" src="im/line.gif">

<h1>Christmas baking may furnish date palm</center></h1>

Brian Baldwin<P>

<P>

If any of your favourite Christmas recipes call for dates,

there's a chance the upcoming frenzy of Christmas baking will

provide you with a few date seeds. Those blocks of pitted baking

dates we buy often contain a seed or two, and as long as these

seeds have not been cooked or chopped before you find them, they

can grow into an attractive date palm. <P>

<P>

Date palms are placed within the genus <I>Phoenix,</I> although

their association with this ancient mythical bird of Egypt is

unclear. There are from 12 to 18 species within the genus,

depending on the source you believe, with three of these

frequently being seen as house plants. <P>

<P>

<I>Phoenix dactylifera</I> is the species which supplies dates to

the world's bakers. This is a large sturdy-looking palm that is

grown in most areas of the world which enjoy a Mediterranean type

climate. For example, in California date palms are used as

boulevard trees where they reach heights of 30 meters or more. In

your house, a date palm may eventually reach the ceiling, but

this will require many years of growth under nearly ideal

conditions.<P>

<P>

The canary date palm <I>(P. canariensis)</I> originated in the

Canary Islands, but is now grown as a landscape tree in most

areas having a suitable climate. It does not supply commercial

dates, but is widely available as an indoor palm. Indoors it

forms a dense attractive palm that reaches a total height of

about 2 meters.

<P>

The miniature date palm <I>(P. roebelenii),</I> seldom exceeds 2

meters outdoors in the tropics, and 1 meter in the house. <P>

<P>

<B>Growing your date seeds</B><P>

<P>

The seeds of some palms may take up to two years to germinate.

Fortunately, date seeds are usually not quite this slow. You

should, however, be prepared to wait a minimum of three months

before expecting any sign of life. Books recommend that each seed

be placed into a small pot where it can be kept moist and warm

until germination. Small pots dry out quite quickly, so if your

habits in watering house plants are anywhere near as negligent as

mine, I would suggest an alternative method. Simply push any date

seeds you happen to find a few centimetres into the growing

medium of a larger potted plant and forget about them. This won't

leaves you tending vacant little pots of soil for months on end,

hoping to someday see a tiny sign of life. Next summer you may be

pleasantly surprised to find a palm seed germinating in a pot

where you had forgotten putting it. By forgetting about the seeds

after planting, you are also spared any disappointment if the

seeds were inviable from the start. <P>

<p>

A young date palm forms far from a spectacular specimen. For most

of the first year it will look like nothing more than a single

stiff grass-like leaf. Eventually a second leaf will emerge,

slightly larger than the first, with each successive leaf

exceeding the previous ones in size. It may be two years or more

before the plant begins to produce leaves with the divisions we

expect to see on palm leaves. (Palm trees are known as "palms"

because the leaves of many are highly divided, with individual

leaflets radiating outward from a central point, like the fingers

around the palm of a human hand.)<P>

<P>

When you eventually decide to move the small palm to its own pot,

you should choose a pot that is narrow and deep. These plants

form strong downward roots that will actually begin to lift the

plant out of the soil if it is growing in too shallow a pot. The

growing medium should consist of one part sterilized soil, one

part peat moss and one part coarse sand.<P>

<P>

As some of our toughest indoor plants, palms are often grown in

dingy, dry locations where few other plants will survive. Your

date palm will survive under these conditions, but will only

really form a fine specimen if given bright sunlight and high

humidity. During winter, the plant should be placed in the

brightest but coolest location available. A heated but cool front

porch would be an ideal spot if you could be sure the temperature

would not drop below about 12&#176;C. Water can be reduced in

winter. During periods of active growth the plant should be given

the brightest indoor light possible, kept moist and fertilized

with 20--20--20 every few weeks. <P>

<P>

Date palms will indicate the need for a larger pot by forming a

net of fine roots along the surface of the growing medium. At

this time the plant should be moved to a pot that is a couple of

centimetres larger. When the plant has reached the largest pot

size you are willing to give it, semi-annual top dressing of the

growing medium with new soil will be all that is needed. The

larger the pot you provide it, the larger the plant will

eventually become. <P>

<P>

With little care, the baking scraps of this Christmas can provide

you with a palm tree that should survive well into the next

century. <P>

<P>

&copy; 1996 Brian Baldwin<br>

