<html> 
<head> 
<title>RENAISSANCE FOR HERBS</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
RENAISSANCE FOR HERBS</center> 
</h1> 
 
by Grant Wood
<p>In recent years, many gardeners have expressed a renewed interest 
in herb growing.  The trend now is to "dine" with basil, savory, 
and marjoram, as opposed to merely "eating" with sugar and salt.  
As we become a more multi-cultural society, we are exposed to new  
foods and dishes that use new and exciting herbs.
<p>The health food movement has also increased interest in herbs for 
their medicinal as well as culinary value.  Heath foods do not 
have to taste bland and boring; they flavour can be greatly 
enhanced with herbs.  
<p>Two other trends that have played a part in promoting herbs are 
the public's growing interest in gardening and in  horticultural 
crafts.  Aromatic herbs in the garden make weeding less of a task 
and provide alternatives to growing the traditional flowers and 
vegetables.  At craft shows  you will find  herb-scented candles, 
ink and writing paper, pot-pourri, herbal dyes, herbal bath and 
beauty products (bath oils, skin cleansers, scalp conditioners), 
perfumes, and air freshners - all made from locally grown herbs.
<p>Have I whet your own appetite for herbs?  In this and the 
following article your will learn some basic facts about growing 
them.
<p>Site Selection: Most herbs do not do well on compact clay soils, 
found in many Saskatchewan gardens.  Prepare the soil by digging 
in organic matter such as well-rotted manure, peat moss, or 
compost in the autumn. Sandy soils are also improved by the 
addition of organic matter.
<p>Herbs reqire a fertile soil.   Generally a garden that grows good 
vegetables, will grow good herbs.  An overly fertile soil for 
herbs, however, should be avoided.  Most herbs are at optimum 
quality just before flowering, but an overly fertile soil will 
delay flowering.  With our short growing season, delayed 
flowering will reduce the likelihood of obtaining the highest 
quality herbs. 
<p>Sun:  Sunlight is important for herbs.  A minimum of eight hours 
a day of uninterrupted sunlight is required.  The more light the 
herbs are exposed to, the better the quality and quantity 
harvested.  Some herbs tolerate partial shade, but these are few 
in numbers.
<p>Watering:  Many herbs do not tolerate drought and must be given 
additional water during the growing season.  As with other garden 
plants, herbs are best watered thoroughly but infrequently.  A 
daily five-minute sprinkling is ineffective and potentially 
harmful to plants.  Thorough watering once a week is far superior 
for the plants, and a more efficient use of water.  Herbs should 
not be allowed to dry excessively in the garden; yield will 
decrease substantially under very dry conditions.
<p>Pests:  Few herbs are troubled by insects and diseases.  Aphids 
feed on dill and lovage, and flea beetles can damage nasturtiums.  
The painted lady butterfly larvae finds borage quite tasty.  
Organic and synthetic insecticides are recommended for the 
control of these pests.  Diseases are seldom a problem.
<p>Wood was an instructor with the Department of Horticulture 
Science.  This column is provided as a service by the Extension 
Division and the Department of Horticulture Science, University 
of Saskatchewan. 
 
<br> 
