<html> 
<head> 
<title>JOHNNY-COME-LATELIES:  LILIES AND DAYLILIES FOR LATE SUMMER</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
JOHNNY-COME-LATELIES:  LILIES AND DAYLILIES FOR LATE SUMMER</center> 
</h1> 
 
Sara Williams
<p>The writer is an Extension Specialist in Horticulture Science 
with the Division of Extension at the University of Saskatchewan.  
This column is provided as an extension service by the Division 
of Extension and Community Relations and the Department of 
Horticulture Science, University of Saskatchewan.
<p>     Perennial borders can provide a succession of colours, 
shapes and textures through the growing season.  Most borders 
reach their peak in June and July, after which they often lapse 
into the late summer doldrums.  However, with careful planning 
they can be just as colourful in August and September.  Lilies 
and daylilies will help to eliminate the blank spaces of late 
summer in your border.
<p><B>LILIES:</B>
<p>     Lily bulbs are best lifted, divided, and replanted in late 
fall, after their foliage has matured and while temperature and 
moisture are still favorable for root growth to continue in a new 
location.  Good drainage is the single most important factor in 
growing lilies successfully.  Full sun is also essential.  Dig 
the soil 20-25 cm (8-l0 in.) deep and incorporate peat moss into 
either heavy clay or sandy soil.  Add bonemeal or 11-48-0 
granular fertilizer (at the rate of 1/4 pound per 50 square 
feet).  Avoid fertilizers which are high in nitrogen; they will 
cause lush leafy growth which is more susceptible to botrytis, a 
fungal disease.  Also avoid the use of fresh manure and never put 
manure or fertilizer in direct contact with the bulbs themselves.  
Plant lily bulbs  30-46 cm (12-18 in.) apart with 10-13 cm (4-5 
in.) of soil over the bulbs so that the stem roots have a chance 
to form between the top of the bulb and the surface of the soil.  
With taller lilies or in windier locations, increase the planting 
depth to 15-20 cm (6-8 in.).
<p>     Firm and then water well immediately after the bulbs have 
been planted.  Mulches are helpful immediately after planting; 
they act as insulation and moderate soil temperature extremes.
<p>     The following lilies are classified as "late season" or 
"season closers".  They will begin blooming in late July and 
continue into August.
<p>'Chippewa Star' - 1.2 m (4 ft), late July; out- and down-facing, 
dark red flowers touched with orange in the dark-spotted center.
<p>'Cidlina' - .6 m (2 ft), late July; down-facing, strongly 
reflexed, small flowers; orange with many small dark spots.
<p>'Citronella' - 1-1.2 m (3-4 ft), late July; down-facing, 
dark-spotted, reflexed yellow Turkscap flowers.
<p>'Dawn Star' - .6 m (2 ft), late July; out-facing flowers open 
flat; soft cream deepens into yellow centre with only a few small 
brown spots.
<p>'Ducat' - late July; down-facing, golden-yellow Turkscap flowers 
with fine, dark spotting; brushed with brown on the reverse.
<p>'Golden Age' - 1 m (3 ft), early to mid-August; rich golden 
yellow with dark bronzy stems; up-facing candelabra type flower 
with 12-15 blooms per stem.
<p>'Nutmegger' - 1.2 m (4 ft), late July; out- and down-facing, 
bright yellow flowers with prominent dark brown spots; good for 
massing at the back of the border.
<p>'Pink Champagne' - 1.2 m (4 ft), late July; out-facing, yellow 
flowers with an overlay of pink, which fades, leaving a clear 
champagne shade.
<p>'Skydancer' - 1.8 m (6 ft), down-facing, spotted yellow; good 
background for the perennial border.
<p>'Yellow Tiger' - 1 m (3 ft), yellow form of Lilium tigrinum; good 
garden lily; down-facing, hardy species lily.
<p>'Red Velvet' - .6 m (2 ft), late July; out-facing, dark red 
flowers are sparsely dark spotted.
<p>'Stoplight' - .6-1 m (2-3ft), late July; up-facing, dark 
orange-red flowers with black flecking, open flat.
<p>'Yellow blaze' - 1 m (3 ft), August; large, up-facing, bright 
yellow flowers with black spotting; blooms after most other 
lilies are finished.
<p>Lilium henryi - 1 m (3 ft), August; species lily with 
amber-orange flowers with spots on recurved petals.
<p>'Red Knight' - 1 m (3 ft), tall, deep red lily; down-facing; 
excellent for massing in the back of border.
<p>'Towering Turk' - 1 m (3 ft), pendant blooms open a delicate 
apricot that soon fades to creamy white.
<p>'Bronze Queen' - 1.5 m (5 ft), down-facing, bronzy-yellow lily 
which carries up to 30 or more blooms  on a stem and holds up 
well to wind.
<p>'Rosabelle' - .6-1 m (2-3 ft), up-facing lily of unusual deep old 
rose shade.
<p>'Sutter's Gold' - .6-1 m (2-3 ft), down-facing, rich yellow-gold; 
flowers open wide into a cup shape.
<p>Double-flowered tiger lily - orange flowers have up to 36 petals 
with a peculiar looking "cushion-like" bloom.
<p><B>DAYLILIES COLOR LATE-SUMMER BORDERS</B>
<p>Sara Williams
<p>The writer is an Extension Specialist in Horticulture Science 
with the Division of Extension at the University of Saskatchewan.  
This column is provided as an extension service by the Division 
of Extension and Community Relations and the Department of 
Horticulture Science, University of Saskatchewan.
<p>     Along with lilies, which I discussed last week, daylilies 
will provide a variety of colours for borders that can brighten 
your spirits through the late summer.
<p>     Daylilies (Hemerocallis) are not true lilies.  Each flower 
lasts for a single day, but an individual plant, once 
established, will continue to bloom for several weeks with 50 to 
100 buds.  Colours range from shades of yellow through to orange, 
pink, red, and mahogany.  Heights vary from dwarf varieties of 
.5-1m (18 in.-3ft).
<p>     Daylilies are one of the most adaptable and insect and 
pest-free perennials.  They will grow equally well in sun or 
shade and, although they do best with adequate moisture, they are 
quite drought tolerant. The grass-like foliage remains attractive 
throughout the growing season.
<p>     The roots are fleshy, and given adequate care, can be 
transplanted or planted at almost any time, although they are 
best transplanted in the spring.  Each clump will eventually have 
a spread of .8-.9m (2 1/2-3ft), so make allowance for future 
growth when spacing them.
<p>     The following varieties are classified as later blooming:
<p>'Amber Eyes' - 64 cm (25 in); burnt orange with a reddish halo 
and yellow throat; broad ruffled petals.
<p>'Bitsy Tetra' - 71 cm (28 in); small, bright yellow trumpets with 
very stiff substance over a long season.
<p>'Buddha' - 76 cm (30 in), darkest red above a tiny green throat.
<p>'Double Dixie' - 64 cm (25 in); many layers of petals; light 
orange over a reddish orange halo.
<p>'Egyptian Spice' - 76 cm (30 in); deep amber or coppery orange 
with lighter midribs.
<p>'Fiesta Skirt' - 64 cm (25 in); deep rosy red contrasts with 
frosted margins and yellow throat.
<p>'Graham Bell' - 61 cm (24 in); pink peach with a golden 
throat.'Ivory Sprite' Ñ 15 in); tiny, light ivory orange flowers.
<p>'Lemon Drops' - 64 cm (25 in); small pure yellow flowers, 3 in) 
\across with fine substance; colour lightens in ruffled margins.
<p>'Oriental Influence' - 64 cm (25 in); pale yellow, overlaid with 
reddish purple markings.
<p>'Paprika Velvet' - 64 cm (25 in); reddish orange with a darker 
halo over the golden throat.
<p>'Rosedale' - 64 cm (25 in); wide, overÑlapping petals with rosy 
ends fading to peach and then to a yellow throat.
<p>'Stella de Oro' - 38 cm (15 in); prolific miniature which blooms 
from June to hard frost; small golden yellow trumpets.
<p>'Stoplight' - 89 cm (35 in); velvety red spreading petals give 
this large flower a spidery shape.
<p>'Sweet Harmony' - 51 cm (20 in); small light peach or pinkish 
buff flowers with a distinct red halo over a yellow throat.
<p>'Tahitian Isle' - 64 cm (25 in); large, prominent flowers; wide, 
reddish orange petals and lighter orange sepals, blending to a 
yellow throat.
<p>'Wild Eye' - 51 cm (20 in); wide overlapping petals of pale peach 
with a reddish halo above a yellow throat. 
 
<br> 
<a href="index.html"><img align=left border=0 alt="" src="im/back.gif"> 
