<head> 
<title>Home Gardeners Beware of Lythrum</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
Home Gardeners Beware of Lythrum</center> 
</h1> 
 
Bruce Hobin
<p>I recently came across an article written in an Alberta 
Agriculture publication about lythrum.  The wild lythrum (lythrum 
salicaria) has become a severe problem in western North America.
<p>Alberta earlier this year declared it a noxious weed, and 
Manitoba has it on its noxious weed list.  Minnesota has banned 
all Lythrum.
<p>The problem with the wild lythrum is that it is such a prolific 
weed.  It can very easily invade waterways, drainage ditches, and 
wetlands.  The Canadian Wildlife Federation has labelled it the 
"beautiful killer" because it will completely eliminate all 
habitat and wildlife.  The plant, which is also known as purple 
loosestrife grows between 1- 1.8 m (3-6 ft) high and has long 
pink/purple spike flowers from June through September.
<p>So what does this mean for the lythrum (perennial) that you have 
in your garden.  What you are growing is likely the ornamental 
cultivar.  This cultivar generally does not produce viable seeds 
and if managed carefully, should not spread to wetlands.  The 
recommendation to home gardeners is that they buy a specific 
variety of ornamental lythrum, Morden Pink.
<p>Dr. Campbell Davidson from the Agriculture Canada Research 
Station at Morden, Manitoba recommends the following steps that 
nursery and garden centre operators can take to ensure that the 
lythrum is contained:
<p>1. Ensure that the plants are correctly identified and are 
   propagated from cuttings.  Use only Morden Pink.<BR>
2. Do not propagate any lythrum from seed. <BR>
3. Advise the public of the problem of Lythrum salicaria. <BR>
4. Avoid planting the garden types near water courses, ditches,  
   or other wetland areas. <BR>
5. Develop a list of alternate species for your location and your 
   clients needs. <BR>
6. Support local programs to help control Lythrum salicaria.<BR>
<p>Gardeners should also remember that this is not the first plant 
that has been lost or threatened to be deleted from nursery 
lists.  Other plant species such as barberry (Berberis), 
babysbreath (Gypsophila), and burning bush (Kodia) have 
experienced the same fate.
<p>Hobin is an extension specialist with the Extension Division  
This column is provided as a service by the Extension Division 
and the Department of Horticulture Science, University of 
Saskatchewan. 
 
<br> 
