<head> 
<title>Lynchis Who?  The Malese Cross and Its Relations</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
Lynchis Who?  The Malese Cross and Its Relations</center> 
</h1> 
 
Sara Williams
<p>Maltese cross (Lychnis chalchedonica) is an old-fashioned garden 
perennial with bright green opposite leaves and dense heads of 
scarlet flowers on 60-cm-1m (2-3 ft.) stems in July.  A white 
form is also available but is not as showy.  Each floret 
composing the flower head resembles a cross.
<p>The species name (chalchedonica)is from Chalcedon, the ancient 
name of an area near Istanbul, Turkey in which they are found.  
One legend says that these plants were brought back to Europe 
from Turkey by the Knights of Malta at the time of the Crusades.
<p>The Maltese cross grows equally well in sun or partial shade in 
moist but well-drained soil.  A good addition to the perennial 
border, it is also excellent as a cut flower.  The Maltese Cross 
is easily propagated by seed of division.  Do not cover the seeds 
as light is beneficial to germination. Plants grown from seed 
will bloom their second year.
<p>Other Family Members 
A first cousin of the Maltese cross is the rose campion (Lychnis 
coronarla).  Often biennial in habit, it has white, wooly leaves 
and sprays of contrasting bright red flowers.  The foliage alone 
is a worthwhile addition to the border.  It does well in full sun 
with good drainage.
<p>It is best grown where it can self-sow and naturalize so that the 
bed as a whole can perpetuate itself.  Plants should be cut back 
after flowering.
<p>Also related to the Maltese cross is the clammy campion (Lychis 
viscaria 'Splendens florepleno').  Closely resembling a 
carnation, the clammy campion  has double, rose-magenta flowers 
and grassy foliage.  It is 45 cm (18 in.) high and blooms in 
July.  It does well in full sun and well-drained soil.
<p>The name "clammy campion" arises from the sticky stems.  These 
plants were once hung from ceilings to trap insects during an era 
which predated yellow fly paper -  definitely an organic 
alternative!
<p>Another cousin of the Maltese Cross, the Haages campion (Lychnis 
haageana) produces large, orange-scarlet flowers on 30 cm (12 
in.) stalks in July.  Salmon and orange-red forms are also 
available.  The Haages campion requires even mosture.  
<p>Finally, there is The Arkwright campion (Lychnis arkwrightii),  a 
hybrid of the Maltese cross and Haages campion.  It has scarlet 
flowers the size of those produced by the Haages campion and 
grows to a height of 25 cm (10 in.).  It blooms in July and is 
characterized by bronze-purple leaves.  Unless given sheltered 
conditions, it is not long lived under prairie conditions. 
 
<br> 
<a href="index.html"><img align=left border=0 alt="" src="im/back.gif"> 
Return to plant index</a><br> 
<br><br><br>Accesses: 49.</Body> 
