Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html> 
<head> 
<title>The Brilliant Lychnis</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
The Brilliant Lychnis</center> 
</h1> 
 
Sara Williams 
Williams was a graduate student in horticulture.  This column is 
offered as a service of the Division of Extension and Community 
Relations and the Department of Horticulture Science, University 
of Saskatchewan..
<p>Many gardeners may not be familiar with the genus name, Lychnis.  
But most Saskatchewan gardeners have been growing this plant, 
commonly known as Maltese cross,  for years.  Pronounced 
"lik-nis" (from the Greek word "luchnos" for "lamp" which refers 
to the flame-colored flowers of some species), the genus name 
describes the brilliance of the flowers.  The individual florets 
have petals and are in the shape of a cross.  Most do well in 
full sun in well-drained soils and tend to be drought-tolerant.  
Most are easily grown from seed or division.
<p>The following have proven hardy in Saskatchewan gardens:
<p>Maltese cross (Lychnis chalcedonica) - An old-fashioned flower 
which has been in cultivation for over 300 years, Maltese cross 
is the most commonly grown of the Lychnis.  A native of Russia 
and Siberia, it had spread as far as the Mediterranean region by 
the Middle Ages, and is said to have been introduced to Europe 
during the time of the Crusades by the Knights of Malta.
<p>About .6-1 m (2-3 ft) high, Maltese cross grows equally well in 
sun or shade.  It prefers evenly moist soil.  The flowers are 
scarlet and are formed in dense terminal heads, consisting of 
many individual florets, each with 4 petals.  It blooms in July.  
The plants are erect, very attractive "en mass", and somewhat 
aggressive, although easily controlled.
<p>Orange lychnis (Lychnis x haageana) - Only 30-38 cm (12-15 in.) 
high, and also blooming in July, the orange lychnis has 
brilliant, single orange-scarlet flowers, each about 5 cm (2 in.) 
in diameter.  Lychnis arkwrightii is very similar to orange 
Lychnis but is characterized by purplish leaves and stems.  
Though well worth growing, both have a life-span of only 2-3 
years.  Like the Maltese cross, they do better with even 
moisture.
<p>German catchfly (Lychnis viscaria 'splendens-plena') - Blooming 
in June on 46 cm (18 in.) stems, the German catchfly is fragrant 
and has very attractive, deep-pink double flowers which resemble 
carnations.  The evergreen foliage is grasslike and formed in 
tufts.  Although native to Europe and northern Asia, it is of 
questionable hardiness in this area and will sometimes die over 
winter.  Thus, it is best planted in a sheltered location where 
it will receive maximum snow cover.  The common name refers to 
the sticky nature of the stem, which is said to be useful as a 
fly-catcher.  Propagation is by division.
<p>Rose Campion (Lychnis coronaria) - The rose campion is a rather 
short-lived perennial from southern Europe, but one which usually 
perseveres in the border through self-seeding.  (To encourage 
self-seeding, refrain from mulching around rose campions.)  It is 
characterized by soft, silvery-gray, velvet-like foliage and 
contrasting brilliant rose flowers on 46-62 cm (18-24 in.) stems 
in July and August. 
 
<br> 
<a href="index.html"><img align=left border=0 alt="" src="im/back.gif"> 
Return to plant index</a><br> 
<br><br><br>Accesses: 49.</Body> 
