<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Gardening On The Move</TITLE>

</HEAD><BODY background="im/backgrnd.gif">

<center><img alt="" src="im/line.gif">

<h1>Gardening On The Move</center></h1>

Maureen Troesch<P>

<P>

You've found the home of your dreams, your bags are packed, and

you're on the move. But what do you do with your treasured

collection of perennials - the pink peony you inherited from your

grandmother, or the perfect sky - blue delphiniums your best

friend gave you on your last birthday - some of them

irreplaceable? Your new yard is full of possibilities, but empty

of plants, and a visit to your local garden centre causes your to

seriously ponder the profitability of selling your firstborn.

However, you need not resign yourself to the inevitability of a

petunia dominated landscape. Even in midsummer, most perennials

are relatively portable, and with a little extra care and

encouragement will readily establish themselves in their new

environment.<P>

<P>

Unless specified to the contrary, all existing landscaping is

generally included in the purchase price of a home. Therefore,

before you take out your spade and start digging, make very

certain the landlord or purchaser of your old home is aware that

you will be taking all or some of your plants with you. Once the

legal niceties have been satisfied, the next step is preparing a

site in your new yard. <P>

<P>

If you are very lucky, most of this work will have been done for

you. Existing flower beds or a vegetable garden can be used as a

temporary home for your plants, as long as the soil has been well

worked and is relatively free of perennial weeds. If you are not

so lucky and your new yard is a wasteland of bare turf, you will

have to prepare an area large enough to hold any plants you will

be moving over. If time is very limited, you may be restricted to

simply digging or rototilling a suitable area and physically

removing as many grass roots and perennial weeds as possible. A

more effective solution is first treating the site with a non-

selective herbicide such as Roundup, waiting a week or two, then

digging or rototilling. You may wish to incorporate peat moss or

other organic matter into the soil at this time, but as this will

only be a holding site, this step is not as important as when

establishing permanent beds. <P>

<P>

Once the site has been adequately prepared, you can begin moving

your plants to their new home. Whether this is done in stages or

en masse will depend on the time available and your own

preference. If possible, choose a calm, cool day, as this will

substantially reduce transplant shock. Plants should be well

watered a couple of days prior to moving, but don't wait until

the last minute to do this as digging and moving sodden,

waterlogged plants and soil is an extremely heavy, messy chore.

When digging the plants, try to preserve as much of the root mass

and surrounding soil as possible. This is quite simple to do with

shallow rooted species, but others, such as peonies and bleeding

hearts almost require the services of a tree spade. Plants may be

placed in tubs or sturdy, plastic-lined boxes. If they cannot be

moved immediately, place them in a cool shaded area and do not

let them dry out. If you have the time and energy, especially if

you are moving only a few, particularly treasured perennials, you

may want to consider placing them in pots. This is probably your

best alternative if you have not had an opportunity to establish

a site in your new yard. The odds of your plants surviving

several days, or even weeks, in a well-watered pot are much

higher than they would be languishing in a box with their naked

roots exposed to the elements.<P>

<P>

Even if you are very careful when digging and moving a plant, you

will inevitably damage or remove a portion of its root system.

Keeping in mind that plants lose large volumes of water through

their leaves-sort of a botanical version of perspiration - you

will probably want to remove a third to one half of the plant's

leaf mass. This is particularly important when moving plants in

hot weather; the reduced root system simply cannot take up enough

water to support a full canopy of leaves under these conditions.

As tempting as it may to let developing flowers remain, these

should be removed as well. Flowering and seed production require

a great deal of the plant's energy, which for this season would

be more profitably spent reestablishing its root system.<P>

<P>

Plants should be dug in to the same depth as they were originally

planted. Don't waste a lot of time worrying about positioning and

placement. This is merely a temporary solution; you will have an

endless Saskatchewan winter to plan exactly where you want things

to go once permanent beds have been established. Water plants in

thoroughly (you may want to include a phosphate-rich fertilizer

such as 10-52-10 or 10-52-17 to encourage root development), but

don't be unduly alarmed if plants still appear somewhat droopy

and resentful for the first week or two-everyone needs a little

time to adjust to a new environment. Keep them watered and weeded

and chances are good they will return next spring, healthy and

vigorous and ready to grace your yard for years to come.<P>

<P>

One note of caution when moving plants into a new neighbourhood.

If you are moving from a slug-infested area to one that is slug-

free, be very careful not to import your pest with you. Even if

there are no slugs present on the plant itself, the soil

surrounding its roots may contain masses of slug eggs,

guaranteeing their continued presence in your new home. If you

have certain plants you absolutely cannot bear to part with,

shake or wash most of the soil from the root ball; this is hard

on the plant but will remove most of the slug eggs. Otherwise, it

may be better to simply leave your plants behind, as the

punishment your outraged neighbours will inflict on you for

introducing this slimy, noxious pest into their gardens is too

dreadful to print. Consider yourself warned.<P>

<P>

&copy; 1995 Maureen Troesch<br>

