<html> 
<head> 
<title>October Best Time to Plant Lilies</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
October Best Time to Plant Lilies</center> 
</h1> 
 
by Sara Williams
<p>The writer is an Extension Specialist in Horticulture Science 
with the Division of Extension at the University of Saskatchewan.  
This column is provided as an extension service by the Division 
of Extension and Community Relations and the Department of 
Horticulture Science, University of Saskatchewan.
<p>     If October is the best time to plant lilies, now is also the 
time to write for catalogues, choose varieties, and prepare your 
lily beds.  Gone are the days when only a few types of orange 
speckled "tiger" lilies were available to Prairie gardeners.  
Today's lilies are beautiful, vigorous, and come in an amazing 
array of colours, shapes and heights.  They're easy to grow and 
require little special care.
<p>     Most lilies grown in the prairie provinces are termed 
"Asiatic hybrids" because the species from which they were 
derived originated in Asia.  They are cold-hardy, usually flower 
in July, have the broadest range of colours of any group of 
lilies, and are easy to grow.  Most are unscented.
<p>     Asisatics are further classified by the arrangement of their 
flowers.
<p>     Class A contains all the up-facing flowered varieties.  They 
are showy in the garden and make attractive cut flowers, but have 
a shorter flowering season than other classes.
<p>     Class B out-facing Asiatic lilies carry more flowers per 
stem and thus provide a longer season of colour.  They also make 
good cut flowers.  Class C are the pendant or down-facing lilies.  
They carry the most flowers of all, but may not have the same 
initial impact.  Because of their grace and beauty, the pendant 
lilies are a valuable addition to the perennial border, 
especially when grouped.
<p>     A number of dwarf lilies, ideal for a rock garden, are also 
included among the Asiatic hybrids.
<p>     A second large group of lilies suitable for the prairies are 
the Martagons.  These are tall lilies with many little turkscap 
blossoms and whorled leaves.  They are also called "wheel" lilies 
because their leaves are placed in whorls and wheels around the 
stem.  The flowers themselves are small, down-facing, and almost 
waxy in appearance, with "recurved" petals (thus the name 
turkscap) and often with speckles and freckles.
<p>     The last group of lilies grown on the prairies are the 
species lilies.  These are the original species found by plant 
breeders all over the world from which the modern hybrids have 
been derived.
<p>     Within these major groupings, lilies are also classified as 
to their season of bloom.  Ths gardeners can find varieties 
described in catalogues as early, intermediate, mid-season 
(July), late season, and season closers.
<p>     Lilies are best planted in late October.  Although the bulbs 
are never truly dormant, they do go through a resting period at 
that time, when top growth has died down, and bulbs can be 
lifted, sorted, shipped, and replanted.
<p>     Good drainage is probably the most important single factor 
in successful lily growing.  They will not tolerate locations 
where water collects after a rain or where melt water remains in 
the spring.  Gardeners can improve drainage, as well as a heavy 
soil structure, by building raised beds with the addition of 
coarse sand and peat moss.
<p>     Digging the soil to a depth of 30-35 centimetres and 
incorporating humus and compost and a little bonemeal is also 
helpful.  Lilies do best in a sunny location, although most will 
perform well given only afternoon sun.
<p>     Planting depth will depend on both the size of the bulb and 
the soil type.  Small bulbs should have 7.5 - 10 centimetres of 
soil above them, larger bulbs 10-15 centimetres.  In light, sandy 
soils this can be increased slightly, while in heavy clay soils, 
depth can be shallower.  In windy locations, plant bulbs deeper 
to provide better anchorage.
<p>     Lilies are most effectively planted in groups of three or 
more, leaving at least 30-35 centimetres between the bulbs.  
Remember, they will soon multiply and need this additional space.  
Plant with the roots downward and the scales upward, cover with 
soil, and firm well.  This will prevent the formation of air 
pockets in which the tiny rootlets can become dry.
<p>     Water well.  Two or three additional good soakings prior to 
freeze-up will ensure good root growth.
<p>     Purchase lily bulbs from reputable local growers and 
breeders.
<p>     The Saskatoon lily society receives a shipment of bulbs each 
fall, and the public can place orders by writing to Bob Caldwell, 
1616 Landa, Saskatoon, Saskatchewan, S7J OP6, or telephone 
374-2873 for more information. 
 
<br> 
<a href="index.html"><img align=left border=0 alt="" src="im/back.gif"> 
Return to plant index</a><br> 
