<head> 
<title>PEONIES</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
PEONIES</center> 
</h1> 
 
Sara Williams
<p>The writer was a graduate student of Horticulture Science at the 
University of Saskatchewan.  This column is offered as an 
extension service by the Division of Extension and Community 
Relations and the Department of Horticulture Science, University 
of Saskatchewan.
<p>The peony is native to many parts of Europe and was first brought 
to England by the Roman legions about the year 1200.  In England, 
the red-flowered peony was said to glow in the dark (some 
varieties do have phosphorescent qualities) and was often planted 
beside doorways to ward off evil spirits.
<p>It was described in botanical books as early as 1636 and was soon 
considered so tolerant of neglect that the rich thought it 
"vulgar" and left it to flourish in the cottage gardens of the 
peasantry.
<p>Other species originated in China, where as early as 1596 at 
least 30 varieties were listed in nursery catalogues.  A French 
missionary stationed in China, Pere Delevay, introduced some of 
these to Europe in the 1800s.
<p><B>PEONY TYPES </B>
<P>Many types of peonies are available to Saskatchewan gardeners.  
Chinese peonies have large double flowers in shades of red, pink, 
and white.  (Botanically speaking, it is interesting to note that 
the inner row of petals actually consists of sepals which have 
been modified to form petals!)
<p>Semi-double peonies are characterized by several rows of petals  
and a centre of petals mixed with stamens.  Because they have 
fewer petals, the flowers weigh less and therefore do not bend 
over under windy or rainy conditions.
<p>Anemone peonies are similar to the double Chinese, but with a 
centre of narrow petals.
<p>The Japanese peonies are noted for the contrasting color of the 
centre petals (actually stamens which have been partially 
modified to form petals) and their finely divided foliage.
<p>The fernleaf peonies have delicate, fern-like foliage, are dwarf 
in stature, and bloom very early.  They are more difficult to 
propagate than the other types and therefore tend to be less 
available and more expensive.
<p>The beauty of the single peonies, with only a few rows of petals, 
lies in their simplicity.  They tend to be early-flowering with 
delicate, divided foliage.
<p>Tree peonies, are more shrub-like.  Though sometimes advertised 
in the prairie provinces, they are generally not hardy and are 
not recommended.
<p><B>PLANTING</B> 
<P>Choose a sunny, well-drained location, away from competing tree 
roots.  Peonies are best planted, transplanted, and divided in 
the fall.  Mature plants will reach a diameter of 1 m (3 ft) or 
more and so it is important to give them enough room in which to 
develop.  A spacing of 1-1.2 m (3-4 ft) is recommended.  The 
planting hole should be large enough so that the peony is not 
crowded.  Heavy clay soils or light sandy soils can be improved 
by the addition of an equal amount of peat moss, thoroughly mixed 
with the existing soil.
<p>The new division should be planted so that the pink bud (also 
called an "eye" or "nubbins") is 5 cm (2 in.) below the soil 
surface.  Deeper planting will delay or inhibit flowering, while 
shallower planting might make the bud more vulnerable to frost or 
mechanical injury.  Deep planting is the most common reason for 
failure of peonies to bloom.  But keep in mind that it is normal 
for some varieties to take up to 2 or 3 years to bloom after 
planting or transplanting.  (Not the type of perennial whose 
location one wants to keep changing!)
<p>When dividing an older peony, wait until mid-September when the 
foliage has begun to yellow.  Cut and remove the stems at ground 
level and then lift the entire clump.  Allow it to sit in the sun 
for a few hours before dividing.  This will cause the brittle 
roots and buds to become more "rubbery" and less likely to break.  
Shake or wash off the soil and then, using a sharp spade or 
knife, divide the old crown so that each new division contains  
3-5 buds or eyes.  Replant as above.
<p><B>CARE </B>
<P>Like most perennials, peonies should be watered thoroughly and 
deeply to the depth of their roots and beyond into the soil below 
- 46-61 cm (18-24 in.) - once every 10-14 days.  This is 
preferable to watering them shallowly and frequently.  Deep 
watering will encourage deep rooting.  Once established, peonies 
are very drought-resistant.
<p>An application of 11-48-0 or 16-20-0, at the rate of 3 
tablespoons per plant, incorporated shallowly around each plant, 
is beneficial in the spring.
<p>Some of the older, double varieties of peonies have weak stems in 
relation to the heavy flowers they carry.  These plants may need 
support to prevent the stems from "flopping," especially after 
wind or a heavy rain.  Commercial "hoops" are available for this 
purpose.
<p><B>PROBLEMS </B>
<P>Botrytis (peony blight), a fungal disease, is the most common 
problem associated with peonies.  Symptoms include brown flower 
buds which fail to develop and wilted shoots.  Remove and destroy 
all affected foliage.  It is also recommended that even on 
healthy plants all foliage be cut to ground level and removed in 
late fall, as fungal spores can overwinter on the old foliage to 
infect plants the following spring.  Botrytis can be controlled 
by using captan or benomyl according to label directions.
<p>Peonies are sometimes heavily infested with ants, which are 
attracted by the sugars exuded by the flower buds.  Though they 
are unsightly, the ants do not harm the peonies.  The 
oft-repeated idea that ants are needed for peony flower 
development is false.
<p>Occasional aphid infestations may be controlled with malathion. 
 
<br> 
