<head> 
<title>PERENNIALS ON THE MOVE PART 1</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
PERENNIALS ON THE MOVE PART 1</center> 
</h1> 
 
WHAT TO DIG, DIVIDE AND CLEAN UP THIS FALL
<p>Sara Williams
<p>According to the old rule of thumb, most perennials can be 
planted, moved, or divided early in the spring.  With the advent 
of containerized plants, this rule of thumb has been given a lot 
more flexibility.  While it's generally advisable not to move 
plants in extremely hot or windy conditions or those which are 
actively growing or in flower, plants can survive a move at most 
any time if they are given the proper care.  
<p><B>How to transplant</B>
<p>Always move perennials with as large a soil ball as possible.  
Have their new home ready before you dig.  The move itself should 
be done carefully and quickly, exposing the roots to the air as 
little as possible.  If the perennial has a lot of top growth, it 
should be cut down to about 15 cm (6 in.).  Roots which have been 
disturbed or damaged by a move will not be able to support a 
large amount of top growth until they themselves are 
re-established.  
<p>The new planting hole should be roomy enough to hold the soil 
ball.  Set the perennial in the hole at about the same depth at 
which it was previously.  Firm the soil well around the plant.  
This is important.  If the soil is thrown in around the plant 
loosely, there will be air pockets which will allow the 
microscopic root hairs to dry out.  On the other hand, don't feel 
obligated to compress the soil to the point of compaction - let 
moderation be your guide.  
<p>Once the soil has been firmed, water the plant well.  This means 
the soil should be moist to a depth of about 46 cm (18 in.).  
It's a much better horticultural practice to water deeply but 
less frequently.  This approach will ensure a deeper root system 
and a plant better able to cope with 'stress' in the form of 
heat, cold, wind, drought, or children stomping across the 
perennial bed in search of their ball.  
<p>Finally, mulch around (not over) the newly transplanted perennial 
to a depth of 8 cm (3 in.).  Grass clippings make an excellent 
mulch.  Mulching will prevent surface evaporation of water, 
leaving the plant more evenly moist and allowing you to water 
less frequently.  It will also prevent the vast majority of weed 
seeds from germinating, thus cutting down on a lot of labour.  If 
you really don't love the look of grass clippings like, use them 
anyway, but apply a thin layer of peat moss over them to improve 
the appearance of the planting.  
<p><B>What to transplant</B>
<p>     Iris:
<p>Iris can be transplanted at almost any time during the growing 
season, although preferably not just prior to or during bloom.  
Late July, August and early September are fine.  Dig up the old 
clump, shaking off or washing off the soil so you can see what 
you're doing.  On larger clumps, the middle portion will most 
likely have dried out and the most vigorous growth will be on the 
outer edges.  When dividing an older clump, first cut the leaves 
off 8 cm (3 in.) above the rhizome to form a 'fan.'  Discard any 
rhizomes which are dried out or mushy.  Often but incorrectly 
called roots, rhizomes are horizontal stems that grow partly or 
entirely underground, often thickened, and serving as a storage 
organ.  A healthy rhizome should resemble an apple or potato when 
cut into.  Divide the clump into small sections, each one 
containing a piece of rhizome with a fan of leaves attached.  
<p>When replanting, set the rhizome just below soil level, digging a 
shallow trench 5 to 8 cm (2 to 3 in.) deep on either side of it.  
Place the roots in the trench on either side of the rhizome and 
cover them with fine soil, firming the soil afterwards.  The top 
of the rhizome should remain exposed or be just covered with soil 
if winter losses have been a problem.  Deep planting will not 
kill the iris but may retard blooming and make it more 
susceptible to soft rot diseases.  Water well.  Space the 
rhizomes 25 to 30 cm (10 to 12 in.) apart.  The appearance of the 
beds is sparse the first year, but they soon fill in.
<p>Some growers recommend mulching around the base of the iris prior 
to their first winter to even out possible temperature 
fluctuations and provide a measure of insulation.  Once 
established, this practice is not needed unless varieties are 
only marginally hardy.
<p>Williams is a specialist in horticulture with the Extension 
Division.  This column is provided as a service by the Extension 
Division and the Department of Horticulture Science, University 
of Saskatchewan. 
 
<br> 
