</DOCHDR>
<html> 
<head> 
<title>PLANTS THAT CAN KILL</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
PLANTS THAT CAN KILL</center> 
</h1> 
 
By Grant Wood
<p>In response to a number of Garden Line requests, Wood  
presents a revised and updated version of an article that has  
appeared previously in this series..  The writer is a lecturer with the  
Department of Horticulture Science.  This column is provided by the  
Division of Extension and Community Relations and the Department  
of Horticulture Science, University of Saskatchewan.
<p>Most people are vaguely aware that some plants can be  
poisonous.  In fact, some of Nature's most beautiful plants are quite  
deadly - including some common house plants.
<p>General Safety Precautions
<p>*Avoid eating any seeds, berries, leaves, flowers,  
roots or any other plant material until the plant has been  
positively identified and found to be safe.  Avoid making tea  
from plant materials unless the plant is non-toxic;
<p>*Avoid eating all plants with milky or colored sap.   
Lettuce is an exception.  Milky sap is often a skin irritant  
that causes swelling of tissues.  It will cause a rash, and if  
eaten will cause the throat tissues to swell, possibly  
leading to death by asphyxiation;
<p>*Avoid eating bulbs.  Those with an onion or garlic smell are   
safe;
<p>*Learn to recognize poisonous plants. 
<p>Special Measures for Children
<p>The most common victims of plant poisoning are children.  For  
their safety, take the following precautions:
<p>*Plants that are known to be toxic should be removed from  
the home; or at the very least placed out of reach of  
children;
<p>*Seeds, berries, bulbs, and other plant materials known to  
be toxic should be safely locked away, or removed from the  
home.
<p>*Teach young children not to chew leaves, seeds, flowers,  
berries or any other plant material from house plants;
<p>*Teach children at an early age the dangers of certain plants,  
and how to recognize these plants;
<p>*Do not allow children to suck the nectar from flowers, as  
this can be toxic;
<p>*Natural toys and jewelry (made from seeds, sticks, etc.)  
should be examined for potential toxicity before they are  
given to children.
<p>*Identify all plants in the home.  Be sure you know both their  
common and botanical names.  This information will greatly  
assist the physician in case of accidental poisoning.
<p>Some Toxic House Plants
<p>Potentially poisonous common house plants are listed below.   
Many are not fatal but can cause severe digestive problems, pain and  
discomfort.  The most toxic plant parts are listed and these should  
be avoided.  Plants marked with an * are potentially fatal.
<p>	Azalea, Rhododendron (some species), all parts;  <BR>
	Cacti (avoid eating any cacti with white or colored sap) <BR>
	Crown of Thorns, Euphorbia milii, sap; <BR>
	Cyclamen, Cyclamen persicum, bulb; <BR>
*	Dieffenbachia, Dieffenbachia (some species), all parts; <BR>
	Elephant Ear, Caladium (some species), all parts; <BR>
	Elephant Ear, Colocasia (some species), all parts; <BR>
	Elephant Ear, Alocasia (some species), all parts; <BR>
	English Ivy, Hedera helix, leaves; <BR>
	Euphorbia (all species), includes Pencil tree and milk bush, sap <BR>
	Fig, Ficus (some species), sap; 
	Hyacinth, Hyacinth orientalis, bulb; <BR>
	Hydrangea, Hydrangea (some species), all parts; <BR>
*	Jerusalem Cherry, Solanum pseudocapsicum, all parts, unripe fruit; <BR>
	Lily (many members of the Lily family are potentially poisonous. <BR>
             Avoid eating bulbs unless identified as non-toxic); <BR>
*	Mistletoe, Phoradendron serotinum, berries; <BR>
*	Oleander, Nerium oleander, leaves twigs, flowers; <BR>
	Philodendron, Philodendron (some species), Monstera (Swiss  
                     Cheese Plant), leaves and stems, especially sap; <BR>
*	Poinsettia, Euphorbia pulcherrima, sap; <BR>
*	Rosary Pea, Abrus precatorius, seeds (used in jewellery) <BR>
	Rubber Tree, Ficus elastica, sap; <BR>
	Sedum, Sedum (some species), all parts;<BR>
<p>If poisonous plant material is accidentally consumed or if a  
reaction is occurring due to contact with a poisonous plant, call the  
Poison Control Centre in Saskatoon immediately at 653-1010. 
 
<br> 
