<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Self-Seeding Annuals for the Back Lane</TITLE>

</HEAD><BODY background="im/backgrnd.gif">

<center><img alt="" src="im/line.gif">

<h1>Self-Seeding Annuals for the Back Lane</center></h1>

Grant Wood<P>

<P>

Many homeowners find the space between the back fence and the

lane a source of aggravation.  While quackgrass and other weeds

usually flourish on the site, potatoes, or other crops often

don't seem to do well at all.  The growing conditions in this

area are frequently far from ideal.  The ground can be rocky,

dusty, hot and dry, or shaded cool and overgrown.  Despite the

difficult conditions a number of annual flowers are well suited

to such rugged situations and can be used to transform an

unsightly space into a pleasing back entrance to your property. 

What's even better, many of these tough plants self-seed, re-

establishing themselves year after year with very little care. 

<P>

<P>

<B>Preparation</B><P>

<P>

Deciding what to do with your back lane should be based upon the

conditions that exist there at present.  If the area is blanketed

with weeds, don't be fooled into thinking that a few scattered

flower seeds will overpower the existing weeds.  The smart money

is always on the pigweed!  If weeds weren't competitive and able

to easily choke out most other plants, they would have vanished

from existence long ago.  Before anything is done, annual and

perennial weeds must be controlled.  This can be accomplished

with weekly employment of a sharp hoe, or a timely application of

herbicide.  Roundup kills perennial and annual grassy and

broadleaf weeds with a single application, so it is a good

choice.<P>

<P>

Once all the weeds are dead, you should dig the area to the depth

of a spade.  At this time you are quite likely to find that soil

conditions are far from ideal.  It may therefore be wise to add

and thoroughly incorporate organic matter such as compost.  Don't

make conditions too good, however.  Only moderate fertility is

recommended because an excessively rich soil can produce lush

vegetative growth and delay or reduce flowering.  You may also

wish to incorporate a few handfuls of a high phosphorus

fertilizer.  Any fertilizer with a high second number will be

rich in phosphorus, encouraging flowering rather than leafy

growth.  <P>

<P>

<B>Design</B> <P>

<P>

Initially you may seed taller plants along the back and shorter

ones along the front.  This orderly arrangement will last for

only the first season, however, as plants tend to seed themselves

in a somewhat more disorganized manner.  This should not be a

problem, however, as it will give the area a slightly untamed,

but attractive look.  <P>

<P>

To sow the area, simply rake the prepared soil flat, sprinkle the

seed on the ground, rake again lightly to incorporate the seed

and water gently.  Frequent shallow watering for the first few

weeks will be most beneficial to seedlings emergence.  As the

plants establish, decrease watering frequency and increase the

volume of each watering.  Deeper watering encourage deeper

rooting and stronger plants.  Most self-seeding annuals will

tolerate or thrive in dry areas, so they won't need a great deal

of water once they have become established.  Next year's

seedlings will likely germinate early enough in spring to take

advantage of early spring moisture, and may require no additional

water at all.  <P>

<P>

<B>Weeding and Thinning</B><P>

<P>

After having sown a mixed assortment of flower seeds, weeding can

pose a bit of a problem.  Unless you are an expert, you may not

be able to identify weeds from flowers.  Of course most gardeners

will recognize the usual set of weed seedlings that appear in

their garden, but if you're not sure, it may be better to wait a

while to see what develops.  In any case, if you let some weeds

grow until a positive identification can be made, be sure to

remove them before they flower and set seed.  Kochia, lamb's

quarters, chickweed and others have very inconspicuous flowers

that are easily overlooked.  You should be careful therefore not

to leave these weeds too long, as they may actually be blooming

and setting large numbers of seeds without your noticing.  <P>

<P>

Depending on the first year's seeding rate, and the emergence

rate in subsequent seasons, you may wish to thin the flowers. 

While a heavy blanket of emerging seedlings may appear to hold

great promise for a brilliant display, over-crowding will

actually reduce the number and size of flowers produced as each

plant competes for light, nutrient and moisture.  A lower number

of robust plants will usually produce a much more showy display.

<P>

<P>

<B>Autumn Care</B><P>

<P>

By not removing mature flower heads, the seeds will mature and

disperse naturally to provide for next year's show.  After a few

years you will probably begin to find that some flowers in a mix

are more aggressive than others.  These may begin to crowd out

the others by setting more seed, or by shading the other plants. 

This leaves you with two options.  You can either let the plants

fight it out amongst themselves, with the most aggressive members

eventually taking over; or you can intervene to preserve

diversity.  By removing flower heads from more aggressive

species, and selectively thinning aggressive species more

heavily, a better balance can be maintained.  You may also assist

seed dispersal on some plants.  Sometimes poppy seed capsules may

not appear to be distributing the seed.  If you don't think the

seed is being release, the dry capsules can be snapped off and

shaken over the area to assure the seed is actually being

distributed.  <P>

<P>

<B>Recommended Self-Seeding Annuals</B> <P>

<P>

When choosing flowers for your back lane, try to select those

with variability in height, flower colour and flowering-time. 

This will assure a longer bloom period and diversity to the

scene.  <P>

<P>

Some of the most reliable self-seeding annuals include: 

Calendula, California poppy, Shirley poppy, columbine, cornflower

(bachelor's button), cosmos, dame's rocket, forget-me-not and

annual hollyhock.  A number of other annuals perform well in

these types of areas and can be expected to regularly self-seed. 

These include: ageratum, sweet alyssum, anchusa, garden atriplex

(orach), coreopsis, nicotiana, phlox and safflower.<P>

<center><img alt="" src="im/line.gif">

<h1>Perennials for the Back Lane</h1></center>

Sara Williams<P>

<P>

Grant Wood described preparation and establishment of self-

seeding annuals in the waste space between the back fence and

back lane.  Another suggestion for this space could be the

inclusion of some of our toughest perennials either in

combination with self-seeding annuals, or as perennials alone. 

Either way, soil preparation along with faithful weeding and

watering during the year of establishment are all critical.  <P>

<P>

A number of perennial plants are tough enough to perform well in

a back lane meadow.  Remember, the same qualities which make

these plants suitable for the rugged conditions of the back lane

make them aggressive and competitive under the luxuriant

conditions of your perennial border.  <P>

<P>

All of the yarrows (<I>Achillea spp</I>.) prefer full sun and

well drained soil where they can be expected to spread rapidly by

underground stems.  <B>Fern-leaf yarrow</B> (<I>A.

filipendulina</I>) has flat heads of yellow flowers on 100 to 130

cm stems.  The flowers can be cut for fresh or dried

arrangements.  <B>Common yarrow</B> (<I>A. millefolium</I>) is

similar but only 45 to 60 cm in height.  Flower colours range

from cream to pink and purple.  <B>Sneezewort</B> (<I>A.

ptarmica</I>) is the same height but has clusters of small

button-like cream to yellow flowers.  <P>

<P>

<B>Bishop's goutweed</B> (<I>Aegopodium podagraria

`variegatum'</I>) is the groundcover to end all groundcovers. 

Its bright green and white variegated leaves will reach heights

of 30 to 40 cm creating billowing masses.  The insignificant

dill-like flower heads can be removed when the pop up above the

mass of leaves in June.  This plant spreads rapidly in full sun

or deep shade.  Where it is grown with other plants, goutweed

will quickly take over, shading out all others.  Because of this,

it is best grown on its own as a groundcover, rather than in a

mixed setting.  Before planting this one, however, remember that

plants don't perceive visual obstructions such as fences the same

was you do.  If you plant goutweed just behind the fence that

separates your garden from the back lane, you will very quickly

discover that your groundcover has found its way under the fence

and begun its sprint across the yard.  You were warned! 

<P>

<B>Snowdrop anemone</B> or <B>windflower</B> (<I>Anemone

sylvestris</I>) is a spreading plant of 30 to 40 cm with pure

white nodding flowers in May and June.  It grows equally well in

sun or shade and spreads both below ground and by self-seeding.

<P>

<B>Golden Marguerite</B> (<I>Anthemeis tinctoria</I>) is a yellow

60 cm daisy-like flower which blooms in July and self-seeds

prolifically.<P>

<P>

<B>Snow-in-summer</B> (<I>Cerastium tomentosum</I>)  Is a fine

textured, spreading low plant with soft grey leaves and tiny

white flowers which will self-seed.  On hot dry sites in full

sun, flowers will be produced in great profusion.  

<P>

<B>Shasta daisy</B> (<I>Chrysanthemum x superbum</I>) produce

white flowers on 60 to 90 cm stems in mid-summer.  They do well

in sun or partial shade and will naturalize quickly by self-

seeding.<P>

<P>

<B>Cypress spurge</B> (<I>Euphorbia cyparissias</I>) grows to 30

cm.  The plants themselves are often considered by children to

resemble a forest of tiny spruce trees as they would appear from

an airplane.  Plants produce yellow-green flower-like bracts

around the very small true flowers.  Plants spread by self-

seeding and below ground stems.<P>

<P>

<B>Blanket flower</B> (<I>Gaillardia arisitata</I>) will grow

easily from seed and naturalize by self-seeding.  Broad daisy-

like flowers are produced in a colour range of gold and orange to

rusty-red and burgundy with central portions of the flower

usually darker coloured.  Flowers on 60 to 90 cm stems are

produced from July to hard frost where there is full sun.

<P>

Among the <B>cranesbill geraniums</B>, the <B>big root

geranium</B> (<I>Geranium macrorrhizum</I>) is ideal for the back

lane.  It thrives in full sun or partial shade, and produces pink

flowers on dense 30 to 40 cm plants will deeply cut leaves.

<P>

<B>Iceland poppies</B> (<I>Papaver nudicaule</I>) bear flowers in

bright orange, yellow, white and salmon pink.  Before they open,

flower buds nod on the tops of dainty 35 cm leafless stems.  They

behave like biennials and seed themselves reliably.<P>

<P>

<B>Oriental poppies</B> (<I>Papaver orientale</I>) are flamboyant

bloomers with enormous flowers in red, white, pink, salmon and

purple.  The flowers are borne on 60 cm stems above large jagged

hairy leaves.  

<B>Sea campion</B> (<I>Silene vulgaris maritima</I>) is a low

plant with grey-green leaves covered in tiny white flowers for

most of the summer.  Although individual plants tend to be short-

lived, they perpetuate themselves through seed.

<P>

&copy; 1994 Grant Wood and Sara Williams<br>

