<html> 
<head> 
<title>The Skinner hybrids:</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
The Skinner hybrids:</center> 
</h1> 
 
"It was a chaste and dainty little lily, and I regret very much that I have  
never been able to reproduce it."  Thus Frank Skinner wrote about "Evening  
Star", an orange-yellow, late flowering hybrid lily resulting from the unusual  
and difficult cross of L. Leichtlinii var. Maximowiczii and L. concolor.  He  
introduced it in 1954 but lost it soon after through basal rot.  This statement  
is characteristic of the blend of scientific inquiry, compassion, and a love of  
the art of horticulture which inspired and drove many of the early hybridizers  
of Asiatic lilies from the Canadian Prairies.
<p>Frank Skinner was born in Scotland and immigrated to Canada with his parents in  
1895 when he was 13 years old.  He soon developed a nursery at Dropmore,  
Manitoba, where he worked diligently over many years, introducing hardy plants  
from other parts of the world into the Prairie provinces as well as developing  
many of his own.  His son, Hugh, now runs the nursery.
<p>In his work with lilies from the early 30's to the late 50's his goal was to  
develop new colors as well as fragrance.  Among the many parent plants he used  
were L. auratum-speciosum and L. centifolium hybrids, L. davidi, L.  
philadelphicum (our own Prairie lily), L. tigrinum, and L. dauricum.  Today, the  
best known of his hybrid lilies are "Maxwill", "Scottiae", "Juanita" and "Lemon  
Lady."
<p>Of "Maxwill", introduced in 1932, Skinner himself said, "It is, without  
question, the best known of my lilies."  A half of a century later, it is still  
true.  It is a vigorous, free flowering, orange-red lily, held on strong stems  
of 6 to 7 feet and needing no staking.  It is one of the most reliable of garden 
lilies with up to 30 flower buds per stem.
<p>"Stottiae", introduced in 1931, is an orange-red, out-facing lily with dark  
foliage.  (It was later used by Bert Porter to develop his dwarf, upfacing  
hybrids-lilies which were diminutive but strong and sturdy.)
<p>"Juanita" (introduced in 1954) is a martagon hybrid with pink buds which open to 
flat, downward facing white flowers spotted with pink.  The petals are thick and 
of good substance.
<p>"Lemon Lady" is a clear lemon yellow; out-facing lily with martagon type  
reflexed flowers.  It was introduced in 1951.
<p>The Porter hybrids:
<p>We seldom have a winter that does not give us at least one spell of 40 below  
zero weather and occasionally we get 50 or even 60 below.  Hardiness was a  
necessity in the development of Bert Porter's lily.  Disease resistance was also 
a priority.
<p>Another immigrant from England, Bert came to Canada with his family in 1907 at  
the age of 6.  He remembers crossing the North Saskatchewan River near Prince  
Albert in the spring on the way to their homestead.  They traveled by wagon and  
there was already a foot of melt water on the river ice.  While he found it  
exciting his mother was clearly nervous.  Bert became a school teacher but  
positions were difficult to secure in the 1930's.  He applied for a teaching  
post only to receive a reply that all of the members on the local school board  
were bachelors and even though he was well qualified they were looking for a  
young lady to fill the post.  Thus he began the nursery in 1934 which was to  
become Honeywood Lilies.  Located near Parkside, Saskatchewan, the nursery at  
first grew on hardy fruit.  It was not until the 1950's that Bert began his lily 
breeding.  Today, at the age of 90, Bert Porter is still actively developing new 
 
<P>Asiatic hybrids at Honeywood Lilies.
<p>Among his selections are 'Earlibird', 'Suntan', 'Red Carpet', 'Happy Thoughts',  
and 'Flaming Giant'.
<p>'Earlibird' is one of the earliest outfacing lilies.  It is a clear vivid  
apricot with fine dark spots near the base.  It has strong resistance to  
botrytis and is a durable garden lily with a height of 75 cm (21/2 ft.)
<p>'Suntan' is an outfacing lily with rich coppery-bronze blooms with green  
nectaries.  It blooms in midsummer on 120 cm stems and is excellent for flower  
arranging.
<p>'Red Carpet' is a short, upfacing, vivid red lily (of only 45 cm) which is  
excellent for the front of the border and becoming increasingly popular as a pot 
  
plant for indoor forcing.
<p>'Happy Thoughts' was introduced in 1986.  It is an upfacing lily of 75-90 cm.  
(2.5 - 3 ft) of clear white with a hint of green in the throat of newly opened  
flowers and an ivory stripe along the midrib of each petal.  The  
candelabran-type inflorescence bears 20-30 buds and blooms in mid-season.
<p>'Flaming Giant' is a vigorous lily facing directly upward with large, cup-shaped 
  
blooms which flare to show the vivid red-orange color.  It has very good  
substance, blooms in July, and with a height of 120 cm (4 ft.) makes an  
outstanding lily for the back of the border.
<p>Williams is a specialist in horticulture with the Extension Division.  This  
column is provided as a service by the Extension Division and the Department of  
Horticulture Science, University of Saskatchewan. 
 
<br> 
