<html> 
<head> 
<title>THE VENUS FLY TRAP</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
THE VENUS FLY TRAP</center> 
</h1> 
<p>If your children think that plants are boring, you may want to 
tell them about the Venus Fly Trap, a plant that eats insects.  
<p>If conditions are correct, a healthy Venus Fly Trap can snap its 
jaw-like leaves (appropriately called "traps") shut with almost 
lightening speed on insects.  Trapped insects are slowly digested 
by the plant until only a skeleton remains.  The Venus Fly Trap 
developed on acid soils high in organic matter but low in mineral 
fertility.  By trapping insects it is able to supplemnent its 
"diet" so that it can survive on soils of lower fertility.  Quite 
a trick!
<p><B>How exactly does it work? </B>
<P>Each trap has six sensitive hairs on its inner surface.  The trap 
is triggered when insects touch any one of these hairs.  Once the 
insect is caught, the trap slowly closes more and more tightly as 
the struggling insect continues to brush against the trigger 
hairs.  When the trap is fully closed, enzymes begin to digest 
the prey.  About one week later, when the digestion process is 
complete, the trap opens to reveal the insect skeleton.  The trap 
is then ready to capture another meal.  Though the plant does not 
have to capture insects to survive, plants that are fed will 
generally be more healthy.
<p><B>Living with a Venus Fly Trap </B>
<P>The best way to assure that the plant will survive in the home is 
to grow it in a small covered terrarium - basically a glass 
container with a top.  The plant needs bright light, acid soil 
and high humidity.  A growing medium of unshredded sphagnum moss 
is ideal.  If this is unavailable, milled sphagnum peat can be 
used.  Full sun will produce healthy plants with bright red 
coloration in the traps.  Use rain water to water the plant; tap 
water in many areas will eventually neutralize the acidity of the 
growing medium.  
<p>Since this plant is adapted to soils of low fertility, fertilizer 
is not recommended.  Instead, drop one or two live ants into the 
terrarium.  
<p>The Venus Fly Trap may not appeal to everyone, but for those who 
are looking for a truly unique plant that is almost like a pet, 
there is no better choice.   
 
<br> 
<a href="index.html"><img align=left border=0 alt="" src="im/back.gif"> 
Return to plant index</a><br> 
