<DOCNO>WT24-B02-239</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA002-000014-B027-111</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://pine.usask.ca:80/cofa/departments/hort/hortinfo/trees/avoiding.html 128.233.59.24 19970101092609 text/html 5000
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: WebSTAR
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html> 
<head> 
<title>AVOIDING BIRCH DIEBACK</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
AVOIDING BIRCH DIEBACK</center> 
</h1> 
 
Grant Wood
<p>Wood was an instructor with the Department of Horticultural 
Science.  This column is offered as an extension service by the 
Division of Extension and Community Relations and the Department 
of Horticultural Science, University of Saskatchewan.
<p>Few trees are more attractive than the stately birch.  The 
weeping birch and paper birch are native to areas that are cool, 
moist and sheltered from strong winds.  In their native state, 
they are found on sandy to silty loam soils.  Because their root 
systems are shallow, these trees do poorly under prolonged 
drought conditions.  
<p>If your site offers a hostile environment to birches, consider 
growing another type of tree to avoid the frustrations associated 
with growing birches under adverse conditions.  You will find 
many other mid- to large-size trees that will grow well in this 
area.
<p>Birch trees in Saskatchewan are susceptible to dieback, a 
condition that leads to general deterioration and eventual death 
of the trees if it is not controlled.  The first symptom of 
dieback is sparse, stunted foliage near the top of the tree.  If 
measures are not taken to improve the condition, branches will 
begin to die from the top of the tree progressively downwards.  
The foliage that remains on the tree is often stunted and 
chlorotic (yellow).  A heavy seed-set is often associated with 
dieback.  Once the branches have died, of course, they will not 
refoliate.  
<p>Dieback is caused primarily by poor cultural conditions which can 
be improved by the following control measures:
<p>Watering:  Because they are native to moist areas, birch trees 
require frequent, deep waterings.  A tree that shows signs of 
dieback should be watered immediately.  If you simply water the 
lawn with a sprinkler, the tree will not receive enough water.  
Place a soaker hose on the ground in a circle under the outer 
ends of the branches (the drip line).  Punch holes in the soil 
about 15 cm deep, 1 cm in diameter, and about 30 cm apart. along 
the edge of the hose.  Turn the hose upside down over the holes 
so that it will soak into the ground.  The tap should be adjusted 
so that the water flows slowly; allow the ground to soak for 3 to 
6 hours.  Repeat the procedure once every three weeks from May 
until late August.  
<p>During September and October, water sparingly.  This allows the 
growth to "harden-off" for winter.  Birch trees should drop all 
foliage before winter.  Leaf retention indicates that the trees 
have not hardened-off properly for winter; as a result, they may 
suffer some winterkill. 
Fertilization:  A nutrient deficiency is one of the factors that 
may lead to dieback.  Most trees do not require fertilizing; they 
derive nutrients through an extensive root system that covers a 
large area.  However, if the leaves of the birch tree show 
yellowing (chlorosis) in the spring, an application of fertilizer 
is likely to help.  
<p>The following recommendations from Alberta Agriculture are also 
applicable to Saskatchewan.  Fertilize in the spring with 10-8-6, 
10-30-10, 16-20-0, or 14-14-7 at 0.4 kg/10 sq m (about 2 cups/100 
sq ft).   Make holes in the soil about 40 cm deep and 40 to 60 cm 
apart in circles around the tree, starting about 0.3 to 0.5 m 
from the trunk.  The holes can be made with a tool such as an 
auger, a crowbar or a hollow pipe.  They should extend out to the 
drip line of the tree.  Mix the fertilizer (at the rate 
recommended above) with enough soil to fill the holes, then pour 
the soil-fertilizer mixture into the holes and thoroughly soak 
the treated area with water.  
<p>Pruning:  Birch trees under stress or in a weakened state are 
more prone to insect and disease attack.  Birches suffering from 
dieback are commonly attacked by the bronze birch borer.  Proper 
pruning practices will help eliminate this pest.  Because the 
insect attacks dead wood, the basic approach is to remove all the 
dead wood.
<p>Soil improvement: Soil compaction reduces soil aeration and 
drainage, thereby damaging the root system of the birch trees.  
Soil compaction can be somewhat reduced by limiting excess 
pedestrian traffic near the base of the tree, but heavy (clay) 
soils tend to be compact and cannot be easily improved.
<p>Wind Protection:  Dieback can be a serious problem with birches 
in exposed areas subject to strong, drying winds.  There is 
little that can be done to provide wind protection for existing 
birches; it is best to locate them in areas sheltered by 
buildings or other trees to the north and west. 
 
<br> 
<a href="index.html"><img align=left border=0 alt="" src="im/back.gif"> 
Return to tree index</a><br> 
<br><br><br>Accesses: 98.</Body> 
</html>
