<html> 
<head> 
<title>Bracing Saves Split Branches</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
Bracing Saves Split Branches</center> 
</h1> 
 
Stu Nelson
<p>The writer is a professor emeritus of horticulture with the 
Department of Horticulture Science.  This column is presented as 
an extension service by the Division of Extension and Community 
Relations and the Department of Horticulture Science, University 
of Saskatchewan.
<p>Even if they are pruned regularly, large limbs can sometimes 
split at the crotch area where they join the main trunk.  With 
certain trees (such as apple) that send out water sprouts freely, 
weak crotches can be easily braced by winding the growth from the 
trunk and limb together in the area of the crotch.  The water 
sprouts will grow together to form a natural graft.  
<p>Mechanical bracing using cables and eye bolts is another 
effective way to secure split limbs.  A cable extending from the 
trunk to the limb is used to bring the split crotch together and 
hold it in place so that the bark can grow and reinforce the area 
of the split.  This method can be used where breakage has 
occurred but the branch has not split to any great degree.  It 
will stop further splitting and prevent the entry of moisture and 
rot organisms in to the heart wood of the tree.  
<p>For the cable anchors, you will need two eye bolts: one for the 
trunk and the other for the limb.  They must be long enough to 
pass through, with thread left over for tightening.  
<p>1.  Bore holes the same diameter of the bolts through the 
thickest part of the branch and trunk.  
<p>2.  Coat the bolts with a tree wound dressing such as Braco and 
insert them into the holes.  
<p>3.  Insert washers on the threads and then place the nuts on the 
threads, but do not tighten them yet.  Diamond washers are 
preferred to round ones because they are narrower and therefore 
allow greater circulation of water and nutrients up through the 
tissue layers under the bark.  The washers are usually 
countersunk into the bark.
<p>4.  Place galvanized cable through the eyes and clamp the cable 
as tightly as possible (Two cable clamps, available from hardware 
stores, are required).  As you pull the crotch back into place, 
be sure that the split are fits snugly together.  Trim excess 
rough bark in the vicinity of the split but do not create a 
cavity.
<p>5.  Tighten the nuts on the eye bolts.  This will pull the cable 
even more taut.  
<p>6.  Insert bolts through the crotch area and about every 15 to 20 
cm down the split to further reinforce the bracing job.  Insert 
washers and nuts, and tighten.
<p>6.  Apply Braco over the nuts and heads of all the bolts.  The 
bark will eventually grow over the bolts.  
<p>If you cannot obtain eye bolts long enough for this procedure, 
eye screws can be used instead and the cable tightened with a 
turnbuckle.  On smaller limbs, #9 wire can be used instead of 
cable; the wire can be attached to the limb and trunk with eye 
screws and tightened with a turnbuckle.  
<p>Severe CasesIn severe cases, when the limb has fallen from its 
position, but is still attached by a small area of wood at the 
bottom, remedial action is more difficult.  Short, deep breaks 
that occur with certain fruit trees are almost impossible to fix 
because there is no practicable way they can be stabilized and 
reinforced long enough to heal properly.  
<p>In contrast, limbs with long splits can be brought back into 
position and reinforced.  In moving the branch, bring it back up 
slowly and in stages to avoid a "crimp" in the bark at the thin, 
basal part of the split.  If a crimp does form, the flow of water 
and nutrients will be blocked and the limb will likely die.  
After the branch is back in position, it can be reinforced using 
cable and bolts as described above. 
 
<br> 
