<html> 
<head> 
<title>DUTCH ELM DISEASE</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
DUTCH ELM DISEASE</center> 
</h1> 
 
Saskatchewan Parks and Renewable Resources.
<p>Introduction.  Dutch Elm Disease (DED) is a fatal disease which 
can affect any elm tree.  Since its introduction form Europe 
about 1930, it has destroyed millions of elm trees across North 
America.  At present, the disease is prominent in Manitoba, North 
Dakota and Montana, placing all Saskatchewan elms at risk.  
Saskatchewan Parks and Renewable Resources (SPRR) is determined 
to resist the spread of this devastating disease.
<p>Disease Cycle.  DED is caused by a fungus and is spread from one 
elm tree to another by elm bark beetles.  The fungus disrupts the 
tree's water conduction system, causing the leaves to wilt and, 
usually within one to two seasons, the tree to die.
<p>Elm bark beetles breed under the bark of dead or dying elm wood.  
As a new generation of infected adult beetles emerges and begins 
feeding on healthy elm trees, the disease spreads.
<p>Symptoms of DED.  The early symptoms of the disease appear from 
the latter half of June to the middle of July when the leaves on 
one or more branches may wilt, droop or curl.  The leaves then 
turn brown and usually remain on the tree.  If the tree is 
infected later in the summer, the leaves will droop, turn yellow 
and drop prematurely.
<p>All of these symptoms are accompanied by brown streaks in the 
sapwood that can be seen by removing the bark of infected twigs.
<p>Surveillance.  SPRR Forestry Branch, Saskatchewan Agriculture and 
the Prairie Farm Rehabilitation Administration (PFRA) have joined 
with municipal parks and recreation departments across the 
province to form the Saskatchewan DED Committee.
<p>Because early detection is vital to controlling the spread of the 
disease, surveillance is the committee's most important role.  
Each member undertakes an annual survey of elms in their area.
<p>However, public assistance in identification and reporting of 
possible DED cases is an important part of controlling the spread 
of the disease in Saskatchewan.
<p>Since many other diseases may cause symptoms similar to those of 
DED, positive identification must be made in a laboratory.
<p>Sampling Procedures.  A twig sample for laboratory testing may be 
obtained using this method: 
<P>-Cut three sections from a twig showing brown staining, each 
about as big around as your finger and 10 cm (four inches) long.  
Do not remove the bark. 
<P>-Before sampling another tree, clean cutting tools with alcohol 
to avoid spreading infection. 
<P>-Wrap the samples in wax paper and put them in an envelope. 
<P>-Include your name, address, phone number and where the sample 
was collected. 
<P>-Send samples as soon as possible to: 
 <P>          Saskatchewan Agriculture and Food <BR>
           Plant Disease Laboratory <BR>
           3085 Albert Street <BR>
           Regina, Saskatchewan <BR>
           S4S 0B1<BR>
<p>Prevention and Care.  Prevention starts by keeping elm trees 
healthy, vigorous and properly pruned.  In the fall and early 
spring, examine the lower part of the tree trunk for red dust, a 
sign of elm bark beetles.  Toward summer, watch for wilting and 
yellowing leaves.  As soon as the disease is discovered and 
confirmed, dead or dying trees should be cut down and burned.
<p>Because Dutch Elm Disease can be carried on firewood, non- 
resident campers are advised to rely on the generally abundant 
firewood supplies at Saskatchewan campgrounds and not to bring 
fuelwood into the province.
<p>Through public co-operation and vigilance, we can all help to 
ensure Dutch Elm Disease does not have the opportunity to become 
established in Saskatchewan.
<p>Information.  For further information on DED or if you suspect 
the presence of this disease contact: 
<P>-The nearest office of Saskatchewan Parks and Renewable 
Resources, Saskatchewan Agriculture and Food; or
<p>          -SPRR, Forestry Branch <BR>
           P.O. Box 3003 <BR>
           Prince Albert, Saskatchewan <BR>
           S6V 6G1 <BR>
           Phone 953-2221; or
<P>         -PFRA Shelterbelt Centre <BR>
           Indian Head, Saskatchewan <BR>
           S0G 2K0 <BR>
 
<br> 
<a href="index.html"><img align=left border=0 alt="" src="im/back.gif"> 
Return to tree index</a><br> 
