<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Diseases of the Elm Tree (Part 2)</TITLE>

</HEAD><BODY background="im/backgrnd.gif">

<center><img alt="" src="im/line.gif">

<h1>Elm - Diseases of the Elm Tree (Part 2)</h1>

<a href="elm-1.html">[previous segment - Part 1]</a></center><br>

Russell Friesen<P>

<P>

Most people are aware of the possibly catastrophic situation

faced by the many thousands of elm trees that presently line the

streets of Saskatchewan's towns and cities. The arrival of Dutch

elm disease in Saskatchewan poses a threat to each and every elm

tree in this province, and could result in almost total losses of

our finest street trees. Prevention is the only practical

solution. Unfortunately successful prevention relies heavily upon

our ability to identify this disease whenever and wherever it

appears. A further complication here, is that the symptoms of

Dutch elm disease can sometimes be confused with the symptoms of

various other less-destructive elm diseases.<P>

<P>

Symptoms of Dutch elm disease usually appear just as the leaves

are emerging in spring. The leaves on one or more branches in an

affected tree will be lightþalmost lime-green and appear wilted.

In late June to mid-July leaves wilt to the point of curling.

They may also turn yellow or brown at this time. When the disease

strikes a tree late in the season, symptoms include wilting and

yellowing of leaves on specific branches, or premature

defoliation of the tree in fall. In all cases, these symptoms are

accompanied by a brown longitudinal streaking of the sapwood.

This means that wood just under the bark which would normally be

clear white, will have distinct brown lines or bands. Trees that

fail to leaf out in the spring may also have the disease. In all

cases where Dutch elm disease is confirmed, the infected tree

must be fully removed and all wood burned or buried in a

designated landfill. The stump of an infected tree must also be

removed or poisoned with fuel oil to kill beetles and any fungus

that might be in it. <P>

<P>

There are two other diseases that resemble Dutch elm disease so

closely that laboratory tests are the only way to decide which

disease is effecting the tree in question. The symptoms of

<I>Dothiorella</I> wilt and <I>Verticillum</I> wilt look almost

exactly like those of Dutch elm disease. <I>Dothiorella</I> wilt

is caused by a fungus that is spread by insects and the disease

only affects American elms. Verticillum wilt is caused by a soil-

borne fungus, and can appear on elms, maples, and many other

different trees and shrubs. Trees infected with <I>Dothiorella</I> can

be pruned to remove the infection, however pruning is largely

ineffective in controlling Verticillum.

<P>

Because symptoms of these diseases are so similar, twig samples

are taken from infected trees. Samples are sent to a plant

pathology laboratory where small pieces of the infected twig are

cultured and the fungus causing the condition incubated and

grown. Once a pure culture of the fungus is available, positive

identification of the disease is possible. <P>

<P>

From time to time, virtually all elm trees will show symptoms of

a disease known either as bacterial wetwood or slime flux. The

symptoms of this disease are easily identified. A foul-smelling

liquid oozes from bark-cracks, wounds, and large branch crotches

on infected trees. The oozing liquid is produced by bacterial

contamination in the heartwood of the tree, and is caused by

several types of anaerobic soil bacteria. These bacteria can only

live in environments where there is no oxygen, so they survive in

the middle of large trees. In this location the bacteria feed on

substances in the wood, and release fatty acids, methane and

carbon dioxide gas. Here, the fatty acids become rancid leaving

the wood of the tree water soaked and foul smelling. <P>

<P>

The carbon dioxide and methane gas produced by the bacteria

eventually build up within the tree to a level where they begin

to force liquid out of cracks and pruning wounds. When it emerges

from the tree, this fluid is invaded by numerous yeasts, fungi

and bacteria, which only serve to heighten the fetid odour of the

brown slime running down the tree. The bacteria in the centre of

the tree do not cause any wood rot, but actually make the wood

somewhat more resistant to decay. Elm stumps from trees that were

infected with wetwood, tend to decay more slowly than those from

healthy trees. Since wood rot is not promoted by this disease,

damage to the tree is primarily aesthetic. <P>

<P>

In rare cases, bacterial wetwood may generate symptoms similar to

those caused by Dutch elm disease. If gas pressure within the

tree rises high enough, the bacteria-charged liquid may be forced

upward in the tree. In older trees leaves will remain green, curl

upward and fall off. The result of a serious case of bacterial

wetwood is often dead branches in the tree. Sometimes,

particularly in younger trees, leaves will wilt slowly, turning

yellow, then brown and falling off.<P>

<P>

Little can be done about this disease. Since virtually every elm

tree has wetood, a tree can live quite well with it for decades.

It only really becomes a problem when the brown slime flux

becomes offensive to people. Washing away the brown slime flux

with a strong jet of water is all that is recommended.<P>

<P>

The fifth disease, and the most common cause of death in Siberian

elms is <I>Botryodiplodia</I> canker. A canker is a disease that

is seen on living bark and sap-conducting tissue. In Manitoba,

<I>Botryodiplodia</I> canker kills more elms than Dutch elm

disease, with drought-stressed Siberian elms being most

suspectable. A principal symptom of <I>Botryodiplodia</I> is the

development of water soaked, soft, reddish brown to black regions

in newly infected trees. The line between healthy and diseased

bark is sharply defined and the wood beneath the canker is

reddish brown. The canker may expand entirely around the branch,

resulting in wilting foliage and eventual death of the branch.

Many small branches often emerge from the trunk below the canker

and large patches of bark may be loose and peeling. Disease trees

should be removed. 

<P>

This discussion of elm diseases may invoke a sense of doom and

foreboding in some tree lovers. However take heart, 3000 years

ago a disease very similar to Dutch elm disease virtually wiped

out all the elms in what is now the United Kingdom. A few trees

with slightly higher than normal levels of resistance survived

and eventually re-populated the islands with elms which are

resistant to that disease. Eventually, the American elm will

overcome Dutch elm disease in a similar manner. The only problem

is that the development of resistance takes several thousand

years, and not even the most optimistic among us can expect to be

around to see it happen.<P>

<P>

<a href="elm-3.html">[next segment - Part 3]</a><br><br>

&copy; 1995 Russell Friesen<br>

