<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Elm Tree Disease (Part 3)</TITLE>

</HEAD><BODY background="im/backgrnd.gif">

<center><img alt="" src="im/line.gif">

<h1>Elm Tree Disease</center></h1>

<a href="elm-2.html">[previous segment - Part 2]</a></center><br>

Russell Friesen<P>

<P>

Most people are aware of the possibly catastrophic situation

faced by the millions of elm trees that presently line the

streets of Saskatchewan's towns and cities. The arrival of Dutch

elm disease in Saskatchewan poses a threat to each and every elm

tree in the province, and could result in the entire loss of

American elmþarguably our finest street tree. Prevention is the

only practical solution, unfortunately prevention relies heavily

upon upon our ability to identify the disease whenever and

whereever it appears. Unfortunatly, the symptoms of Dutch elm

disease can sometimes be confused with the symptoms of various

other less-destructive elm diseases.<P>

<P>

The first symptoms of Dutch elm disease usually appear as leaves

are emerging in spring. The leaves on one or more branches will

be lightþalmost lime-green and drooping. In late June to mid-July

leaves wilt and curl. They may also brown or turn yellow.

Symptoms of a late summer infection include wilting and yellowing

of leaves, or premature defoliation of the tree in fall. In all

cases, leaf symptoms are accompanied by brown streaking of the

sapwood. The wood just below the bark that should be clear white

will have distinct brown lines or bands. Trees that fail to leaf

out in the spring may also have Dutch elm disease. The only

suitable action to take in the case of an infected tree is total

removal of the tree. All wood is burned or burried, with the

stump also removed and treated similarly. <P>

<P>

Two other diseases resemble Dutch elm disease so closely that

laboratory analysis is the only way to decide which disease is

effecting the tree in question. The symptoms of

<I>Dothiorella</I> and <I>Verticillum</I> wilt look almost

exactly like those of Dutch elm disease. Dothiorella wilt is

caused by a fungus that is usually spread by insects; it only

affects American elm. <I>Verticillum</I> wilt is caused by a

soil-borne fungus, and can appear on elms, maples, and many other

different trees and shrubs. Trees infected with Dothiorella can

be pruned to remove the infection, however pruning is not usually

effective in controlling <I>Verticillum.</I>  <P>

<P>

It is because the symptoms of these diseases are so similar that

twig samples are taken from infected trees. Samples can then be

sent to a plant pathology laboratory where a small pieces of the

infected twig will be cultured and the fungus causing the

condition incubated and grown. Each fungus has a distinctive

growth pattern which can be identified when growing in cultures.

Identification of the fungus under laboratory conditions permits

a positive identification of the disease to be made. <P>

<P>

From time to time, virtually all elm trees will show a condition

known as bacterial wetwood or "slime flux." The symptoms of this

disease are easily identified as a foul-smelling liquid oozing

from bark cracks, wounds, and large branch crotches. The oozing

liquid is caused by a bacterial infection in the heartwood of the

tree. Several types of anaerobic soil bacteria (bacteria which

can only live in an environment where there is no oxygen). These

bacteria feed on substances in the wood, releasing fatty acids,

methane and carbon dioxide gas. Eventually, the fatty acids go

rancid leaving the wood of the tree water soaked and foul

smelling. <P>

<P>

The gaseous by-product of the infection create pressure to build

up within the tree, eventually forcing the liquid out of cracks

and pruning wounds. These fluids are invaded by numerous yeasts,

fungi and bacteria once they have emerged into the air, with

these infections serving to heighten the fetid odor of the ooze

dripping down the bark. The liquid raises the pH of the tree

making the interior more alkaline. The bacteria do not cause any

wood decay, and infected wood is also very resistant to decay. It

has been observed that elm stumps with wet wood, are protected

from decay for at least three years.<P>

<P>

Damage to the tree is primarily aesthetic, but slime flux soaked

wounds do not close properly as tree tissues involved in wound

closure are killed by the seeping fluids. The fluid can cause a

brown patch with a distinctive white border on the bark. The

condition may also result in branch dieback. Bacterial wetwood is

usually not the cause of the death of the tree. Liquid dripping

from a branch infection can prevent turf growth beneath the

dripping wound.<P>

<P>

Bacterial wetwood in elm trees can cause symptoms very similar to

Dutch Elm Disease. Wetwood liquids can be forced into sap

conducing tissues of the tree by the high gas pressures. If this

happens, the liquids flow up into the tree crown. In older trees

leaves will curl upward and fall off, but remain green. The

result is often dead branches. Sometimes, particularly in younger

trees, leaves will wilt slowly, turning yellow or brown before

falling off.  <P>

     <P>

The fifth and the most common cause of death in

Siberian/Manchurian elms is <I>Botryodiplodia</I> canker and

dieback. In Manitoba, this particular disease kills more elms

than DED. Drought stressed Siberian elms are particularly

suspectable to this disease. Cankers are diseases that are

restricted to the bark and the living sap conducting tissues

underneath the bark. One of symptoms of Botryodiplodia in newly

infected trees is a water soaked, soft and reddish brown to black

region. The demarcation between healthy and diseased bark is

sharply defined. The wood beneath the canker is also reddish

brown. The canker may expand and girdle branches, resulting in

the wilting and yellowing foliage above the canker. Witches broom

suckering growth often emerges from the trunk below the canker

and large areas of bark are loose and peeling. Disease trees

should be removed. 

<P>

This discussion of elm diseases may invoke a sense of doom and

foreboding in some tree lovers. However take heart, 3000 years

ago a disease very similar to DED virtually wiped out all the

elms in what is now the United Kingdom. Some elms survived and

were able to resist this disease. English elms reestablished

themselves, over a period of several thousand years. The American

elms will overcome DED, we may just have to wait 10,000 years,

leading to next week's article the which will address future of

Elm tree.<P>

<P>

&copy; 1995 Russell Friesen<br>

