<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Evergreens browned off by winter</TITLE>

</HEAD><BODY background="im/backgrnd.gif">

<center><img alt="" src="im/line.gif">

<h1>Evergreens browned off by winter</center></h1>

Brian Baldwin<P>

<P>

Having just emerged from one of the most miserable winters in

recent memory, that last thing you probably want to hear about is

something relating to winter. Unfortunately, browning of

evergreens was such a major problem this winter that many people

are wondering what to do. <P>

<P>

Usually only the tender evergreens such as cedars show winter

browning. This winter, however, some of our toughest junipers,

pines and spruces were browned off. On Colorado spruces, the

damage usually shows up as more of a purple than a brown patch.

<P>

<P>

Trees that are newly planted (within the previous two growing

seasons) are more susceptible than their fully established

counterparts. Many of your newly planted pines may show total

browning of the newest growth. <P>

<P>

On established trees, much of the browning occurred in

association with street lights. A tree only knows that winter is

approaching by monitoring the lengthening nights of late summer.

Pine or spruce branches that are growing directly in the zone lit

by a streetlight have their nights artificially lengthened, so

these branches cannot tell that winter is approaching, and do not

adequately prepare. Sodium vapour (orange) street lights causes

greater problems than mercury vapour (blueish) lights. This is

because the red wavelengths of the light are most influential in

telling the plant the length of the day, or night. <P>

<P>

If you pines or spruces have brown needles, there's a good chance

that the bud at the end of the branch is still alright. The best

thing to do is wait for new growth to emerge and mask the

symptoms of damage. If no new growth has occurred by mid-June,

the buds are probably dead. In that case, severely browned

branches can be removed, and all living parts of the tree left.

Small pines or spruces will not be disfigured for life, and will

generally recover an acceptable form after a few seasons. <P>

<P>

Cedars are the real problem. In general, cedars growing along

north or east facing walls will be alright, but those along south

or west facing walls will be damaged. This is because exposure to

late-afternoon sun, when daily temperatures are at their highest,

results in a daily freeze/thaw cycle in their tissues which is

very damaging. If the south or west side of your cedars have

turned brown, wait until mid-June and then crumble the dead bits

out using your fingers. Anything that is crisp enough to break

off when gently squeezed is dead and will not come back to life.

If you wish to replace cedars growing along a west or south

exposure, you should consider an upright form of Rocky Mountain

juniper. These have the same columnar form, but are tougher than

cedars. If you really want cedars, and your house faces west,

plant them along the back wall, where they will receive an east

exposure.<P>

<P>

&copy; 1996 Brian Baldwin<br>

