<head> 
<title>GRAFTING: A Challenge for this Spring</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
GRAFTING: A Challenge for this Spring</center> 
</h1> 
 
S. H. Nelson 
<P>Department of Horticulture Science
<p>Nelson is a past professor of the Department  
of Horticulture Science, and this column is provided as a  
service of the Division of Extension and Community  
Relations and the Department of Horticulture Science,  
University of Saskatchewan.
<p>[****figures not included****] 
   
<P>Fruit trees, some deciduous shade trees and special forms of  
weeping shrubs do not come true to variety if they are propagated by  
seed.  They must therefore be propagated by "asexual means" such as  
budding or grafting.  These methods involve growing parts of the  
desired tree on seedlings or limbs of trees from the same family.  
<p>I discussed various methods of budding in a column that appeared  
last summer. Budding is ideal for the summer period, although some  
types of budding can be done in the spring or fall as well.  In this  
column I will focus on  grafting, which is best done in the spring  
when the trees are just breaking dormancy.  
<p>Scions and Rootstocks 
<P>The two components of a graft are the scion taken from the desired  
variety and the rootstock onto which the scion is grafted.  The  
scion should be taken in the fall from the current year's growth and  
stored over winter in a slightly moist medium at a temperature  
close to freezing.  Regular readers of this column will recall that I  
mentioned this in an article last fall as a reminder in case any of  
you had any grafting plans. 
<p>The scion must be in a dormant state when it is grafted.  Scions  
harvested from trees in the spring are often starting to break  
dormancy and may have severe winter injury.  Therefore it is not  
desirable to use them for grafting. However, if you took no scions in  
the fall and have your mind set on grafting, gather some scions  
immediately and store them as described above until it is time to  
graft.  Your chances of success will be less than optimum, and if the  
pith of the wood is badly browned from winter injury, it is very  
unlikely your graft will succeed.   
<p>The rootstock may be a young seedling or even a mature tree,  
depending upon the purpose of the graft.  For propagating new trees,   
grafts are made onto young seedling rootstocks.  Cleft and whip- 
and-tongue grafts, the methods discussed in this column, are not  
usually used to propagate new trees.  They are normally used with a  
mature tree as the rootstock in order to change the variety of the  
entire tree or a portion of it.  
<p>Although grafting can be done when the trees are still dormant in  
the spring, it is better to wait until the sap is up in the rootstock  
before the dormant scions are inserted.
<p>Cleft Grafting 
<P>This method is used on larger rootstocks.  Two scions are used, each  
with 3 buds.  As noted above, the scions should be from wood taken  
the previous season, and they must be in a dormant conditions when  
grafted. 
<p>The steps for cleft grafting are as follows:
<p>1. Make a  sloping smooth cut about 2.5 cm long on both sides of each  
scion and bevel the sides of the cut surfaces slightly.  Be sure to  
make the sloping cut so that there is a bud just above it.  Fig. 1a  
shows two views of a scion cut in this way.   
<p>2. A tree limb  serves as a rootstock.  As noted earlier, the tree  
must be of the same family as the scion - e.g., a scion from an apple  
tree must be grafted onto another apple tree.  To prepare the  
rootstock, cut off part of the limb.  It is recommended that grafts be  
placed about 30 cm from the main trunk.  
<p>3. The saw cut will leave rough edges on the remaining section of  
limb (Fig. 1b).  Trim the rough edges with a sharp knife and cut a slit  
down the centre of the rootstock (Fig. 1c).  
<p>4. Insert the scions in the slit (Fig. 1, d and e).  As shown in Fig. 1e,  
the bottom bud on each scion should face outwards and lie just above  
the cut surface of the rootstock.  
<p>Cambium layer contact is essential for a successful graft.  The  
cambium layer, or "inner bark," is a ring of cells just inside the  
outer bark of the scions and the rootstock.  The layer is capable of  
dividing to form new cells.  In a graft, callus cells form to make a  
union between the two components.  
<p>Some care must be taken to insert each scion so that its cambium  
layer makes good contact with the cambium layer of the rootstock.   
Fig. 1h, an enlarged top view of the cleft graft, shows the contact  
between the cambium layers.  The scions, wedged-shaped in this  
view, are shown positioned in the rootstock.  The bevelled cut on  
each scion helps to assure good contact between the cambium layers.   
Note that the outer bark of the scion is thinner than the outer bark  
of the rootstock.  It is necessary to allow for this difference in  
positioning the scion so that the cambium layers match (Fig. 1h).
<p>5. Wrap the completed graft with rubber (not plastic) electrical  
splicing tape (Fig. 1f). 
<p>6. Cover the entire graft region with a grafting compound such as  
grafting wax or an asphalt tree wound compound (Fig. 1g).  As  
indicated in Fig. 1g, the cut ends of the 3-bud scions are also  
covered, but the overall scion is not coated with grafting compound,  
or coated very lightly.
<p>Whip-and-Tongue Grafting 
<P>This method is used on materials too small for cleft grafting.   
Normally, rootstocks for whip-and-tongue grafting are about the  
diameter of one's little finger.  Follow these steps for a successful  
whip-and-tongue graft:
<p>1. A 3-bud scion is used.  Cut both the scion and the rootstock with a  
long sloping cut at the same angle so that they will match (Fig. 2, a  
and b).  This cut should be at least 2.5 to 4 cm long.  Make the graft  
about 30 cm from the main trunk, as for cleft grafting.   
<p>2. Cut a slit about the same length down the centre of the scion and  
rootstock (Fig. 2, a and b). 
<p>3. Since the points on the scion and rootstock will not have a cut  
surface to contact and will tend to dry out, remove them (Fig. 2c).  
<p>4. Push the scion and rootstock together as shown in Fig. 2d.  If the  
scion and the rootstock are not equal in diameter, take special care  
to make sure the cambium layers match on one side.  
<p>5. Wrap and coat the graft as described for the cleft graft (Fig. 2, e  
and f).
<p>Subsequent Care of Grafts 
<P>The rubberized tape used to bind the grafts will usually stretch and  
deteriorate over time.  But the grafts should be checked as a  
safeguard against strangulation, and the tape cut if necessary.  For  
both cleft and whip-and-tongue grafts, growth from the lower bud of  
the scion is preferred, and the other growth is removed unless the  
lower bud fails. 
<p>In the cleft graft, both scions are allowed to develop initially, but  
after the first year the poorer of the two should be reduced by  
pruning.  Do not remove it completely, because it helps to seal the  
cleft wound.  In 3 to 4 years after the graft is made, the scions will  
have grown so that they are just beginning to touch in the cleft.   
When this occurs, remove the poorer scion. 
 
<br> 
