<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Grafting offers endless possibilities</TITLE>


</HEAD><BODY background="im/backgrnd.gif">


<center><img alt="" src="im/line.gif">


<h1>Grafting offers endless possibilities</center></h1>


Brian Baldwin<P>


<P>


Grafting is the process of joining two or more different plants


and permitting them to grow as one. Although the techniques of


grafting sometimes seem like mysterious surgical procedures


accessible only to highly-specialized professionals, a bit of


instruction is usually all that is needed for most people to


accomplish successful grafts. <P>


<P>


Of course certain limitations exist. Only closely related plants


will form a compatible union. Generally this means apple-to-


apple, rose-to-rose, but some plants permit you more leeway.


Saskatoons can be grafted to the roots of cotoneaster, mountain


ash or hawthorn because all these plants are members of the rose


family. Lilacs and green ash can be grafted together because they


are both members of the olive family, but plants in the cactus


family are perhaps the most amenable to grafting. <P>


<P>


The bright pink or orange-topped cactus plants that are sometimes


sold as "flowering" cacti in supermarkets, are actually small


grafted plants. The pink portion is not a flower, but a stem from


a cactus that mutated, losing its normal green colour, and


adopting a more flamboyant hue. These colourful mutants are


grafted onto their plain green rootstocks which not only supply


them with water and soil nutrients, but also feeds them through


photosynthesis. The non-green mutants cannot perform


photosynthesis, so they are living on their host much like a


parasite.  <P>


<P>


Nurseries often carry `Walker' weeping caragana grafted to a


trunk of `Sutherland' upright caragana. This union creates a


small tree with a vertical trunk that abruptly turns and weeps


back to the ground. In the last decade these little weeping trees


have become quite fashionable, but like many garden ornaments


they are met with conflicting opinions. Some people love them,


while others view them as little more than a living form of the


tacky pink flamingoes that dotted urban lawns in the 1960's. <P>


<P>


Grafting solves many horticultural problems. Some of the most


floriferous lilacs also have the disagreeable habit of suckering


from their roots. The attractive-blooming lilacs can therefore be


grafted to the roots of less attractive, non-suckering types to


capture the best qualities of both.<P>


<P>


In many apple-growing areas, orchard trees are grown on dwarfing


rootstocks. A dwarfing rootstock greatly reduces the size of the


tree. For example, on their own roots, `Granny Smith' apple trees


become very large, requiring high ladders to harvest. If `Granny


Smith' buds are grafted to dwarfing rootstocks, the same size and


quality of fruit can be produced, but the entire tree may never


exceed a few meters in height.<P>


<P>


If a friend or neighbour has a particular type of apple you have


always admired, why not try grafting a few twigs from that tree


onto your own. If you'd like to try it, now is the time to act.


Simply collect some healthy twigs about the thickness of a


pencil. Wrap them in damp paper towel in a plastic bag, and store


them in your refrigerator. When the new leaves are just breaking


this spring, these dormant twigs can be grafted to your existing


tree. <P>


<P>


Once you know how it's done, there is very little to limit you.


I've seen a single tree that produced over 100 different types of


apple. Guides are available, or you can take a class.<P>


<P>


&copy; 1996 Brian Baldwin<br>


