<head> 
<title>Planting Your Ornamentals</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
Planting Your Ornamentals</center> 
</h1> 
 
by ?
<p>Ornamental trees and shrubs are sold by nurseries as bare-root or 
potted plants.  Bare-root plants are usually less expensive than 
potted plants because of lowerer production costs for labor and 
materials.  If bare-root trees and shrubs are not planted soon 
after purchase, however, they will die unless stored in the soil 
by a method known as "healing in."  In contrast, potted trees and 
shrubs, though more expensive than bare-root plants, can be 
stored more easily.  Thus they can be more conveniently planted 
in spring, summer or fall, though spring and fall are the 
preferred seasons for planting.  
<p>Bare Root Plants
<p>Storage:  If you cannot plant your bare-root tree or shrub 
immediately after you buy it, place it in the shade out of the 
wind and keep it moist until it is planted.  If you must store it 
for a week or two, heal it in:  choose a site on the north side 
of your home, dig a hole (trench) in the soil, lay the plant in 
the hole and bury the root and much of the top growth.  The plant 
will remain quite dormant in the cool soil.  Be sure to keep the 
soil moist.  
<p>Planting:  A bare root tree or shrub should be planted before 
leafing out.  Cut the top growth back 1/3 to 1/2 before planting. 
<p>      1.   Dig a hole large enough to allow the roots to be spread 
           out.   
 <P>     2.   While digging the hole, allow the plant to stand in a 
           container of water.   
<P>      3.   Keep the top soil separate from the sub-surface soil.   
<P>      4.   Place the plant in the hole about 2.5 cm (1 in.) deeper 
           than its original growing depth.  The part of the 
           plant that grew below the soil at the nursery will 
           usually be somewhat darker.   
<P>      5.   Place the top soil in the hole next to and around the 
           roots, pack it in, and put the sub-surface soil into 
           the top of the hole.  After packing the soil tightly 
           you can water the plant.   
<P>      6.   Be sure you mound the soil to make a "basin" around the 
           plant to hold water.  You will need to water the plant 
           well at the time of planting, (water must penetrate 
           through the root zone and below) and every two weeks 
           throughout the season if conditions are dry.  
<p>Potted Plants
<p>Do not purchase potted plants that have been too long in their 
containers.  The root systems of such plants will likely have 
circled inside the container several times; if planted straight 
from the container the plants will do poorly or die due to root 
gridling.  It is important to redirect some of those root and 
open up the bottom roots so that they are spread out in the 
bottom of the hole.  Note disturbing the root ball too much will 
mean that the top of the plant must be pruned back to compensate 
for the root loss and damage.  
<p>Just potted plants
<p>Watch how you handle newly potted plants that are made available 
from nurseries.  These plants are usually bare root plants that 
did not sell by the first part of June.  The nursery operator 
plants up the left overs, cuts them back and allows them to leaf 
out and be sold as pot grown stock.  These plants are perfectly 
good to buy as long as they are established well in the pots.  
However, plants potted up in June and sold before fall often have 
established little or no new roots and as a result are poor 
transplant candidates.  Poorly established plants when knocked 
out of their pots loose the soil around their roots and the 
planting process resembles the planting of a bare root plant that 
is in full leaf.  
<p>Evergreens
<p>Traditionally evergreens have been sold as a spring dug tree or 
shrub that has had its root ball wrapped in a burlap bag.  Should 
you buy a ball and burlaped tree be sure to handle it carefully.  
Excessive agitation, ganging, dropping, rolling around of the 
root ball will loosen the soil from the roots.  If the soil is 
all knocked loose there is a very good chance that the tree will 
die.  Do not pick the tree up by the trunk as the weight of the 
soil will cause the soil ball to drop into the bottom of the bag 
leaving the roots without soil.  It is also very important to 
keep the soil ball moist prior to planting as drying out may kill 
the plant.  
<p>Note:  You do not have to remove the burlap bag when planting a 
ball and burlaped tree.  Simply dig the hole, place the ball in 
the hole, remove any plastic, push the edges of the burlap down 
away from the top of the ball and pack the top soil in around the 
ball.  Make a basin to hold water and water the tree thoroughly. 
<p>It is also very important to watch your evergreens carefully the 
first year after planting.  Remember that when you dig a tree for 
transplanting you leave behind 1/2 to 2/3 of the trees original 
roots.  A deciduous tree can be cut back to compensate fora the 
root loss while an evergreen can not be cut back.  To help your 
evergreens survive I recommend that you wet the foliage down 
several times a day during hot weather to help cool the plant 
down and reduce transpiration.  I also recommend that you use an 
antidessicant in the fall on your newly planted evergreens to 
help prevent drying out during the trees first winter.   
 
<br> 
