<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Spruce trees provoke turf war</TITLE> 
</HEAD><BODY background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<center><img alt="" src="im/line.gif"> 
<h1>Spruce trees provoke turf war</center></h1> 
Brian Baldwin<P> 
<P> 
Many gardeners are locked in an endless battle of trying to grow 
lawn under spruce trees. The war usually begins when the gardener 
removes just enough of the spruce's lowest branches to get the 
mower underneath. Five or ten years later the lawn has become so 
sparse that it's hardly worth mowing. Now the conclusion is drawn 
that the tree has been secretly engaged in chemical warfare - 
dripping acid on the soil and making it impossible for grass to 
grow.
<P> 
I'll stop here and suggest a little experiment we can perform in 
our minds.
<P> 
Imagine parking your car in the middle of your front lawn and 
leaving it there for the next five years. (Don't forget to raise 
it on blocks so you can get the mower underneath.) After just one 
summer you will probably find the lawn below the car has been 
reduced to a few feeble sprigs. Why?
<P> 
Possibly battery acid escaped, ran along the car's undercarriage 
and killed a perfectly rectangular patch of grass. It's possible 
- but a quick check of the car's battery would show no 
leakage.
<P> 
A second explanation could be that the car has blocked most of 
the incoming rain and sunlight so there was simply not enough 
moisture or light to sustain healthy turf.
<P> 
Few of us have trouble accepting that the dry shade under a 
permanently-parked car would kill the grass below it. Why then, 
do we so readily accept the myth of soil acidification when the 
grass dies in the dry shade under a permanently-parked spruce? 
Within its lifetime, a spruce cannot significantly acidify the 
soil below it. 
<P> 
What to do: First, admit that growing conditions below a car and 
a spruce are very similar. Next, recognize how silly you'd look 
trying to growing grass under your car. The best solution is to 
let the spruce branches sweep right to the ground and edge a 
perfect circle into the healthy turf just beyond them.
<P> 
By drawing a line in the turf and declaring that <I>"no grass 
shall grow beyond this point,"</I> you and the tree are fighting 
the same battle, so victory is possible. Also, a tree standing in 
a precisely-edged bed looks very dignified - as if the whole 
thing were somehow planned this way from the start! 
<P> 
What you should not do, is hack off more and more of your 
spruce's bottom branches until the tree is left looking like a 
one-legged giant. Hacking off branches as high as you can reach 
does not guarantee a healthy lawn beneath, but it does guarantee 
a funny looking tree for many years to come. 
<P> 
If you simply cannot accept the natural beauty of bare soil below 
a spruce, apply a thick mulch of spruce cones to the edged 
circle. If you still feel utterly compelled to attempt growing 
plants there, bergenia or <I>Geranium macrorrhizum</I> may be 
coaxed to survive (not thrive). Goutweed and lily-of-the-valley 
will also survive, but these plants will cause a whole new set of 
problems when they begin to run rampant in your lawn a few years 
later. 
<P> 
&copy; 1996 Brian Baldwin<br> 
<br><a href="index.html"><img align=left border=0 alt="" 
src="im/back.gif">Return to previous index</a><br> 
<br><br>Accesses: 102. 
