<html> 
<head> 
<title>Some tree troubles not caused by insects or diseases</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
Some tree troubles not caused by insects or diseases</center> 
</h1> 
 
Stu Nelson
<p>The writer was a professor of horticulture with the Department of 
Horticulture Science.  This column is presented as an extension 
service by the Division of Extension and Community Relations and 
the Department of Horticulture Science, University of 
Saskatchewan.
<p>In Saskatchewan, many tree injuries are not caused by insect or 
diseases.  The most common of these are the various forms of 
winter injury that can damage trees here.  
<p>Tip kill, which is prevalent in Saskatchewan, indicates lack of 
hardiness, but is not considered a serious problem.  Normal 
pruning will remove the dead parts of the branches.
<p>Crotch and trunk injury, a much more serious form of winter 
injury, usually causes death of the trees.  Injured trees may 
show no symptoms in the spring, but later in the growing season 
leaves will unfurl and wither because moisture cannot pass 
through the injured area of the crotch or trunk.  There is no 
known treatment for this form of crotch and trunk injury.
<p>Root injury is another serious form of winter kill that cannot be 
treated.  The roots are less resistant to cold than the upper 
parts of the tree and if there is little snow cover during the 
winter to protect the roots, injury often occurs.  As with crotch 
and trunk injury, root injury shows up later in the growing 
season.  The affected tree will likely lose its foliage and die. 
<p>Bark and wood splitting can occur on the same tree trunk, the 
latter usually only after very severe weather.  These are 
longitudinal splits that do not hinder transport of moisture up 
through the trunk to any extent; but they should be sealed to 
prevent the entry of rot organisms.  Tack down any loose bark and 
seal the entire area affected with tree wound compound.
<p>Sunscald, which can occur in late winter and early spring, shows 
up on the south side of the trunk and limbs as dry, discolored, 
sunken areas that may split open.  The sun starts the sap 
flowing; when the sun sets, tissue is frozen.  This injury 
normally occurs on trees with shiny, smooth bark.  Seal the 
injured area with a tree wound compound.  If only a few trees are 
affected, try shading the trunks or spraying them with a white 
compound to reflect the heat such as a water-based white paint.  
Winterburn on evergreens is also the result of alternating 
heating and freezing, and affected trees can be treated as 
described above 
<p>In addition to winter kill injuries, trees can also be affected 
by the following: 
Girdling is commonly caused by wire labels or guy-wires around a 
trunk or limb.  If the wires are not removed, they will 
eventually restrict the flow of water and nutrients.  Girdling 
can also be caused by a root that grows around the base of the 
trunk and blocks water and nutrients movement upwards.  Such a 
root can develop if the root system is not properly spread out at 
planting time.  It should be chiseled out to prevent further 
blockage.  Rabbits, porcupines and mice can also girdle trees by 
gnawing on the bark.  The work of rabbits and porcupines will be 
quite noticeable, but mice bites may be hidden by the grass 
around the trees.  
<p>If the affected area is very small, trim the rough bark and seal 
the wound with a tree wound compound.  Serious girdling injuries 
can be corrected by bridge grafting or inarching - methods 
described in Extension Publication Propagation for the Home 
Gardener available for $4.00 from U Learn, Box 22, University of 
Saskatchewan S7N 0W0.
<p>Chlorosis, often thought to be a disease, is actually a nutrient 
deficiency caused by a lack of certain nutrients, usually iron, 
in alkaline soils.  Trees with chlorosis exhibit a yellowing of 
the leaves.  Spraying the trunk with soluble iron (Sequestrene Fe 
Chelate) will usually correct the problem.  
<p>Salt spray, which can cause severe injury to grass, can also 
injure trees, particularly evergreens.  Fortunately, salt is not 
applied in large amounts to Saskatchewan roads.
<p>Weed killers have caused much considerable damage to trees, 
especially when these chemicals have been misused.  Manitoba 
maple and Siberian elm are very susceptible to this type of 
injury.  They often develop symptoms in response to the minute 
amounts of herbicide in the atmosphere, even if no chemicals have 
been sprayed nearby.  Trees can also be damaged by gas.  Pure, 
natural gas does not appear to injure trees, but injury will 
result from leaks of manufactured gas, where pure in in mixtures 
with natural gas.  
<p>The bruises resulting from hail and the holes created by Sap 
Suckers can adversely affect trees if the injury is severe 
enough.  Nothing can be done about the hail damage, but holes 
caused by the Sap Sucker should be sealed with a tree wound 
compound.   
 
<br> 
