<html> 
<head> 
<title>Help Protect Our City's Trees:  Hints for Healthy Trees</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
Help Protect Our City's Trees:  Hints for Healthy Trees</center> 
</h1> 
 
Leaflet from Civic Buildings and Grounds Department, Saskatoon
<p>City trees are a community resource.  They beautify, shade and 
shelter our neighbourhoods.  They protect us from harsh winter 
winds and summer heat.  They increase real estate values.  They 
provide habitats for a variety of birds.
<p>TREES PROTECT OUR ENVIRONMENT
<p>Trees also help maintain a healthy environment.  As fears over the 
greenhouse effect grow, the natural value of our trees becomes 
increasingly clear.  Trees absorb carbon dioxide, a major 
pollutant, and use it to produce oxygen.You can help protect our 
city trees by learning a few important facts.
<p>BOULEVARD TREES
<p>The City of Saskatoon maintains approximately 72,000 boulevard 
trees.  These trees are under the City's direction, management and 
control.  They are cared for by experienced professionals in the 
Civic Buildings and Grounds Department.
<p>- A boulevard is an area situated between the street and the front 
side of residential property.
<p>- Boulevards are City property, and trees growing on them are 
maintained by the City.
<p>- The width of boulevards differs from street and neighbourhood to 
neighbourhood.
<p>Who's responsible for Boulevard Trees?
<p>- Trees on city boulevards are maintained and controlled by the 
City.
<p>- The City is responsible for fare and maintenance of all boulevard 
trees.
<p>- You ave not allowed to prune or remove city trees.  If you do so, 
you may be liable to a fine and/or damages for the cost or 
repairing or replacing the tree.
<p>- Make sure you understand where City property begins.
<p>You Can Help by...
<p>Watering trees, to help them grow healthy and green.Urban Forestry
<p>Saskatoon is known across western Canada as a scenic, green city.  
Our trees are an important part of that reputation.  To Maintain 
tree health and beauty, the civic Buildings and Grounds Urban 
Forestry section provides specialized tree care. 
Block Pruning Program:from November through April specific areas of 
the city undergo tree pruning.  Pruning protects tree health, and 
provides for public safety.  It is done on a cyclical neighbourhood 
by neighbourhood basis.
<p>City Tree Inquiry Program:
<p>from May through September, you can call Civic Buildings and 
Grounds with questions and concerns about city trees.  We will 
investigate the tree in question or provide information over the 
phone.
<p>Emergency Tree Maintenance:
<p>if you notice severely damaged or broken trees causing a public 
hazard, contact Civic Buildings and Grounds.  We will send a crew 
out to correct the problem.
<p>Trees provide beauty, shade and shelter throughout our city.  Help 
protect this valuable community resource.  If you have any concerns 
or questions about tree maintenance or management, contact the 
Civic Buildings and Grounds Department at 975-3300.
<p>Hints for Healthy Trees
<p>Did you know that the cause of many tree problems isn't pests or 
disease? These are often secondary agents which attack trees 
already weakened through wounds and/or neglect.
<p>You can help keep your neighbourhood trees healthy by following 
these simple DO's and DON'Ts.
<p>DO water your established trees every 3-4 weeks during the summer.  
The best watering methods are those which penetrate to the roots, 
e.g. soakerhoses or deep root waterers.
<p>DON'T contaminate tree soil with de-icing salt.  High 
concentrations in the soil can kill trees.
<p>DO take care not to hit tree trunks, roots and branches when using 
lawnmowers or other equipment.  A gash may not look serious, but it 
is a "wound".  Tree wounds provide entry points for harmful pests 
and disease organisms.
<p>DON'T allow heavy machine or foot traffic to compact soil around 
tree roots.  This decreases the oxygen and water available to the 
roots, which can result in tree decline and death.
<p>DO handle yard & garden pesticides and herbicides with care.  They 
can harm trees.  Lawn herbicides, for example, can damage tree 
leaves and small roots.
<p>DON'T drive nails in, or attach wires to trees.
<p>DO enjoy your trees.  They add beauty, shade and shelter to every 
neighbourhood.  Just remember, even established trees need a little 
help. 
 
<br> 
