<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Hazard Trees</TITLE>

</HEAD><BODY background="im/backgrnd.gif">

<center><img alt="" src="im/line.gif">

<h1>Hazard Trees</h1>

<B>Why They Fall and How to Prevent More Damage</B></center><p>

Russell Friesen<P>

<P>

Sometimes, the wind storms of Saskatchewan can make this province

feel like "Kansas of the north."  High winds during summer storms

can inflicted serious damage to trees, uprooting or breaking off

large limbs.  High winds may also introduce cracks into large

branches which, although they are damaged, do not fall from the

tree.  Such branches can present a hazard to people or property

long after the original wind storm has passed.<P>

<P>

Many tree and limb failures are due to structurally unsound

branch attachments.  A tree branch can be attached to the trunk

in one of two ways.  Branches with strong connections will show a

single rough ridge of bark pushing out at the intersection of the

branch and the trunk.  In weak or "including" crotches, the rough

ridge is absent, and the bark grows into the branch crotch

creating a smooth indentation where the branch and trunk meet. 

It's a bit like the sleeve of a tight shirt binding under the

arm.  The inward folded bark of an including crotch blocks the

upper half of the branch from joining with trunk, and a weak

connection is formed.  This weak connection is also the exact

point where the branch is subjected to the greatest force during

strong winds.  The results are split trunks or ripped branches. 

Certain species of tree, such as elm, willow, maple and poplar

tend to have narrow "V"-shaped branching patterns, and are most

likely to break during strong winds.  Trees such as lindens, and

spruces, where the branches emerge from the trunk at nearly right

angles, are less subject to branch breakage.<P>

<P>

A great deal of wind damage can be prevented by proper pruning. 

On a large tree, main branches should be spaced at least a 15-20

cm apart on the main trunk.  A narrower spacing than this may

permit branches to grow together, leading to weakened

connections.  Of course, decayed and rotten branches are highly

subject to wind damage.  The fungi present in decaying wood

consume cellose.  Cellulose is the major structural component of

wood, and the substance which gives wood its enormous strength. 

Rotted wood becomes light, corky-soft and extremely weak.<P>

<P>

Following a wind storm, the immediate results of broken branches

are obvious and serious.  Some long term results are also

serious, but less obvious.  Badly torn bark and improperly

removed branches serve as sites of infection for fungal decay. 

Wood rot fungi may gain entry to the tree through tears and

breakages, leading to problems several years after the original

storm.  If fungi enter the heartwood, they can initiate rotting

in the centre of the tree, greatly reducing the tree's structural

integrity.<P>

<P>

Not all wind-damaged branches will fall to the ground.  When

branches are only partially broken, they may remain attached, and

undetected in the tree.  After a severe wind, it is a good idea

to check for cracks, splits, trunk leaning, or roots lifting from

the soil.  If a split has developed in the trunk of a tree, long

metal bolts are very effective in bracing the weakened area. 

Under no circumstances should a split tree be tied, wired or

clamped together.  Tying a tree will lead to girdling as the tree

trunk expands in successive years.  Eventually, either the tree

will snap off, or simply die above the point of constriction. 

Unfortunately, the symptoms of girdling are often overlooked

until the damage has become irreparable.  <P>

<P>

Should a large branch break during a wind storm, the remaining

area should be sawed cleanly off to leave the cleanest possible

wound.  Branch stubs should not be left on the tree, as they will

not heal properly, and will serve as entry sites for disease. 

Large jagged bark tears should be cleaned up with a sharp knife,

leaving the cleanest cut possible.  Once the cuts have been

smoothed, the tree will begin the slow process of healing over

damaged areas.  <P>

<P>

If you choose to hire a pruning contractor to deal with a

hazardous tree, it is best to hire a tree care professional with

special training in removal or evaluation of hazard trees.  A

good indication of contractor competence is membership in the

International Society of Arboriculture or completion of an

arborist certification program.  You might also ask to see

examples of the person's previous work.<P>

<P>

<P>

&copy; 1995 Russell Friesen<br>

