<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Trees Tell A Story</TITLE>

</HEAD><BODY background="im/backgrnd.gif">

<center><img alt="" src="im/line.gif">

<h1>Trees Tell A Story</center></h1>

Brian Baldwin<P>

<P>

If you could travel back in time to walk through Saskatoon's river

valley as it was 100 year ago, you would find the valley lined by

Manitoba maple, birch, poplar and green ash trees. Because much of

the river valley is now preserved and protected, native trees can

still be seen lining the banks of the river in stands nearly

unaffected by the growth of the city around them. In a sense,

therefore, you can walk through portions of Saskatoon's river

valley and see it almost as it was 100 years ago.<P>

<P>

Settlers brought with them new trees from distant lands. Of these

trees, American elm has been the most popular and successful. These

stately, arching trees line the streets of almost all of

Saskatoon's older neighbourhoods. But, the westward movement of

Dutch Elm Disease, continues to pose an ever-increasing threat of

destruction to Saskatoon's elms, and because elms constitute

approximately 80% of Saskatoon's mature tree canopy, the city's

character would be vastly altered by their loss.<P>

<P>

While most Saskatoon residents of the past seemed content with

planting mainly elm, a few pioneering residents experimented with

unusual trees. Some have survived to maturity, and can now be seen

as examples of shade trees suitable for replacement of elms. The

following is a list of some of the better examples of Saskatoon's 

uncommon trees.<p>

<P>

<B>Bur oak</B> is a long-lived stately tree, fully adapted to our

environment. Eighty years ago, few residents experimented with this

tree, so although it is gradually becoming more popular, there are

very few mature oaks in Saskatoon. Two of the city's best examples

of mature bur oak can be seen in a yard in the 900 block of

Temperance Street. One of the two oaks in this yard towers well

above the neighbour's two-story house, and rivals the neighbourhood

elms for size and grandeur. A third excellent example of mature bur

oak is found in the 300 block of Saskatchewan Crescent West.

Surrounded and almost hidden by elms, this tree stands beside a

large silver maple, another tree under-utilized in Saskatoon's

past.<P>

<P>

<B>Silver maple</B> is a tree that can surprise you. I have walked

past magnificent examples of silver maple for years without

noticing them, until one autumn day a classic "Canada Flag" maple

leaf on the sidewalk alerted me to the tree's presence. Three

excellent examples of enormous silver maple can be seen in the 300

block of Saskatchewan Crescent West. One stands beside the oak

mentioned above, the other two stand almost directly across the

street. Test yourself with the last one. Test yourself on the last

one: Can you spot the large silver maple visible from the

intersection of Temperance Street and Lansdowne? It took me years

to notice it, yet it's right there! 

<P>

<B>Little-leaf-linden</B> is another shade tree that has recently

begun to gain in popularity. Of the few mature lindens that exist,

one of the best examples stands just south of the university campus

in the 1100 block of Elliot Street. A new house and stone fence

were recently constructed very close to the tree, and although the

fence disrupted the tree's roots rather badly, this tree seems to

have survived the construction. Another example of a mature linden

can be seen directly adjacent to Lorne Avenue at the intersection

of 4th street. This multi-trunked linden would perhaps be larger

than the one on Elliot street if it had not lost its top as a

sapling and regrown from the ground as numerous shoots. 

<P>

A mature <B>Ohio buckeye</B> is a true rarity in Saskatoon. Such

trees are perhaps most easily noticed in autumn when their deep red

coloration causes them to stand out against our limited pallet of

gold and yellow fall colour. One of the very few Ohio buckeye trees

to have reached mature stature in Saskatoon stands in a back yard

along Queen Street. The tree can be seen from 9th avenue, rising

above a concrete block fence. A second mature Ohio buckeye stands

in front of a house on the south side of University Drive, in the

900 block.  <P>

<P>

Saskatoon's coniferous landscape has long been dominated by

<B>white</B> and <B>Colorado blue spruce</B>. Although neither of

these trees is native to the city, their popularity among early

residents is evident in the many mature examples found within the

city. <P>

<P>

<B>Scots pine</B> is perhaps Saskatoon's most popular pine. The

tree is remarkably tolerant of hot dry summers and long cold

winters. Many excellent representatives of this species can be

observed in the city, but an exceptional example of Scots pine

stands on a front lawn just west of Broadway on 10th street. It's

a tree you cannot miss!  

<P>

Less common pines found in Saskatoon include <B>lodgepole</B>,

<B>ponderosa</B> and <B>Swiss stone pine</B>. Some of our best

examples of rare pines were planted by Dieter Martin in ambitious

designs on the University of Saskatchewan campus. 

<P>

<B>Lodgepole pine</B> is the forest tree of Cypress Hills. It is

found in limited numbers in Saskatoon. Perhaps the best example of

this species is the lone tree standing in the experimental plots

just west of the intersection of 14th street and Preston Avenue.

Several sister trees to this one can be seen further along that

fence line to the west. They may be less obvious but they are no

less spectacular representatives of their species. 

<P>

Possibly the city's largest <B>ponderosa pine</B> is found on the

university campus, in a grouping of Scot's pine, directly west of

the Veterinary Medicine building. With needles almost a foot long,

this tree has a tall straight trunk, and the rounded top that is

characteristic of mature pines in their natural range.  <P>

<P>

<B>Swiss stone pine</B> is another rarity. This attractive, slow

growing, full-to-the-base pine maintains a perfect "christmas tree

shape" if grown in full sunlight. To truly appreciate the softness

of the needles, you simply have to touch them. Of the few excellent

example of this tree I know in Saskatoon, two stand as a matched

pair along the south wall of the PFRA building, across from

Education's parking lot on the campus. The best Swiss stone pine in

the city is possibly the one standing against the south wall of a

house on 33rd Street, approximately a block east of Avenue P. It's

gorgeous! <P>

<P>

While there are certainly many more unusual species of trees that

have been tried and proven successful in Saskatoon, those mentioned

here should offer some good examples of trees we can grow in

Saskatoon. If readers are aware of other unusual mature trees in

Saskatchewan, they may wish to write to Brian Baldwin at the

Department of Horticulture Science, University of Saskatchewan, 51

Campus Drive, Saskatoon, Saskatchewan, S7N 5A8. A further reference

of interest is <I>Saskatchewan Trees of Renown,</I> published by

the Saskatchewan Forestry Association in 1985.<P>

<P>

Other rare trees since publication. <P>

<P>

<I>Celtis occidentalis</I> in Nutana back alley (can't remember

street number) <P>

Butternuts on Saskatchewan and Poplar Crescent.<P>

White pine in Sutherland and a back alley in Simpson Crescent<P>

Norway Spruce near 5 corners and on 14th street. <P>

Salt Tree on 12th<P>

Mayday tree on campus at Little Stone Schoolhouse. <P>

Mugo pine on campus at Murry Building.<P>

<P>

&copy; 1996 Brian Baldwin<br>

