<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Delayed winter injury appearing</TITLE> 
</HEAD><BODY background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<center><img alt="" src="im/line.gif"> 
<h1>Delayed winter injury appearing</center></h1> 
Brian Baldwin
<P> 
The winter of 1995-1996 in Saskatchewan was one of the hardest on trees in the past 
thirty years. While the damage on evergreens had become very 
conspicuous by late winter, many deciduous trees only began to 
show signs of winter damage with the arrival of hot weather.
<P>A wide array of trees are showing winter dieback, but apples are 
among the hardest hit. This is understandable if you consider the 
breeding programs that generated most of our prairie-hardy fruit 
trees. 
<P>None of the excellent large-fruited apples grown in commercial 
orchards have adequate hardiness to survive the average prairie 
winter. On the other hand, the Siberian crabapple is as hardy as 
a rock. Unfortunately, fruit quality on a Siberian crab is also 
distinctly rock-like. Because of this, breeding programs have 
focused on finding a reasonable compromise between the hardiness 
of Siberian crabapples and excellent quality of large-fruited 
cultivars. This means most of our apples are intermediate, with 
fair to good fruit quality and fair to good winter hardiness. 
With only intermediate hardiness, however, fruit trees often show 
some dieback following a very severe winter.  
<P> 
What you are probably seeing:
<P> 
Soon after the first hot days arrived this spring, you may have 
noticed the leaves on your apple (or other tree) becoming stunted 
and wilted. The new leaves on some branches failed to expand to 
full size and many of them may have dried and died right on the 
tree. 
<P> 
The problem is a result of damage to the plant's water conducting 
tissue that occurred last winter. It can be visualized as 
something similar to bursting of frozen water pipes in a 
building. With only a portion of the plant's water conducting 
pipelines still functional, enough moisture would have been 
reaching the top of the plant during the cool spring when the 
leaves were small. Once the leaves began to enlarge, and the 
weather became hot, the damaged vascular system could no longer 
replace water at the rate it was being lost so the top portion of 
the tree began to die.  
<P> 
The best thing to do is keep your tree well watered for the rest 
of the growing season to minimize the drought effects it is 
already feeling. The larger and older the limbs, the better they 
will have handled the winter, so although some of the younger 
branches will probably die completely, new ones will emerge along 
the trunk to replacing them. By the end of summer, those branches 
which are dead and brittle, can be pruned cleanly away to make 
room for the re-growth that will likely follow.
<p> 
&copy; 1996 Brian Baldwin<br> 
<br><a href="index.html"><img align=left border=0 alt="" 
src="im/back.gif">Return to previous index</a><br> 
<br><br>Accesses: 58. 
</body> 
</html>
