<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT24-B02-270</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA002-000015-B012-180</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://pine.usask.ca:80/cofa/departments/hort/hortinfo/trees/winter.html 128.233.59.24 19970101093601 text/html 4961
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: WebSTAR
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html> 
<head> 
<title>Winter Injury</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
Winter Injury</center> 
</h1> 
 
Grant Wood
<p>The winter of 1990 was devastating for many trees and shrubs.  
Especially affected were apple, crabapple, mountain ash and 
cotoneaster.  The Hort Info Service (formerly Garden Line) at the 
University of Saskatchewan received many hundreds of calls 
complaining about deciduous trees and shrubs not leafing out at 
all, or leafing out poorly and then dying.  The cause was winter 
injury.  
<p><B>Types of Winter Injury</B> 
<P>There are many forms of winter injury.  Damage from winter injury 
alone may not result in death of the plant.  In combination with 
other stresses such as drought, insects and disease, however, 
winter injury can prove fatal.  
<p><B>Bud Death:</B>  If a branch is still flexible but flowers and leaves 
are not developing, its buds will likely have been killed by 
winter injury.  Plants not fully hardy in Saskatchewan are most 
susceptible to this damage, but all plants can be affected.  
<p><B>Sunscald:  </B>This occurs most on smooth-barked plants such as 
apple, crabapple, amur cherry and mountain ash.  Damage occurs 
early in the year when the warm spring sun stimulates the flow of 
sap in the trunk.  At night the sap freezes.  This alternating 
thawing and freezing leads to death of the bark usually on the 
south or south west side of the tree.  The movement of nutrients 
from the ground to the brtanches occurs in the bark area.  When 
the bark is killed, movement of nutrients ceases, and death of 
the branches on that side of the tree occurs.  Shading the trunk 
from the warm spring sun usually prevents sunscald.  Physical 
barriers such as burlap or cardboard can be used for this 
purpose.  
<p><B>Tip Dieback:</B>  Any plant that continues to put out new growth well 
into the autumn is susceptible.  Growth that occurs late in the 
year has little chance of hardening off before winter, and 
frequently dies during the winter.  Commonly affected are plants 
not fully hardy for Saskatchewan, as well as raspberries, elders 
and Manchurian elms.  Avoid heavy watering and fertilizing in the 
fall, as these practices may encourage continued growth.  
<p><B>Heartwood Damage:</B>  This damage is visible as browning of the wood 
inside the branches.  It is caused by cold temperatures early in 
the winter, combined with poor snow cover.  Cutting into 
branches, trunks or roots at a 45 degree angle will expose the 
center wood for easier inspection.  
<p>Why does hearwood damage occur?  Normally, water content in 
plants decreases before winter.  In some cases this does not 
happen, and as a result water freezes inside the cells forming 
tiny ice crystals with sharp edges.  These sharp edges puncture 
the cell walls, resulting in death of the cells.  This inhibits 
movement of nutrients and water.  
<p>If only some of the cells are killed, the plant will be able to 
survive in the spring when demands for water and nutrients are 
relatively low.  In the summer, when such demands increase, the 
plant may show signs of delayed winter injury, because its 
damaged cells cannot move enough nutrients and water.  Water may 
be plentiful at this time, but the plant will not be able to take 
it up as quickly as required.  Symptoms of delayed injury include 
browning of leaves, flower and fruit loss.  
<p>If damage of the cells by winter injury is not severe, plants may 
recover completely.  Each successive year the plant will produce 
new cells around the damaged areas, allowing water and nutrients 
to move normally.  
<p><B>Control of winter injury</B> 
<P>Not much can be done to prevent winter injury.  You do not want 
the above-ground parts of the plant to go into winter in a 
succulent state.  Excess moisture may lead to winter injury.  
Therefore, do not water plants in the early fall (September and 
October).  In early November, jsut before the ground freezes, 
water thoroughly.  This will maintain sufficient moisture in the 
root system, but will likely not increase the succulence of the 
above ground parts of the plant.  
<p><B>Pruning:</B>  Branches killed by winter injury will be dry and 
brittle.  These branches should be pruned off in spring.  If the 
branches are still moist and felxible, do not prune themm.  Also, 
do not prune branches that show signs of delayed witner injury; 
they may return to normal growth next year.  
<p>Wood was an instructor with the Department of Horticulture 
Science.  This column is offered as a service by the Extension 
Division and the department of Horticulture Science, University 
of Saskatchewan.   
 
<br> 
