<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Carrots (Part 2)</TITLE>

</HEAD><BODY background="im/backgrnd.gif">

<center><img alt="" src="im/line.gif">

<h1>Carrots (Part 2)</h1>

<a href="carrot-1.html">[previous segment - Part 1]</a></center><br>

Brian Baldwin<P>

<P>

Last week's article listed carrot cultivars which performed well

when tested at the University of Saskatchewan's Department of

Horticulture Science. <P>

<P>

Regardless of cultivar, carrot seed is small and light, yielding

some of the weakest seedlings of the vegetable patch. On clay

soils, poor germination is often a result of the thin crust which

develops on the soil surface following rain. Since radishes

germinate quickly and more strongly, they may be planted with the

carrots to help loosen the soil and mark the row until the slower

carrot seedlings emerge.<P>

<P>

The forking of carrot roots is one of the major problems faced by

Saskatchewan gardeners. Forking can be caused by hard clay soil,

excessive nitrogen, or crowding in the row. Sandy loam is the

ideal soil for carrots, but a heavier clay soil will also yield

nearly perfect roots if it has been well-enough worked so that

all hard clods in the top foot (30 cm) are broken up. The

addition of compost or well-rotted manure is also very helpful.

Manure should only be incorporated the fall prior to planting,

however, because the elevated nitrogen levels of newly-applied

manure will also lead to root forking. <P>

<P>

Thinning is almost always essential. While a crowded carrot row

will exhibit healthy-looking tops, the roots will be thin,

misshapen and often twisted around each other. If you plan to

harvest immature carrots through the summer, thin the row the

first time when the plants are only about an inch (2.5 cm) high,

leaving one plant per inch. As you remove carrots to eat through

the summer, try to increase the spacing of the remaining plants

to three inches (7-8 cm). <P>

<P>

A soil temperature in the range of 15 to 20&#176; produces the

sweetest, most tender and brightly coloured roots. Higher soil

temperatures lead to stubbier roots with a woody texture and

strong flavour. While the total percentage of sugar in a carrot

root does not increase with age, there is a shift from glucose

(simple sugar) to sucrose (table sugar). This causes a gradual

increase in sweetness. Although some carrots are sold as

"coreless," there is no such thing as a carrot root that is core-

free. "Coreless" really only means they have smaller less-

prominent cores than other carrots. Most of the sugar is located

in the outer ring of flesh which circles the core.<P>

<P>

Immature vegetables of all sorts are often sold for a premium

price because of the general impression that "baby" vegetables

are sweeter. With a well-grown carrot this is assumption is not

necessarily true. Packages of "baby-cut" or "mini-cut" carrots

are available in most supermarkets. These are simply mature

carrots which were cut into short pieces and mechanically

whittled down (as though having been put into a large pencil

sharpener) to give them the appearance of "baby" vegetables. This

process chips off some of the sweeter outside flesh which is then

sold for use in dried soup mixes.<P>

<P>

Harvesting of your carrots should be one of the last chores done

in the vegetable garden each fall because the later you leave

them, the sweeter they become. Of course there's a gamble here þ

leave them too long and you may have to shovel snow to find

them.<P>

<P>

Loosen the roots by digging along the row with a spading fork.

The tops should be removed by cutting the leaves at exactly the

point where they meet the root; your cut should not remove actual

root tissue. The roots can then be washed gently in cold water to

remove as much soil as possible without damaging the skin.

Dipping of washed roots into a 5% bleach solution will kill many

of the micro-organisms responsible for in-storage rotting, and

will not adversely affect flavour. Stored in a plastic bag with a

few air holes and held at 0&#176; carrots will maintain excellent

quality for 7 to 9 months. A temperature of 0&#176; maintains

sweetness without causing freezing, and high humidity inside a

plastic bag will maintain crispness. A carrot needs only lose 5%

of its moisture before it becomes rubbery.<P>

<P>

Aster yellows is one of the few diseases that appears in the

carrot patch. A carrot affected with this disease will have

multiple tops, yellowish leaves, and a large number of very small

hair-like root emerging from the shrunken taproot. The disease is

caused by a virus-like particle brought to the plant by a feeding

leafhopper insect. It seldom affects more than one or two carrots

in the patch, so when aster yellows shows up, the best thing to

do is pull that carrot and throw it into the garbage to prevent

further spread. Like almost all plant diseases, aster yellows is

in no way dangerous to humans.<P>

<P>

&copy; 1996 Brian Baldwin<br>

