<html> 
<head> 
<title>Making the Most of Your Garden</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
Making the Most of Your Garden</center> 
</h1> 
 
by ?
<p>Many people grow a garden just to have fresh vegetables for 
summer and fall.  If they grow more vegetables than they can use, 
they give them away or sell them.  But it's good economic and 
nutritional sense to make the most of your garden by storing the 
produce you cannot use in the short term.  The produce you grow 
is probably equal to or better than "store bought" vegetables in 
nutritional value, and of course you have already paid for the 
vegetables in your garden.  With a little further effort, you can 
store them for later use. 
<p>Short-Term Cold Storage 
<P>Produce for use in salads, such as lettuce, spinach, radish, 
green pepper, tomatoes and immature squash (zucchini), are best 
stored in plastic under refrigerated conditions.  They may last 
about 1 month before they start to deteriorate.  
<p>Frozen 
<P>Vegetables such as peas, beans and corn freeze very well, and 
with proper blanching (heat treatment prior to freezing) produce 
a thawed and cooked product very similar to the fresh cooked 
vegetable.  Vegetables such as cauliflower, broccoli and cabbage 
can be stored fresh for few months; however, when blanched and 
frozen these vegetables also keep very well in long-term storage. 
<p>Produce such as tomatoes and green peppers that you plan to use 
for winter's home-cooked meals can also be frozen very easily.  
Choose smaller ripe tomatoes, wash them,  and freeze in plastic 
bags.  Peppers are best washed, cut up, bagged and frozen.  Both 
require no blanching and can be quickly popped from the frozen 
state right into your chilli or spaghetti sauce.  
<p>Warm dry storage (10 - 13C) 
<P>Vegetables in this category include pumpkins and winter squash.  
To store properly these vegetables must be mature and have a hard 
rind.  Pick them before frost, dry at room temperature for a week 
of two and then cool down to near 10C.  These crops also require 
dry conditions, with low relative humidity.  
<p>Cold, dry storage (1C) 
<P>Crops to store under these conditions include onions and 
shallots.  Be sure to dig your onions before heavy frost, and dry 
very thoroughly by hanging them in a shed or garage.  Commercial 
growers dig and tip the onions, then blow hot dry air through 
them to make sure they dry quickly and completely.  Once dry, the 
onions are stored at 1C under very dry conditions.  
<p>Cold, dark and moist storage (2.5C - 4.5C) 
<P>Potatoes store best at cold temperatures, but not colder than 
2.5C.  Colder temperatures cause potatoes to convert starch to 
sugar, resulting in a sweet tasting potato.  
<p>Before putting your potatoes in storage, dig them carefully, 
avoiding injury and store them for about two weeks at cool (13C) 
room temperature under moist conditions.  Do not allow potatoes 
at any time to be stored in the light.  Even a small amount of 
light can cause potatoes to become bitter.  After the two weeks 
at cool room temperature, your tubers are ready to store in the 
dark at 2.5C to 4.5C and under high humidity.  Warmer 
temperatures allow the tubers to sprout and low humidity causes 
dehydration.  
<p>Slightly colder and damp (0C to 2.5C) 
<P>Most root crops such as turnip, carrot, parsnip and beets require 
near freezing temperatures and high relative humidity.  To 
achieve these conditions many people place clean mature 
vegetables in slightly damp peatmoss or plastic bags.  Both work 
well.  
<p>Should you have a common storage area for potatoes and root 
vegetables, store the root crops on the floor, (the colder area) 
and the potatoes higher on a shelf where temperatures will be a 
few of degrees warmer.  
<p>Pamphlet available Home Storage Room for fruits and Vegetables 14 
pages 1478-E Ag. Canada.
<br> 
