<html> 
<head> 
<title>THE SIMPLE YET COMPLEX PUMPKIN</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
THE SIMPLE YET COMPLEX PUMPKIN</center> 
</h1> 
 
by ?
<p>The history of the pumpkin is interesting and potentially 
confusing.  Technically, a pumpkin is a type of winter squash, 
and belongs to the taxa Cucurbita.  There are three species in 
this taxa, all being common garden vegetables.  C. maxima, C. 
moshcata, and C. pepo.The confusion arises because a pumpkin can 
belong to any of these species.  The term pumpkin simply means a 
winter squash that is round in shape, orange in color when 
mature, and has orange flesh.  After years of breeding and 
selecting within the squash family, scientists have selected 
plants with a specific shape and color and called this a 
'pumpkin'.
<p>Knowing the history fo the pumpkin will help explain why there 
can be such a vast difference in the size of the mature fruit.  
It will also help explain why squashes, marrows and pumpkins can 
cross pollinate, and why they kind of taste similar.  Genetically 
there is very little difference between a winter squash, a marrow 
and a pumpkin.
<p>Varieties:  Most gardeners agree that 'pie' or 'sugar' pumpkins 
are far superior for eating than all other types.  Common pie 
varieties for Sask. include Small Sugar, Spirit, and Autumn Gold.  
These produce a small to medium round, squatty, very tasty fruit.  
Slightly larger than these are the jack o'lantern  varieties.  
Although quite edible, they are mainly grown because of their 
elongated shape which is very desirable for halloween.  The 
common varieties in this group include Jack O'Lantern, Half Moon, 
Connecticut Field, Ghost Rider and Tallman.
<p>The 'giant' pumpkins are popular for gardeners who want to see 
just how big a pumpkin can grow.  This group produces a fruit 
with a more coarse textured flesh making it less desirable for 
eating, although they are commonly grown for the canning market.  
Atlantic Giant is the variety brought to fame for being the 
largest pumpkin in the world.  Other giant pumpkin varieties 
include Big Max, and King of Mammoths.  At the opposite end of 
the scale are the mini pumpkins.  This group produces tiny fruit 
that is commonly used for ornamental purposes, but can be used 
for pies.  Sweetie pie, Baby Pam and Little Lantern are the 
common varieties in this group.
<p>Triple Treat is a new variety, boasting the fact that it has a 
very tasty orange flesh, makes a great jack o'lantern, and has 
hulless seeds (naked seed) that can be roasted to make a 
delicious snack.  This sounds like a perfect pumpkin!
<p>Growing:  Pumpkins are a warm season crop, and therefore the soil 
must be fairly warm (16 C) before germination will occur.  They 
are also intolerant of freezing temperatures.  Many gardeners 
start pumpkins indoors in mid May, and transplant outdoor in 
early June.  Make sure to start them in individual peat pots, as 
these plants do not like having their root system disturbed when 
transplanting.  Fertilize with 20-20-20 once before transplanting 
to the garden.
<p>Pumpkins prefer soil with a good supply of organic matter, 
therefore incorporating compost and some fertilizer (11-48-0) 
into the soil is advisable.  Pumpkins also require a location 
with full sunlight.  Most pumpkin varieties are vine producing 
and therefore allow 2 square meters per plant.  Urban gardeners 
seldom have massive gardens and often cannot afford the space 
that pumpkins require.  New on the market are the bush type 
pumpkins.  These varieties require less space and will still give 
a fair yield of pumpkins.
<p>The use of plastic mulches and tunnels have been proven to 
greatly increase the yield of pumpkins.  This technique creates a 
more suitable environment for growth, by increasing the 
temperature of the soil and the air surrounding the plants.  It 
also protects the plants from wind.  Pumpkins have very large 
leaves, up to 50 cm wide, and these can easily be damaged by 
strong winds.  Tunnels must be large (1-2 m wide) to allow for 
the expansion of the plants.
<p>Plants that have large leaves are more prone to water stress, 
because all leaves loose (transpire) water.  For this reason, it 
is very important to water pumpkins well during the growing 
season.  This is especially important during July and August.
<p>Flowering:  Pumpkins are monoecious, that is having male and 
female flowers on the same plant.  In order to get the fruit to 
develop, there must a transfer of pollen from the male flowers to 
the female flowers.  It is very common for pumpkins to develop 
into large plants before they start to flower.  Most gardeners 
want the pumpkins to start to develop starting in early to mid 
July.  Also common is the production of only male flowers, 
therefore there may be lots of flowers on the plant, but no fruit 
is setting.  With time the female flowers will start to form.  If 
bees are not numerous, it may be wise to hand pollinate the 
female flowers.  This is done by gently cutting the male flowers 
off, and dabbing them onto the female flowers.  Female flowers 
can be recognized by the small fruit below the flower.  (See 
diagram)
<p>Many gardeners will allow only one pumpkin to develop on each 
vine.  Instead of dividing the energy into a number of fruits and 
getting small fruit, all the energy goes into one fruit, allowing 
it to get larger and mature properly before frost.  Often the 
tips of the vines are cut off about 1-2 meters past the 
developing fruit.  This also helps direct the energy into the 
fruit.
<p>Harvest:  Pumpkins can be left on the vines until after a frost.  
Providing they have matured somewhat, a light frost will not harm 
the fruit.  Some gardeners cover their pumpkins to protect them 
from frost and to extend the growing season, but if the average 
daily temperature is below 15 C growth will be reduced or stopped 
and the benefits of covering will be questionable.  If the 
tunnels are used again in fall to keep the average daily 
temperature above the critical 15 C, then growth of the pumpkins 
will continue.
<p>The rind of the pumpkin should be hardened in the garden if 
possible, but it can also be done inside the home.  The rind is 
hardened when it is difficult to sink your fingernail into the 
rind.  If this occurs in the garden, then the fruits can be put 
directly into cold storage.  If the rinds are not hardened, the 
pumpkins should be kept at room temperature for a couple of weeks 
until the rinds harden.  When harvesting, try to minimize damage 
to the fruit as this can lead to rotting of the fruit. 
<p>Pumpkins are best stored in a cool (10C) room with average 
humidity.  Under good storage conditions, the pumpkins should 
last for 2 to 3 months.  Ensure there is good air movement around 
the fruits, making sure they do not touch.,  This will help 
reduce losses due to rotting. 
 
<br> 
