<head> 
<title>Reducing the Guesswork in Selecting Vegetables for Your Garden</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
Reducing the Guesswork in Selecting Vegetables for Your Garden</center> 
</h1> 
 
Dave Schmitz
<p>Every spring the new seed catalogues presents an overwhelming 
array of vegetable cultivars (cultivated varieties) .  
Experienced gardeners make their choice based on the previous 
year's performance and add a few cultivars.  The performance of 
any cultivar can vary widely, depending on soil type, growing 
environment and management practices.  City and town gardens tend 
to be sheltered and well watered, while rural gardens tend to be 
more exposed and prone to drought.
<p>Planting of appropriate cultivars is one of the easiest methods 
of improving both yields and quality in your vegetable garden.  
While it is often difficult and expensive to change or improve 
your growing environment, it is usually possible to find 
cultivars that will perform well in your garden.  
<p>Unfortunately, you cannot always tell from seed catalogue 
descriptions if a cultivar will do well in your garden 
environment.  There are very few seed companies actively breeding 
vegetables for the conditions encountered on the northern 
prairies.  Consequently, many new cultivars are not adapted to 
local conditions.
<p>To reduce some of the guesswork involved in vegetable cultivar 
selection for Saskatchewan gardens, the University of 
Saskatchewan's Department of Horticulture Science has an ongoing 
program of cultivar testing.  Each summer the Department tests at 
least eight vegetable crops, comparing newly released cultivars 
with established, standard types.  Tests have been conducted at 
seven different sites to provide a representative sample of 
Saskatchewan growing conditions.  If a recently introduced 
cultivar consistently out-performs the standards, it is then 
recommended for grower use.
<p>The Department's recommendations should be considered a good 
starting point for compiling a list for this year's garden.  Some 
of the cultivars listed may be difficult to obtain, but ask your 
supplier, who may be able to help.
<p>Broccoli:  Packman, Premium Crop, Cruiser and Mariner (large head, 
           good color)
<p>Cabbage:   Polar Green and Princess (early) <BR>
           Lennox and Rio Grand (late storage types, large heads)
<p>Cauliflower:    Snow King (very early, good yields)<BR> 
                Snowball (late-maturing, self-blanching)
<p>Corn:      Buttervee (early, short cobs) <BR>
           Norgold and Seneca Horizon (mid-season, good flavor) <BR>
           Northern Super Sweet (super sweet type) 
<P>Lettuce:   Cos (green romaine, large, high-quality heads) <BR>
           Roseleta (red romaine, small heads with good eye 
           appeal) <BR>
           Great Lakes and Mesa-659 (head lettuce, large heads)
<p>Tomato:    Taxi (medium-sized, yellow fruit) <BR>
           Nova (paste type, good yields) <BR>
           Prairie Pride and Blazer (large slicing type)
<p>Celery:    Starlet (good flavor, not stringy)
<p>Cooking Onions: Hustler, Hynoon and Redman (store well, 
                high yields)
<p>Green Peppers:  Super Set and Marengo (blocky, thick- walled, good 
                for stuffing)
<p>Muskmelon:  Earligold hybrid (large fruit, early, very sweet 
            and aromatic) <BR>
            Earlisweet hybrid (smaller, with good color and 
            flavor)<BR>
<p>Potato:    Norland (early, red skin, high yields, good for 
           boiling) <BR>
           Russet Norkotah (mid-season baker) <BR>
           Yukon Gold (yellow flesh, good flavor)
<p>More detailed reports on the performance of vegetable cultivars 
may be obtained by writing the Horticulture Science Department at 
the University of Saskatchewan, Saskatoon, S7N 0W0
 
<br> 
