<html> 
<head> 
<title>A SUCCESSFUL BACKYARD VEGETABLE-GROWING EXPERIENCE</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
A SUCCESSFUL BACKYARD VEGETABLE-GROWING EXPERIENCE</center> 
</h1> 
 
Tom Ward
<p>The writer is a Departmental Assistant in the Department  
of Horticulture Science at the University of Saskatchewan.   
This column is provided as an extension service by the  
Division of Extension and Community Relations and the  
Department of Horticulture Science, University of  
Saskatchewan.
<p>You are a gardener who likes fresh, home-grown vegetables.  You  
have trouble choosing vegetable varieties.  The vegetables you plant  
often grow well but yield little for the table.  If this profile fits,  
perhaps my article can help you.
<p>Choices That May Disappoint
<p>A number of vegetables do not seem to be very good producers under  
small-scale, backyard conditions, and for this reason it may be best  
not to grow them.
<p>Corn requires a lot of space and is best grown in a block for good  
pollination.  Under backyard conditions it often yields a few small or  
poorly filled cobs, though the plants appear strong and healthy.
<p>Peas can give fair production in the backyard; however, they tend to  
take up a lot of space for the amount produced.  Should you choose to  
grow peas, make sure you provide adequate space by giving them  
climbing support.  Peas often show very poor stands when grown in  
the backyard.  One reason is that the seed planted is often not  
treated for fungus; as a result the seed rots in the ground.  Use  
treated seed.  Seeds that do germinate may be eaten by sparrows.   
The unsuspecting homeowner may believe the seeds did not  
germinate, but in many cases the sparrows, not the seeds, are to  
blame.
<p>Potatoes will usually yield fairly well but, like peas, they take up a  
lot of valuable space in a small garden.  Because potatoes are  
relatively inexpensive, I feel it is best to devote garden space to  
other crops.
<p>Large, sprawling pumpkin and squash also tend to yield poorly,  and  
their competition for light often reduces other vegetable production.   
Choose the bush type pumpkins and squash.
<p>Reliable, Space-saving Vegetables
<p>Lettuce, onion, and radish, when seeded early, can provide you  
with fresh greens that are relatively expensive to purchase and  
therefore economical to grow yourself.  Plant as soon as the soil  
warms up (May 1) in the spring.  Because radish and lettuce do not  
grow well in hot weather, they should be used up by about the first  
of July; any remaining unusable plants should be pulled out and  
discarded.  For a great fall crop, seed the lettuce about July 15 and  
the radish about August 15.  Onions not used for greens can be left to  
mature in storage.
<p>Other valuable space-saving vegetable crops include the miniature,  
dwarf or patio strains of cucumber and tomato.  Check your  
catalogues for a number of choices.
<p>Root crops (carrot, turnip, beet, and parsnip) also tend to be very  
good yielders for the amount of space they require.  Plant those  
species your family likes.  For example, young people usually like  
carrots because they can be picked and eaten out-of-hand.  Plant  
root crops close enough together to cover the space between your  
rows by August 15.
<p>Vegetables to grow in a city garden include:
<p>1. 20 to 30 plants of green, purple, and yellow beans (about 10  
                of each color);
<p>2. 6-m to 12-m rows of carrots almost any variety;
<p>3. 6-m row of beets (cylindrical or rounds);
<p>4. 3-m row of parsnips (short, thick types);
<p>5. 3-m row of turnips (Swedish, Rutabaga);
<p>6. 10 to 15 plants of cucumber (bush or patio type);
<p>7. 10 to 15 plants of tomato (dwarf or patio type);
<p>8. 2 zucchini (one yellow, one green);
<p>9. 1/2 package of radish and lettuce seeded in early spring,  
                with the remainder seeded for the fall crop;
<p>10. 1 package of Dutch sets and 1 package of bunching onions.
<p>All of these vegetables should fit in and grow in a 6-m x 7.5-m  
garden patch.  If you have a large garden, you may wish to consider  
growing cauliflower, cabbage and other vegetables that take more  
space. 
 
<br> 
<a href="index.html"><img align=left border=0 alt="" src="im/back.gif"> 
Return to vegetable index</a><br> 
