<html> 
<head> 
<title>THE EVER POPULAR TOMATO</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
THE EVER POPULAR TOMATO</center> 
</h1> 
 
Grant Wood
<p>Wood is an instructor with the Department of Horticulture 
Science.  This column is provided as an extension service by the 
Division of Extension and Community Relations and the Department 
of Horticulture Science, University of Saskatchewan.
<p>The tomato is one of the most common, if not the most common 
vegetable grown in the home garden.  We receive numerous calls 
each year from competitive homeowners trying to out do their 
neighbours and friends in terms of size, flavour and earliness of 
their tomatoes.  All gardeners should first realize that tomatoes 
have three general types of growth habit; determinate, 
indeterminate and semi-determinate.
<p>Determinate:  varieties of this type are often called bush 
tomatoes.  This is because the terminal (top and end) buds end in 
a flower cluster that produces fruit.  The plant stops growing 
when the terminal flowers develop.  The fruit develops and ripens 
over a short period of time.  These varieties are usually 
early-maturing and produce small plants with generally smaller 
fruit.  Because of their small size, this type of tomato is 
seldom pruned or staked.
<p>Indeterminate:  these varieties are favoured by many homeowners 
because they often produce high-quality, flavourful, desirable 
fruit, even though they are generally later-maturing varieties.  
The growth habit of the plant is indeterminate, meaning that it 
continues to grown and flower until a killing frost.  These are 
tall plants that require staking for best results.  They also 
require pruning for optimum quality.  Flowering and fruiting 
occur over a longer time period.
<p>Semi-Indeterminate:  as the name implies, these varieties have 
characteristics intermediate between the above-mentioned ones.  
They are basically indeterminate in nature.  Staking and pruning 
will improve quality, bit is not essential.  These varieties are 
also very popular with the homeowner, because they can provide a 
fairly early and good-quality yield.
<p>Pruning:  As mentioned above, some varieties respond well to 
pruning.  In general the staking or indeterminate varieties are 
pruned to a single stem, and staked to a height of 1.5-1.8 m (5-6 
feet).  At the base of each leaf, a side shoot will develop.  By 
pinching out all side shoots, you are re-directing the plants' 
energy into the production of the fruit on the main stem and not 
into excess foliage.
<p>Contrary to what you may have heard, flower clusters do not form 
in the leaf axils (where the leaf joins the main stem).  The 
flower clusters are formed directly on the main stems.  They 
arise 'internodally' that is, half way in between the leaves.  
Because of our short growing season, it is recommended that only 
5 or 6 flower clusters per plant are allowed to develop.  Later 
flower clusters should be pinched off, for there is little chance 
they will develop mature fruit before winter.
<p>Some homeowners chose to prune semi-determinate varieties.  This 
process is much like pruning indeterminate varieties in that 
excess side shoots and late flower clusters should be pruned.  
Allow the lowest 4 to 5 side shoots to develop, then remove all 
later side shoots that form.  Remember that the more side shoots 
you leave on, the more energy that will go into the production of 
foliage and the later the harvest will likely be. 
 
<br> 
