<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Vegetable cultivars for Saskatchewan</TITLE>

</HEAD><BODY background="im/backgrnd.gif">

<center><img alt="" src="im/line.gif">

<h1>Vegetable cultivars for Saskatchewan</center></h1>

Rebecca Ehman<P>

<P>

Despite the cool, wet weather conditions, it's that time of year

again; time to select and plant your favourite vegetables for the

garden. If you are curious as to which cultivars will do well in

Saskatchewan conditions, the following list of cultivars may

assist you in your choice.<P>

<P>

<B>Beans</B> should pull easily from the plant, be visible and

pick easily. Pods should not be too large and should have good

colour. Yields should be high and the beans should be straight.

Recommended cultivars: `Belna', `Blenda', `Delinel', `Dandy

Green', and `Rushmore'.<P>

<P>

<B>Broccoli</B> heads should be dense with no interleafing

(leaves growing up through the broccoli head). Stems should be

solid and the colour should be an attractive blue-green.

Recommended cultivars: `Arcadia', `Excelsior', `Patriot',

`Mariner', `Marathon', and `Major'.<P>

<P>

<B>Brussels sprouts</B> should develop uniformly for easy harvest

and be very dense. However, the sprouts should not be too densely

packed on the plant in order to promote easy sprout removal.

Recommended cultivars: `Golfer', `Prince Marvel', and

`Oliver'.<P>

<P>

<B>Cabbage</B> heads will be very dense and in uniform in shape.

Chinese cabbage often bolts early therefore cultivars selected

should resist bolting (flowering) during the growing season.

Recommended cultivars: `Lennox' (white), `Polar Green' (white),

`Masada'(white), `Red Jewel' (red), `Red Acre' (red), `Raven'

(red), `Sombrero' (red), `Jade Pagoda' (Chinese), `Shori'

(Chinese), and `Ming Choi' (Chinese).<P>

<P>

<B>Carrots</B> should be straight and sweet. Forking can be

related to the cultivar and should be avoided. A high yielding,

uniform crop is desired. Recommended cultivars: `Narvora',

`Kamaran', and `A-Plus'.

<P>

<B>Cauliflower</B> heads should be white and smooth. The crop

should ripen uniformly with no hollow stems or interleafing.

Heads should be compact and not oversized. Many self blanching

cultivars are available. Recommended cultivars: `Ardego',

`Arctic', `Serrano', and `Rushmore'.<P>

<P>

<B>Corn</B> þ gardeners are constantly searching for a sweet,

crispy and juicy cob of corn that will mature during the

Saskatchewan growing season. The husk should be easily removed

from the cob and the kernels should be full and evenly coloured.

Recommended cultivars: `Seneca Horizon', `Early Sunshine',

`Seneca Dawn', `Northern Super Sweet', and `Monte Carlo'.<P>

<P>

<B>Ornamental corn</B> cultivars are selected for the ability to

mature in Saskatchewan conditions. Many cultivars do not mature

in Saskatchewan. Some successful cultivars include: `Fiesta',

`Little Jewels', and `Wampum'.<P>

<P>

<B>Cucumbers</B> are selected based on yield. Qualities such as

size are not as important since the grower can select the size

simply by picking when the cucumber has reached the desired

stage. Cucumbers should be straight and uniform in colour.

Recommended cultivars: `Jazzer' (slicing), `Salad Bush'

(slicing), `Morden Early' (pickling), `Homemade Pickles'

(pickling), and `Northern Dawn (pickling).

<P>

<B>Lettuce</B> heads should be spherical and dense. High yields

are important. Recommended cultivars: `Mantilla' (Bibb type),

Summer Bibb (Bibb), and `Green Tower' (Romaine).<P>

<P>

<B>Onions</B> should be large in size and uniform. Pungent

cultivars will also store the longest. Recommended cultivars:

`Oro Grande' (Spanish), `Benchmark' (yellow), `Yula' (yellow),

Sweet Sandwich (yellow), `New Mexico White', and `Mercury' (red).

<P>

<B>Peas</B> should have a sweet flavour. Yields should be high,

pods should be visible and easy to pick. Recommended cultivars:

`Cascadia', `Green Arrow', and `Sugar Snap'.<P>

<P>

<B>Peppers</B> should be selected for their earliness and yields. 

Peppers are picked when walls are firm. Peppers should be of

uniform size and shape. Recommended cultivars: `Banana Supreme'

(banana), `Italian Gourmet' (cubanelle), `Marengo' (green bell),

`Super Set' (green bell), `Staddon's Select' (green bell),

`Inferno' (hot), `Volcano' (hot), and Cayenne Long Slim. <P>

<P>

<B>Pumpkins</B> should have a smooth and consistent shape. The

cultivar should be able to mature in Saskatchewan conditions.

Recommended cultivars: `Baby Bear' (pie type), `Spirit', and `Big

Moon'.<P>

<P>

Growing a <B>rutabaga</B> that is free of root maggots can be a

challenge. `Golden Ball' appears to exhibit some resistance to

root maggots however the yellowish flesh may not be desirable.

Laurentian-Thompson Strain is not maggot resistant but is the

more typical rutabaga colour. Spinach plants should be slow to

bolt. The taste should not be too bitter. Recommended cultivars:

`Spokane', `Bolero', `Springfield', and `Spinnaker'. <P>

<P>

<B>Tomatoes</B> should be high yielding and uniform in size.

Plants should have high yield. Tomatoes are often selected for

earliness and resistance to cracking and bacterial spot.

Recommended cultivars: `Kotlas' (very early), `Roadside Red',

`Summerset VF', and `Johnny's 361'.

<P>

<B>Watermelon</B> crops should be high yielding and produce large

melons. In Saskatchewan, early maturity is extremely important.

The flesh should be sweet and smooth (not gritty) as well as

having good colour. Recommended cultivars: `Sweet Favourite' and

`Gold Baby' (gold flesh).<p>

<p>

Winter squash</B> is selected for yield and ornamental value.

Recommended cultivars: `Cream of the Crop' (acorn), `Nutty Baby'

(buttercup), `Early Butternut' (butternut), `Spaghetti' and

`Turk's Turban' (ornamental).<P>

<P>

<B>Zucchini</B> should be of uniform shape and colour. The yields

should be high. Recommended cultivar: `Super Select'<P>

<P>

For further information on vegetable cultivars or a complete list

of cultivars, please contact Vegetable Cultivar Information,

Department of Horticulture Science, University of Saskatchewan,

51 Campus Drive, Saskatoon, SK, S7N 5A8.<P>

<P>

&copy; 1996 Brian Baldwin<br>

<br><a href="index.html"><img align=left border=0 alt=""

src="im/back.gif">Return to previous index</a><br>

<br><br>Accesses: 46.

