<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Different summer weather favours different

vegetables</TITLE>

</HEAD><BODY background="im/backgrnd.gif">

<center><img alt="" src="im/line.gif">

<h1>Different summer weather favours different vegetables

</center></h1>

Brian Baldwin<P>

<P>

When you can awaken on a mid-May morning to the sight of the

garden covered yet again with snow, it's easy enough to wonder

just how successful the upcoming growing season is going to be.

<P>

<P>

Vegetables crops are divided into warm-season and cool-season

types, with the performance of the two classes being greatly

influenced by the type of summer weather we experience. <P>

<P>

Cool-season vegetables thrive and produce a bountiful crop during

relatively cool prairie summers. If the present weather trends

continue (and I'm hoping to be proven wrong), these will be our

best performers this summer. Most cool-season crops can withstand

a few degrees of frost, but are intolerant of extremely hot

weather. When it's too hot their quality tends to decline as they

toughen, lose sweetness or split. Onions, peas, carrots,

radishes, beets, lettuce, spinach, potatoes and all members of

the cabbage clan are cool season vegetables.<P>

<P>

Warm-season vegetables are all extremely tender to frost and

require a long hot growing season. With these types, the hotter

the summer the better they will do, provided there receive enough

moisture. Because they need a long hot growing season, these

plants may be started as transplants, or be grown with row covers

and ground mulches that trap heat and artificially extend the

growing season. Corn, tomatoes, cucumbers, peppers, melons,

eggplant and squash are some of our most common warm-season

vegetables. <P>

<P>

When should you plant your vegetable garden? Soil temperature is

the main factor to consider. In cool soil, germination and

seedling growth will be very slow. Slow growth during germination

exposes the young plants to a long period of time when soil-borne

disease organisms can attack and kill them. Seeds which are

planted later, into warmer soil will often emerge quickly enough

to catch those that have been sitting in cold soil. <P>

<P>

How do you know when the soil is warm enough to plant your

vegetable garden? Kick off your shoes and socks and give the

garden a quick raking after supper some night. If the soil is

warm enough that you can work comfortably in bare feet, it's

probably warm enough to provide your vegetable seedlings the

quick start they'll need.<P>

<P>

&copy; 1996 Brian Baldwin<br>

<br><a href="index.html"><img align=left border=0 alt=""

src="im/back.gif">Return to previous index</a><br>

<br><br>Accesses: 49.

