Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html> 
<head> 
<title>Fairy Ring Biology and Control</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
Fairy Ring Biology and Control</center> 
</h1> 
 
Canadex - Agriculture Canada, December 1978<BR>
Horticulture Crops <BR>
Turf <BR>
Plant Diseases  273.630 <BR>
J. Drew Smith
<p>     BIOLOGY
<p>          Fairy rings caused by Marasmius oreades are most severe 
in light soils of low fertility and inadequate moisture. AIthough 
other rings may be caused by different soil-inhabiting fungi those 
due to M. oreades particularly, pose a major problem in irrigated 
lawn turf throughout Canada. 
 <P>         Initial infestations probably derive from infected, 
imported soil or from the spores produced in large numbers by the 
fruiting bodies. When the spores germinate, the mycelium at first 
produced (monokaryotic) grows fairly slowly. After pairing, the 
resultant mycelium (dikaryotic) is more vigorous. Fairy ring 
mycelium is of the latter kind. Growth through the soil is in a 
radial direction. It probably takes two or more seasons for rings 
to become identifiable in herbage. Rings have, so far, been 
difficult to start in turf. When young, rings of fruits may occur 
without the characteristic zones. 
<P>          Characteristic zones of mature rings follow:
<p>     -    An outer zone wilere the grass is a lush green. 
<P>     -    A middle zcne which may have dead grass and the 
tan-colored fruiting caps of the fungus, usually around the outer 
edge. 
<P>     -    An inner zone of stimulated lush grass growth. 
<P>     -    An inner circle where grass growth is similar to that 
     outside the ring. 
<P>     The mycelium of" the fungus, recognizable as white threads, 
which gives the soil a musty smell, may be deep seated and dense in 
the soil, especially towards the outside of the bare zone. This 
mycelium makes tlle soil very difficult to wet, rendering it 
practically impossible to eradicate rings with solutions of 
fungicides in water. During the growing season the mycelium extends 
into the otlter green ring, where it stimulates plant growth. It is 
so abundant in the bare zone that it prevents water penetration and 
"droughts out" the plants. The mycelium in the inner green zone 
decomposes, liberating plant nutrients which stimulate lush plant 
growth there. Fruiting (cap production) may occur from spring to 
fall, being most abundant in warm weather when the soil is moist. 
The amount of soil moisture greatly affects the rate of progress 
and persistence of rings. This is probably related to the 
establishment and maintenance of soil microorganisms antagonistic 
to the fairy ring fungus.
<p>Control 
<P>     One of the main problems in control is in determining whether 
rings are still present after treatment. Rings may be ephemeral or 
apparently die out for a season only to return the next. Control 
measures can be divided into those which suppress ring symptoms and 
those which actually eradicate the fungus.
<p>SUPPRESSION
<p>(1)  Applications of nitrogen, and ample irrigation during the 
growing season may mask the symptoms, but will not eliminate the 
problem. Rings are usuaily most severe, and common, where adequate 
fertilization and sufficient water are lacking. Excessive organic 
fertilizer may aggravate the problem.
<p>(2)  Spike the turf with a garden fork to 25 cm depth at 10 to 15 
cm centres starting 30 cm outside the furthest extent of the outer 
green zone and work inwards to include the bare zone. Motor driven 
aerifiers do not penetrate deeply enough for this purpose. Make up 
a solution of 1 : 10,000 (0.01%) of a turf wetting agent (Aquatrol, 
etc.) or, at a pinch, a mild liquid dish detergent (Joy, Lux, 
Palmolive etc.*Caution -do not use chlorine bleach, borax or 
similar materials) and water the spiked portion of the ring with 
this until the spike holes will take no more, Soak the spiked area 
with a hose or hydrogun daily, for 4- to 8 weeks using plain water. 
If rings are inadequately treated they may fragment and start new 
centres of infection. If this treatment is done thoroughly it may 
not only suppress but also eradicate fairy rings. Forks and 
hydrogun should be sterilized in a 5% solution of domestic 
hypochlorite bleach before being used on clean areas of lawn, 
othewise they may spread infection. There is also a danger that 
rented lawn maintenance equipment, eg. scarifiers and aeriflers, 
may spread the fungus.
<p>(3)  Some commercially available lawn fungicides applied as 
solutions or water suspensions to the turf surface may reduce cap 
production, but few of those so far tested have much effect on the 
mycelium in the soil. Collecting the fruits as they appear may 
reduce chances of furtiler infection of the lawn by reducing spore 
production. This is not feasible on extensive areas.
<p>ERADICATION
<p>(1)  Effective control of small isolated rings may be achieved with 
the same volatile fungicides used for the treatment of soil for 
horticultural purposes. The prescribed precautions should be taken 
in their use. The partial sterilization of the soil by these 
materials results in the development of a fungal soil flora 
antagonistic to M. oreades. The soil is treated "in situ" which 
solves the problem of its disposal. Cultivation of fairy ring soil 
facilitates effective fungicide action, For domestic use, a 
fungicide solution, sufficient for 10m2 of soil, consists of:
<p>     2.5 litres of 40% formaldehyde solution (formalin). 
     200 ml of wetting agent (turf wetting agent or dish washing 
     detergent).  50 litres of water.
<p>     During warm weather in late spring, summer or early fall, when 
the fungus is active, strip the turf with a sharp flat spade, from 
30 cm outside the outer green ring to inside the bare zone. Put 
this turf on a polyethylene tarp, taking care not to spill any on 
the "clean" lawn. The turf may be composted away from the lawn site 
to eliminate the fairy ring fungus. Break up the soil of the ring 
with a digging fork to its full depth starting round the 
circumference. Sterilize tools and footwear with the fungicide. Use 
a sprinkling can to apply the fungicide to the forked soil, keeping 
it off the remaining turf which would be damaged by it. Cover the 
treated soil with weighted down polyethylene sheets to seal in the 
vapour for 7 to 10 days, then remove the covers and stir the soil 
carefully with a digging fork. Leave for 2 to 3 weeks to eliminate 
the formaldehyde gas. Level the site with soil from adjacent flower 
borders or vegetable plot. Imported topsoil may be infected. The 
site may then be seeded. 
<P>(2)  M. oreades rings will die out when they encounter paths, 
roadways, walls, flower borders or other cultivated soil areas. 
Therefore, put additional pathways or flower borders across their 
progression.
<p>(3)  Another promising method of eradication is based on the fact 
(a) that when two M. oreades rings contact tlley eliminate each 
other and (b) that normal soil contains other fungi and bacteria 
antagonistic to M. oreades. This is a biological control method in 
which no fungicides are used. The method is most effective when 
ring incidence is high. Two slightly different techniques have been 
tried: (a) Using a heavy duty rotary cultivator the infested turf 
is scuffed off, preferably in fall, and the site left to allow the 
snow melt water to soften the soil below. The following spring the 
soil is cultivated with a rotary cultivator several times to mix 
the mycelium-infested soil as thoroughly as possible with the 
surrounding soil. The area is levelled, packed and sown with grass 
seed or returfed with turf from a ring-free source. If there are 
weed grasses such as couch or bromegrass in the original turf, use 
a suitable non-residual total herbicide to kill all vegelation 
before scuffing up the turf. In the alternative method (b) the 
original turf is stripped off with a turf cutter and the soil below 
thoroughly mixed with a rotary cultivator as above before being 
reseeded or returfed. Whatever method of eradication is employed 
the chances of reinfection will be greatly reduced by good turf 
management Including adequate fertilization and irrigating to 
ensure that the soil is wetted to a depth of 15 cm, Shallow 
watering is particularly to be avoided.  
 
<br> 
