<DOCNO>WT24-B02-305</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA002-000015-B014-267</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://pine.usask.ca:80/cofa/departments/hort/hortinfo/yards/lawn-fer.html 128.233.59.24 19970101094429 text/html 5121
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: WebSTAR
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Fertilizing The Lawn</TITLE>

</HEAD><BODY background="im/backgrnd.gif">

<center><img alt="" src="im/line.gif">

<h1>Fertilizing The Lawn</center></h1>

Russell Friesen<P>

<P>

Mid-May is the time to fertilize the lawn. At the University of

Saskatchewan's Horticulture Information Service, we recommend

that lawns be fertilized three times during the growing season,

with applications being made about six weeks apart. Good target

dates to mark on your calendar are: May 15, July 1, and August

15. It is not recommended to fertilize much earlier than mid-May,

because the lush new growth that follows fertilization is highly

susceptible to freezing damage, and may easily be damaged by a

late spring frost. Similarly, fertilizing much later than mid-

August will encourage lush growth late into the fall, when the

grass should be slowing its growth and preparing for winter.<P>

<P>

It is sometimes surprising that people who have used fertilizers

for years are not always fully informed on what the numbers on

the fertilizer bag actually mean. From left to right, the three

numbers indicate the relative amount of nitrogen, phosphorus and

potash (N-P-K) contained in the fertilizer. The higher the number

the greater the amount of the particular nutrients. Most lawn

fertilizers will have a high first number, indicating a high

level of nitrogen. High nitrogen levels are ideal for lawn growth

because nitrogen is the nutrient which encourages the production

of lush green leafy growth. A good lawn fertilizer may or may not

contain phosphorous. This nutrient encourages healthy roots,

shoots and the production of flowers. Too high a level of

phosphorous, can encourage the lawn to produce seed heads.

Fertilizers which are well suited for use on the prairies often

contain no Potash (indicated by the last number being a zero).

Although potash plays a number of vital roles in the proper

health of plants, most prairie soils are already well supplied

with this nutrient. Evidence for this is most conspicuous in the

fact that our potash mines supply this element to many parts of

the world. Fertilizers purchased from retail outlets will often

contain some potash. While this additional potash will not damage

your plants, you should remember that you are paying good money

for something that you are just going to throw away. Some of the

most useful, and least expensive fertilizer formulations for lawn

use are: 26-13-0, 21-0-0, 26-0-0, 34-0-0.<P>

<P>

Any of the above fertilizers can be applied at a rate of 2.0-2.5

kg per 100 square meters of lawn. To assure a more even

distribution, and avoid dark green streaks, it is a good idea to

apply half the allotted portion of fertilizer in a north-to-south

direction, and then apply the other half in an east-to-west

direction. Your lawn should be dry when fertilizer is applied so

that the granules fall right through the leaves to the top of the

soil surface. If a wet lawn is fertilized, granules will stick to

wet leaf surfaces, resulting in burning. Immediately after

applying fertilizer, the lawn should be watered for about an

hour. This will dissolve the granules and begin to carry the

nutrients to the roots. <P>

<P>

In spring, it is often recommended that a fertilizer containing

phosphorous be applied. Since phosphorous remains available in

the soil for a year or more after it is applied, only one

application with phosphorous is usually recommended per year.

Once phosphorous has been applied, your lawn will probably only

require additional nitrogen for the rest of that season. <P>

<P>

Specialized fertilizers such as liquids are absorbed directly be

the leaf blade of the plant. These fertilizers appear to be

highly effective because they provide an almost instant green-up

following application. The effect is short-lived, however, with

additional fertilizations being required again two or three weeks

later. Fertilizers containing herbicides are also popular with

home owners since these products appear to accomplish two goals

with half the work. The main problem with these products is that

they pose the serious problem of inadvertent damage to non-target

plants growing in or adjacent to the lawn. The price of

convenience may well be your prized birch tree, your favourite

flower bed or this year's vegetables! It is both more economical

and more effective to fertilize your lawn to satisfy its

nutritional needs, and spot-treat individual weeds with a small

quantity of the appropriate herbicide. If you do choose to use

the duel purpose products, be certain to read and follow label

safety precautions. Remember that you are applying a large dose

of pesticide over a large area. This can cause serious harm to

plants, animals and people who may come in contact with it. <P>

<P>

&copy; 1995 Russell Friesen<br>

