<html> 
<head> 
<title>PRACTICAL TURF AREAS</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
PRACTICAL TURF AREAS</center> 
</h1> 
 
Lawns have traditionally been among the highest landscape 
consumers of water.  They also take up the largest amount of 
space in our landscape.  This is very much a North American 
phenomena associated with our concept of space and coupled with 
lack of the population pressure which is so prevalent in other 
parts of the world.
<p>A.  Lawn Use
<p>We should take a second look at the amount of turf we have and 
consider what we actually do with it.  How much of it is actually 
USED AS TURF?  Actually walked on, sat on, played on, or 
sensuously felt between one' toes?  How much of the lawn area is 
simply there by default because we can't think of what else "to 
do with it"?  How much does your family really need and how much 
of it could be substituted by ground-covers or shrubs which take 
less maintenance and less water?  Begin by eliminating narrow 
strips, odd corners, and out-of-the-way areas which are grass 
simply because other alternatives have never come to mind.
<p>Then look at your main lawn areas.  How often do you actually use 
your front lawn (lie down on it)?  Could a curving hard surface 
surrounded by drought-tolerant ground covers or ornamental 
grasses substitute for the lawn/  Ornamental grasses will provide 
interesting color, texture, and form.  Thy may be used as 
individual clumps, as a ground cover, or as background.  Ribbon 
grass, blue fescue, Skinner's golden brome, and blue lyme grass 
are a few which have proven hardy on the Prairies.  (Would you 
miss the mowing and fertilizing?)  What about the lawn in the 
back yard - could its size be reduced with little effect on 
family activities?
<p>B.  Grass Cultivars
<p>Although "miracle" dryland grasses are sometimes suggested as 
substituted for the recommended mixture of Kentucky blue grass 
and creeping red fescue, many of these are bunch grasses and not 
very comfortable.  If your intent is to lie down or walk on your 
lawn, you would be better sticking with the recommended "ammenity 
turf grasses".
<p>Even drought-tolerant grasses will need regular watering until 
established (two seasons) as well as occasional water during 
periods of drought.  Otherwise they will become thin, unthrifty 
and infested with weeds.
<p>"The key to drought-tolerance, regardless of variety chosen, is 
deep root development.  This is brought about by dep and thorough 
soil preparation and deep, infrequent watering."  One of the 
problems with turf irrigation systems is that they typically 
apply more water per hour than can be absorbed into the turf 
grass and soil.  The result is run-off onto the sidewalks and 
streets.  Time irrigation so that there is water for 20 minutes 
every hour for 3 or 4 hours or until the depth of most soil 
desired has been reached.
<p>Grasses which are recommended for Saskatchewan lawns with no 
irrigation include:
<p>100% Russian wild rye <BR>
100% streambank wheat grass <BR>
20% creeping red fescue and 80% Russian wild rye <BR>
20% creeping red fescue and 80% stream bank wheat<BR>
<p>The seeding rate for all of these would be 2.5 kg/100 m2
<p>Streambank wheat grass (<I>Agropyron riparium</I>) is a hardy and 
drought tolerant bunch grass.
<p>Russian wild rye (<I>Elymus junceus</I>) is native to Siberia, very 
hardy and drought tolerant.  IT is a bunch grass and 
uncomfortable to sit or lie on.
<p>Fairway crested wheatgrass (<I>Agropyron cristatum</I>) is a very hardy 
and drought-resistant bunch grass which greens up readily in the 
spring, becomes dormant in times of drought, and regreens with 
moisture.
<p>Perennial rye grass (<I>Lolium perenne</I>) is a bunch grass with poor 
cold hardiness which is not recommended for permanent turf in 
Saskatchewan.
<p>C.  Mowing
<p>Water use reduction can also be achieved by mowing grass at a 
slight higher level but less often.  The taller grass will shade 
and cool the soil and therefore reduce the amount of water lost 
by evaporation.  As well, taller grass will grow at a slower rte, 
therefore requiring less water (and less mowing).
<p>APPROPRIATE PLANT SELECTION
<p>A.  Xeric Plants
<p>Xeric plants or xerophytes are plants which use little water.  
These plants may be indigenous or native to the area (such as 
saskatoons or buffaloberry), or they may be introduced from a 
similar climatic zone from another part of the world (like 
caragana which is native to Siberia).  Plants which take in and 
utilize little water often have the added advantage of using 
little nutrients as well.  Xerophytes may be trees and shrubs, 
perennials, annuals, grasses, or bulbs.
<p>Bulbs may be termed "seasonal drought evaders' in that most of 
their growth is in the spring and fall when it is cool and moist, 
and they are dormant over the hot, dry summer when little 
moisture is available.  Groundcovers, a common substitute for 
lawns, may be in the form of herbaceous perennials, ornamental 
grasses, or deciduous or coniferous shrubs.
<p>B.  How They Work
<p>Drought resistance is the capacity of a plant to withstand 
periods of dryness.  This ca be achieved in a number of ways:  
(1)  improved water uptake from the soil, (2) reduced loss of 
water, and (3) better water storage.
<p>Water from the soil enters the plant through the tiny root hairs 
at the end of the roots.  Some drought-resistant plants have 
extensive root systems with a large active surface area which is 
capable of rapid growth into the deeper subsoil strata where 
moisture may be available.  The seedlings of some trees and 
shrubs adapted to drier areas (such as bur oak) may have tap 
roots many times longer than the shoots which enable them to 
obtain subsoil moisture.  Native grasses are also very deep 
rooted.  Alternatively, some of these plants have shallow, 
fibrous roots systems which simply act as a sponge, immediate 
absorbing any rainfall which might fall on the soil surface.
<p>Water loss from the surface of the plant through transpiration 
may also be reduced.  The stomata are the openings in the 
epidermal layer of the leaves through which water leaves the 
plant in the process of evaporation called transpiration.  In 
drought-resistant plants the stomata may be sunk deep into the 
epidermal layer or be of a smaller size, thus reducing water 
loss.  These plants may also have mechanisms for triggering early 
closure of the stomata.  In some confiers there is a spongy wax 
plug in the stomata which reduced transpiration to a third of 
what it would otherwise be
<p>The cuticle is a waxy layer made up of cutin which covers the 
surface of the leaves, reducing water loss.  This si usually 
thicker in  drought-tolerant plants.
<p>Leaves and stems may sometimes be covered with microscopic hairs 
called trichomes which shade the plant while at the same time 
reducing wind velocity.
<p>This protective covering of hair is called pubescence and appears 
grey to the naked eye.  Many xerophytes are pubescent:  yucca, 
Artemisia 'Silver Mound',Russian olive, wolf willow.
<p>Many plants will fold or roll up their leaves in items of 
drought, again reducing the surface area from which water can 
evaporate.  Others are termed "cushion" plants and are shaped so 
that they physically catch all available water.  Saxifrage are an 
example.
<p>Plants which are extremely succulent with thick, waxy leaves have 
an extra capacity for storing water which they can use in times 
of drought - the camel's hump of the plant world.  Hens and 
chicks and sedum are examples of drought survival through 
succulence.  Other plants have storage organs in their root 
systems (bulbs and tubers) which allows them to live through 
periods of drought.
<p>Xerophytic plants are those plants which are so adapted as to 
survive on natural precipitation or with minimal irrigation.  In 
Saskatchewan, the average annual precipitation is 33 centimeters.  
By utilizing drought-tolerant plant  material the home gardener 
is taking out an insurance policy on the survival of his/her 
plants in times of drought or water supply limitations.
<p>For specific plant material recommended for the concept of 
xeriscape see the Manual of Drought Tolerant Plant Material.
<p>USE OF MULCHES
<p>A mulch is any material, organic or inorganic, applied t the soil 
surface in a layer at least eight to ten centimeters deep.  For 
the purposes of xeriscape, organic mulches are preferred to 
inorganic mulches.  Inorganic mulches include stone or gravel, 
plastic, and woven landscape cloth.
<p>A.  The Inorganic
<p>Stone and gravel collect heat, cause temperature increases and 
therefore increase cooling costs of the home and irrigation costs 
to the landscape during summer.  (Plants do the opposite, shading 
and cooling).  Weed seeds are easily blown into gravel or stone 
and soon establish themselves.  Another problem sometimes 
associated with gravel on the Prairies is their high pH which may 
cause an iron deficiency or chlorosis in susceptible woody 
plants.  
<p>Woven fabrics and fiber mats exclude weeds and yet allow for 
water and air exchange.  But if used under an organic mulch they 
prevent it from enriching the soil as it decomposes.
<p>Plastic excludes air and water essential to plant growth.  It 
breaks down over time or if exposed to sunlight.  It should not 
be used under organic mulches.
<p>For all of the above reasons it is generally recommended that 
organic rather than inorganic mulches be utilized in the 
xeriscape.  It is also well to remember that, "Achieving water 
conservation by substituting plastic and gravel for living plants 
will not add enjoyment to your landscape or value to your home" 
(James Feucht, 1987).
<p>B.  Benefits of Organic Mulches
<p>The benefits of an organic mulch are many, but the most important 
is the reduction of water loss by reducing surface evaporation.  
It is estimated that as much as 75% of rain falling on bare soil 
may be lost to plants through evaporation or run-off.
<p>Organic mulches will also prevent annual weed growth by 
establishing a physical barrier so that weed seeds blown in will 
have difficulty establishing themselves.  Likewise, seeds already 
within the soil will have difficulty penetrating upwards through 
the mulch.  (Perennial weeds are not usually controlled by mulch 
and should be removed prior to applying the mulch layer)
<p>An organic mulch will also insulate the soil surface against 
temperature fluctuations.  In summer, a layer of mulch will cool 
the soil making it a more hospitable environment for root growth 
and beneficial micro-organisms.  During spring and fall the mulch 
will prevent alternate freeing and thawing and associated 
"heaving" and plant damage.
<p>Because of its "cushioning' effect, a mulch lessons soil 
compaction due to human foot traffic while weeding or working in 
flower, tree or shrub, or groundcover beds - or the vegetable 
garden.
<p>It prevents mud or rain splash on flowers and fruit (such as 
strawberries).  Mulches can also prevent wind and water erosion 
of soil.
<p>As they break down and decay, organic mulches add to the soil 
fertility and improve its structure.
<p>Mulches have design benefits as well.  Many as aesthetically 
pleasing and provide visual interest through texture and color.  
At the same time they function to unify a planting or bed.  This 
is especially true when the bed if first planted and the plant 
material is small and occupies only a small proportion of the 
space it will eventually use when mature.
<p>C.  Types of Mulches
<p>Some of the characteristics to look for in a mulch:  a substance 
which will not blow away (except near Kindersley where everything 
blows); one which looks pleasing (or can be "top-dressed" with a 
thin layer of something else which will look nice); is easy to 
apply; non-toxic; and will not act as a wick and draw moisture 
from the soil.  If its free, cheap, or readily available, so much 
the better.
<p>Among the mulches commonly used in the Prairies are:
<p>Peat moss - the coarser grade is better than fine grades; apply 
when already moistened or it will blow away; excellent water 
retention but if allowed to dry out may act as a "wick" and draw 
moisture from the soil.
<p>Grass clippings - excellent if applied 4 inches thick; certainly 
prevents annual weed growth and evaporation; may not look 
pleasing and therefore need to be cosmetically :top-dressed" with 
peat moss.  If sprayed with 2,4-D, allow 30 days for herbicide to 
biodegrade before using.
<p>Compost/manure - should be very well rotted and free of weed 
seeds.
<p>Leaves - may be too coarse unless first pulverized; composted 
leaves may be better.
<p>Wood chips - may be too coarse for fine perennials but excellent 
for tree-shrub borders; very long lasting and effective.
<p>Commercial bark chips - expensive but fairly long lasting; better 
with trees and shrubs than perennials; attractive.
<p>Hay and straw - coarse for ornamentals; better used for fruit and 
vegetables; may contain weed seeds
<p>Evergreen needles and cones - nature's own; attractive, 
long-lasting, effective, and free.
<p>APPROPRIATE MAINTENANCE
<p>Maintenance of a xeriscape is not much different from the normal 
maintenance which Prairie gardeners have done for decades.  The 
emphasis may be slightly different in that the major function is 
reduced water consumption.  Therefore, weeding and irrigation 
system maintenance and monitoring are high on the list.  So is 
the annual renewal of the mulch layer as needed.  Because 
drought-tolerant plant material also tend to use less nutrients, 
fertilizing is usually not a high priority in xeriscape 
maintenance.
<p>Water, water everwhere, 
But not as much as you think.
<p>Williams is a specialist in horticulture with the Extension 
Division. 
 
<br> 
