<html> 
<head> 
<title>SNOW MOLD</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
SNOW MOLD</center> 
</h1> 
 
Knud Mortenson, Plant Pathology Specialist, SDA, Regina
<p>     Snow mold is very common on lawns in Saskatchewan and sometimes it causes 
severe damage.  One or several of the following fungi are involved in the 
disease:  Typhula spp., Fusarium nivale, Sclerotinia borealis, non-sclerotial 
low temperature basidiomycete (LTB), and sclerotial low temperature 
basidiomycete (SLTB).
<p>SYMPTOMS
<p>     These fungi cause damage in the fall and in spring when snow covers the 
grass.  The damage will likely occur in shaded or wet areas where the snow is 
slow to melt, but it is especially severe in years when a heavy and persistent 
snow falls on unfrozen ground.  Symptoms show up in early spring with the 
appearance of irregular patches of dead turf.  Also just at snow melt a mass of 
white to grey or pink cottony fungal growth will often be seen on the affected 
areas.
<p>LIFE CYCLE
<p>     These fungi only grow at temperatures around the freezing point and they 
survive over summer as spores, as 1 to 7 mm. black or tan colored resting 
bodies (sclerotia) or as mycelium on dead grass.  These resting structures can 
be spread to other areas by mowing and by foot traffic.
<p>CONTROL
<p>WHEN DAMAGE IS PRESENT 
  <P>   Snow mold rarely kills the grass completely but affected areas may take 
most of the summer to recover.  Once the damage is evident, one can only apply 
adequate fertilizer and water, and wait for recovery.  If these areas do not 
recover, they should be resown.
<p>TO PREVENT DAMAGE 
 <P>    In order to lessen snow mold damage several preventative measures can be 
taken.  It is however, a good practice to grow the more disease resistant, 
winter hardy Kentucky bluegrass.
<p>1.  CULTURAL METHODS 
<P>a)  Do not overfertilize the lawn in late summer and continue mowing in the 
fall until growth stops.  Remove tree leaves from the lawn in the fall. 
<P>b)  As compaction of snow favors snow mold, discourage the use of parts of the 
lawn as a walkway during the winter. 
<P>c)  In the spring, spread snow drifts as this speeds up melting and discourages 
snow mold growth.
<p>CHEMICAL CONTROL
<p>     In the spring when symptoms appear it is pointless to apply fungicides. 
For prevention however, fungicides should be applied in the fall.  WHEN USING 
CHEMICAL CONTROL, FOLLOW INSTRUCTIONS ON THE LABEL FOR PRECAUTIONS AND FOR 
RECOMMENDED RATES OF APPLICATION [also check current registrations]. 
<P>     Make at least one application of a fungicide just before permanent snow 
cover (about the end of October).  If possible another previous application at 
the end of September will give better control. 
<P>     Registered fungicides for control of snow mold are: 
<P>Anilazine (Dyrene, Proturf FIII) <BR>
Benomyl (Benlate, Tersan 1991) <BR>
Chloroneb (Tersan-Sp, Demosan, Proturf FII) <BR>
Chlorothalonil (Bravo, Daconil 2878, Termil) <BR>
Mercury compounds (Calo-Clor, Merfusan, Mersil, PMA-10) <BR>
Quintozene (Brassicol, PCNB, Proturf FFII, Terraclor, Tritisan) <BR>
Thiophenate-methyl (Easout, NF-44, Cercobin-M, Topsin M. Proturf systemic) <BR>
Thiram (Planto Turf Fungicide). 
 <P>    Benomyl is the only fungicide registered for domestic use, the others are 
registered for commercial use only.  (Doubtful if still registered.) 
<P>     Some of these products are sold at seed and garden supply centres in local 
stores or through mail order catalogue companies. 
 
<br> 
