<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Snow Mold</TITLE>

</HEAD><BODY background="im/backgrnd.gif">

<center><img alt="" src="im/line.gif">

<h1>Snow Mold</center></h1>

Brian Baldwin<P>

<P>

Snow mold presents at least a minor problem on Saskatchewan lawns

during most springs, and this spring seems to be no exception.

<P>

<P>

Symptoms of snow mold are fairly obvious, with affected lawns

showing distinct dead patches in spring. These can be about the

size of a dinner plate or much larger, and if you look closely

just as the snow is melting you should also be able to see a very

fine matting of grey or pink cottony fungal growth. The fungi

which cause the trouble are always present in lawns, but they

only become active and begin to attack the grass when conditions

are moist and the temperature hovers around 0&#176;C for a number

of weeks. Since these are exactly the conditions you find under

melting snow, a cool spring which favours a long period of snow

melt favours the disease. <P>

<P>

The grass is seldom killed outright, but if the patches created

are quite large it may take most of the growing season for some

areas to recover. <P>

<P>

If you've discovered irregular patches of dead grass in your lawn

this spring, rake up any debris on these sites, and throw it

away. Normal fertilizer and water through the growing is probably

all that is needed to encourage rapid regrowth. If no regrowth

has occurred by mid-summer, bare areas can be re-seeded to help

them along.<P>

<P>

Some simple guidelines will help reduce your chances of getting

snow mold. <P>

<P>

1. Do not fertilizer any later than August 15. Late fertilizer

application maintains the grass tissues in a soft and succulent

condition which is much more susceptible to attack from

fungus.<P>

<P>

2. Continue regular mowing in fall to maintain the grass at its

normal growing height. Long grass that is matted beneath the snow

is much more susceptible. For the same reason, leaves should be

raked and removed in fall. <P>

<P>

3. Avoid compacting snow on the lawn. If you shovel snow from the

sidewalks into large piles on the lawn, spread these piles out in

the early spring to speed their melting. <P>

<P>

Preventative fungicides are used only by commercial turfgrass

managers who are licensed to apply these chemicals. In home

gardens, fungicides should not be used to prevent snow mold. <P>

<P>

A reminder about birch trees. Application of cygon for prevention

of birch leaf miner should be made just as the leaves are

unfolding and expanding up to size. Usually this is around May

15, but we're about ten to fourteen days late this spring, so you

may wish to hold off a little bit longer. The late spring will

also have slowed down the development of the insects.



<p>&copy; 1996 Brian Baldwin<br>

<br><a href="index.html"><img align=left border=0 alt=""

src="im/back.gif">Return to previous index</a><br>

<br><br>Accesses: 50.

