</DOCHDR>
<html> 
<head> 
<title>SPRING CARE OF LAWNS</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
SPRING CARE OF LAWNS</center> 
</h1> 
 
As the days lengthen and become warmer, homeowners are tempted to 
start working around the yard.  Remember however, that in 
Saskatchewan, our spring weather is far from stable.  Therefore 
don't be too anxious to start yard work yet.
<p>Spring is a good time of year to do lawn work.  Operations such 
as dethatching and aerating are usually best done in the spring 
just as the grass starts growing.  There is generally no need to 
do both operations every year.  In many yards, these operations 
are done every second or third year.
<p>Dethatching:  The "thatch layer" in the lawn consists of decaying 
grass layer on the soil surface.  A certain amount of thatch (1 
cm) is very desirable.  It cools the grass crowns, helps 
eliminate moisture loss due to evaporation, cushions the crowns 
against wear and tear, and protects the crowns in fall, winter 
and spring.  For these reasons, we recommend leaving all or most 
of the grass clippings on the lawn during the year.  Make sure 
the lawn is cut frequently to avoid long clippings, as they do 
not produce good thatch.
<p>Excessively deep thatch (more than 1-1 1/4 cm) can cause 
problems.  A deep layer holds moisture, and roots tend to form in 
this layer.  When dry, hot weather or unusually cold weather 
occurs, these tender roots are more likely to be damaged.  
<p>"Dethatching," the process of removing the thatch, is best done 
in spring as growth commences, but not too early, because the 
thatch protects the crowns from the freezing spring temperatures.  
If done too late (when the lawn is fully green and actively 
growing) it puts undue stress on the lawn.  Experience is your 
best guide.
<p>You can buy a dethatching attachment for the home lawn mower, or 
rent a dethatching machines.  Dethatching can be stressful for 
new or weak lawns.  In such cases, cut the lawn to 2 1/2 cm and 
rake it well afterwards, but do not dethatch.
<p>Aeration:  Lawns on clay soil and those that get a lot of foot 
traffic tend to become quite compacted.  Only small amounts of 
oxygen can enter the hardened soil; deprived of sufficient 
oxygen, the roots and crowns can be damaged.  Compacted soils are 
also much harder to water, as runoff usually occurs before enough 
water is applied.  Aerating the lawn will help correct this 
problem.
<p>Machines that remove plugs of soil and deposit them on the soil 
surface are available for rent. You can also rent machines that 
slice into the soil  The plug-removal machines tend to work best.  
Two passes, first north and south and second east and west, will 
usually ensure good aeration.  Some homeowners prefer to remove 
the plugs of soil that are deposited on the lawn surface, but 
this is not necessary. The plugs will break down quickly after a 
few waterings.  Unlike dethatching, aeration can be done almost 
any time of the year but it is usually done in the spring.  
<p>Aeration is only necessary for lawns subject to compaction.  
Lawns that are especially susceptible to compaction should be 
aerated annually.  
<p>Fertilization:  Do not fertilize until mid May.  If the lawn was 
fertilized in mid-August the previous year, there will be 
sufficient carryover of nutrients to result in a green lawn this 
spring.  [but if they did not fertilizer in mid-Aug, are you 
suggesting they do fertilize earlier than mid-May or are you 
saying that, well, hell, their lawn may not be as green as they 
might like it to be but they should learn to live with it because 
in the long run the lawn will be healthier?  
Excessively early fertilizing will encourage early lush growth 
that is susceptible to spring frost.
<p>Grant Wood 
 
<br> 
