<html> 
<head> 
<title>Day-Neutral Strawberries</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
Day-Neutral Strawberries</center> 
</h1> 
 
Tom Ward
<p>You may have heard about a new kind of strawberry called 
day-neutrals.  The traditional everbearing types fruit the first 
two weeks of July.  They produce a small amount of fruit again in 
late August.  Like the everbearing types, the day neutrals fruit 
in early July but their fall fruiting period starts earlier in 
August than the everbearers, and carries on until frost stops the 
fruiting.  They also yield much more than the everbearers and the 
fruit size and quality are better.
<p>You should plant day-neutral strawberries in early May in double 
rows about 12" apart and 6" between the double row.  Early 
planting is necessary to get them well established for good fall 
production.  It is usually best to remove the first flower buds 
that appear after planting or their production will check the 
plants' development.
<p>Although may people  expect to get only l year's production out 
of these plants, they can be overwintered.  The best method of 
overwintering is to cover the plants with a clear plastic about 
October 10 and an 8" straw cover about November 1 to the 15.  Be 
sure there is wind protection to keep the straw from blowing 
away.  Leave the straw on as late as you can in the spring.  This 
will delay flowering and therefore reduce flower damage from 
frosts.  You must take the straw off once growth starts.  Dig 
down under the straw.  If growth is starting, you will see new 
leaves, which will be pale in color.  
<p>The two cultivars we are recommending for Saskatchewan are Hecker 
and Fern.  Both yield well but Fern produces larger fruit. In the 
past day-neutrals have been rather difficult to obtain.  Check 
with your local horticultural suppliers and seed catalogues.  It 
is likely that a good supply of day-neutals will be available in 
Saskatchewan for the 1992 planting season.  They are usually 
supplied as bare-root crowns which should be planted as soon as 
possible after you have purchased them.
<p>A fact sheet on strawberries is available from Garden Line.  
<p>Ward is a staff member with the Department of Horticulture 
Science.  This column is provided as a service by the Extension 
Division and the Department of Horticulture Science, University 
of Saskatchewan. 
 
<br> 
