<head> 
<title>How can I Protect my Fruit Trees from the Prairie Winter?</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
How can I Protect my Fruit Trees from the Prairie Winter?</center> 
</h1> 
 
Tom Ward
<p>Some trees are simply cannot live through our hot, dry summers 
and our cold, dry winters.  The McIntosh apple, for example does 
well in the warmers parts of British Columbia but cannot be grown 
here successfully.  
<p>Many trees that do have the genetic capacity to withstand the 
harsh prairie climate still require protection to survive without 
serious injury. One such tree is the Hyer 12 apple, which  will 
take -40 if it "hardens down" sufficiently before winter.  In its 
hardened-down state, the tree is effectively in a state of 
no-growth hybernation that serves to protect it from severe cold.
<p>  If proper protective measures are not taken, however, even the 
hardy Hyer 12 won't make it.  
<p>Tree injury or death can result from many, many different causes 
or conditions, and can be further complicated by previous care or 
weather conditions.  Your tree may die in the winter because you 
over-fertilized it in the summer.  It may die in the winter 
because you under- or over-watered it in the summer.  It may die 
in the summer because of extreme cold injury the tree suffered in 
the winter.  In short, it can die from injuries or conditions 
that occured much ealier, so that it is often difficult to 
determine the cause of death.
<p>How can you protect that genetically hardy tree?
<p>1.  Keep the tree in top condition. <BR>
* Do not allow insects to damage the tree.  If the tree is 
damaged, regrowth will occur in the area of the injuries.  If 
this happens in the fall, the tree will harden down late, and 
therefore go into winter susceptible to injury.  <BR>
* Control or prevent disease. <BR>
* Avoid stray chemical damage<BR>
<p>2.  Locate the tree in a sheltered location. <BR>
* Reduced wind means the tree has less breakage and drying out, 
and more favorable summer and winter temperatures.
<p>3.  Water throughout the growing season if rain is not plentiful 
and water the tree well about the middle of October to reduce 
winter desiccation (drying out).
<p>4.  Fertilize sparingly in the spring and only if the tree is 
pale and shows poor growth.  Never fertilize young trees.
<p>5.  Pruning in the spring and usually in small amounts will 
ensure enough vigor and regrowth.
<p>6.  Prevent mice, rabbits, porcupine and deer from damaging the 
tree throughout the year.
<p>If you have taken care of your hardy tree in the above manner 
your tree will grow a small amount each year.  It will remain 
healthy and harden down each fall.  It should produce fruit most 
years and be the envy of the neighbourhood.
<p>Protect Your Fruit Plants in the Fall
<p>Fruit trees on the prairies are particularly vulnerable to 
sunscald damage during early spring.  Sunscald usually occurs 
during March while the roots of the trees are still solidly 
frozen.  The bright sun shining on the bark of the trees can warm 
the tissues to a temperature of 20C.  The warmed tissues become 
active but cannot take the night time temperature of -20C.  As a 
result the cells die and the bark becomes discolored.  Damage 
occurs on the south and west sides of the trees.  Some trees die 
from their injury, others struggle along and do poorly.
<p>You can help protect your tree from sunscald by using white 
plastic tree guards which reflect the heat of the sun, so that 
the tree remains inactive until the real spring weather comes.  
These devices are available from garden suppliers and are usually 
put on in late fall.
<p>Other measures against sunscald that may be taken in the fall 
include painting the south and west sides of the trunk with white 
latex, or leaning boards against the tree to help shade the 
trunk.  People have also used aluminum foil (shiny side out) to 
shade the trunk.  The foil can be removed in the spring and 
reused next year.
<p>Damage from Mice
<p>The control of sunscald using the foil or the tree guards is also 
effective against another winter problem:  Mice.  Mice often 
become very hungry when winter snow hides their food, and young 
tree bark offers a tasty alternative to grain or weed seeds.  The 
tree guards or foil prevent the mice from stripping the bark 
away.  Another good control is a heavy hardware wire mesh, which 
prevents mice from getting to the trunk of the tree.  Mice 
usually eat only below the snow line and do not climb over the 
mesh.
<p>In orchards, cultural practices related to growing fruit trees 
can also influence the abundance of mice and hence mice damage.  
Uncut grass or other cover left in the area will encourage mice.  
In contrast, low cut grass and clean cultivation will discourage 
mice, reducing or eliminating the problem.  Commercial growers 
often use a bait station to kill mice.  A bait station should 
allow mice in to eat the bait, but be both child and pet proof.
<p>Mice can be very destructive.  In bad years they can kill out 
most of an orchard.  Repairing mouse damage involves grafting, 
which is difficult and costly, but damaged fruit trees will die 
if untreated.
<p>Bush fruits such as currants and saskatoons, even if severely 
damaged by mice, will usually not die.  They are difficult to 
repair and are usually left to send up new shoots from below the 
damaged area.  Fruiting, however, will not occur until several 
years after the damage has been done.
<p>Rabbits and Other Animals
<p>Mice damage can occur in the city or farm; deer and rabbit damage 
usually occurs only in the country.  Deer and rabbits can be 
controlled by a high (1.8 m.6 ft) mesh fence.  The fence must be 
high enough to keep deer from jumping in and with small enough 
sections to prevent rabbits from entering.
<p>Deer can be a problem throughout the year, feeding on leaves and 
new growth in the summer and shortening back the ends of branches 
in the winter.  Deer have also been known to damage strawberries 
in the winter by eating the leaves of the plants.  To get at the 
leaves, they remove the straw cover, which provides needed 
insulation; without adequate straw cover, the plants can also be 
damaged by winter cold.
<p>Rabbits usually damage only trees and bush fruits in the winter.  
They may remove twigs or strip off bark from the trunk or 
branches.  It is very time-consuming to repair bark that has been 
stripped.
<p>You can discourage deer and rabbits from entering your orchard by 
spreading blood meal.  The meal offends the animals and they tend 
to stay away.  When food supplies are low, the meal does not 
deter the animals.  
<p>Watch for porcupines.  They may attack your trees in the winter 
months.  They tend to feed on the bark of trees, and the fruit 
tree is one of their favorites.  There is little you can do 
except remove porcupines from the are.  Otherwise they will 
return nightly and eventually kill the trees.
<p>Ward is a staff member with the Department of Horticulture 
Science.  This column is offered as a service by the Extension 
Division and the Department of Horticulture Science, University 
of Saskatchewan.
<p>Fall Care of Fruit Trees:  Don'ts and Do's
<p>DON'T:  Prune your fruit trees in the fall.  Pruning in the late 
summer or fall may encourage the trees to continue growing.  They 
must stop growing for some time in order to harden-off before 
winter.  If they do not have this hardening-off period, they will 
not become fully winter-hardy, and winter injury will occur.
<p>DO:  All major pruning in the spring.  Only minor pruning should 
be done in other seasons.
<p>DON'T:  Water shallowly, or the water may not penetrate down to 
the root zone.
<p>DO:  Water your trees throughout the growing season whenever 
Nature fails to do so.  In dry times, you should water the trees 
about once every two weeks.  To determine that you have watered 
sufficiently, place a pan or dish under the tree and water until 
the container accumulates 5-8 cm (2-3 in.) of water.  This amount 
will water the trees deeply down into the root zone, whereas less 
water will only dampen the soil close to the surface.  Make sure 
that your tree is watered well into mid-October so that the tree 
goes into the winter with a good moisture supply.
<p>DON'T:  Fertilize your tree under most circumstances.  Most fruit 
trees in our soils do not require fertilizer.  Do not apply 
fertilizer after July 1.  Never fertilize young trees.  If 
fertilized, they will take longer to mature and bear fruit.  If 
fertilized in the fall, young trees in particular will lack 
winter-hardiness because they will continue to grow.
<p>DO:  Fertilize your fruit trees only if they show pale leaves and 
weak growth.  If these signs occur, a small amount (1 cup) of a 
balanced fertilized (e.g., 16-20-0) for a larger tree will 
usually help it along.  Use less for a smaller tree.
<p>DON'T:  Ignore insect infestations, or you will wind up with no 
leaves or fruit on your trees.
<p>DO:  Control insects.  Did you have canker worms on your trees 
last spring?  If you did, fall is the time to get some tanglefoot 
on that tree to prevent those female moths from going to the top 
of the tree, where they lay the eggs that hatch into next year's 
worms.  Did you have tent caterpillars on your tree last spring?  
Watch for their egg bands on the twigs in the fall.  Remove any 
bands, and you will have few or no problems next spring.
<p>DON'T:  Leave your fruit on the tree too long before picking, or 
they may rot.
<p>DO:  Pick pears before mature and allow them to ripen in the 
house at cool room temperature.  Cut into a pear and check the 
seed colour.  Pick pears at the first hint of browning of the 
seeds.  Apples can be picked when each seed is about half brown.  
Once picked, they can be stored at room temperature for a few 
days and then used.  If you want to store your apples for a 
longer period, pick them when you notice the first hint of brown 
in the seeds.  Place newly picked apples for storage in the 
refrigerator and reduce wilting by placing them in a perforated 
plastic bag.
<p>Plums are tricky, and often fall from the tree just before they 
are ripe.  They should be picked when they are a little on the 
green side and allowed to ripen at cool room temperatures.
<p>DON'T:  Remove the spurs (little short twigs) when you pick 
apples.  The fruit for subsequent years is produced on these 
spurs.
<p>DO:  Leave the spurs on the tree for next year's growth.
<p>Ward is a staff member with the Department of Horticulture 
Science.  This column is provided as a service by the Extension 
Division and the Department of Horticulture Science, University 
of Saskatchewan. 
 
<br> 
