<head> 
<title>Picking Northern Berries</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
Picking Northern Berries</center> 
</h1> 
 
Tom Ward
<p>You can pick wild fruit in most areas of Saskatchewan, but the 
north offers more choices.  In the bush areas you will find 
saskatoons, wild raspberries, chokecherries, pincherries, 
blueberries, wild strawberries, buffaloberries, low bush 
cranberries, high bush cranberries and lingonberries.  It makes 
the mouth water just to list them!  
<p>Many wild fruits will yield more in an area close to cultivation 
or where trees have recently been removed.  In such areas, there 
is less competition, and the wild fruits tend to produce more 
abundantly.  
<p>Wild raspberries produce fruit in August   Use them in your 
favorite desserts just as you would their "tame" or domesticated 
counterparts.  
<p>Many good wild stands of saskatoons are found in the province.  
Depending on the area, climate and type of saskatoon, the fruit 
may mature any time between the beginning of July to early 
August.  The saskatoon is very popular in pies and can be made 
into syrup, jelly, jam, and wine.  It can be used fresh, or 
frozen and used when required.  
<p>Chokecherries and pincherries are usually not ready until late 
August or September.  Both make top-quality jelly and pancake 
syrup.  Chokecherries make a dark, rich wine many people find 
tasty.  
<p>Highbush cranberries usually grow in damp, boggy areas.  They 
produce a tasty fruit with a very pungent odour.  Many people use 
them to make a sauce to accompany wild meat, but in both taste 
and appearance they are very different from the cranberries used 
with your Christmas turkey.  You will either like this fruit a 
lot or quickly dismiss it.  
<p>Low bush (or ground) cranberries and lingonberries are very 
similar in appearance and taste.  They both grow in the north 
only, and are found in boggy areas.  Treat them as you would the 
cranberries you use for Christmas.  These wild fruits, however, 
have a more pleasant taste than the Christmas cranberries.  Some 
specialty food stores sell lingonberry preserves that have been 
imported from Scandinavian countries, where the berries are a 
favorite food of ptarmigans.  If a ptarmigan is shot it keeps for 
several weeks without spoiling because lingonberries have natural 
preservative properties.  Our lingonberries are equal in quality 
to the imported fruit, but we cannot guarantee that the berries 
will preserve people as well as they preserve birds.  Watch for 
these fruits to ripen towards the end of August.  
<p>Another fruit found only in the north is the wild blueberry.  
Like low bush cranberries, they thrive on the acid soils found in 
the north.  In good years they are very productive; you may pick 
them yourself or buy them from local pickers who make some of 
their income from the wild harvest.  Wild blueberries can be 
easily frozen in plastic bags.  They have a whole variety uses, 
in preserves, jellies, pies, muffins, etc.  
<p>You may come upon the wild strawberry this summer.  It is usually 
ready to pick from early July to late in the summer and sometimes 
right into the frost period.  They are very small and take a long 
time to fill up a basket.  However, they are very flavourful and 
make an excellent fruit fresh or preserved.  
<p>Ward is a staff member with the Department of Horticulture 
Science.  This column is offered as a service by the Extension 
Division and the Department of Horticulture Science, University 
of Saskatchewan. 
 
<br> 
