<html> 
<head> 
<title>Plums, Cherries and Cherry-Plums for Saskatchewan</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
Plums, Cherries and Cherry-Plums for Saskatchewan</center> 
</h1> 
 
Published by the Division of Extension and Community Relations <BR>
Publication N. 546,Ag Dex 210/30
<p>By Dr. C. Stushnoff 
<p>     Over the years, numerous culitvars (varieties) of tree fruits 
have been developed and made available to prairie gardeners. Some 
have withstood the rigors of our climate while others have perished 
from cold damage or fireblight and many have been discarded because 
of poor quality. Even though the perfect cultivars of cherries, 
plums or other mernbers of the genus Prunus may not yet have been 
developed for the prairies, there are a number with excellent 
qualities for special purposes such as jams, jellies, sauces, pies 
and fruit juice. The purpose of this fact sheet is to provide a 
brief description of recommended Prunus cultivars and to illustrate 
their unique virtues and shortcomings.
<p>     Cold Hardiness, micro-environment and site selection
<p>     Most of the high quality, large fruited plums and cherries 
with good handling properties, such as the Italian prune plums and 
Bing Cherries, will not survive in Saskatchewan because they lack 
resistance to severe winter low temperatures. In general, minus 
40C is about the coldest-mid winter temperature even the hardiest 
(wild North American) plums will endure without some damage; 
therefore, it is imperative to plant only hardy, recommended 
cultivars In some years the recommended cultivar may show varying 
degrees of damage and kill back even at temperatures of -30C. 
     Micro-environment can play an important role in avoidlng 
winter damage to fruit trees. Sometimes the choice of a planting 
site is limited, but if there is a choice the following should be 
considered: 
<P>     (1) Trees on a north or east-facing slope will
<p>    escape sunscald damage compared to a south or west-facing 
slope, and indications are that these trees bloom later, thus 
escaping spring frosts
<p>     (2) A shelterbelt on all sides will help prevent wind damage, 
improve pollination and help build up heat units to mature fruit in 
the fall. 
 <P>    (3) Fruit trees grow best in a loam or clay loam subsoil with 
at least one meter of soil which has no salinity or evidence of a 
high water table. Grey layers in the subsoil within one meter of 
the soii surface are not suitable for fruit trees. Plums and 
cherries do well on sandy loam soils; however, these low 
water-holding soils will need to have irrigation to supplement the 
natural rainfall in many Saskatchewan summers. 
    <P> (4) A planting site on an upland ridge or plateau adjacent to 
a low area is preferable to a flat low area. A low spot is often a 
frost pocket, and often with poor subsoil drainage, and should be 
avoided.
<p>     Pollination
<p>     Most plums grown on the prairies, whether originated from 
native plums or hybrids, are self incompatibie - that is, will not 
pollinate themselves - and will not set a crop of fruit unless a 
pollinator cuitivar which overlaps in bloom time is planted close 
by or grafted into the same tree. 
     The hybrid plums listed are also poorly compatible as a group 
and may not set any amount of fruit without the presence of one of 
the native plums, such as Bounty or Dandy. Much work needs to be 
done to determine pollination compatability among the plums. 
Seedlings of sandcherry, Nanking cherry and Mongolian cherry will 
set fruit provided you have two plants of the species. The 
sandcherry x plum hybrids are best provided with a sandcherry as a 
pollinator.
<p>     Plums
<p>     Native: Prunus nigra (plums native to North America) 
  <P>        BOUNTY - Dark red, egg-shaped fruit, approximately 3 8 cm 
in size, Skin tough and astrigent, flesh juicy, tender, 
orange-yellow, sour. Ripen midAugust. Good for preserves. Tree is 
upright, robust, hardy and productive. 
  <P>        DANDY - Approximately 3.8 cm in size, yellow blushed with 
red, thin tender skin, mild, juicy, yellow flesh. Ripens in late 
August. Good for preserves. Tree is spreading, very hardy, and 
productive.
<p>     Japanese Plums: Prunus salicina (burgany, red or yellow plums 
native to the orient) 
 <P>    IVANOVKA - Approximately 3.8 cm, green with reddish purple or 
bluish mottling, yellow to pink flesh, good out-of-hand or 
preserved. 
 <P>    PTITSIN SELECTIONS - #5, #9, #10 - Approximately 3-8 cm. 
Greenish-yellow. Good to eat fresh or preserved. 
  <P>   BROOKRED, BROOKGOLD, and FOFONOFF -Three varieties not fully 
tested.
<p>     Hybrid Plums: Hybrids resulting from crosses between P. nigra 
and P.salicina 
<P>     PATTERSON PRIDE - Up to 5 cm, deep red in color, and of 
excellent quality. Patterson Pride matures in mid-September. Good 
fresh or cooked. It is a small tree with a weeping habit. 
<P>     PEMBINA - Up to 5 cm, a red plum, superior in quality. Good 
fresh or preserved. 
<P>     ACME, ELITE and PRAIRIE - Up to 5 cm, dark red, of good 
qualitY, low astringency, mature in early to mld September.
<p>     Hybrid Cherry Plums: Hybrids resulting from crosses between 
prunus besseyi and other plum species 
<P>     MANOR - Dark, almost black fruit. Ripens early and is of good 
quality. Good out-of-hand or preserved. Bush form. 
<P>     OPATA - Bluish-green with green flesh. The fruit is sweet, of 
good quality, and has a small pit- Bush form, 
<P>     There are many more named selections with flesh colors ranging 
through yellow, green and red, to black. Some of these are: Beta, 
Convoy, Dura, Epsilon, Kapa, New Oka, and Sapa. Although most are 
shrubs, some are attractive small trees with ornamental value.
<p>     Nanking: Prunus tomentosa (native to China) 
<P>     This large shrub is useful as an ornamental, producing 
dime-sized, red, low acid cherries. Good out-of-hand as well as for 
jams and jeilies. Use seedlings from the Northern limit strain 
which have been proven to be most suitable for the prairies.
<p>     Mogolian: Prunus fruiticosa (native to Siberia and 
N.E.contenental Europe). 
<P>     This suckering shrub, which can be used as an ornamental, 
produces dime-sized, sour cherries excellent for pies, sauces and 
preserving. Use selected seedlings.
<p>     Sandcherry: Prunus besseyi (native to North American Prairies) 
     Small black fruit for jelly or iam. Selections of superior 
strains are offered by various nurseries.
<p>Pincherry - Prunus pennsylvanica (native to North America) 
<P>     JUMPING POUND - and its seedlings grown as 
an ornamental or for jelly.
<p>Chokecherry (Canada Cherry): Prunus virginiana (native to North 
America).  Grown as an ornamental or for syrup and jetly.
<p>     Apricots: Prunus armeniaca siberica 
     PRAIRIE GOLD; SUNRISE; BROOKCOT; WESTCOT 
 
<br> 
