<head> 
<title>SASKATOON VARIETIES</title> 
</head> 
<body background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1>  
<center> 
<img alt="" src="im/line.gif">    
SASKATOON VARIETIES</center> 
</h1> 
 
Sara Williams
<p>      All of the varieties of saskatoons cultivated at the present 
time are based on selections from the wild:  someone walking in 
the bush noticed a plant that was quite superior to its neighbors 
in fruit production, dug up a sucker, and brought it home.  None 
of these varieties has been the result of deliberate crosses or 
part of a plant breeding program.
<p>      None of the present varieties have ever been tested together 
at one location for comparisons of fruit size, average yield per 
bush, uniformity of ripening, ease of culture, or disease 
resistance.
<p>      Some growers favor growing more than one selection in a 
commercial orchard.  This assumes different levels of disease 
resistance among varieties, thus hopefully avoiding total crop 
failure in case of a severe outbreak.
<p>      At the present time, based on fruit trials at Brooks, 
Alberta, major producers appear to be Northline, Smoky, and 
Thiessen.  Overall size and flavor was superior in Thiessen.
<p>      SMOKY
<p>      Smoky is the most common cultivar planted for commercial 
production.  In 1916, W.D. Albright set up a shelterbelt made up 
of saskatoon suckers and root pieces from various parts of his 
farm in Alberta's Peace River country.  His farm later became the 
experimental sub-station of Beaverlodge.  He noticed marked 
differences among the plants in the shelterbelt and eventually 
named one which he considered superior 'Smoky' after the Smoky 
River drainage basin.  Selected in the 1940's, 'Smoky' was 
released in 1952.
<p>      The fruit is large, one cm in diameter, fleshy, round, 
sweet, and mild-flavored.  It is very productive and has 
consistent production from year to year.  The berries are borne 
in medium-sized clusters.  It flowers in the mid-range of bloom, 
making it reasonably resistant to spring frost.
<p>      The bushes are spreading, and up to eight feet in height.  
It has a suckering habit which enables it to quickly form a 
hedge.  This characteristic makes Smoky very suited to commercial 
production and mechanical harvesting.
<p>      Eighty-five per cent of first generation seedlings of Smoky 
were reported to be so similar to the parent as to be considered 
identical.  Successive generations show increasing variability 
and should not be considered for seedlings.
<p>      PEMBINA 
      Pembina was also selected in the Peace River country of 
Alberta.  Named after the Pembina River valley, near Barrhead, it 
was the selection of John Wallace, then head gardener in charge 
of the saskatoon project at Beaverlodge Research Station.  It was 
selected in 1928 and formally released in 1952.  Smoky and 
Pembina were the first two saskatoon cultivars officially named 
and released in Canada.
<p>      Pembina produces large berries which are fleshy, slightly 
oval, full-flavored, and sweet.  The fruit is produced in long 
clusters.  Compared with smoky, is it better flavored but less 
sweet, and slightly less productive.
<p>      The bush itself is vigorous but more upright and taller (up 
to 10 feet).  Under normal conditions it produced very few root 
sprouts.  It has become a favorite of the home gardener because 
it does not tend to sucker much under home garden conditions.  
For this same reasons, up until recently it has remained in short 
supply because propagation was mainly by root suckers which 
proved to be a slower means of propagation.
<p>      HONEYWOOD
<p>      Honeywood was introduced by A.J. (Bert) Porter of 
Parkside, Saskatchewan, in 1973.  It produces large fruit in 
large fruit clusters with good flavor and good productivity.  
Because it blooms late, it is more likely to avoid frost damage.
<p>      THIESSEN
<p>      Thiessen was found growing near Langham, Saskatchewan, and 
introduced by George Krahn in 1976.  It is perhaps the largest 
fruiting cultivar (1.5 cm) with good flavor and productivity.  
However, it blooms early which puts it more at risk to frost 
damage.
<p>      MOONLAKE
<p>      Moonlake was found near Moon Lake, Saskatchewan, and 
introduced by George Krahn in 1974.  The fruit is medium in size 
and of good flavor.  It bears erratically with moderate to low 
production.
<p>      NORTHLINE
<p>      Northline is very similar to Pembina but with a slightly 
more spreading bush form.  It was introduced by the Beaverlodge 
Nursery.  It is 1.5 m in height and suckers freely.  The berries 
are large and it is considered very productive.
<p>      ALTAGLOW
<p>      Another selection from the Peace River country, Altaglow was 
introduced in 1935 by Brooks Research Station in Alberta.  It was 
released in 1960.  It is considered an ornamental rather than a 
fruiting variety.  It has an erect columnar form and brilliant 
fall color.  With a height of eight feet, its foliage is retained 
into fall, changing from dark green to deep purple, bright red, 
and yellow.  It is self-sterile and white-fruited.  But is 
readily pollinated by blue-fruited saskatoons.
<p>Williams is a specialist in horticulture with the Extension 
Division.  This column is provided as a service by the Extension 
Division and the Department of Horticulture Science, University 
of Saskatchewan. 
 
<br> 
