</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Growing Our Wild Cherries</TITLE> 
</HEAD><BODY background="im/backgrnd.gif"> 
<h1><center><img alt="" src="im/line.gif"> 
Growing Our Wild Cherries</h1> </center>

<P>The pin cherry and choke cherry may not be as well known as 
the "Saskatoon", but for most of us in the prairies the names 
bring to mind the unforgettable tastes of pin cherry jelly and 
choke cherry syrup.  
<P>    When our pioneer ancestors first came to the prairies they 
were unable to grow or access the fruits they had previously used 
in making jelly, syrups and wines.  It is no surprise that they 
turned to the native fruits for their winter preserves.  They 
harvested the same fruits which the native peoples had been 
harvesting from the prairies for centuries.  History tells us 
that the North American Indians used dried and ground choke 
cherry fruit in soups, stews and pemmican.  There are no recorded 
uses of pin cherry fruit, but it's certain that they were used in 
a similar manner as the choke cherry.  The wood of the choke 
cherry was used in the construction of poles, bows, arrows and 
skewers.  The bark of both trees was boiled to make a medicinal 
tea, although this remedy is not recommended because of the high 
levels of cyanide in the bark. 
<P>   In the last few years there have been increasing concerns 
over wild fruit harvest due to the prevalence of pesticide 
residues in fruit harvested in close proximity to agricultural 
land.  Also our urban lifestyles make it more difficult to find 
the time to search for, and harvest, wild fruit.  These factors 
have contributed to the increasing interest in growing native 
fruits in the backyard garden.  With the increasing availability 
of choke cherry and pin cherry selections from the wild, there 
are a fair number of good fruiting and ornamental varieties 
available to the prairie gardener.  Both species are fairly easy 
to grow, requiring very little maintenance.  They contribute to 
the beauty of the garden landscape by their beautiful spring 
bloom and their attractive fall leaf colour.  While at the same 
time producing a large amount of good quality fruit suitable for 
home processing.
<P>      The pin cherry (<I>Prunus pensylvanica</I>) and the choke 
cherry (<I>Prunus virginiana</I>) are two closely related wild 
cherries belonging to the rose family (Rosaceae).  They both can 
be found growing over a large part of North America, from as far 
north as the Yukon and the North West Territories and as far 
south as Virginia, California and New Mexico.  They are  found 
across the continent from coast to coast.  Both species like full 
sun and can be found growing in the open along fence lines, 
bluffs, ravines, stream-banks and along the borders of wooded 
areas.  The pin cherry is often the first species to recolonize 
woodland areas disturbed by logging or fires.  They can be found 
growing on a large range of soil types, from rich, moist well- 
drained soils to dry, sandy, infertile soils.  The choke cherry 
has a medium to low salt tolerance, and doesn't grow well on arid 
soils.  The salt tolerance of the pin cherry is not known but it 
is assumed to be somewhat similar to that of the choke cherry.
 <P>    The pin cherry is one of the first native trees to flower in 
the spring.  It begins to flower from the middle to the end of 
May.  Choke cherry flowers about one to two weeks later.  Both 
species have  showy, sweet smelling, white flowers about 10mm 
(1/2") in diameter.  Pin cherry flowers are borne in clusters of 
5 to 7 flowers arising from a single point, similar to that of 
the cultivated cherries.  The choke cherry produces its flowers 
in an elongated cluster of 20-40 flowers.  Full bloom lasts for 
about a week in both wild cherries. 
  <P>   Cross pollination is necessary for good fruit set in both 
the pin cherry and the choke cherry.  The planting of at least 
two different varieties will be required to ensure good fruit 
set.
 <P>      Botanically the fruit of the choke cherry and the pin cherry 
are like that of our domesticated cherries, containing a single 
stone. 
 <P>      Pin cherry fruit is red, ranging in size from 5 to 10mm 
(1/4-1/2") depending on the selection.  Bigger fruit tend to have 
more flesh making them more desirable for processing.  The fruit 
is tart but has a lovely flavour when made into jelly or syrup.  
     Depending on the selection, choke cherry fruit can vary in 
colour from purple-black, to red, yellow or orange.  The fruit is 
on average slightly larger than that of the pin cherry. The fruit 
of the choke cherry is very flavourful but astringent.  This 
astringency is what is often referred to as the "choke" of the 
choke cherry.  There are selections available that are reputed to 
have little or no astringency. 
 <P>      The fruit of both species takes about 8-10 weeks to mature 
after fruit set. Pin cherries are normally harvested at the end 
of July and choke cherries during the middle of August.  Both 
wild cherries will begin to fruit at about 4 years of age.<P> 
  <P>   Both wild cherries seem to do well on most soil types.  They 
tolerate a wide range of pH levels, from 5.0-7.0, with the 
optimum being around 6.0.  The only vital part of site selection 
when planting either wild cherry, is that they are planted in an 
area of full sun, as they do not tolerate shade.  <P> 
  <P>   Water requirements of both trees are not large and they can 
survive and produce fruit under normal moisture conditions.  
Supplemental watering may increase plant growth and maximize 
fruit yield.  
<P>      If the soil is of reasonably good fertility, supplemental 
fertilization will be unnecessary for good growth and fruit 
production.  Small amounts of fertilizer will do no harm and may 
increase plant growth and help maximize fruit yield.  Fertilizers 
are best applied in early spring before the leaves flush or in 
late fall after the trees are dormant.<P> 
     Regular, careful pruning is important  to maintain plant 
health and improve yield.  Pruning involves the removal of 
diseased or damaged branches and older less productive branches.   
Thinning the centre area of the tree allows good air flow through 
the canopy decreasing disease problems.  It also allows better 
light penetration resulting in more even ripening of the fruit. 
<P>      Selections of choke cherry and pin cherry vary in the amount 
of suckers produced.  Heavy suckering selections will require 
frequent pruning to control this undesirable growth. <P> 
<P>     As "natives" of the prairies, pin cherry and choke cherry 
are well adapted to our climates and rarely suffer winter damage.  
Both wild cherries are susceptible to sunscald injury, a 
splitting of the bark which results from direct exposure to the 
sun during the winter.  Injury can be avoided by selecting a site 
in which the stem bark is not exposed to direct winter sun, or by 
painting the stem bark with white paint.
<P>      Problems with pest insects and diseases are minimal.  In 
most years an acceptable fruit yield can be obtained without any 
insect or disease control.  However there are some pests which 
should be noted as having the potential to reduce fruit yield in 
certain years.  The gardener can keep a watchful eye on the 
developing fruit and note any signs of pest damage.  Often there 
is little one can do to prevent pest damage but there are some 
non-chemical controls which if followed may help in preventing 
total fruit loss.
<P>      The fruit tree leaf roller (<I>Archips argyrospila</I>) is 
so named because it rolls the leaf around itself while feeding.  
It primarily feeds on the foliage, but it can cause damage to 
flower clusters and newly set fruit.  This pest is not unique to 
the choke cherry, but attacks a wide variety of deciduous trees.  
In late July, the adult lays a large egg mass on the tree stem 
and branches. The caterpillars emerge in early spring just as the 
choke cherry begins to leaf out and flower.  They feed on the 
foliage for about 3 weeks before entering a cocoon stage.  This 
stage  will last for 2-3 weeks before emergence of the adult.  
These insects have only one cycle per year, but if the population 
is allowed to build up over a number of seasons, they can cause 
quite severe yield loss.  High quality dormant oil applied to the 
egg masses in early spring when the tree is still dormant, may 
limit the number of eggs that hatch.
 <P>      Other caterpillars causing damage to the choke cherry 
include the tent caterpillars (<I>Malacosoma sp.</I>).  These 
pests construct a webbed nest near a fork in the stem, and feed 
on the surrounding leaves.  A nest containing about 200 larvae 
can potentially defoliate a 2-3m (5-10ft) high shrub.  Some 
damage control may be obtained by removing and destroying the 
tent and as many of the caterpillars as possible.
<P>      The fruit gall midge (<I>Contarinia virginianae</I>) can 
cause a significant amount of fruit loss in choke cherry.  The 
main symptom of gall-midge damage is an enlarged, pear-shaped, 
hollow fruit.  These galls may begin to develop soon after fruit 
set and persist until late July.  Normally the fruit-galls will 
dry up and drop to the ground prior to harvest. Removal and 
destruction of the galls soon after they appear will reduce the 
chances of increased damage the following year.
<P>      The insect of most concern to pin cherry is the cherry fruit 
fly (<I>Rhagoletis cingulata</I>).  This fruit fly lays its eggs 
under the skin of the ripening fruit.  The emerging maggot feeds 
on the flesh of the fruit.  At harvest time, the maggots will 
emerge from the fruit and fall to the ground where they over- 
winter.  Infested fruit can usually be identified by a slightly 
shrivelled look.  Good sanitation around the base of the tree in 
combination with very shallow cultivation of 7-10cm (3-5") will 
control an increase in maggot damage the following season.
  <P>         A sawfly (<I>Hoplocampa lacteipennis</I>) can cause yield 
loss in both wild cherries.  Eggs are laid by the adult at the 
base of the flowers in early spring.  After hatching, the larvae 
feed on the seeds of a number of developing fruit, before falling 
to the ground where they overwinter.   Infested fruit can be 
identified by the visible larval exit holes, or the shrivelled 
appearance of the developing fruit.  Fruit infested with sawfly 
larvae are unusable and will often drop from the tree prior to 
harvest.  Good sanitation and shallow cultivation similar to that 
used for maggot control will also help control sawfly 
populations. 
 <P>      Black Knot of cherry (<I>Apiosporina morbosa</I>), a disease 
common to both wild cherries, is characterized by the appearance 
of a large black gall on the stem and branches.  The disease will 
cause gradual dieback of the infected branch.  Pruning to remove 
the galls as soon as they appear should provide adequate 
control.<P> 
     The pin cherry can be effected by Cytospora canker 
(<I>Cytospora leucostoma</I>).  The first signs of Cytospora may 
be a gum-like substance exuding out of cracks in the bark.  The 
foliage of infected branches turns bright reddish-brown, 
remaining attached for several weeks before falling.  This 
disease results in death of the infected branch.  If the infected 
branch is not removed as quickly as possible, the disease will 
spread to other branches and other nearby pin cherry trees.  Good 
pruning is usually provides sufficient control.<P> 
     Cultivars of the pin cherry and the choke cherry should be 
available from most prairie nurseries.  These cultivars are 
superior ornamental and fruiting plants that have been 
vegetatively propagated (through  cuttings for example) in order 
to reproduce a large quantity of plants having the same 
characteristics.  It is important to note that some nurseries may 
sell pin cherry or choke cherry plants grown from seed.  These 
seedlings will be variable in their characteristics and the 
ornamental and fruit quality relatively unknown<B></B>.  It 
therefore of utmost importance that when purchasing a choke 
cherry or pin cherry that you ensure that it is in fact one of 
the vegetatively propagated named cultivars and not a seedling.   
                                 
