<P> 
     For more complete information on choke cherry and pin cherry 
management and cultivar descriptions, two manuals published by 
Dr. R. St. Pierre of the Horticulture Science Department at the 
University of Saskatchewan, will prove very useful.  These 
publications are:  
-The Choke Cherry, A Guide For Growers (Currently Available)<P> 
-The Pin Cherry, A Guide For Growers (In Press - Available late    
 1995/early 1996).<P> 
     The real reward of growing either of the wild cherries is of 
course the fruit.  Without any recipes for home processing the 
reward is greatly diminished.  Many local Saskatchewan cookbooks 
include recipes for jelly and syrup.  The recipe insert in the 
Certo<em sup>TM</em> packages also includes recipes for choke cherry 
and pin cherry jelly.<P> 
     I think any gardener who buys a few choke cherry or pin 
cherry trees for the garden will be more than satisfied with the 
results.  The low maintenance requirements and limited pest 
problems make choke cherry and pin cherry an ideal choice for the 
gardener who wants to get a consistent fruit yield without alot 
of effort. The added advantages of growing a native plants 
adapted to growing and producing fruit in our prairie region, 
make them a viable alternative to attempting to grow the more 
often grown domestic fruit trees.  <P> 
